{"title_page": "Nikephoros I", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Redirect|Nicephorus I}}\n{{Infobox monarch\n|name        = Nikephoros I\n|image       = Nicephorus I Logothetes.jpg\n|image_size  = 200px\n|caption     = Nikephoros I, depicted in the 12th century ''Manasses Chronicle''\n|succession  = [[List of Byzantine emperors|Emperor]] of the [[Byzantine Empire]]\n|reign       = 31 October 802 \u2013 26 July 811\n|predecessor = [[Irene of Athens|Irene]]\n|successor   = [[Staurakios]]\n|issue       = [[Staurakios]]<br/>[[Prokopia]] \n|dynasty     = [[Nikephorian dynasty|Nikephorian]]\n|death_date  = 26 July 811 (age 60-61)\n|death_place = [[Battle of Pliska]], [[Pliska]]\n|title=[[List of Byzantine Emperors|Emperor of the Romans]]\n|birth_date=750\n}}\n{{Nikephorian dynasty}}\n'''Nikephoros I''', or '''Nicephorus I''' ({{lang-el|\u039d\u03b9\u03ba\u03b7\u03c6\u03cc\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u0391\u0384}}, ''Nik\u0113phoros I''; 750 \u2013 26 July 811) was [[Byzantine Emperor]] from 802 to 811, when he was killed in the [[Battle of Pliska]]. Prior to his accession, he had served as ''[[genikos logothetes|genikos logothet\u0113s]]'', whence he is sometimes surnamed \"the Logothete\" (\u1f41 \u039b\u03bf\u03b3\u03bf\u03b8\u03ad\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2) and \"Genikos\" or \"Genicus\" (\u1f41 \u0393\u03b5\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2).\n\n==Background==\nBoth [[Syriac language|Syriac]] sources such as [[Michael the Syrian]] and [[Arabic]] ones like [[al-Tabari]] and [[Mas'udi]] hold that the emperor was of a [[Ghassanid]] [[Arabs|Arab]] origin.<ref name=\"Polemics97\">{{cite book|last1=Bekkum|first1=Wout Jac van|last2=Drijvers|first2=Jan Willem|last3=Klugkist|first3=Alexander Cornelis|title=Syriac Polemics: Studies in Honour of Gerrit Jan Reinink|date=2007|publisher=Peeters Publishers|isbn=9789042919730|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U7tW-jA2yfkC&pg=PA97|page=97}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Cooper|first1=Eric|last2=Decker|first2=Michael J.|title=Life and Society in Byzantine Cappadocia|date=2012|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781137029645|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2ZRZTZ5OZC8C&pg=PA42|page=42}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Biliarsky|first1=Ivan|title=The Tale of the Prophet Isaiah: The Destiny and Meanings of an Apocryphal Text|date=2013|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9789004254381|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mbevAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA208|page=208}}</ref> [[Byzantine]] chronicles, however, although generally hostile to him, make no explicit mention about his ethnic background.<ref name=\"Polemics97\"/> On the other hand, al-Tabari claims that he learned of Nikephoros' Arab origins from Byzantine sources.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Alexander|first1=Paul Julius|title=The Byzantine Apocalyptic Tradition|date=1985|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=9780520049987|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nw-rR_Skb-cC&pg=PA66|page=66}}</ref> Some scholars, like Paul Julius Alexander, accept al-Tabari's account, citing a Byzantine apocalyptic text in which the emperor is said to be \"from the race of Gopsin\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Alexander|first1=Paul Julius|title=The Byzantine Apocalyptic Tradition|date=1985|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=9780520049987|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nw-rR_Skb-cC&pg=PA66|page=66 (note 21)}}</ref> The word \"Gospin\" could be a [[Greek language|Greek]] rendering of the name \"[[Ghassan]]\", or the name \"Gafna\", the [[eponym]] of the Ghassanids.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Shah\u00eed|first1=Irfan|title=Byzantium and the Arabs in the Sixth Century|date=1995|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=9780884023470|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=js30HODt2aYC&pg=PA150|page=150}}</ref>\n\n==Reign==\n{{refimprove|section|date=October 2019}}\n[[File:Byzantine Empire 802 AD.png|left|thumb|The Byzantine Empire at the beginning of the reign of Nikephoros I, in 802 AD.]]\nA patrician from [[Seleucia Sidera]], Nikephoros was appointed finance minister (''[[logothetes tou genikou|logothet\u0113s tou genikou]]'') by the Empress [[Irene (empress)|Irene]]. With the help of the [[patrikios|patricians]] and [[eunuch]]s he contrived to dethrone and exile Irene, and to be chosen as Emperor in her stead on 31 October 802. He crowned his son [[Staurakios]] co-emperor in 803.  \n\nHis rule was endangered by [[Bardanes Tourkos]], one of his ablest generals, who revolted and received support from other commanders, notably the later emperors [[Leo V the Armenian]] and [[Michael II|Michael II the Amorian]] in 803.\n\nBut Nikephoros gained over the latter two, and by inducing the rebel army to disperse achieved the submission of Bardanes, who was blinded and relegated to a [[monastery]]. A conspiracy headed by the patrician [[Arsaber]] had a similar result. \n\nNikephoros embarked on a general reorganization of the Roman Empire, creating new [[Theme (Byzantine district)|themes]] in the [[Balkans]] (where he initiated the re-Hellenization by resettling [[Greeks]] from [[Anatolia]]) and strengthening the frontiers.  Needing large sums to increase his military forces, he set himself with great energy to increase the Empire's revenue. By his rigorous tax imposts he alienated his subjects, especially the clergy, whom he otherwise sought to control firmly. Although he appointed an [[iconodule]], [[Patriarch Nicephorus I of Constantinople|Nikephoros]], as [[Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople|patriarch]], Emperor Nikephoros was portrayed as a [[villain]] by ecclesiastical historians like [[Theophanes the Confessor]].\n[[File:Krum1.jpg|thumb|Khan Krum feasts while a servant brings the skull of Nikephoros I fashioned into a drinking cup.]]\nIn 803, Nikephoros concluded a treaty, called the \"[[Pax Nicephori]]\", with [[Charlemagne]], but refused to recognize the latter's imperial dignity. Relations deteriorated and led to a war over [[Venice]] in 806\u2013810. In the process, Nikephoros had quelled a Venetian rebellion in 807, but suffered extensive losses to the Franks.  The conflict was resolved only after Nikephoros' death, and Venice, [[Istria]], the [[Dalmatia]]n coast and [[South Italy]] were assigned to the East, while [[Rome]], [[Ravenna]] and the [[Pentapolis]] were included in the Western realm. \n\nBy withholding the tribute which Irene had agreed to pay to the caliph [[H\u0101r\u016bn al-Rash\u012bd]], Nikephoros committed himself to a war against the Arabs.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2011|p=222}} Compelled by Bardanes' disloyalty to take the field himself, he sustained a severe defeat at the [[Battle of Krasos]] in Phrygia (805).{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2011|p=222}} In 806 a Muslim army of 135,000 men [[Abbasid invasion of Asia Minor (806)|invaded the Empire]]. Unable to counter the Muslim numbers, Nikephoros agreed to make peace on condition of paying 50,000 nomismata immediately and a yearly tribute of 30,000 nomismata. With a succession struggle enveloping the caliphate on the death of H\u0101r\u016bn al-Rash\u012bd in 809, Nikephoros was free to deal with [[Krum]], Khan of Bulgaria, who was harassing his northern frontiers and had just conquered Serdica (Sofia).\n\nIn 811, Nikephoros invaded [[Bulgaria]], defeated Krum twice, and sacked the Bulgarian capital [[Pliska]]. The Chronicle of the 12th-century patriarch of the Syrian Jacobites, [[Michael the Syrian]], describes the brutalities and atrocities of Nikephoros: \"Nikephoros, emperor of the Byzantine empire, walked into the Bulgarians' land: he was victorious and killed great number of them. He reached their capital, seized it and devastated it. His savagery went to the point that he ordered to bring their small children, got them tied down on earth and made thresh grain stones to smash them.\" During Nikephoros' retreat, the imperial army was ambushed and destroyed in Varbishki mountain passes on [[Battle of Pliska|26 July]] by [[Krum]]. Nikephoros was captured during the battle and sent to [[Pliska]], where Krum ordered his decapitation. Krum is said to have [[skull cup|made a drinking-cup]] of Nikephoros' skull.\n\n==Family==\nBy an unknown wife Nikephoros I had at least two children:\n* [[Staurakios]], who succeeded as emperor.\n* [[Prokopia]], who married [[Michael I Rangabe]], emperor 811\u2013813.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Conflict and Conquest in the Islamic World: A Historical Encyclopedia |volume=Vol. 1 |editor-first=Alexander |editor-last=Mikaberidze |publisher=ABC-CLIO |year=2011 |ref=harv}}\n*''The [[Oxford Dictionary of Byzantium]]'', ed. by [[Alexander Kazhdan]], Oxford University Press, 1991.\n* {{1911|wstitle=Nicephorus|volume=19|pages=647\u2013648}}\n*{{cite book | last=Norwich| first=John J. | title=Byzantium: The Apogee | publisher=Alfred A. Knopf, Inc. | year=1991 | isbn=0-394-53779-3}}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Byzantine Empire}}\n*[[List of Byzantine emperors]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Nikephorian dynasty]]||8th century|26 July|811}}\n{{s-reg|}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[Irene of Athens|Irene]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = [[Byzantine Emperor]]\n| years = 31 October 802 \u2013 26 July 811\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = [[Stauracius|Staurakios]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Roman Emperors}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nikephoros 01}}\n[[Category:9th-century Byzantine emperors]]\n[[Category:Byzantine people of the Byzantine\u2013Bulgarian Wars]]\n[[Category:8th-century Byzantine people]]\n[[Category:8th-century births]]\n[[Category:811 deaths]]\n[[Category:Roman emperors killed in battle]]\n[[Category:Monarchs killed in action]]\n[[Category:Christian monarchs]]\n[[Category:800s in the Byzantine Empire]]\n[[Category:810s in the Byzantine Empire]]\n[[Category:Byzantine people of Arab descent]]\n[[Category:Nikephorian dynasty]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Nicephorus I}}\n{{Infobox monarch\n|name        = Nikephoros I\n|image       = Nicephorus I Logothetes.jpg\n|image_size  = 200px\n|caption     = Nikephoros I, depicted in the 12th century ''Manasses Chronicle''\n|succession  = [[List of Byzantine emperors|Emperor]] of the [[Byzantine Empire]]\n|reign       = 31 October 802 \u2013 26 July 811\n|predecessor = [[Irene of Athens|Irene]]\n|successor   = [[Staurakios]]\n|issue       = [[Staurakios]]<br/>[[Prokopia]] \n|dynasty     = [[Nikephorian dynasty|Nikephorian]]\n|death_date  = 26 July 811 (age 60-61)\n|death_place = [[Battle of Pliska]], [[Pliska]]\n|title=[[List of Byzantine Emperors|Emperor of the Romans]]\n|birth_date=750\n}}\n{{Nikephorian dynasty}}\n'''Nikephoros I''', or '''Nicephorus I''' ({{lang-el|\u039d\u03b9\u03ba\u03b7\u03c6\u03cc\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u0391\u0384}}, ''Nik\u0113phoros I''; 750 \u2013 July 26, 811) was [[Byzantine Emperor]] from 802 to 811, when he was killed in the [[Battle of Pliska]]. Prior to his accession, he had served as ''[[genikos logothetes|genikos logothet\u0113s]]'', whence he is sometimes surnamed \"the Logothete\" (\u1f41 \u039b\u03bf\u03b3\u03bf\u03b8\u03ad\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2) and \"Genikos\" or \"Genicus\" (\u1f41 \u0393\u03b5\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2).\n\n==Background==\nBoth [[Syriac language|Syriac]] sources such as [[Michael the Syrian]] and [[Arabic]] ones like [[al-Tabari]] and [[Mas'udi]] hold that the emperor was of a [[Ghassanid]] [[Arabs|Arab]] origin.<ref name=\"Polemics97\">{{cite book|last1=Bekkum|first1=Wout Jac van|last2=Drijvers|first2=Jan Willem|last3=Klugkist|first3=Alexander Cornelis|title=Syriac Polemics: Studies in Honour of Gerrit Jan Reinink|date=2007|publisher=Peeters Publishers|isbn=9789042919730|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U7tW-jA2yfkC&pg=PA97|page=97}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Cooper|first1=Eric|last2=Decker|first2=Michael J.|title=Life and Society in Byzantine Cappadocia|date=2012|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781137029645|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2ZRZTZ5OZC8C&pg=PA42|page=42}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Biliarsky|first1=Ivan|title=The Tale of the Prophet Isaiah: The Destiny and Meanings of an Apocryphal Text|date=2013|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9789004254381|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mbevAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA208|page=208}}</ref> [[Byzantine]] chronicles, however, although generally hostile to him, make no explicit mention about his ethnic background.<ref name=\"Polemics97\"/> On the other hand, al-Tabari claims that he learned of Nikephoros' Arab origins from Byzantine sources.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Alexander|first1=Paul Julius|title=The Byzantine Apocalyptic Tradition|date=1985|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=9780520049987|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nw-rR_Skb-cC&pg=PA66|page=66}}</ref> Some scholars, like Paul Julius Alexander, accept al-Tabari's account, citing a Byzantine apocalyptic text in which the emperor is said to be \"from the race of Gopsin\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Alexander|first1=Paul Julius|title=The Byzantine Apocalyptic Tradition|date=1985|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=9780520049987|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nw-rR_Skb-cC&pg=PA66|page=66 (note 21)}}</ref> The word \"Gospin\" could be a [[Greek language|Greek]] rendering of the name \"[[Ghassan]]\", or the name \"Gafna\", the [[eponym]] of the Ghassanids.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Shah\u00eed|first1=Irfan|title=Byzantium and the Arabs in the Sixth Century|date=1995|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=9780884023470|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=js30HODt2aYC&pg=PA150|page=150}}</ref>\n\n==Reign==\n{{refimprove|section|date=October 2019}}\n[[File:Byzantine Empire 802 AD.png|left|thumb|The Byzantine Empire at the beginning of the reign of Nikephoros I, in 802 AD.]]\nA patrician from [[Seleucia Sidera]], Nikephoros was appointed finance minister (''[[logothetes tou genikou|logothet\u0113s tou genikou]]'') by the Empress [[Irene (empress)|Irene]]. With the help of the [[patrikios|patricians]] and [[eunuch]]s he contrived to dethrone and exile Irene, and to be chosen as Emperor in her stead on October 31, 802. He crowned his son [[Staurakios]] co-emperor in 803.  \n\nHis rule was endangered by [[Bardanes Tourkos]], one of his ablest generals, who revolted and received support from other commanders, notably the later emperors [[Leo V the Armenian]] and [[Michael II|Michael II the Amorian]] in 803.\n\nBut Nikephoros gained over the latter two, and by inducing the rebel army to disperse achieved the submission of Bardanes, who was blinded and relegated to a [[monastery]]. A conspiracy headed by the patrician [[Arsaber]] had a similar result. \n\nNikephoros embarked on a general reorganization of the Roman Empire, creating new [[Theme (Byzantine district)|themes]] in the [[Balkans]] (where he initiated the re-Hellenization by resettling [[Greeks]] from [[Anatolia]]) and strengthening the frontiers.  Needing large sums to increase his military forces, he set himself with great energy to increase the Empire's revenue. By his rigorous tax imposts he alienated his subjects, especially the clergy, whom he otherwise sought to control firmly. Although he appointed an [[iconodule]], [[Patriarch Nicephorus I of Constantinople|Nikephoros]], as [[Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople|patriarch]], Emperor Nikephoros was portrayed as a [[villain]] by ecclesiastical historians like [[Theophanes the Confessor]].\n[[File:Krum1.jpg|thumb|Khan Krum feasts while a servant brings the skull of Nikephoros I fashioned into a drinking cup.]]\nIn 803, Nikephoros concluded a treaty, called the \"[[Pax Nicephori]]\", with [[Charlemagne]], but refused to recognize the latter's imperial dignity. Relations deteriorated and led to a war over [[Venice]] in 806\u2013810. In the process, Nikephoros had quelled a Venetian rebellion in 807, but suffered extensive losses to the Franks.  The conflict was resolved only after Nikephoros' death, and Venice, [[Istria]], the [[Dalmatia]]n coast and [[South Italy]] were assigned to the East, while [[Rome]], [[Ravenna]] and the [[Pentapolis]] were included in the Western realm. \n\nBy withholding the tribute which Irene had agreed to pay to the caliph [[H\u0101r\u016bn al-Rash\u012bd]], Nikephoros committed himself to a war against the Arabs.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2011|p=222}} Compelled by Bardanes' disloyalty to take the field himself, he sustained a severe defeat at the [[Battle of Krasos]] in Phrygia (805).{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2011|p=222}} In 806 a Muslim army of 135,000 men [[Abbasid invasion of Asia Minor (806)|invaded the Empire]]. Unable to counter the Muslim numbers, Nikephoros agreed to make peace on condition of paying 50,000 nomismata immediately and a yearly tribute of 30,000 nomismata. With a succession struggle enveloping the caliphate on the death of H\u0101r\u016bn al-Rash\u012bd in 809, Nikephoros was free to deal with [[Krum]], Khan of Bulgaria, who was harassing his northern frontiers and had just conquered Serdica (Sofia).\n\nIn 811, Nikephoros invaded [[Bulgaria]], defeated Krum twice, and sacked the Bulgarian capital [[Pliska]]. The Chronicle of the 12th-century patriarch of the Syrian Jacobites, [[Michael the Syrian]], describes the brutalities and atrocities of Nikephoros: \"Nikephoros, emperor of the Byzantine empire, walked into the Bulgarians' land: he was victorious and killed great number of them. He reached their capital, seized it and devastated it. His savagery went to the point that he ordered to bring their small children, got them tied down on earth and made thresh grain stones to smash them.\" During Nikephoros' retreat, the imperial army was ambushed and destroyed in Varbishki mountain passes on [[Battle of Pliska|July 26]] by [[Krum]]. Nikephoros was captured during the battle and sent to [[Pliska]], where Krum ordered his decapitation. Krum is said to have [[skull cup|made a drinking-cup]] of Nikephoros' skull.\n\n==Family==\nBy an unknown wife Nikephoros I had at least two children:\n* [[Staurakios]], who succeeded as emperor.\n* [[Prokopia]], who married [[Michael I Rangabe]], emperor 811\u2013813.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Conflict and Conquest in the Islamic World: A Historical Encyclopedia |volume=Vol. 1 |editor-first=Alexander |editor-last=Mikaberidze |publisher=ABC-CLIO |year=2011 |ref=harv}}\n*''The [[Oxford Dictionary of Byzantium]]'', ed. by [[Alexander Kazhdan]], Oxford University Press, 1991.\n* {{1911|wstitle=Nicephorus|volume=19|pages=647\u2013648}}\n*{{cite book | last=Norwich| first=John J. | title=Byzantium: The Apogee | publisher=Alfred A. Knopf, Inc. | year=1991 | isbn=0-394-53779-3}}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Byzantine Empire}}\n*[[List of Byzantine emperors]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Nikephorian dynasty]]||8th century|26 July|811}}\n{{s-reg|}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[Irene of Athens|Irene]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = [[Byzantine Emperor]]\n| years = 31 October 802 \u2013 26 July 811\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = [[Stauracius|Staurakios]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Roman Emperors}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nikephoros 01}}\n[[Category:9th-century Byzantine emperors]]\n[[Category:Byzantine people of the Byzantine\u2013Bulgarian Wars]]\n[[Category:8th-century Byzantine people]]\n[[Category:8th-century births]]\n[[Category:811 deaths]]\n[[Category:Roman emperors killed in battle]]\n[[Category:Monarchs killed in action]]\n[[Category:Christian monarchs]]\n[[Category:800s in the Byzantine Empire]]\n[[Category:810s in the Byzantine Empire]]\n[[Category:Byzantine people of Arab descent]]\n[[Category:Nikephorian dynasty]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nikephoros_I"}
{"title_page": "Chris Bender (singer)", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Chris Bender\n| image               = Chris Bender singer.jpg\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Bender in 1991\n| image_size          = \n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Christopher Lamont Bender\n| alias               = Chris Bender\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1972|08|02}}\n| birth_place         = [[Brockton, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| death_date          = {{Death date and age|1991|11|03|1972|08|02}}\n| death_place         = [[Brockton, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| origin              = \n| instrument          = Vocal\n| genre               = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| occupation          = Singer\n| years_active        = 1989\u20131991\n| label               = [[Epic Records]], [[EastWest Records]]\n| associated_acts    = T Calloway, Earl Williams (Mentor/manager)\n| website             = \n}}\n'''Christopher Lamont Bender''', known as '''Chris Bender''', (August 2, 1972 \u2013 November 3, 1991)<ref>[http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GSmcid=46997510&GRid=57715049& Christopher Lamont \"Chris\" Bender (1972 - 1991)] - Find A Grave Memorial</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121105151006/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-7685092.html Article: 500 mourn slain Brockton singer In eulogy, minister urges youth to shun drugs, violence], By Sandy Coleman, GLOBE STAFF, November 9, 1991, The Boston Globe (Boston, MA)</ref> was an [[United States|American]] [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] singer who reached the national music charts in 1991 with the album entitled ''Draped'' before his murder.\n\n==Career==\nHe was from the [[Boston, Massachusetts]] area, growing up in [[Brockton, Massachusetts]] and later living in [[Waltham, Massachusetts|Waltham]] at the age of 14 years old he formed his own professional group called \"steady Life\" with two siblings and two cousins they would perform at clubs in Brockton,Massachusetts.<ref name=\"sullivan\">{{cite news |first=Jack |last=Sullivan |title=Rising Star Shot Dead in Brockton: 19-Year-Old Recording Artist Was Sitting in Car at Housing Project |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BG&p_theme=bg&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EADDF8E203D7CD3&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |work=The Boston Globe   |date=1991-11-04 |accessdate=2007-10-26}}</ref> At the age of 16 he dropped out of high school to become a singer, Bender recorded his first album, ''Chris Bender'', for [[Epic Records]]. The first single \"Baby Girl\" was released in 1989 but limited copies of the album were released. Bender's manager Terryl L. Calloway later stated about ''Baby Girl'': \" The video was never [released]. \"<ref name=\"walker\">{{cite news |first=Adrian |last=Walker |title=Slain Brockton singer heard the call of conflicting worlds |work=The Boston Globe |page=31 |date=1991-11-10}}</ref> Bender nevertheless went on to secure a $500,000 contract with [[EastWest Records]].<ref name=\"walker\"/> He signed a seven-album contract, although only one album on that contract was released before his death.<ref name=\"mcadams\">{{cite news |first=Janine |last=McAdams |title=EastWest Act Chris Bender Dies From Gunshot Wound |work=Billboard |page=20 |date=1991-11-16}}</ref> The album ''Draped'' hit No. 92 on the [[Billboard magazine]] [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|R&B album chart]]. His two charted singles \"I Knew\" and \"That's Not The Way\" broke into the top 70 on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Hot R&B Singles]] chart. Other songs he was known for included \"Who Will I Choose\" and \"Kiss and Make Up\".\n\n==Death==\nOn November 3, 1991, at 2:17 A.M.,<ref>{{cite court | litigants=Commonwealth vs. Stephen Fernandes | vol = 425 | reporter = Mass. | opinion = 357 | date=1997 | url=http://masscases.com/cases/sjc/425/425mass357.html | accessdate = 2009-12-17}}</ref> Bender was shot and killed in Brockton<ref name=\"sullivan\"/><ref>{{cite news |author=Associated Press |title=Singer, 19, is slain in Massachusetts |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=KC&p_theme=kc&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF3D0EE76306A6&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |work=The Kansas City Star   |page=E4 |date=1991-11-05 |accessdate=2007-10-26}}</ref> while sitting in his black \nMercedes Benz outside of the Crescent Court housing project where his mother lived,during Chris Bender was sitting in the driver's seat in his Mercedes Benz with his 17 year old cousin Jesse Starks smoking marijuana and talking and then they heard gunshots and 3 hooded men fired gunshots at the Mercedes Benz and then Chris Bender shielded his 17 year old cousin Jesse Starks from the gunshots and Chris Bender was struck 4 times and in the back and he died from his wounds.<ref name=\"mcadams\"/><ref>{{cite court | litigants=Commonwealth vs. Eroy Kindell | vol = 44 | reporter = Mass. App. Ct. | opinion = 200 | date=1998 | url=http://masscases.com/cases/app/44/44massappct200.html | accessdate = 2009-12-17}}</ref> Eroy Kindell was convicted of second degree murder and has been recently released from prison. His accomplice Stephen \"Sticks\" Fernandes was convicted of first degree murder and sentenced to life without parole.\n\nChris Bender was laid to rest at Melrose cemetery in Brockton Massachusetts in 1991.\n\n==Discography==\n\n=== Chris Bender (12\")===\n:1. Teddy Bear\n:2 Baby Girl\n:3 Any Good Girls Left\n:4 Conceited Girl\n:5 Never Give Up On Me\n:6 That's How Love Happens\n:7 Intimate Lover\n:8 Go On And Love Your Lady\n\n===Draped (12\" / CD)===\n:1. [[I Knew]]\n:2. Draped\n:3. It's All About You\n:4. Spellbound\n:5. Prelude... Stay Til The Morning\n:6. Don't Go Home\n:7. [[That's Not The Way]]\n:8. Sorry Didn't Do It\n:9. [[Who Will I Choose?]]\n:10. Pouring Down Rain\n:11. Kiss & Make Up\n:12. Kiss & Make Up [The Apologize Mix]\n\nUPC: 075679170828<ref>[http://www.swapacd.com/Chris-Bender-Draped/cd/1681/ Chris Bender - Draped (12 tracks) +Album Reviews], swapacd</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{youtube|8OalUpRJx_A|Chris Bender I Know (Promo 12\") }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bender, Chris}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Boston]]\n[[Category:1991 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:American contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Murdered American musicians]]\n[[Category:Murdered African-American people]]\n[[Category:Singers from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Chris Bender\n| image               = Chris Bender singer.jpg\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Bender in 1991\n| image_size          = \n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Christopher Lamont Bender\n| alias               = Chris Bender\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1972|08|02}}\n| birth_place         = [[Brockton, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| death_date          = {{Death date and age|1991|11|03|1972|08|02}}\n| death_place         = [[Brockton, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| origin              = \n| instrument          = Vocal\n| genre               = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| occupation          = Singer\n| years_active        = 1989\u20131991\n| label               = [[Epic Records]], [[EastWest Records]]\n| associated_acts    = T Calloway, Earl Williams (Mentor/manager)\n| website             = \n}}\n'''Christopher Lamont Bender''', known as '''Chris Bender''', (August 2, 1972 \u2013 November 3, 1991)<ref>[http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GSmcid=46997510&GRid=57715049& Christopher Lamont \"Chris\" Bender (1972 - 1991)] - Find A Grave Memorial</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121105151006/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-7685092.html Article: 500 mourn slain Brockton singer In eulogy, minister urges youth to shun drugs, violence], By Sandy Coleman, GLOBE STAFF, November 9, 1991, The Boston Globe (Boston, MA)</ref> was an [[United States|American]] [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] singer who reached the national music charts in 1991 with the album entitled ''Draped'' before his murder.\n\n==Career==\nHe was from the [[Boston, Massachusetts]] area, growing up in [[Brockton, Massachusetts]] and later living in [[Waltham, Massachusetts|Waltham]].<ref name=\"sullivan\">{{cite news |first=Jack |last=Sullivan |title=Rising Star Shot Dead in Brockton: 19-Year-Old Recording Artist Was Sitting in Car at Housing Project |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BG&p_theme=bg&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EADDF8E203D7CD3&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |work=The Boston Globe   |date=1991-11-04 |accessdate=2007-10-26}}</ref> At the age of 16, Bender recorded his first album, ''Chris Bender'', for [[Epic Records]]. The first single \"Baby Girl\" was released in 1989 but limited copies of the album were released. Bender's manager Terryl L. Calloway later stated about ''Baby Girl'': \" The video was never [released]. \"<ref name=\"walker\">{{cite news |first=Adrian |last=Walker |title=Slain Brockton singer heard the call of conflicting worlds |work=The Boston Globe |page=31 |date=1991-11-10}}</ref> Bender nevertheless went on to secure a $500,000 contract with [[EastWest Records]].<ref name=\"walker\"/> He signed a seven-album contract, although only one album on that contract was released before his death.<ref name=\"mcadams\">{{cite news |first=Janine |last=McAdams |title=EastWest Act Chris Bender Dies From Gunshot Wound |work=Billboard |page=20 |date=1991-11-16}}</ref> The album ''Draped'' hit No. 92 on the [[Billboard magazine]] [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|R&B album chart]]. His two charted singles \"I Knew\" and \"That's Not The Way\" broke into the top 70 on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Hot R&B Singles]] chart. Other songs he was known for included \"Who Will I Choose\" and \"Kiss and Make Up\".\n\n==Death==\nOn November 3, 1991, at 2:17 A.M.,<ref>{{cite court | litigants=Commonwealth vs. Stephen Fernandes | vol = 425 | reporter = Mass. | opinion = 357 | date=1997 | url=http://masscases.com/cases/sjc/425/425mass357.html | accessdate = 2009-12-17}}</ref> Bender was shot and killed in Brockton<ref name=\"sullivan\"/><ref>{{cite news |author=Associated Press |title=Singer, 19, is slain in Massachusetts |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=KC&p_theme=kc&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF3D0EE76306A6&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |work=The Kansas City Star   |page=E4 |date=1991-11-05 |accessdate=2007-10-26}}</ref> while sitting in his black \nMercedes Benz outside of the Crescent Court housing project where his mother lived,during Chris Bender was sitting in the driver's seat in his Mercedes Benz with his 17 year old cousin Jesse Starks smoking marijuana and talking and then they heard gunshots and 3 hooded men fired gunshots at the Mercedes Benz and then Chris Bender shielded his 17 year old cousin Jesse Starks from the gunshots and Chris Bender was struck 4 times and in the back and he died from his wounds.<ref name=\"mcadams\"/><ref>{{cite court | litigants=Commonwealth vs. Eroy Kindell | vol = 44 | reporter = Mass. App. Ct. | opinion = 200 | date=1998 | url=http://masscases.com/cases/app/44/44massappct200.html | accessdate = 2009-12-17}}</ref> Eroy Kindell was convicted of second degree murder and has been recently released from prison. His accomplice Stephen \"Sticks\" Fernandes was convicted of first degree murder and sentenced to life without parole.\n\n==Discography==\n\n=== Chris Bender (12\")===\n:1. Teddy Bear\n:2 Baby Girl\n:3 Any Good Girls Left\n:4 Conceited Girl\n:5 Never Give Up On Me\n:6 That's How Love Happens\n:7 Intimate Lover\n:8 Go On And Love Your Lady\n\n===Draped (12\" / CD)===\n:1. [[I Knew]]\n:2. Draped\n:3. It's All About You\n:4. Spellbound\n:5. Prelude... Stay Til The Morning\n:6. Don't Go Home\n:7. [[That's Not The Way]]\n:8. Sorry Didn't Do It\n:9. [[Who Will I Choose?]]\n:10. Pouring Down Rain\n:11. Kiss & Make Up\n:12. Kiss & Make Up [The Apologize Mix]\n\nUPC: 075679170828<ref>[http://www.swapacd.com/Chris-Bender-Draped/cd/1681/ Chris Bender - Draped (12 tracks) +Album Reviews], swapacd</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{youtube|8OalUpRJx_A|Chris Bender I Know (Promo 12\") }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bender, Chris}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Boston]]\n[[Category:1991 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:American contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Murdered American musicians]]\n[[Category:Murdered African-American people]]\n[[Category:Singers from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n", "name_user": "2600:387:0:982::41", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eDeath)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Bender_(singer)"}
{"title_page": "Carney Lansford", "text_new": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Carney Lansford\n|image=Carney_CSN.jpg\n|caption=Carney Lansford in 2010\n|position=[[Third baseman]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1957|2|7}}\n|birth_place=[[San Jose, California]]\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=April 8\n|debutyear=1978\n|debutteam=California Angels\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=October 4\n|finalyear=1992\n|finalteam=Oakland Athletics\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.290\n|stat2label=[[Hit (baseball)|Hits]]\n|stat2value=2,074\n|stat3label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat3value=151\n|stat4label=[[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat4value=874\n|teams=\n* [[California Angels]] ({{mlby|1978}}\u2013{{mlby|1980}})\n* [[Boston Red Sox]] ({{mlby|1981}}\u2013{{mlby|1982}})\n* [[Oakland Athletics]] ({{mlby|1983}}\u2013{{mlby|1992}})\n|highlights=\n* [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[1988 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1988]])\n* [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|1989}})\n* [[Silver Slugger Award]] (1981)\n* [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions|AL batting champion]] (1981)\n}}\n'''Carney Ray Lansford''' (born February 7, 1957) is an [[Americans|American]] former professional [[baseball]] player and [[Coach (baseball)|coach]]. He played in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) as a [[third baseman]] from 1978 to 1992, most notably as a member of the [[Oakland Athletics]] team that won three consecutive [[List of American League pennant winners|American League pennants]] and a [[World Series]] championship in {{wsy|1989}}. He also played for the [[California Angels]] and the [[Boston Red Sox]]. Lansford was the 1981 American League [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions|batting champion]] as a member of the Red Sox and was an American League [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] in 1988 with the Athletics.\n\n==Career==\nDrafted by the California Angels in the 3rd round of the [[1975 Major League Baseball draft]], Lansford was the Angels' most successful rookie in 1978 and finished third in the overall AL [[MLB Rookie of the Year Award|Rookie of the Year]] vote. The Angels dealt Lansford to the Red Sox after the 1980 season. In 1981, he won the American League batting title in the strike-shortened season, becoming the league's first right-handed hitter to do so in 11 years. However, the emergence of [[Wade Boggs]] resulted in the Red Sox sending Lansford to Oakland{{Citation needed|date=November 2009}} in a trade involving [[Tony Armas]] during the 1982 off-season. Lansford became the A's regular third baseman and was there for their 1988 through 1992 dynasty, typically hitting second behind [[Rickey Henderson]]. Lansford narrowly missed winning his second batting title in 1989 with a .336 average (Minnesota's [[Kirby Puckett]] finished with a .339 average). Although his power numbers dropped off during those years, and he missed almost all the 1991 season with an injury, Lansford's speed and solid hitting made him a significant contributor to the A's dynasty. He played in three [[World Series]] with the A's, losing in {{wsy|1988}} and {{wsy|1990}} and winning in {{wsy|1989}}.\n\nIn his 15-year career, Lansford was a .290 hitter with 151 [[home run]]s, 874 [[run batted in|RBI]], and 224 [[stolen base]]s in 1862 [[games played|games]]. In five [[American League Championship Series]] and three World Series covering 33 games, he hit .305 (39-for-128) with two home runs and 18 RBI.\n\n==Coaching career==\nLansford was a hitting coach for the San Francisco Giants during the 2008 and 2009 seasons. Lansford was relieved of his duties following the 2009 season.<ref>http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/giants/detail?entry_id=49609&tsp=1</ref>  Lansford was hired by the Rockies for the 2011 season.<ref>http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_16348829M</ref> In 2015, Lansford was a Batting Coach for the Lamigo Monkeys of the CPBL.<ref>http://twbsball.dils.tku.edu.tw/wiki/index.php/\u862d\u65af\u7236C.L</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLansford had a cameo role as Kit \"Hit or Die\" Kesey, the [[Chicago White Sox]] batter that Mel Clark (played by [[Tony Danza]]) retires for the final out in the Angels' pennant-winning game in the 1994 remake of ''[[Angels in the Outfield (1994 film)|Angels in the Outfield]]''.\n\nHe is a direct descendant of Sir [[Francis Drake]].\n\nHis son, Jared, was drafted by Oakland in the second round of the 2005 amateur draft.  His other son, Josh, was a third baseman in the [[Chicago Cubs]] minor league system. His brother, [[Jody Lansford]], spent nine seasons in the minor leagues, briefly breaking into the big leagues with the [[San Diego Padres]], for whom he recorded 30 at bats with six hits in parts of two seasons, with one career home run.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/L/Jody-Lansford.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-02-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090118161155/http://thebaseballcube.com/players/L/Jody-Lansford.shtml |archivedate=2009-01-18 }}</ref> His other brother, Phil Lansford, was drafted 10th overall in the 1978 draft but never made it to the majors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Phil_Lansford }}</ref>\n\nHe played for the Briarwood Little League team, from [[Santa Clara, California]], which made it to the finals of the 1969 [[Little League World Series]]. In the final game of the World Series on August 2, Carney's team was defeated 5-0 by the team from [[Taipei city|Taipei City]], [[Taiwan]]. Lansford is one of fewer than a dozen men who have played in both the Little League World Series and the MLB World Series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://carneylansford.com/timeline.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-03-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120121404/http://www.carneylansford.com/timeline.html |archivedate=2008-11-20 }}</ref>\n\nLansford went to Wilcox High School in Santa Clara, California. The school's baseball field is named for him.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Baseball}}\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career hits leaders]]\n* [[List of Silver Slugger Award winners at third base]]\n* [[List of Boston Red Sox award winners]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career runs scored leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career stolen bases leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions]]\n* [[List of St. Louis Cardinals coaches]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Baseballstats |mlb= |espn= |br=l/lansfca01 |fangraphs=1007331 |brm=lansfo001car |retro=L/Plansc001}}\n*[http://seamheads.com/baseballgauge/player.php?ID=117488 Baseball Gauge]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040604011727/http://www.baseballlibrary.com/baseballlibrary/ballplayers/L/Lansford_Carney.stm Baseball Library]\n*[http://www.purapelota.com/lvbp/mostrar.php?id=lanscar001 Venezuelan Professional Baseball League]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130712095005/http://www.littleleague.org/series/history/year/1969.htm 1969 Little League World Series]\n*{{IMDb name|id=0487087|name=Carney Lansford}}\n*[http://twbsball.dils.tku.edu.tw/wiki/index.php/\u862d\u65af\u7236C.L Taiwan Baseball Wiki]\n{{AL batting title}}\n{{AL 3B Silver Slugger Award}}\n{{1989 Oakland Athletics}}\n{{Hutch Award}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lansford, Carney}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:American League batting champions]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from California]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox players]]\n[[Category:California Angels players]]\n[[Category:Colorado Rockies (baseball) coaches]]\n[[Category:El Paso Diablos players]]\n[[Category:Idaho Falls Angels players]]\n[[Category:Leones del Caracas players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball first basemen]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball hitting coaches]]\n[[