a [[World Series]] championship in {{wsy|1989}}. He also played for the [[California Angels]] and the [[Boston Red Sox]]. Lansford was the 1981 American League [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions|batting champion]] as a member of the Red Sox and was an American League [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] in 1988 with the Athletics.\n\n==Career==\nDrafted by the California Angels in the 3rd round of the [[1975 Major League Baseball draft]], Lansford was the Angels' most successful rookie in 1978 and finished third in the overall AL [[MLB Rookie of the Year Award|Rookie of the Year]] vote. The Angels dealt Lansford to the Red Sox after the 1980 season. In 1981, he won the American League batting title in the strike-shortened season, becoming the league's first right-handed hitter to do so in 11 years. However, the emergence of [[Wade Boggs]] resulted in the Red Sox sending Lansford to Oakland{{Citation needed|date=November 2009}} in a trade involving [[Tony Armas]] during the 1982 off-season. Lansford became the A's regular third baseman and was there for their 1988 through 1992 dynasty, typically hitting second behind [[Rickey Henderson]]. Lansford narrowly missed winning his second batting title in 1989 with a .336 average (Minnesota's [[Kirby Puckett]] finished with a .339 average). Although his power numbers dropped off during those years, and he missed almost all the 1991 season with an injury, Lansford's speed and solid hitting made him a significant contributor to the A's dynasty. He played in three [[World Series]] with the A's, losing in {{wsy|1988}} and {{wsy|1990}} and winning in {{wsy|1989}}.\n\nIn his 15-year career, Lansford was a .290 hitter with 151 [[home run]]s, 874 [[run batted in|RBI]], and 224 [[stolen base]]s in 1862 [[games played|games]]. In five [[American League Championship Series]] and three World Series covering 33 games, he hit .305 (39-for-128) with two home runs and 18 RBI.\n\n==Coaching career==\nLansford was a hitting coach for the San Francisco Giants during the 2008 and 2009 seasons. Lansford was relieved of his duties following the 2009 season.<ref>http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/giants/detail?entry_id=49609&tsp=1</ref>  Lansford was hired by the Rockies for the 2011 season.<ref>http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_16348829M</ref> In 2015, Lansford was a Batting Coach for the Lamigo Monkeys of the CPBL.<ref>http://twbsball.dils.tku.edu.tw/wiki/index.php/\u862d\u65af\u7236C.L</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLansford had a cameo role as Kit \"Hit or Die\" Kesey, the [[Chicago White Sox]] batter that Mel Clark (played by [[Tony Danza]]) retires for the final out in the Angels' pennant-winning game in the 1994 remake of ''[[Angels in the Outfield (1994 film)|Angels in the Outfield]]''.\n\nHe is a direct descendant of Sir [[Francis Drake]].\n\nHis son, Jared, was drafted by Oakland in the second round of the 2005 amateur draft.  His other son, Josh, was a third baseman in the [[Chicago Cubs]] minor league system. His brother, [[Jody Lansford]], spent nine seasons in the minor leagues, briefly breaking into the big leagues with the [[San Diego Padres]], for whom he recorded 30 at bats with six hits in parts of two seasons, with one career home run.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/L/Jody-Lansford.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-02-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090118161155/http://thebaseballcube.com/players/L/Jody-Lansford.shtml |archivedate=2009-01-18 }}</ref> His other brother, Phil Lansford, was drafted 10th overall in the 1978 draft but never made it to the majors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Phil_Lansford }}</ref>\n\nHe played for the Briarwood Little League team, from [[Santa Clara, California]], which made it to the finals of the 1969 [[Little League World Series]]. In the final game of the World Series on August 2, Carney's team was defeated 5-0 by the team from [[Taipei city|Taipei City]], [[Taiwan]]. Lansford is one of fewer than a dozen men who have played in both the Little League World Series and the MLB World Series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://carneylansford.com/timeline.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-03-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120121404/http://www.carneylansford.com/timeline.html |archivedate=2008-11-20 }}</ref>\n\nLansford went to Wilcox High School in Santa Clara, California, and due to his success, the school's baseball field is named for him.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Baseball}}\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career hits leaders]]\n* [[List of Silver Slugger Award winners at third base]]\n* [[List of Boston Red Sox award winners]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career runs scored leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career stolen bases leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions]]\n* [[List of St. Louis Cardinals coaches]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Baseballstats |mlb= |espn= |br=l/lansfca01 |fangraphs=1007331 |brm=lansfo001car |retro=L/Plansc001}}\n*[http://seamheads.com/baseballgauge/player.php?ID=117488 Baseball Gauge]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040604011727/http://www.baseballlibrary.com/baseballlibrary/ballplayers/L/Lansford_Carney.stm Baseball Library]\n*[http://www.purapelota.com/lvbp/mostrar.php?id=lanscar001 Venezuelan Professional Baseball League]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130712095005/http://www.littleleague.org/series/history/year/1969.htm 1969 Little League World Series]\n*{{IMDb name|id=0487087|name=Carney Lansford}}\n*[http://twbsball.dils.tku.edu.tw/wiki/index.php/\u862d\u65af\u7236C.L Taiwan Baseball Wiki]\n{{AL batting title}}\n{{AL 3B Silver Slugger Award}}\n{{1989 Oakland Athletics}}\n{{Hutch Award}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lansford, Carney}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:American League batting champions]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from California]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox players]]\n[[Category:California Angels players]]\n[[Category:Colorado Rockies (baseball) coaches]]\n[[Category:El Paso Diablos players]]\n[[Category:Idaho Falls Angels players]]\n[[Category:Leones del Caracas players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball first basemen]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball hitting coaches]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball third basemen]]\n[[Category:Minor league baseball managers]]\n[[Category:Oakland Athletics coaches]]\n[[Category:Oakland Athletics players]]\n[[Category:Quad Cities Angels players]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Cardinals coaches]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Giants coaches]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from San Jose, California]]\n[[Category:Tacoma Tigers players]]\n[[Category:Silver Slugger Award winners]]\n", "name_user": "Caro7200", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carney_Lansford"}
