{"title_page": "Michael Cohen (lawyer)", "text_new": "{{about|the former lawyer of Donald Trump and The Trump Organization|the lawyer, author, and former Harvard professor|Michael H. Cohen}}\n{{short description|American former attorney}}\n{{use American English|date=September 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = Michael Cohen\n| image = File:Michael Cohen headshot.jpg\n| caption = Cohen in 2011\n| birth_name = Michael Dean Cohen\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1966|8|25}}\n| birth_place = [[Lawrence, Nassau County, New York]], U.S.\n| education = {{plainlist|\n*[[American University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n*[[Western Michigan University Cooley Law School|Cooley Law School]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\n| party = {{plainlist|\n*{{nowrap|[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]}} {{nowrap|(before 2002;}} {{nowrap|2004\u20132017;}} {{nowrap|2018\u2013present)}}\n*{{nowrap|[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]}} {{nowrap|(2002\u20132004; 2017\u20132018)}}}}\n| spouse = {{marriage|Laura Shusterman|1995}}\n| children = 2\n| module = '''Criminal information'''{{Infobox criminal\n | child = yes\n | conviction = [[Fraud]]; [[perjury]]\n | criminal_charge = {{Bulleted list |5 counts of [[tax evasion]]| 1 count of making false statements to a financial institution |1 count of willfully causing an unlawful corporate contribution |1 count of making an excessive campaign contribution at the request of a candidate or campaign |1 count of making false statements to a congressional committee}}\n | conviction_penalty = {{nowrap|3 years in federal prison;}} {{nowrap|fines;}} {{nowrap|[[asset forfeiture]];}} {{nowrap|[[disbarment]]}}\n | conviction_status = Currently incarcerated at [[Federal Correctional Institution, Otisville]] #86067-054.\n}}\n}}\n'''Michael Dean Cohen''' (born August 25, 1966) is an American former attorney.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2017/01/19/michael-cohen-special-counsel-to-donald-trump-will-follow-him-to-washington/ |title=Michael Cohen will stay Trump's personal attorney\u2014even in the White House |last=Helderman |first=Rosalind |authorlink=Rosalind Helderman |date=January 19, 2017 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=February 1, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170129230446/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2017/01/19/michael-cohen-special-counsel-to-donald-trump-will-follow-him-to-washington/ |archive-date=January 29, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/11/michael-cohen-not-trump-attorney-583902 |title= Giuliani: Cohen is not Trump's lawyer anymore 'as far as we know' |last=Samuelsohn |first=Darren |date=May 11, 2018 |work=[[Politico]] |accessdate=January 29, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190129010907/https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/11/michael-cohen-not-trump-attorney-583902 |archive-date=January 29, 2019 |url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nCohen was a vice-president of [[The Trump Organization]], and the personal counsel to Trump, and was often described by media as Trump's \"[[fixer (person)|fixer]]\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/dec/12/michael-cohen-sentence-trump-loyalty |title=From fixer to inmate: Michael Cohen reckons with his 'blind loyalty' to Trump |last=Durkin |first=Erin |date=December 12, 2018 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=December 14, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181213194232/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/dec/12/michael-cohen-sentence-trump-loyalty |archive-date=December 13, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Stracqualursi |first=Veronica |title=Michael Cohen says Donald Trump knew hush payments were wrong |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=December 14, 2018 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/14/politics/michael-cohen-abc-interview/index.html |access-date= December 15, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181214211037/https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/14/politics/michael-cohen-abc-interview/index.html |archive-date=December 14, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> He previously served as co-president of [[Trump Entertainment]] and was a board member of the [[Eric Trump Foundation]], a children's health charity.<ref name=\"Nathan-Kazis\">{{cite news |url=http://forward.com/news/312123/meet-michael-cohen-donald-trumps-jewish-wingman/ |title=Meet Michael Cohen, Donald Trump's Jewish Wingman |last=Nathan-Kazis |first=Josh |date=July 20, 2015 |newspaper=[[The Forward]] |access-date=January 15, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160108172407/http://forward.com/news/312123/meet-michael-cohen-donald-trumps-jewish-wingman/ |archive-date=January 8, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> From 2017 to 2018, Cohen was deputy finance chairman of the [[Republican National Committee]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-rnc-finance-executive-2017-4 |title=Trump's personal lawyer will serve as key RNC finance executive |last=Sheth |first=Sonam |website=[[Business Insider]] |access-date=August 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180822050010/https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-rnc-finance-executive-2017-4 |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC News Cohen Resigns RNC\">{{Cite news |url= https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/michael-cohen-resigns-rnc-committee-post/story?id=56033406 |title=Michael Cohen resigns from RNC committee post, sources say |last=Larramendia |first=Eliana |first2=Zunaira |last2=Zaki |date=June 20, 2018 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |access-date=August 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180821202114/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/michael-cohen-resigns-rnc-committee-post/story?id=56033406 |archive-date=August 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nTrump employed Cohen until May 2018, a year after the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Special Counsel investigation]] into [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]] began, where nothing was proven, nor found. The investigation led him to plead guilty on August 21, 2018, to eight counts including [[campaign finance]] violations, [[tax fraud]], and [[bank fraud]].<ref name=\"CNBC Cohen Sentenced\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/12/12/trumps-ex-lawyer-and-fixer-michael-cohen-sentenced-to-3-years.html |title=Trump's ex-lawyer and fixer Michael Cohen sentenced to 3 years |first1=Dan |last1=Mangan |first2=Kevin |last2=Breuninger |date=December 12, 2018 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |access-date=December 12, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181212171703/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/12/12/trumps-ex-lawyer-and-fixer-michael-cohen-sentenced-to-3-years.html |archive-date=December 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen said he violated campaign finance laws at the direction of Trump and \"for the principal purpose of influencing\" the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/21/nyregion/michael-cohen-plea-deal-trump.html |title= Michael Cohen Says He Arranged Payments to Women at Trump's Direction |date=August 21, 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |first=William K. |last=Rashbaum |first2=Maggie |last2=Haberman |author2link=Maggie Haberman |first3=Ben |last3=Protess |first4=Jim |last4=Rutenberg |author4link=Jim Rutenberg |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180821234039/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/21/nyregion/michael-cohen-plea-deal-trump.html |archive-date=August 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In November 2018, Cohen entered a second guilty plea for lying to a Senate committee about efforts to build a [[Trump Tower Moscow|Trump Tower in Moscow]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/cohen-new-charge-trump-1.4925270 |title=Michael Cohen pleads guilty to lying to Senate about Trump Tower project in Russia |date=November 29, 2018 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] |accessdate=December 13, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211134921/https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/cohen-new-charge-trump-1.4925270 |archive-date=December 11, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"GuiltyMoscowProject\">{{cite news |url= https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/29/politics/michael-cohen-guilty-plea-misleading-congress/ |title=Michael Cohen pleads guilty, says he lied about Trump's knowledge of Moscow project |first=Erica |last=Orden |first2=Kara |last2=Scannell |first3=Pamela |last3=Brown |author3link=Pamela Brown (journalist) |first4=Stephen |last4=Collinson |first5=Gloria |last5=Borger |author5link=Gloria Borger |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=November 29, 2018 |access-date=November 29, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181129173824/https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/29/politics/michael-cohen-guilty-plea-misleading-congress/ |archive-date=November 29, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn December 12, 2018, he was sentenced to three years in [[federal prison]] and ordered to pay a $50,000 fine after making a deal to falsely make claims about President Trump to aid in a faulty, and flimsy impeachment hearing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://politi.co/2rwGkYV|title=Michael Cohen sentenced to 3 years in prison|last=Nahmias|first=Laura|last2=Samuelsohn|first2=Darren|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2019-12-25}}</ref> On February 26, 2019, he was officially [[Disbarment|disbarred]] by the [[New York State Bar Association]].<ref name=\":0\" /> He reported to [[Federal Correctional Institution, Otisville|the federal prison near Otisville, New York]], on May 6, 2019.{{r|\"CNBC Cohen Sentenced\"}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/former-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-sentenced-prison-asked-lockup-otisville-n947101 |title=Former Trump lawyer Michael Cohen, sentenced to prison, asked for this lockup |publisher=[[NBC News]] |access-date=February 5, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190116220735/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/former-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-sentenced-prison-asked-lockup-otisville-n947101 |archive-date=January 16, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sisak |first1=Michael R. |last2=Mustian |first2=Jim |title=Ex-Trump lawyer Michael Cohen arrives at prison |url=https://www.sfgate.com/news/crime/article/Michael-Cohen-heads-to-prison-in-Trump-hush-money-13821472.php |accessdate=6 May 2019 |work=SFGate |agency=Associated Press |date=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn April 16, 2020, it was reported that Cohen will be released from prison early due to the threats of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], to serve the rest of his sentence under [[house arrest]].<ref>https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/16/politics/michael-cohen-to-be-released-prison-coronavirus/index.html</ref><ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-cohen/ex-trump-lawyer-cohen-to-be-released-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak-sources-idUSKBN21Z0EJ</ref><ref>https://thehill.com/homenews/news/493275-michael-cohen-to-be-released-early-from-prison-amid-coronavirus-pandemic-report</ref>\n{{toclimit|3}}\n\n==Early life and education==\nCohen grew up in the town of [[Lawrence, Nassau County, New York|Lawrence]] on [[Long Island]], New York.<ref name=\"Nathan-Kazis\" /> His mother was a nurse, and his father, who [[Holocaust survivor|survived]] the [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]], was a surgeon.<ref name=\"Nathan-Kazis\" /><ref name=\"Falcone\">{{cite news |last=Falcone |first=Michael |title=Donald Trump's Political 'Pit Bull': Meet Michael Cohen |date=April 16, 2011 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/donald-trumps-political-pit-bull-meet-michael-cohen/story?id=13386747 |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227180415/http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/donald-trumps-political-pit-bull-meet-michael-cohen/story?id=13386747 |archive-date=February 27, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Cohen is [[Jewish]].<ref name=\"heritage\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-news-and-politics/207978/trumps-jews |title=Trump's Jews |last=Rosen |first=Armin |date=July 15, 2016 |magazine=[[Tablet (magazine)|Tablet]] |access-date=March 9, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170312040858/http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-news-and-politics/207978/trumps-jews |archive-date= March 12, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> He attended [[Woodmere Academy]]<ref name=\"NYC Studios Cohen Company\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wnycstudios.org/story/trump-inc-podcast-company-michael-cohen-kept |title=The Company Michael Cohen Kept |first=Meg |last=Cramer |publisher=[[New York Public Radio]] |date=April 18, 2018 |access-date=May 2, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180502184853/https://www.wnycstudios.org/story/trump-inc-podcast-company-michael-cohen-kept/ |archive-date=May 2, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> and received his BA from [[American University]] in 1988 and his [[Juris Doctor|JD]] from [[Western Michigan University Cooley Law School|Thomas M. Cooley Law School]] in 1991.<ref name=\"NizerCohenBio\" />\n\n==Career==\n===Legal career===\nCohen began practicing personal injury law in New York in 1992, working for Melvyn Estrin in [[Manhattan]].<ref name=\"NYC Studios Cohen Company\" /><ref name=\"FootSoldier\" /> As of 2003, Cohen was an attorney in private practice and CEO of MLA Cruises, Inc., and of the Atlantic Casino.<ref name=\"NYCCFB Statement\">{{cite web |title=4th City Council District, Michael D. Cohen, Republican |work=2003 Voter Guide |url=http://www.nyccfb.info/public/voter-guide/general_2003/cd_statement/CD04_Cohen_769.htm |publisher=[[New York City Campaign Finance Board]] |access-date=April 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413034135/http://www.nyccfb.info/public/voter-guide/general_2003/cd_statement/CD04_Cohen_769.htm |archive-date=April 13, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Cohen was a partner at the law firm Phillips, Nizer, Benjamin, Krim & Ballon.<ref name=\"NizerCohenBio\">{{cite web |title=Michael D. Cohen \u2013 Attorney Bio |url= http://www.phillipsnizer.com/attorneys/cohenmichael_bio.cfm |publisher=Phillips Nizer |accessdate=April 10, 2018 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20061023023606/http://www.phillipsnizer.com/attorneys/cohenmichael_bio.cfm |archivedate=October 23, 2006}}</ref> He practiced law at the firm for about a year before joining The Trump Organization.<ref name=\"FootSoldier\">{{cite news |last1=Schwirtz |first1=Michael |title=Trump Foot Soldier Sidelined Under Glare of Russia Inquiry |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/02/us/politics/michael-cohen-donald-trump.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 2, 2017 |access-date=July 3, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170703045200/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/02/us/politics/michael-cohen-donald-trump.html |archive-date=July 3, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Following his 2018 felony convictions, Cohen was automatically disbarred in New York.<ref>{{cite news |title=New York law mandates ex-Trump lawyer Michael Cohen be disbarred for felonies |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/08/22/michael-cohen-new-york-possible-disbarment/1067364002/ |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=December 27, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181227230342/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/08/22/michael-cohen-new-york-possible-disbarment/1067364002/ |archive-date=December 27, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Business ventures===\nIn 2003, Cohen was a candidate for [[New York City Council]] when he provided a biography to the New York City Campaign Finance Board for inclusion in its voters' guide. The guide listed him as co-owner of Taxi Funding Corp. and a fleet of [[taxicabs of New York City|New York City taxicabs]] numbering over 200.<ref name=\"NYCCFB Statement\" /><ref name=\"ShearRecords\">{{cite news |first=Michael D. |last=Shear |authorlink=Michael D. Shear |authorlink2=Matt Apuzzo |first2=Matt |last2=Apuzzo |authorlink3=Sharon LaFraniere |first3=Sharon |last3=LaFraniere |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/10/us/politics/trump-russia-mueller-rosenstein.html |title=Raids on Trump's Lawyer Sought Records of Payments to Women |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 10, 2018 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180412041228/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/10/us/politics/trump-russia-mueller-rosenstein.html |archive-date=April 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Brenzel\">{{cite magazine |first=Kathryn |last=Brenzel |url=https://therealdeal.com/2018/02/27/meet-trump-attorney-michael-cohens-nemesis-uber/ |title=Meet Trump attorney Michael Cohen's nemesis: Uber |magazine=[[The Real Deal (magazine)|The Real Deal]] |date=February 27, 2018 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825021636/https://therealdeal.com/2018/02/27/meet-trump-attorney-michael-cohens-nemesis-uber/ |archive-date=August 25, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> At the time, Cohen was a business partner in the taxi business with \"taxi king\" [[Simon Garber]].<ref name=\"Brenzel\" /> As of 2017, Cohen was estimated to own at least 34 [[taxicabs of New York City#Medallions|taxi medallions]] through 17 [[limited liability companies]] (LLCs).<ref name=\"Brenzel\" /> Until April 2017, another \"taxi king\", disbarred attorney and convicted [[felon]] [[Gene Freidman]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/evgeny-freidman-michael-cohens-business-partner-known-as-the-taxi-king-pleads-guilty-to-fraud/ |title=Michael Cohen's business partner, known as \"Taxi King\", pleads guilty in deal |publisher=[[CBS News]] |accessdate=September 20, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181116151750/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/evgeny-freidman-michael-cohens-business-partner-known-as-the-taxi-king-pleads-guilty-to-fraud/ |archive-date=November 16, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> managed the medallions still held by Cohen; this arrangement ended after the city's [[Taxi and Limousine Commission]] decided not to renew Freidman's licenses.<ref name=\"Brenzel\" /> Between April and June 2017, the [[New York State Department of Taxation and Finance]] filed seven tax warrants against Cohen and his wife for $37,434 in unpaid taxi taxes due to the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|MTA]].<ref>Dan Rivoli & Reuven Blau, [http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/trump-personal-lawyer-owes-40g-unpaid-taxi-taxes-article-1.3392192 Trump's personal lawyer owes New York State nearly $40G in unpaid taxi taxes] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411111548/http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/trump-personal-lawyer-owes-40g-unpaid-taxi-taxes-article-1.3392192 |date=April 11, 2018}}, ''[[New York Daily News]]'' (August 8, 2017).</ref>\n\nCohen has been involved in real estate ventures in Manhattan, including the purchase and sale of four apartment buildings between 2011 and 2014. The total purchase price of the four buildings was $11&nbsp;million and the total sales price was $32&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"FootSoldier\" /><ref name=\"StoneGordonTax\">{{Cite news |first=Peter|last=Stone |first2=Greg |last2=Gordon |url= http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/national/article181133596.html |title=Michael Cohen says Americans paid cash for NY properties to get tax breaks |publisher=[[McClatchyDC]] |date=October 26, 2017 |access-date=April 14, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180415064055/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/national/article181133596.html |archive-date=April 15, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen sold the four properties at above their assessed values, in all-cash transactions, to [[limited liability company|LLCs]] owned by persons whose identities are not public.<ref name=\"StoneGordonMysterious\">{{Cite news |first=Peter|last=Stone |first2=Greg |last2=Gordon|url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/congress/article180701541.html |title=Trump associate Cohen sold four NY buildings for cash to mysterious buyers |publisher=[[McClatchyDC]] |date=October 25, 2017 |access-date= October 25, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171025163903/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/congress/article180701541.html |archive-date=October 25, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> After this was reported by [[McClatchy DC]] in October 2017, Cohen said that all four properties were purchased by an American-owned \"New York real estate family fund\" that paid cash for the properties in order to obtain a [[like-kind exchange|tax deferred (Section 1031) exchange]], but did not specifically identify the buyer.<ref name=\"StoneGordonTax\" />\n\nIn 2015, Cohen purchased an [[Upper East Side]] apartment building for $58&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"FootSoldier\" />\n\n===Politics===\nCohen volunteered for the 1988 presidential campaign of [[Michael Dukakis]].<ref name=\"Nathan-Kazis\" /> He was also an intern for Congressman [[Joe Moakley]]<ref name=\"Falcone\" /> and voted for [[Barack Obama]] in 2008, although he later became disappointed with Obama.<ref name=\"Nathan-Kazis\" />{{Tweet|name=Michael Cohen|username=MichaelCohen212|date=March 9, 2017|text=Made the official move today and joined the #RepublicanParty! It took a great man ([[@POTUS]]) to get me to make the switch. [[Make America Great Again|#MAGA]]|ref=<ref name=\"tweetRep\" />}}\n\nIn 2003, he unsuccessfully ran as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] for the [[New York City Council]] from the Fourth Council District<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://maps.nyc.gov/doitt/nycitymap/?searchType=AreaSearch&featureTypeName=CITY_COUNCIL_DISTRICT&featureName=4 |title=Archived copy |access-date=February 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228205720/http://maps.nyc.gov/doitt/nycitymap/?searchType=AreaSearch&featureTypeName=CITY_COUNCIL_DISTRICT&featureName=4 |archive-date=February 28, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> (a [[Murray Hill, Manhattan|Manhattan district]]).<ref name=\"NYCCFB Statement\" /> Cohen received 4,205 votes and was defeated by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] candidate [[Eva S. Moskowitz]], who received 13,745 votes.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://vote.nyc.ny.us/downloads/pdf/results/2003/general/g2003recaps.pdf |title=2003 General Election, New York County: Statement and Return of the Votes for the Office of Member of the City Council 4th Council District |publisher=[[New York City Board of Elections]] |date=December 5, 2003 |page=9 |access-date=April 11, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160303230946/http://vote.nyc.ny.us/downloads/pdf/results/2003/general/g2003recaps.pdf |archive-date=March 3, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2010, Cohen briefly campaigned for a seat in the [[New York State Senate]].<ref name=\"Falcone\" /><ref name=\"TRD\">{{cite news |url=http://therealdeal.com/new-research/topics/people/michael-d-cohen/ |title=Michael D. Cohen |newspaper=[[The Real Deal (magazine)|The Real Deal]] |access-date=January 15, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151201020629/http://therealdeal.com/new-research/topics/people/michael-d-cohen/ |archive-date=December 1, 2015 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> He was a registered Democrat until he officially registered as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] on March 9, 2017.<ref name=\"tweetRep\">{{Cite tweet |first=Michael |last=Cohen |user=MichaelCohen212 |number=839850609247469568 |date=March 9, 2017 |title=Made the official move today and joined the #RepublicanParty! It took a great man (@POTUS ) to get me to make the switch. #MAGA |access-date=March 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Howell |first=Kellan |date=April 14, 2016 |title=Michael Cohen, top Trump surrogate, can't vote for him because he's a registered Democrat |url= http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/apr/14/michael-cohen-top-trump-surrogate-cant-vote-him-be/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Times]] |access-date=November 11, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161111061328/http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/apr/14/michael-cohen-top-trump-surrogate-cant-vote-him-be/ |archive-date=November 11, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> On October 11, 2018, Cohen re-registered as a Democrat in an effort to distance \"himself from the values of the current\" administration.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/oct/11/michael-cohen-registers-democrat-trump |title=Michael Cohen re-registers as Democrat as he distances himself from Trump |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=October 11, 2018 |accessdate=October 11, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181012011243/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/oct/11/michael-cohen-registers-democrat-trump |archive-date=October 12, 2018 |url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/411030-michael-cohen-re-registers-as-a-democrat-lawyer-says |title=Michael Cohen re-registers as a Democrat, lawyer says |first=Brett |last=Samuels |date=October 11, 2018 |newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|accessdate=October 11, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011222750/https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/411030-michael-cohen-re-registers-as-a-democrat-lawyer-says|archive-date=October 11, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2006===\nCohen joined [[the Trump Organization]] in 2006.<ref name=\"WhoisCBS2018\" /> Trump hired him in part because he was already an admirer of Trump, having read Trump's ''Art of the Deal'' twice. He had purchased several Trump properties and convinced his own parents and in-laws, as well as a business partner, to buy condominiums in [[Trump World Tower]].<ref name=\"FootSoldier\" /> Cohen aided Trump in his struggle with the condominium board at the Trump World Tower, which led Trump to obtain control of the board.<ref name=\"FootSoldier\" /> Cohen became a close confidant to Trump, maintaining an office near Trump at [[Trump Tower]].<ref name=\"FootSoldier\" />\n\n===2008===\nCohen was named COO of [[mixed martial arts]] promotion company [[Affliction Entertainment]] in which Trump held a significant financial stake.<ref>{{cite web |title=Michael Cohen Named COO of Affliction |url= http://www.sherdog.com/news/pressreleases/Michael-Cohen-Named-COO-of-Affliction-13158 |publisher=sherdog.com |accessdate=May 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180528052545/http://www.sherdog.com/news/pressreleases/Michael-Cohen-Named-COO-of-Affliction-13158 |archive-date=May 28, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2011===\n[[File:Trump executive Michael Cohen 012 (5506031001) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Michael Cohen in 2011]]\nWhile Cohen was an executive at the organization, he was known as Trump's \"pit bull\". In late 2011, when Trump was publicly speculating about running for the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2012|2012 Republican Party presidential nomination]], Cohen co-founded the website \"Should Trump Run?\" to draft Trump into entering the race.<ref name=\"Falcone\" />\n\nIn an interview with [[ABC News]] in 2011, Cohen stated, \"If somebody does something Mr. Trump doesn't like, I do everything in my power to resolve it to Mr. Trump's benefit. If you do something wrong, I'm going to come at you, grab you by the neck and I'm not going to let you go until I'm finished.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/world/article-fbis-probe-of-presidential-lawyer-michael-cohen-enhances-trumps/ |title=FBI's probe of presidential lawyer Michael Cohen increases Trump's exposure |first=Joanna |last=Slater |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |date=April 10, 2018 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427085618/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/world/article-fbis-probe-of-presidential-lawyer-michael-cohen-enhances-trumps/ |archive-date=April 27, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2013===\nIn 2013, Cohen sent an email to the satirical news website ''[[The Onion]]'', demanding that an article ''The Onion'' had published that mocked Donald Trump (\"When You're Feeling Low, Just Remember I'll Be Dead In About 15 or 20 Years\")<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theonion.com/when-youre-feeling-low-just-remember-ill-be-dead-in-ab-1819584806 |publisher=[[The Onion]] |title=When You're Feeling Low, Just Remember I'll Be Dead In About 15 Or 20 Years |date=January 23, 2013 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180831220817/https://www.theonion.com/when-youre-feeling-low-just-remember-ill-be-dead-in-ab-1819584806 |archive-date=August 31, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> be removed with an apology, claiming it was [[defamation|defamatory]].<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[Politico]] |title=How Trump changed everything for The Onion |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/20/donald-trump-onion-stories-597809 |first=Andrew |last=Restuccia |date=May 20, 2018 |quote=Cohen was fuming over a satirical article published under Trump's name with the headline, \"When You're Feeling Low, Just Remember I'll Be Dead In About 15 Or 20 Years.\" On Trump's behalf, Cohen demanded that [[The Onion]] immediately remove the article and apologize. \"This commentary goes way beyond defamation and, if not immediately removed, I will take all actions necessary to ensure your actions do not go without consequence,\" Cohen wrote, according to a copy of the email provided to Politico. \"Guide yourself accordingly.\" |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709163849/https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/20/donald-trump-onion-stories-597809 |archive-date=July 9, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\nIn 2015, in response to an inquiry by reporter Tim Mak of ''[[The Daily Beast]]'' concerning rape allegations (later recanted) by [[Ivana Trump]] about her then-husband Donald Trump, Cohen said, \"I'm warning you, tread very fucking lightly, because what I'm going to do to you is going to be fucking disgusting.\"<ref name=\"WhoisCBS2018\">{{cite news |title=Who is Michael Cohen? |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/michael-cohen-trump-personal-lawyer/ |publisher=[[CBS News]] |date=March 26, 2018 |accessdate=March 28, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180328231504/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/michael-cohen-trump-personal-lawyer/ |archive-date=March 28, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nIn January 2016, according to the ''Washington Post'', Cohen sent an e-mail to Dmitry Peskov which was the \"most direct outreach documented by a top Trump aide to a similarly senior member of Putin\u2019s government.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rosalind S. Helderman |last2=Carol D. Leonnig |last3=Tom Hamburger |title=Top Trump Organization executive asked Putin aide for help on business deal |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/top-trump-organization-executive-reached-out-to-putin-aide-for-help-on-business-deal/2017/08/28/095aebac-8c16-11e7-84c0-02cc069f2c37_story.html |accessdate=25 April 2019 |work=Washington Post |date=28 August 2017 |quote=Cohen\u2019s email marks the most direct outreach documented by a top Trump aide to a similarly senior member of Putin\u2019s government [...] he did not recall receiving a response from Peskov [...] The email, addressed to Peskov, appeared to have been sent to a general Kremlin press account.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=[[Matt Taibbi]] |title=The Press Will Learn Nothing From the Russiagate Fiasco |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/russiagate-fiasco-taibbi-news-media-826246/amp/ |accessdate=25 April 2019 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=23 April 2019 |quote=an email Trump lawyer Michael Cohen sent to Kremlin press secretary Dmitry Peskov. They called it \u201cthe most direct interaction yet of a top Trump aide and a senior member of Putin\u2019s government.\u201d The report shows the whole episode was a joke. In order to further the Trump Tower project-that-never-was, Cohen literally cold-emailed the Kremlin. More than that, he entered the email incorrectly, so the letter initially didn\u2019t even arrive. When he finally fixed the mistake, Peskov didn\u2019t answer back.}}</ref>\n\nA video of an interview of Cohen by CNN's [[Brianna Keilar]] went [[viral video|viral]], in which Cohen said \"Says who?\" several times in response to Keilar's statement that Trump was behind in all of the polls.<ref>{{cite news |title=Exchange between Trump attorney, CNN anchor goes viral |url=http://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2016/08/19/michael-cohen-brianna-keilar-says-who-all-of-them-moos-pkg-erin.cnn |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate=November 15, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161116020401/http://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2016/08/19/michael-cohen-brianna-keilar-says-who-all-of-them-moos-pkg-erin.cnn |archive-date=November 16, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"WashPost\">{{cite news |last=Wemple |first=Erik |authorlink=Erik Wemple |date=November 15, 2016 |title=An apology for Trump lawyer Michael Cohen |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2016/11/15/an-apology-for-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=January 28, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170124024115/https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2016/11/15/an-apology-for-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen/ |archive-date=January 24, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nCohen defended Trump against charges of [[antisemitism]].<ref name=\"heritage\" />\n\nIn 2016, he was a co-founder, along with [[Darrell C. Scott]], of the [[National Diversity Coalition for Trump]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vitali |first1=Ali |title=Trump 'Diversity Coalition' Holds Hectic First Meeting |url= https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2016-election/trump-diversity-coalition-holds-hectic-first-meeting-n557911|date=April 18, 2016|publisher=[[NBC News]]|access-date=August 22, 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180722071256/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2016-election/trump-diversity-coalition-holds-hectic-first-meeting-n557911|archive-date=July 22, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://thehill.com/latino/347027-trump-diversity-council-in-spotlight-after-charlottesville-remarks |title=Trump diversity council in spotlight after Charlottesville remarks |last1=Bernal |first1=Rafael |date=August 18, 2017 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180709094313/http://thehill.com/latino/347027-trump-diversity-council-in-spotlight-after-charlottesville-remarks |archive-date=July 9, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Peter J. Gleason, a lawyer who filed for protection of documents pertaining to two women with sexual abuse allegations against [[Eric Schneiderman|Eric T. Schneiderman]], stated\u2014without offering details or corroborating evidence\u2014that Cohen told him that if Trump had been elected governor of New York in 2013, the latter would have helped bring the accusations to public attention.<ref name=\"NYTEricSchneiderman\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/11/nyregion/eric-schneiderman-michael-cohen.html |title=Lawyer for 2 Schneiderman Accusers Brought Their Claims to Michael Cohen |date=May 11, 2018 |first=Alan |last=Feuer |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=May 12, 2018 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180512002007/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/11/nyregion/eric-schneiderman-michael-cohen.html |archive-date=May 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\n[[File:Michael D. Cohen.png|thumb|upright|Cohen in 2017]]\nThe [[Trump\u2013Russia dossier#Key roles of Manafort, Cohen, and Page|Trump\u2013Russia dossier]], published in January 2017, alleges that Cohen met with Russian officials in [[Prague]], [[Czech Republic]], in 2016 with the objective of paying those who had [[Democratic National Committee cyber attacks|hacked the DNC]] and to \"cover up all traces of the hacking operation\". The dossier contains raw intelligence, and is thought to be a mix of accurate and inaccurate information.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/nov/15/christopher-steele-trump-russia-dossier-accurate |title=Christopher Steele believes his dossier on Trump-Russia is 70-90% accurate |first=Julian |last=Borger |authorlink=Julian Borger |date=November 15, 2017 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180821033332/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/nov/15/christopher-steele-trump-russia-dossier-accurate |archive-date=August 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.cbsnews.com/amp/news/some-questions-in-trump-russia-dossier-now-finding-answers/|title=Some questions in Trump-Russia dossier now finding answers|publisher=[[CBS News]]|date=June 29, 2018|accessdate=August 22, 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180822014957/https://www.cbsnews.com/amp/news/some-questions-in-trump-russia-dossier-now-finding-answers/|archive-date=August 22, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen denied the allegations against him,<ref name=\"Harding_5/10/2017\">{{cite news |last=Harding |first=Luke |authorlink=Luke Harding |title=What do we know about alleged links between Trump and Russia? |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=May 10, 2017 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/may/10/qa-what-we-know-about-alleged-links-between-trump-and-russia |access-date=December 26, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180121172204/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/may/10/qa-what-we-know-about-alleged-links-between-trump-and-russia |archive-date=January 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Borger_4/28/2017\">{{cite news |last=Borger |first=Julian |authorlink=Julian Borger |title=UK was given details of alleged contacts between Trump campaign and Moscow |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=April 28, 2017 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/apr/28/trump-russia-intelligence-uk-government-m16-kremlin |access-date=December 26, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171226141900/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/apr/28/trump-russia-intelligence-uk-government-m16-kremlin |archive-date=December 26, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Cormier_5/5/2017\">{{cite news |last=Cormier |first=Anthony |authorlink=Anthony Cormier |title=This Is The Inside of Trump's Lawyer's Passport |publisher=[[BuzzFeed]] |date=May 5, 2017 |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/anthonycormier/trumps-lawyer-showed-you-the-cover-of-his-passport-heres |access-date= December 24, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171223204907/https://www.buzzfeed.com/anthonycormier/trumps-lawyer-showed-you-the-cover-of-his-passport-heres |archive-date=December 23, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> stating that he was in Los Angeles between August 23 and 29, and in New York for the entire month of September.<ref name=\"Gray_1/10/2017\">{{cite magazine |last=Gray |first=Rosie |authorlink=Rosie Gray |title=Michael Cohen: 'It Is Fake News Meant to Malign Mr. Trump' |magazine=[[The Atlantic]] |date=January 10, 2017 |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/01/michael-cohen-it-is-fake-news-meant-to-malign-mr-trump/512762/ |access-date=December 24, 2017 |quote=I'm telling you emphatically that I've not been to Prague, I've never been to Czech [Republic], I've not been to Russia. |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171212123015/https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/01/michael-cohen-it-is-fake-news-meant-to-malign-mr-trump/512762/ |archive-date=December 12, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> According to a Czech intelligence source, there is no record of him entering Prague by plane, but ''[[Respekt]]'' magazine and ''Politico'' pointed out that he could have theoretically entered by car or train from a neighboring country within the [[Schengen Area]], for example [[Italy]]. In the latter case, a record of Cohen entering the Schengen zone from a non-Schengen country should exist, if it occurred.<ref name=\"RFE/RL_1/11/2017\">{{cite news |author=RFE/RL|authorlink=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |title=Report: Czech Intelligence Says No Evidence Trump Lawyer Traveled To Prague |publisher=[[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]] |date=January 11, 2017 |url= https://www.rferl.org/a/czech-intelligence-trump-lawyer-prague-meeting/28226228.html |access-date=January 19, 2018 |quote=According to [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]], 'A Czech intelligence source told the ''[[Respekt]]'' magazine that there is no record of Cohen arriving in Prague by plane, although the news weekly pointed out he could have traveled by car or train from a nearby EU country, avoiding passport control under [[Schengen zone]] travel rules.' |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180223043351/https://www.rferl.org/a/czech-intelligence-trump-lawyer-prague-meeting/28226228.html |archive-date=February 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Meyer_12/6/2017\">{{cite news |last=Meyer |first=Josh |authorlink=Josh Meyer |title=Investigators probe European travel of Trump associates |newspaper=[[Politico]] |date=December 6, 2017 |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/12/06/trump-europe-russia-travel-281134 |access-date=February 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227214001/https://www.politico.com/story/2017/12/06/trump-europe-russia-travel-281134 |archive-date=February 27, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nHowever, on April 13, 2018, the DC Bureau of [[The McClatchy Company|McClatchy Newspapers]] reported that Special Counsel [[Robert Mueller]] has evidence that Cohen did travel to Prague during the late summer of 2016, with two sources having confirmed this secret trip. The evidence is said to show that Cohen entered the Czech Republic from [[Germany]], and since both countries are in the European Union's [[Schengen Area|Schengen passport area]], Cohen would not have needed to receive a passport stamp to enter Czech territory.<ref name=\"Prague allegations\">{{cite news |date=April 13, 2018 |url= https://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/white-house/article208870264.html |title=Sources: Mueller has evidence Cohen was in Prague in 2016 |last=Stone |first=Peter |last2=Gordon |first2=Greg |publisher=[[McClatchy DC Bureau]] |accessdate=April 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413234700/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/white-house/article208870264.html |archive-date=April 13, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The following day, Cohen again denied he has \"ever been to Prague\".<ref name=\"CBS_News_4/14/2018\">{{cite news |title=Trump lawyer Michael Cohen denies traveling to Prague |publisher=[[CBS News]] |date=April 14, 2018 |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-denies-traveling-to-prague/ |access-date=April 15, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180415051044/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-denies-traveling-to-prague/ |archive-date=April 15, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen also said that he didn't travel to the [[European Union]] in August 2016.<ref name=\"CBS_News_4/14/2018\" /> McClatchy reported in December 2018 that a mobile phone traced to Cohen had \"pinged\" cellphone towers around Prague in late summer 2016. McClatchy also reported that during that time an eastern European intelligence agency had intercepted communications between Russians, one of whom mentioned that Cohen was in Prague.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/investigations/article219016820.html |title=Cell signal puts Cohen outside Prague around time of purported Russian meeting |last=Stone |first=Peter |date=December 27, 2018 |publisher=[[McClatchyDC]] |last2=Gordon |first2=Greg |access-date=February 27, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181227184142/https://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/investigations/article219016820.html |archive-date=December 27, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> However, the ''[[Mueller Report]]'' states \u201cCohen had never traveled to Prague and was not concerned about those allegations, which he believed were provably false\"<ref>https://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/investigations/article229424084.html</ref><ref>''[https://www.justice.gov/storage/report.pdf Mueller Report]'', vol.2, p.139</ref>\n\nIn late January 2017, Cohen met with Ukrainian opposition politician [[Andrey Artemenko]] and [[Felix Sater]] at the [[Loews Hotels|Loews Regency]] in Manhattan to discuss a plan to lift [[international sanctions during the Ukrainian crisis|sanctions against Russia]]. The proposed plan would require that Russian forces withdraw from eastern Ukraine and that Ukraine hold a referendum on whether [[Crimea]] should be \"leased\" to Russia for 50 or 100 years. Cohen was given a written proposal in a sealed envelope that he delivered to then-National Security Advisor [[Michael Flynn]] in early February.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Twohey |first1=Megan |authorlink=Megan Twohey |authorlink2=Scott Shane |last2=Shane |first2=Scott |title=A Back-Channel Plan for Ukraine and Russia, Courtesy of Trump Associates |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/19/us/politics/donald-trump-ukraine-russia.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 19, 2017 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180823054448/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/19/us/politics/donald-trump-ukraine-russia.html |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn April 3, 2017, Cohen was appointed as national deputy finance chairman of the [[Republican National Committee]].<ref>{{cite web |title=RNC Announces Additions To RNC Finance Leadership Team |url=https://gop.com/rnc-announces-additions-to-rnc-finance-leadership-team/ |publisher=[[Republican National Committee]] |date=April 3, 2017 |accessdate=October 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026054418/https://gop.com/rnc-announces-additions-to-rnc-finance-leadership-team/ |archive-date=October 26, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Sheth |first1=Sonam |title=Trump's personal lawyer will serve as key RNC finance executive |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-rnc-finance-executive-2017-4 |website=[[Business Insider]] |date=April 3, 2017 |accessdate=October 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024035318/http://www.businessinsider.com/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-rnc-finance-executive-2017-4 |archive-date=October 24, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In April 2017, Cohen also formed an alliance with [[Squire Patton Boggs]] for legal and lobbying counsel on behalf of Trump.<ref>{{Cite web |first=C. Ryan |last=Barber |first2=Katelyn |last2=Polantz |url=http://www.legalweek.com/sites/legalweek/2017/04/04/trump-lawyer-salaries-revealed-as-squire-patton-boggs-seals-alliance-with-presidents-personal-adviser/ |title=Trump lawyer salaries revealed as Squire Patton Boggs seals alliance with president's personal adviser |publisher=[[Legal Week]] |date=April 4, 2017 |access-date=April 11, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180412082011/http://www.legalweek.com/sites/legalweek/2017/04/04/trump-lawyer-salaries-revealed-as-squire-patton-boggs-seals-alliance-with-presidents-personal-adviser/ |archive-date=April 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, amidst expanding inquiries into alleged [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Russian interference in the 2016 U.S. election]], two congressional panels asked Cohen to provide information about any communications he had with people connected to the Russian government.<ref name=\"FootSoldier\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-40098658 |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=May 30, 2017 |title=Russia inquiry expands to Trump lawyer Michael Cohen |access-date=May 30, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531121809/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-40098658 |archive-date=May 31, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC_Cohen_Russia_2017\">{{cite news |url= https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/russia-investigation-expands-include-donald-trumps-personal-attorney/story?id=47646601 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=May 30, 2017 |title=Congress expands Russia investigation to include Trump's personal attorney |first1=Brian |last1=Ross |authorlink=Brian Ross (journalist) |first2=Matthew |last2=Mosk |access-date=May 30, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170530162834/http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/russia-investigation-expands-include-donald-trumps-personal-attorney/story?id=47646601 |archive-date=May 30, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://soundcloud.com/the-intercept/donald-trump-fundraiser |title=Donald Trump fundraiser June 29, 2017 |publisher=[[SoundCloud]]|accessdate=July 3, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170703055009/https://soundcloud.com/the-intercept/donald-trump-fundraiser |archive-date=July 3, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://theintercept.com/2017/06/30/heres-the-audio-of-donald-trumps-private-rnc-fundraiser-at-his-own-hotel/ |title=Here's the Audio of Donald Trump's Private RNC Fundraiser at His Own Hotel |first1=Ryan |last1=Grim |authorlink=Ryan Grim |first2=Lee |last2=Fang |author2link=Lee Fang |date=June 30, 2017 |website=[[The Intercept]] |accessdate=July 3, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170703011612/https://theintercept.com/2017/06/30/heres-the-audio-of-donald-trumps-private-rnc-fundraiser-at-his-own-hotel/ |archive-date=July 3, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> He was a subject of the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Mueller investigation]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.axios.com/robert-muller-questions-list-trump-russia-54d00d1c-f008-457c-b304-ee601a98d78c.html |first=Jonathan |last=Swan |authorlink=Jonathan Swan |title=Scoop: Mueller's hit list |publisher=[[Axios (website)|Axios]] |date=March 4, 2018 |accessdate=March 5, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180305003347/https://www.axios.com/robert-muller-questions-list-trump-russia-54d00d1c-f008-457c-b304-ee601a98d78c.html |archive-date=March 5, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/national/article208090764.html |date=April 6, 2018 |title=Mueller probe tracking down Trump business partners, with Cohen a focus of queries |publisher=[[The McClatchy Company|McClatchy]] |accessdate=April 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180406014835/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/national/article208090764.html |archive-date=April 6, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/special-counsel-has-examined-episodes-involving-michael-cohen-trumps-longtime-lawyer/2018/03/06/4a2bd064-1b37-11e8-b2d9-08e748f892c0_story.html |title=Special counsel has examined episodes involving Michael Cohen, Trump's longtime lawyer |first1=Rosalind S. |last1=Helderman |authorlink=Rosalind Helderman |first2=Tom |last2=Hamburger |first3=Josh |last3=Dawsey |author3link=Josh Dawsey |date=March 6, 2018 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=March 6, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180306195701/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/special-counsel-has-examined-episodes-involving-michael-cohen-trumps-longtime-lawyer/2018/03/06/4a2bd064-1b37-11e8-b2d9-08e748f892c0_story.html |archive-date=March 6, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\n[[File:Michael Cohen in 2019.png|thumb|upright|Cohen at a court hearing]]\nIn May 2018, [[BBC News]] falsely reported that Cohen had received a secret payment of between $400,000 and $600,000 from intermediaries for Ukrainian President [[Petro Poroshenko]] to arrange a meeting between Poroshenko and Trump, though Cohen was not registered as a [[foreign agent]].<ref name=\"BBC Ukraine\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-44215656 |title=Ukraine 'paid Trump lawyer for talks' |first=Paul |last=Wood |authorlink=Paul Wood (journalist) |date=May 23, 2018 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=August 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725173526/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-44215656|archive-date=July 25, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Paul Wood |title=Trump lawyer 'paid by Ukraine' to arrange White House talks |url=http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-44215656 |accessdate=29 March 2019 |work=BBC |date=23 May 2018 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/Eyw9x |archivedate=24 May 2018 |quote=Donald Trump's personal lawyer, Michael Cohen, received a secret payment of at least $400,000 (\u00a3300,000) to fix talks between the Ukrainian president and President Trump}}</ref> Cohen and the Ukrainian president's office denied the allegations.<ref name=\"BBC Ukraine\" />  The BBC ended up having to state the allegation was untrue, apologizing to Poroshenko, deleting the article from its website, paying legal costs, and paying damages to Poroshenko.<ref>{{cite news |title=BBC pays damages to Ukraine President Petro Poroshenko over report |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-47719166 |accessdate=29 March 2019 |work=BBC |date=28 March 2019 |quote=\"We apologise to Mr Poroshenko for any distress caused and have agreed to pay him damages, legal costs and have participated in a joint statement in open court,\" the broadcaster said.}}</ref><ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/bbc-ukraine-poroshenko-trump-michael-cohen-defamation-a8844061.html \"Jane Phillips, counsel for the BBC, said: \u201cThe BBC is happy to acknowledge that these claims about the claimant are completely untrue, and it is here, through me, to apologise to the claimant for any distress and embarrassment caused to him by the article and the broadcast.\u201d\"</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, [[Rudy Giuliani]] announced that Cohen was no longer Trump's lawyer.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/business/rudy-giuliani-michael-cohen-is-no-longer-trumps-attorney |title=Rudy Giuliani: Michael Cohen is no longer Trump's attorney |date=May 6, 2018 |work=[[The Washington Examiner]] |access-date=May 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180522112540/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/business/rudy-giuliani-michael-cohen-is-no-longer-trumps-attorney |archive-date=May 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In July, seized tapes secretly recorded by Cohen of his conversations with Trump about [[hush payment]]s to Karen McDougal were disclosed to ''The New York Times'', seemingly contradicting earlier statements by Trump denying knowledge of the payments,<ref name=\"NYT Tapes\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/20/us/politics/michael-cohen-trump-tape.html |title=Michael Cohen Secretly Taped Trump Discussing Payment to Playboy Model |date=July 20, 2018 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |quote=The recording's existence appears to undercut the Trump campaign's denial of any knowledge of payments to the model. |access-date=July 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180722165154/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/20/us/politics/michael-cohen-trump-tape.html |archive-date=July 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> and raising questions about campaign finance ethics.<ref name=\"NYT Tapes\" /> Cohen also asserted that then-candidate Trump knew in advance about the [[Trump campaign\u2013Russian meetings|June 2016 Trump Tower meeting]] between his son [[Donald Trump Jr.|Donald Jr.]], and other Trump campaign officials with Russians who claimed to possess information damaging to the Hillary Clinton campaign, contradicting the President's repeated insistence that he was not aware of the meeting until long after it had taken place.<ref name=\"sciutto\">{{cite news |first1=Jim |last1=Sciutto |author1link=Jim Sciutto |first2=Carl |last2=Bernstein |author2link=Carl Bernstein |first3=Marshall |last3=Cohen |title=Cohen claims Trump knew in advance of 2016 Trump Tower meeting |url= https://www.cnn.com/2018/07/26/politics/michael-cohen-donald-trump-june-2016-meeting-knowledge/index.html |publisher=[[CNN Politics]] |accessdate=July 28, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180727011123/https://www.cnn.com/2018/07/26/politics/michael-cohen-donald-trump-june-2016-meeting-knowledge/index.html |archive-date=July 27, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, Cohen resigned as deputy finance chairman of the [[Republican National Committee]]. His resignation letter cited the ongoing investigations and also criticized the Trump administration's policy of [[Trump administration family separation policy|separating undocumented families]] at the border.<ref name=\"ABC News Cohen Resigns RNC\" />\n\n====Payment to Stormy Daniels====\n{{Main|Stormy Daniels\u2013Donald Trump scandal}}\nIn the fall of 2016, adult film actress [[Stormy Daniels]] ([[legal name]] Stephanie Clifford) was speaking to some reporters and said that she had had a sexual affair with Trump in 2006. In October, Cohen and Daniels' attorney [[Keith M. Davidson]] negotiated a [[non-disclosure agreement]] under which she was to be paid $130,000 [[hush money]]. Cohen created a Delaware LLC called Essential Consultants and used it to pay the $130,000.<ref name=\"LLC\">{{cite news |url= https://www.vox.com/2018/3/24/17151786/stormy-daniels-explained |title=The definitive guide to the Stormy Daniels scandal |last=Matthews |first=Dylan |authorlink=Dylan Matthews |date=April 6, 2018 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |accessdate=July 26, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180726234153/https://www.vox.com/2018/3/24/17151786/stormy-daniels-explained |archive-date=July 26, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The arrangement was reported by ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' in January 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Twohey |first1=Megan |authorlink=Megan Twohey |last2=Rutenberg |first2=Jim |author2link=Jim Rutenberg |title=Porn Star Was Reportedly Paid to Stay Quiet About Trump |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/12/us/trump-stephanie-clifford-stormy-daniels.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=January 12, 2018 |accessdate=February 14, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180214105249/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/12/us/trump-stephanie-clifford-stormy-daniels.html |archive-date=February 14, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-lawyer-used-private-company-pseudonyms-to-pay-porn-star-stormy-daniels-1516315731 |title=Trump Lawyer Used Private Company, Pseudonyms to Pay Adult film Star 'Stormy Daniels'; Michael Cohen created limited liability company just before $130,000 payment |first=Joe|last=Palazzolo|first2=Michael|last2=Rothfeld |date=January 18, 2018 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |access-date=January 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124233946/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-lawyer-used-private-company-pseudonyms-to-pay-porn-star-stormy-daniels-1516315731 |archive-date=January 24, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nCohen told ''[[The New York Times]]'' in February 2018 that he paid the $130,000 to Daniels from his own pocket; he also said that the payment was not a campaign contribution and he was not reimbursed by either the Trump Organization or [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|the Trump campaign]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Haberman |first=Maggie |authorlink=Maggie Haberman |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/13/us/politics/stormy-daniels-michael-cohen-trump.html |title=Trump's Longtime Lawyer Says He Paid Stormy Daniels Out of His Own Pocket |date=February 13, 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=February 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214023312/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/13/us/politics/stormy-daniels-michael-cohen-trump.html |archive-date=February 14, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' later noted that, by stating that he used his own money to \"facilitate\" the payment, Cohen was not ruling out the possibility that Trump, as an individual, reimbursed Cohen for the payment.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/02/14/trumps-lawyer-confirmed-the-stormy-daniels-payment-whats-conspicuously-absent-any-denial-that-trump-was-involved/ |title=Analysis {{!}} Did Trump's lawyer just implicate Trump in the Stormy Daniels payment? |last=Blake |first=Aaron |date=February 14, 2018 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=February 15, 2018 |issn=0190-8286 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214202706/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/02/14/trumps-lawyer-confirmed-the-stormy-daniels-payment-whats-conspicuously-absent-any-denial-that-trump-was-involved/ |archive-date=February 14, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In April 2018, Trump acknowledged for the first time that Cohen has represented him in the Stormy Daniels case, after previously having denied knowledge of the $130,000 payment.<ref>{{cite news |first=Philip |last=Rucker |authorlink=Philip Rucker |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-says-for-first-time-that-cohen-represented-him-in-stormy-daniels-case/2018/04/26/43c48962-4951-11e8-827e-190efaf1f1ee_story.html |title=Trump says for first time that Cohen represented him in Stormy Daniels case |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=April 26, 2018 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822204335/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-says-for-first-time-that-cohen-represented-him-in-stormy-daniels-case/2018/04/26/43c48962-4951-11e8-827e-190efaf1f1ee_story.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn March 5, ''The Wall Street Journal'' cited anonymous sources recounting Cohen as saying he missed two deadlines to pay Daniels because Cohen \"couldn't reach Mr. Trump in the hectic final days of the presidential campaign\", and that after Trump's election, Cohen had complained that he had not been reimbursed for the payment. Cohen described this report as \"[[fake news]]\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Palazzolo |first1=Joe |last2=Rothfeld |first2=Michael |title=Trump Lawyer's Payment to Stormy Daniels Was Reported as Suspicious by Bank |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-lawyers-payment-to-porn-star-was-reported-as-suspicious-by-bank-1520273701?tesla=y&mod=e2tw |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=March 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180310200019/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-lawyers-payment-to-porn-star-was-reported-as-suspicious-by-bank-1520273701?tesla=y&mod=e2tw |archive-date=March 10, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn March 9, [[NBC News]] reported that Cohen had used his Trump Organization email to negotiate with Daniels regarding her nondisclosure agreement, and that Cohen had used the same Trump Organization email to arrange for a transfer for funds that would eventually lead to Daniels' payment.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fitzpatrick |first1=Sarah |last2=Connor |first2=Tracy |title=Michael Cohen used Trump company email in Stormy Daniels arrangements |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/michael-cohen-used-trump-org-email-stormy-daniels-arrangements-n855021 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |accessdate=March 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180310233230/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/michael-cohen-used-trump-org-email-stormy-daniels-arrangements-n855021 |archive-date=March 10, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In response, Cohen acknowledged that he had transferred funds from his [[home equity line of credit]] to the LLC and from the LLC to Daniels' attorney.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Llamas |first1=Tom |authorlink=Tom Llamas |last2=Zaki |first2=Zunaira |last3=Faulders |first3=Katherine |last4=Peck |first4=Christina |title=Michael Cohen dismisses claims of email as proof that Trump knew about payment to porn star to buy her silence |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/michael-cohen-dismisses-claims-email-proof-trump-knew/story?id=53642094 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |accessdate=March 11, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180310205756/http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/michael-cohen-dismisses-claims-email-proof-trump-knew/story?id=53642094 |archive-date=March 10, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn a March 25, 2018, interview with ''[[60 Minutes]]'', Daniels said that she and Trump had sex once, and that later she had been threatened in front of her infant daughter and felt pressured to later sign a [[non-disclosure agreement]].<ref name=\"60m-transcript\">{{cite news |url= https://www.cbsnews.com/news/stormy-daniels-describes-her-alleged-affair-with-donald-trump-60-minutes-interview/ |title=Stormy Daniels describes her alleged affair with Donald Trump |work=[[60 Minutes]] |publisher=[[CBS News]] |date=March 25, 2018 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180326002719/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/stormy-daniels-describes-her-alleged-affair-with-donald-trump-60-minutes-interview/ |archivedate=March 26, 2018 |url-status=live |access-date=March 26, 2018}} Includes video and transcript.</ref><ref name=\"npr-graphic-details\">{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2018/03/25/596868354/stormy-daniels-shares-graphic-details-about-alleged-affair-with-trump |title=Stormy Daniels Shares Graphic Details About Alleged Affair With Trump |first=Miles |last=Parks |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=March 25, 2018 |accessdate=March 26, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180326012144/https://www.npr.org/2018/03/25/596868354/stormy-daniels-shares-graphic-details-about-alleged-affair-with-trump |archive-date=March 26, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, David Schwarz, a lawyer for Cohen, told [[ABC Studios|ABC's]] ''[[Good Morning America]]'' that Daniels was lying in the ''60 Minutes'' interview. Cohen's lawyer sent a cease-and-desist letter claiming Daniels' statements constituted \"libel per se and intentional infliction of emotional distress\" to Cohen.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.cbsnews.com/news/lawyers-for-trump-attorney-say-stormy-daniels-lied-in-60-minutes-interview/ |title=Lawyers for Trump attorney say Stormy Daniels lied in '60 Minutes' interview |publisher=[[CBS News]] |access-date=March 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326165445/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/lawyers-for-trump-attorney-say-stormy-daniels-lied-in-60-minutes-interview/ |archive-date=March 26, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nCohen initiated a private arbitration case against Daniels in February 2018, based on an October 2016 non-disclosure agreement signed by Daniels in October 2016, in exchange for $130,000. Cohen obtained an order from an arbitrator barring Daniels from publicly discussing her alleged relationship with Trump.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fitzpatrick |first1=Sarah |title=Trump lawyer Michael Cohen tries to silence adult-film star Stormy Daniels |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-tries-silence-stormy-daniels-n854646 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |accessdate=March 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308000908/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-tries-silence-stormy-daniels-n854646 |archive-date=March 8, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"ReutersForce\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-daniels/trump-attorney-seeks-to-force-porn-stars-lawsuit-into-arbitration-idUSKCN1HA058 |title=Trump attorney seeks to force porn star's lawsuit into arbitration |work=[[Reuters]] |date=April 2, 2018 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180914122314/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-daniels/trump-attorney-seeks-to-force-porn-stars-lawsuit-into-arbitration-idUSKCN1HA058 |archive-date=September 14, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Daniels subsequently brought a lawsuit in federal court against Trump and Cohen, arguing that the non-disclosure agreement is legally invalid because Trump never signed it,<ref>{{cite news |date=April 2, 2018 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-daniels/trump-attorney-seeks-to-force-porn-star-lawsuit-into-arbitration-idUSKCN1HA058 |title=Trump attorney seeks to force porn star's lawsuit into arbitration |first=Eric |last=Beech |first2=Karen |last2=Freifeld |work=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=May 9, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180823174123/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-daniels/trump-attorney-seeks-to-force-porn-star-lawsuit-into-arbitration-idUSKCN1HA058 |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen responded by seeking to compel arbitration, which would avoid public proceedings.<ref name=\"ReutersForce\" /> In April 2018, Cohen filed a [[affidavit|declaration]] in the court saying that he would invoke his [[Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifth Amendment]] right not to [[self-incrimination|incriminate himself]] in the Daniels lawsuit.<ref>{{cite news |first=Alan |last=Feuer |first2=Benjamin |last2=Weiser |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/25/nyregion/michael-cohen-stormy-daniels.html |title=Michael Cohen to Take Fifth Amendment in Stormy Daniels Lawsuit |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 25, 2018 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180822205018/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/25/nyregion/michael-cohen-stormy-daniels.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Emma |last=Brown |first2=Rosalind S. |last2=Helderman |author2link=Rosalind Helderman |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/cohen-says-he-would-invoke-his-fifth-amendment-right-in-stormy-daniels-case/2018/04/25/c72a5c5a-48d9-11e8-827e-190efaf1f1ee_story.html |title=Michael Cohen to invoke Fifth Amendment right in Stormy Daniels case |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=April 25, 2018 |access-date=April 27, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180427122215/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/cohen-says-he-would-invoke-his-fifth-amendment-right-in-stormy-daniels-case/2018/04/25/c72a5c5a-48d9-11e8-827e-190efaf1f1ee_story.html |archive-date=April 27, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn May 18, lawyers for Cohen filed an [[objection (United States law)|objection]] to Daniel's lawyer Michael Avenatti being allowed to represent her in a case involving Cohen, claiming it (the objection) was based on the violations of ethical rules and local court rules, among other issues.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/05/18/michael-cohen-objects-to-stormy-daniels-lawyer-being-admitted-to-case.html |title=Cohen lawyers object to Stormy Daniels' attorney Michael Avenatti intervening in New York case |last2=Breuninger |first1=Dan |last1=Mangan |first2=Kevin |date=May 18, 2018 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |access-date=May 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180519224307/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/05/18/michael-cohen-objects-to-stormy-daniels-lawyer-being-admitted-to-case.html |archive-date=May 19, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> After Cohen's August 2018 conviction, Trump stated that the payment to Daniels came from him personally and not from the campaign during a [[Fox & Friends]] interview.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-45279047 |title=Trump: Hush money payments came from me |date=August 23, 2018 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823042305/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-45279047 |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Recording of discussion regarding Karen McDougal====\nIn 2016, [[Karen McDougal]], a former ''[[Playboy]]'' model, claimed that she and Trump had an affair from 2006 until 2007, a claim that Trump has since denied.<ref name=\"clientprivilege\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/07/21/politics/trump-cohen-recording-privilege/index.html |title=Trump attorneys waive privilege on secret recording about ex-Playmate payment |first=Gloria |last=Borger |authorlink=Gloria Borger |first2=Erica |last2=Orden |first3=Dana |last3=Bash |author3link=Dana Bash |first4=Evan |last4=Perez |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=July 22, 2018 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180822203651/https://www.cnn.com/2018/07/21/politics/trump-cohen-recording-privilege/index.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The ''[[National Enquirer]]'' paid McDougal $150,000 for her story but never published it, a practice known as [[catch and kill]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://money.cnn.com/2018/02/16/media/trump-catch-and-kill/index.html |date=February 16, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |title= 'Catch and kill': How a tabloid shields Trump from troublesome stories |first=Brian |last=Shelter |authorlink=Brian Stelter |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823234417/https://money.cnn.com/2018/02/16/media/trump-catch-and-kill/index.html |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> On September 30, 2016, Cohen created Resolution Consultants LLC, a [[Delaware]] shell company, to purchase the rights to McDougal's story from the ''National Enquirer'', though the rights to the story were ultimately never purchased.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/trumps-former-lawyer-michael-cohen-formed-delaware-company-to-pay-playboy-model-1532526807 |title=Trump's Former Lawyer Michael Cohen Formed Delaware Company to Purchase Ex-Playboy Model's Story |archive-url= https://archive.today/20180725193109/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trumps-former-lawyer-michael-cohen-formed-delaware-company-to-pay-playboy-model-1532526807 |archive-date=July 25, 2018 |date=July 25, 2018 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |first=Joe |last=Palazzolo |first2=Michael |last2=Rothfeld |first3=Rebecca |last3=Ballhaus |accessdate=August 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Resolution_Consultants_LLC_01_12_18.pdf |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180118230907/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Resolution_Consultants_LLC_01_12_18.pdf |archive-date=January 18, 2018 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |title=State of Delaware Limited Liability Company Certificate of Formation: Resolution Consultants LLC |date=September 30, 2016 |first=Michael |last=Cohen |publisher=[[Secretary of State of Delaware]] ([[Jeffrey W. Bullock]])}}</ref>\n\nCohen had been known to record conversations and phone calls with other people.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/382951-trump-advisers-fear-fbi-seized-trump-lawyers-recordings-of |title=Trump allies fear feds seized lawyer's recordings of conversations: report |last=Thomsen |first=Jacqueline |date=April 12, 2018 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |accessdate=July 21, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180722011510/http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/382951-trump-advisers-fear-fbi-seized-trump-lawyers-recordings-of |archive-date=July 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> According to his lawyer Lanny Davis, \"Michael Cohen had the habit of using his phone to record conversations instead of taking notes.\"<ref name=\"voxseized\">{{Cite news |first=Li |last=Zhou |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/7/26/17616548/michael-cohen-trump-recordings |title=Report: federal authorities have seized more than 100 Michael Cohen tapes |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=July 26, 2018 |access-date=July 27, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180726175435/https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/7/26/17616548/michael-cohen-trump-recordings |archive-date=July 26, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Altogether the prosecutors have been given more than one hundred audio recordings from the material seized from Cohen in the April raid, after the Trump team withdrew their claims of [[privilege (law)|privilege]] for those items; reportedly only one of them features a substantive conversation with Trump.<ref name=\"voxseized\" /> The existence of that tape was revealed on July 20 and the actual recording was released on July 25.<ref name=\"clientprivilege\" /><ref name=\"tape\" />\n\nOn July 20, it was revealed that Cohen secretly recorded a conversation between Trump and him. The discussion involved a potential hush payment to the publisher of the ''National Enquirer''. The recording had been classified as a [[attorney\u2013client privilege|privileged attorney-client communication]] by the Special Master reviewing the Cohen material, but Trump's attorneys waived that claim, meaning that prosecutors can have it and use it. The conversation in that tape occurred in September 2016, two months before the election and weeks after the ''Enquirer'' paid McDougal the $150,000. In the conversation, Trump and Cohen discuss whether to buy the rights to her story from the ''Enquirer'', and Trump appears to approve the idea. Trump's lawyer, Rudy Giuliani, initially claimed that the tape shows Trump saying \"make sure it's done correctly, and make sure it's done by check.\" Giuliani also noted that no payment was ultimately made, and asserted that Trump's team waived privilege and allowed the recording to be revealed because it shows no violation of law.<ref name=\"clientprivilege\" /> The recording appears to contradict [[Hope Hicks]], then Trump's spokeswoman, who said when the story of the ''Enquirer'' payment came out a few days before the election that the Trump campaign had \"no knowledge of any of this\".<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Tucker|first1=Eric |last2=Peltz|first2=Jennifer |url= https://apnews.com/3faf47db59054b3c9c8dd414b943c9ea/Trump-was-taped-talking-of-paying-for-Playboy-model's-story |title=Trump was taped talking of paying for Playboy model's story |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |date=July 20, 2018 |access-date= October 19, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180722164507/https://www.apnews.com/3faf47db59054b3c9c8dd414b943c9ea/Trump-was-taped-talking-of-paying-for-Playboy-model's-story |archive-date=July 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn July 25, Cohen's attorney [[Lanny Davis]] released the actual recording to [[CNN]], which played it on the air on the ''[[Cuomo Prime Time]]'' program. On it, Trump can be heard concluding a telephone conversation with an unidentified person and then discussing several items of business with Cohen. Cohen mentions that he needs to \"open up a company for the transfer of all of that info regarding our friend David\", interpreted as meaning [[David Pecker]], the head of [[American Media, Inc.|American Media]], which publishes the ''National Enquirer''. Later when they discuss financing, Trump is heard saying something about \"pay with cash\", to which Cohen responds \"no, no, no\", but the tape is unclear and it is disputed what is said next; the word \"check\" can be heard.<ref name=\"tape\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/07/24/politics/michael-cohen-donald-trump-tape/index.html |title=Exclusive: CNN obtains secret Trump-Cohen tape |date=July 25, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate=July 25, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180725010902/https://www.cnn.com/2018/07/24/politics/michael-cohen-donald-trump-tape/index.html |archive-date=July 25, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> A transcript provided by Trump's attorneys has Trump saying \"Don't pay with cash ... check.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/trump-cohen-secret-audio-tape-made-public/story?id=56798373 |title=Trump-Cohen secret audio tape made public |last=Faulders |first=Katherine |date=July 25, 2018 |work=[[ABC News]] |accessdate=July 25, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180725025936/https://abcnews.go.com/US/trump-cohen-secret-audio-tape-made-public/story?id=56798373 |archive-date=July 25, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The tape cuts off abruptly at that point.<ref name=\"first\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/07/24/the-trump-michael-cohen-tape-transcript-annotated/ |title=The Trump-Michael Cohen tape transcript, annotated |last=Blake |first=Aaron |date=July 24, 2018 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=July 25, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180725020958/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/07/24/the-trump-michael-cohen-tape-transcript-annotated/|archive-date=July 25, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A lawyer for the Trump Organization said that any reference to \"cash\" would not have meant \"green currency\", but a one-time payment (\"cash\") vs. extended payments (\"[[funding|financing]]\"), in either case accompanied by documents.<ref name=\"tape\" /> According to Aaron Blake at ''The Washington Post'', \"the tape provides the first evidence that Trump spoke with Cohen about purchasing the rights to women's stories\u2014apparently to silence them\u2014before the [[United States elections, 2016|2016 election]].\"<ref name=\"first\" /> He also notes that Cohen speaks in \"somewhat coded language\", which Trump understands, suggesting that he is already familiar with the issue.{{citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n\nDespite the taped conversation, on August 23, in a [[Fox News]] interview Trump stated that he was not aware of the hush-money payments until \"later on\": \"Later on I knew. Later on. What he did\u2014and they weren't taken out of the campaign finance, that's the big thing.\" He added: \"In fact, my first question when I heard about it was, did they come out of the campaign, because that could be a little dicey. And they didn't come out of the campaign and that's big. But they weren't ... that's not even a campaign violation.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singman |first1=Brooke |title=Trump rips Cohen for 'flipping,' praises Manafort in exclusive FNC interview |date=August 23, 2018 |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2018/08/23/trump-rips-cohen-for-flipping-praises-manafort-in-exclusive-fnc-interview.html |publisher=[[Fox News]] |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823110631/http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2018/08/23/trump-rips-cohen-for-flipping-praises-manafort-in-exclusive-fnc-interview.html |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> According to U.S. election rules, any payments intended to influence an election vote must be reported.<ref name=\"auto1\" />\n\n====Payment to Shera Bechard====\n{{See also|Keith M. Davidson#Shera Bechard}}\nIn April 2018, ''The Wall Street Journal'' reported that [[Shera Bechard]], a former [[Playboy Playmate|''Playboy'' Playmate]], had an affair with married Republican fundraiser [[Elliott Broidy]]. She became pregnant by him, had an abortion, and was to be paid $1.6 million [[hush money]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-negotiated-1-6-million-settlement-for-top-republican-fundraiser-1523638726 |title=Trump Lawyer Michael Cohen Negotiated $1.6 Million Settlement for Top Republican Fundraiser |last1= Palazzolo |first1=Joe |last2=Rothfeld |first2=Michael |date=April 13, 2018 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate= April 13, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413175435/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-negotiated-1-6-million-settlement-for-top-republican-fundraiser-1523638726 |archive-date=April 13, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ruiz |first1=Rebecca R. |last2=Rutenberg |first2=Jim |author2link=Jim Rutenberg |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/13/us/politics/elliott-broidy-michael-cohen-payout.html |title=R.N.C. Official Who Agreed to Pay Playboy Model $1.6 Million Resigns |date=April 13, 2018 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=April 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416015815/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/13/us/politics/elliott-broidy-michael-cohen-payout.html |archive-date=April 16, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Broidy is a Republican fundraiser and deputy finance chair of the [[Republican National Committee]].\n\nIn a 2018 court proceeding, Cohen said he had given legal advice to only three clients in 2017: Donald Trump, [[Sean Hannity]], and Elliott Broidy.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-04-16/cohen-says-he-gave-legal-advice-to-three-clients-in-past-year |title=Cohen Says He Gave Legal Advice to Three Clients in Past Year |last= Voreacos |first=David |date=April 16, 2018 |publisher=[[Bloomberg News]] |accessdate=May 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180513165311/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-04-16/cohen-says-he-gave-legal-advice-to-three-clients-in-past-year |archive-date=May 13, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In late 2017, Cohen arranged the $1.6 million payment by Broidy to Bechard as part of a nondisclosure agreement requiring Bechard to keep silent about the matter.<ref name=\"CNN Cohen facilitated\">{{Cite news |date=April 13, 2018 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/13/politics/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-settlement/index.html |title=Michael Cohen facilitated $1.6 million agreement on behalf of GOP fundraiser |first1=MJ |last1=Lee |last2=Sara |first2=Sidner |author2link=Sara Sidner |first3=Kara |last3=Scannell |first4=Clare |last4=Foran |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=April 13, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180413204522/https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/13/politics/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-settlement/index.html |archive-date=April 13, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen was Broidy's attorney and [[Keith M. Davidson]] represented Bechard.<ref name=\"CNN Cohen facilitated\" /> Davidson had previously been the attorney for Stormy Daniels and Karen McDougal.<ref name=\"CNN Cohen facilitated\" /> The Bechard nondisclosure agreement used the same [[pseudonym]]s&nbsp;\u2013 David Dennison for the man and Peggy Peterson for the woman&nbsp;\u2013 as in the Daniels agreement.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/05/theory-playboy-model-had-affair-with-trump-not-broidy.html |title=Here's a Theory About That $1.6 Million Payout From a GOP Official to a Playboy Model |last=Campos |first=Paul |authorlink=Paul Campos |date=May 8, 2018 |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |accessdate=July 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180812142316/http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/05/theory-playboy-model-had-affair-with-trump-not-broidy.html |archive-date=August 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The payments were to be made in installments.\n\nOn July 6, 2018, Bechard filed a lawsuit against Broidy, Davidson, and Daniels' attorney [[Michael Avenatti]], claiming the three had breached the agreement in relation to the cessation of the settlement payments.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.vox.com/2018/7/6/17542222/shera-bechard-broidy-trump-lawsuit-pregnancy |title=Shera Bechard lawsuit: Model who Trump donor paid hush money to sues - Vox |last=Prokop |first=Andrew |date=July 6, 2018 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |accessdate=July 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180723003718/https://www.vox.com/2018/7/6/17542222/shera-bechard-broidy-trump-lawsuit-pregnancy |archive-date=July 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Dillon |first=Nancy |url= http://www.nydailynews.com/news/ny-news-playmate-sues-broidy-avenatti-20180706-story.html |title=Ex-Playboy model sues Trump donor Elliott Broidy and Michael Avenatti over hush-money pact tied to secret pregnancy |work=[[New York Daily News]] |date=July 6, 2018 |accessdate=July 7, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180707010249/http://www.nydailynews.com/news/ny-news-playmate-sues-broidy-avenatti-20180706-story.html |archive-date=July 7, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/ex-playmate-files-suit-against-gop-donor-elliott-broidy-over-hush-money-deal-1530904576 |title=Ex-Playmate Files Suit Against GOP Donor Elliott Broidy Over Hush-Money Deal |first=Michael |last=Rothfeld |first2=Joe |last2=Palazzolo |date=July 6, 2018 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180706200055/https://www.wsj.com/articles/ex-playmate-files-suit-against-gop-donor-elliott-broidy-over-hush-money-deal-1530904576 |archive-date=July 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/2018_0706_bechard_vs_broidy_plaintffs_memorandum.pdf?mod=article_inline |format=[[PDF]] |first=Peter K. |last=Stris |first2=Elizabeth R. |last2=Brannen |first3=Dana |last3=Berkowitz |first4=John |last4=Stokes |first5=Shaun P. |last5=Martin |publisher=Stris & Maher LLP via [[The Wall Street Journal]] |archive-date= July 7, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180707154348/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/2018_0706_bechard_vs_broidy_plaintffs_memorandum.pdf?mod=article_inline |date=July 6, 2018 |title=Plaintiff's Memorandum of Points and Authorities in Support of Ex Parte Application to Conditionally Seal the Complaint for 45 Days}}</ref>\n\n====Essential Consultants LLC====\nEssential Consultants LLC is a [[Delaware]] shell company created by Cohen in October 2016 to facilitate payment of hush money to Stormy Daniels.<ref name=\"LLC\" /> For many months thereafter, Cohen used the LLC<ref>{{Cite news |last=Cohen |first=Michael |date=October 17, 2016 |title=State of Delaware Limited Liability Company Certificate of Formation |url= https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Essential_Consultants_01_12_17.pdf |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |publisher=[[Secretary of State of Delaware]] ([[Jeffrey W. Bullock]]) |access-date=May 9, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180417150531/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Essential_Consultants_01_12_17.pdf |archive-date=April 17, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> for an array of business activities largely unknown to the public, with at least $4.4 million moving through the LLC between Trump's election to the presidency and January 2018.<ref name=\"NYTShellCompanyPayments\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/08/us/politics/michael-cohen-shell-company-payments.html |title=Firm Tied to Russian Oligarch Made Payments to Michael Cohen |last=McIntire |first=Mike |date=May 8, 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |last2=Protess |first2=Ben |last3=Rutenberg |first3=Jim |author3link=Jim Rutenberg |access-date=May 9, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180509001006/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/08/us/politics/michael-cohen-shell-company-payments.html |archive-date=May 9, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In May 2018, Stormy Daniels' lawyer [[Michael Avenatti]] posted a seven-page report to [[Twitter]] detailing what he said were financial transactions involving Essential Consultants and Cohen. Avenatti did not reveal the source of his information, which was later largely confirmed by ''The New York Times'' and other publications.<ref name=\"NYTShellCompanyPayments\" /> The data showed that hundreds of thousands of dollars were given to Cohen, via Essential Consultants, from Fortune 500 firms such as [[Novartis]] and [[AT&T]], which had business before the Trump administration. It was also revealed that Essential Consultants had received at least $500,000 from a New York-based investment firm called [[Columbus Nova]], which is linked to a [[Russian oligarch]]. The firm's largest client is a company controlled by [[Viktor Vekselberg]], a Ukrainian-born Russian oligarch.<ref name=\"NYTShellCompanyPayments\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-05-08/oligarch-steered-cash-to-trump-lawyer-s-account-avenatti-says |title=Russian Oligarch Tied to Trump Lawyer in Stormy Bombshell |first=Erik |last=Larson |authorlink=Erik Larson (author) |first2=Andrew |last2=Martin |date=May 8, 2018 |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |accessdate=May 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180508235733/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-05-08/oligarch-steered-cash-to-trump-lawyer-s-account-avenatti-says |archive-date=May 8, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}<br>{{cite news|url= https://assets.bwbx.io/s3/readings/P8GBAG6TTDSH1525865905564.mp3 |title=Russian Oligarch Tied to Trump Lawyer in Stormy Bombshell |first=Erik |last=Larson |authorlink=Erik Larson (author) |first2=Andrew |last2=Martin |date=May 8, 2018 |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |accessdate=March 2, 2019 |type=audio|format=[[MP3]]|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180510212404/https://assets.bwbx.io/s3/readings/P8GBAG6TTDSH1525865905564.mp3 |archive-date=May 10, 2018 |url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=May 8, 2018 |url=https://www.newyorker.com/current/michael-cohen-essential-consulting |title=Why the Revelations About Michael Cohen's Business Dealings Could Be a Very Big Deal |first=Eric |last=Lach |work=[[The New Yorker]] |accessdate=May 9, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180509035833/https://www.newyorker.com/current/michael-cohen-essential-consulting |archive-date=May 9, 2018 |url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"lat Firm paid $500,000\" /> Vekselberg is a business partner of Soviet-born billionaire and major [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] donor, [[Leonard Blavatnik]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=May |first1=Ruth |title=GOP campaigns took $7.35&nbsp;million from oligarch linked to Russia |url= https://www.dallasnews.com/opinion/commentary/2017/08/03/tangled-web-connects-russian-oligarch-money-gop-campaigns |newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |date=August 3, 2017 |access-date=May 9, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180518034059/https://www.dallasnews.com/opinion/commentary/2017/08/03/tangled-web-connects-russian-oligarch-money-gop-campaigns |archive-date=May 18, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> A spokesperson for Columbus Nova said that the payment was a consulting fee that had nothing to do with Vekselberg.<ref name=\"NYTShellCompanyPayments\" />\n\nQuestions were raised about many of the payments, such as four totaling $200,000 that [[AT&T]] paid to the LLC between October 2017 and January 2018,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scribd.com/document/378627744/Executive-Summary |title= Executive Summary|first=Michael|last=Avenatti|authorlink=Michael Avenatti|via=[[Scribd]]|accessdate=May 9, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180612074312/https://www.scribd.com/document/378627744/Executive-Summary |archive-date=June 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2018/politics/news/att-trump-michael-cohen-1202803819/ |title=AT&T Says It Paid Michael Cohen's Firm for 'Insights' Into Trump Administration |first=Ted |last=Johnson |date=May 9, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=May 9, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180509023512/http://variety.com/2018/politics/news/att-trump-michael-cohen-1202803819/ |archive-date=May 9, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> while at the same time the proposed merger between the company and [[Time Warner Cable|Time Warner]] was pending before the Justice Department. AT&T claimed that the money was paid to the LLC and other firms that were used to provide insights into understanding the new administration, and that the LLC did no legal or lobbying work for AT&T.<ref name=\"NYTShellCompanyPayments\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/michael-cohen-took-cash-from-russian-oligarch-after-election |title=Michael Cohen Took Cash From Oligarch-Connected Firm After Election |first1=Noah|last1=Shachtman |authorlink=Noah Shachtman |first2=Kate |last2=Briquelet |date=May 8, 2018 |work=[[The Daily Beast]] |accessdate=May 9, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180508225248/https://www.thedailybeast.com/michael-cohen-took-cash-from-russian-oligarch-after-election |archive-date=May 8, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn May 11, 2018, the CEO of AT&T stated that in early 2017 it was approached by Cohen to provide \"his opinion on the new president and his administration\". Cohen was paid $600,000 ($50,000 per month) over the year, which its CEO described as \"a big mistake\". Novartis was also approached by Cohen and was offered similar services.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://money.cnn.com/2018/05/11/media/att-michael-cohen-randall-stephenson/index.html |title=AT&T CEO says hiring Michael Cohen 'was a big mistake' |first=Brian |last=Stelter |authorlink=Brian Stelter |first2=Hadas |last2=Gold |author2link=Hadas Gold |publisher=[[CNNMoney]] |date=May 11, 2018 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180824002302/https://money.cnn.com/2018/05/11/media/att-michael-cohen-randall-stephenson/index.html |archive-date=August 24, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nNovartis, a [[Switzerland]]&ndash;based pharmaceutical giant paid the LLC nearly $1.2 million in separate payments.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=https://www.fiercepharma.com/pharma/during-davos-trip-trump-takes-meeting-novartis-bayer-ceos-and-other-execs |title=Novartis, Bayer CEOs get time with Trump as he meets with EU business leaders during Davos trip |first=Eric |last= Sagonowsky |publisher=FiercePharma |accessdate=May 9, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180509150956/https://www.fiercepharma.com/pharma/during-davos-trip-trump-takes-meeting-novartis-bayer-ceos-and-other-execs |archive-date=May 9, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Novartis released a statement May 9, 2018, that it hired the LLC to help the company understand the \"health care policy\" of the new administration, but it actually did not receive benefit for its investment. The statement continued that Novartis made a decision to not engage Essential Consultants further, but it could not terminate the contract for \"cause\", raising concerns on why the company did not pursue reimbursement.<ref name=\"WashPostSwampThing\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/05/10/michael-cohen-swamp-thing/ |title=Analysis {{!}} Michael Cohen epitomizes just how much the swamp has thrived under Trump |last=Blake |first=Aaron |date=May 10, 2018 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=May 10, 2018 |issn=0190-8286 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510144426/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/05/10/michael-cohen-swamp-thing/ |archive-date=May 10, 2018 |url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Korea Aerospace Industries]] paid $150,000,<ref name=\"lat Firm paid $500,000\">{{cite news |url= https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-cohen-russia-vekselberg-20180508-story.html |title=Firm linked to Russian mogul paid $500,000 to Trump attorney Michael Cohen |first=Michael |last=Finnegan |date=May 9, 2018 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=May 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509021213/http://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-cohen-russia-vekselberg-20180508-story.html |archive-date=May 9, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> ostensibly for advice on \"cost accounting standards\".<ref name=\"WashPostSwampThing\"/>\n\nFranklin L. Haney agreed to pay Cohen $10 million if he successfully lobbied for the [[United States Department of Energy]] to finance the [[Bellefonte Nuclear Generating Station]], or a reduced fee if the funding targets were only partially met.<ref name=\"nuke\">{{cite news |title=Top Trump Donor Agreed to Pay Michael Cohen $10 Million for Nuclear Project Push |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |first=Michael |last=Rothfeld |first2=Rebecca |last2=Ballhaus |first3=Joe |last3=Palazzolo |date=August 2, 2018 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/top-trump-donor-agreed-to-pay-michael-cohen-10-million-for-nuclear-project-push-sources-say-1533245330 |archive-url= https://archive.today/20180802225217/https://www.wsj.com/articles/top-trump-donor-agreed-to-pay-michael-cohen-10-million-for-nuclear-project-push-sources-say-1533245330 |archive-date=August 2, 2018 |first4=Nicole |last4=Hong}}</ref>\n\n==Federal investigations==\n[[File:Cohen-v-US-Govt-Opposition-to-TRO-Request.pdf|thumb|Cohen v US \u2013 Govt Opposition to TRO Request]]\nAs of April 2018, Cohen was under federal criminal investigation by the [[United States Attorney for the Southern District of New York]] (SDNY).<ref name=\"Winter\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-wants-review-some-materials-seized-cohen-fbi-raid-n866226 |title=Fox News host Sean Hannity revealed as Michael Cohen's mystery client |last1=Winter |first1=Tom |last2=Edelman |first2=Adam |date=April 16, 2018 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |accessdate=April 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416122620/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-wants-review-some-materials-seized-cohen-fbi-raid-n866226 |archive-date=April 16, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"29investigations\" >{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/05/13/us/politics/trump-investigations.html |title=Tracking 29 Investigations Related to Trump |authors=Larry Buchanan and Karen Yourish |date=May 20, 2019 |website=nytimes.com |access-date=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn April 9, 2018, the [[FBI]] raided Cohen's office at the law firm of [[Squire Patton Boggs]], as well as his home and his hotel room in the Loews Regency Hotel in New York City, pursuant to a federal [[search warrant]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Strobel |first1=Warren |last2=Walcott |first2=John |title=FBI raids offices, home of Trump's personal lawyer: sources |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-cohen-raid/fbi-raids-offices-home-of-trumps-personal-lawyer-sources-idUSKBN1HG336 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=April 10, 2018 |accessdate=April 10, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180410012921/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-cohen-raid/fbi-raids-offices-home-of-trumps-personal-lawyer-sources-idUSKBN1HG336 |archive-date=April 10, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/09/politics/michael-cohen-fbi/index.html |title=FBI raids Trump lawyer Michael Cohen's office |first=Eli |last=Watkins |accessdate=May 3, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181006115044/https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/09/politics/michael-cohen-fbi/index.html |archive-date=October 6, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The warrant was obtained by the U.S. Attorney's Office for the SDNY, whose [[public corruption]] unit was conducting an investigation.<ref name=\"ShearRecords\" /> Seeking the warrant required high-level approval from the Department of Justice.<ref name=\"nytimes2018\">{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/09/us/politics/fbi-raids-office-of-trumps-longtime-lawyer-michael-cohen.html |title=F.B.I. Raids Office of Trump's Longtime Lawyer Michael Cohen |first=Matt |last=Apuzzo |authorlink=Matt Apuzzo |date=April 9, 2018 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180409201609/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/09/us/politics/fbi-raids-office-of-trumps-longtime-lawyer-michael-cohen.html |archive-date=April 9, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The Interim U.S. Attorney, [[Geoffrey Berman]], was recused.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/us-attorney-trump-appointee-recused-michael-cohen-investigation/story?id=54365546 |first=Jonathan |last=Karl |authorlink=Jonathan Karl |first2=Josh |last2=Margolin |title=Trump-appointed US attorney recused from Michael Cohen investigation |date=April 10, 2018 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |access-date=April 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411001510/http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/us-attorney-trump-appointee-recused-michael-cohen-investigation/story?id=54365546 |archive-date=April 11, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Deputy Attorney General [[Rod Rosenstein]] and FBI Director [[Christopher A. Wray|Christopher Wray]]\u2014both of whom are Trump appointees\u2014had supervisory roles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/michael-cohen-justice-department-raid-on-trump-lawyer-2018-4 |title=The Justice Department had to go to extraordinary lengths to conduct a raid on top Trump lawyer Michael Cohen |website=[[Business Insider]] |first=Allan |last=Smith |date=April 10, 2018 |accessdate=May 3, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180502230213/http://www.businessinsider.com/michael-cohen-justice-department-raid-on-trump-lawyer-2018-4 |archive-date=May 2, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The FBI obtained the warrant after a referral from [[Robert Mueller]]'s [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Special Counsel investigation]] into [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]], although underlying reasons for the raid were not revealed.<ref name=\"nytimes2018\" /><ref>{{cite news |first1=Erica |last1=Orden |first2=Rebecca |last2=Ballhaus |first3=Michael |last3=Rothfeld |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/fbi-raids-trump-lawyers-office-1523306297 |title=Agents Raid Office of Trump Lawyer Michael Cohen in Connection With Stormy Daniels Payments |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=April 9, 2018 |accessdate=April 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411035157/https://www.wsj.com/articles/fbi-raids-trump-lawyers-office-1523306297 |archive-date=April 11, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Following the raid, Squire Patton Boggs law firm ended its formal working relationship with Cohen.<ref>{{cite web |last=Lovelace |first=Ryan |url=https://www.law.com/nationallawjournal/2018/04/09/after-fbi-raid-squire-says-it-severed-ties-to-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen/ |title=After FBI Raid, Squire Says It Severed Ties to Trump Lawyer Michael Cohen |work=[[The National Law Journal]] |date=April 9, 2018 |accessdate=April 11, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180411145941/https://www.law.com/nationallawjournal/2018/04/09/after-fbi-raid-squire-says-it-severed-ties-to-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen/ |archive-date=April 11, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAgents seized emails, tax records, business records, and other matter related to several topics, including payments made by Cohen to Stormy Daniels,<ref name=\"nytimes2018\" /> and records related to [[Donald Trump Access Hollywood tape|Trump's ''Access Hollywood'' controversy]].<ref>{{cite news |authorlink=Maggie Haberman |last1=Haberman |first1=Maggie |last2=Apuzzo |first2=Matt |author2link=Matt Apuzzo |last3=Schmidt |first3=Michael S. |authorlink3=Michael S. Schmidt |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/11/us/politics/michael-cohen-trump-access-hollywood.html |title=Raid on Trump's Lawyer Sought Records on 'Access Hollywood' Tape |date=April 11, 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=April 11, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180411183333/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/11/us/politics/michael-cohen-trump-access-hollywood.html |archive-date=April 11, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Recordings of phone conversations Cohen made were also obtained.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/13/politics/fbi-phone-recordings-cohen-daniels-mcdougal/index.html |first=Gloria |last=Borger |authorlink=Gloria Borger |first2=Sara |last2=Sidner |author2link=Sara Sidner |first3=Scott |last3=Glover |title=Exclusive: FBI seized recordings between Trump's lawyer and Stormy Daniels' former lawyer |date=April 13, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=April 14, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180414003708/https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/13/politics/fbi-phone-recordings-cohen-daniels-mcdougal/index.html |archive-date=April 14, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> According to Stormy Daniels' attorney [[Michael Avenatti]] and civil rights attorney [[Lisa Bloom]], some of the recordings may have included participants located in California, which would make the recordings illegal, as California is a \"[[telephone recording laws#Two-party consent states|two party consent]]\" state.<ref>{{cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n1f4-vZby88&t=1m19s |date=April 14, 2018 |people=[[Joy Reid]] (interviewer), [[Michael Avenatti]] & [[Lisa Bloom]] (interviewees) |title=Avenatti and Bloom on ''A.M. Joy'' |work=[[A.M. Joy]] |publisher=[[MSNBC]] |access-date=December 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227223857/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n1f4-vZby88&t=1m19s |archive-date=February 27, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nSince Cohen is an attorney, the search included the seizure of materials normally protected by [[attorney-client privilege]], which is subject to a [[crime-fraud exception]] if a crime is suspected.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.lawfareblog.com/michael-cohen-attorney-client-privilege-and-crime-fraud-exception |first=Paul |last=Rosenzweig |title=Michael Cohen, Attorney-Client Privilege and the Crime-Fraud Exception |date=April 10, 2018 |publisher=[[Lawfare (blog)|Lawfare]]|access-date=April 11, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180411094135/https://www.lawfareblog.com/michael-cohen-attorney-client-privilege-and-crime-fraud-exception |archive-date=April 11, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Some legal scholars opined that Trump's denial that he had knowledge of the Daniels payment, combined with denials by Cohen and his lawyer [[David Schwartz (lawyer)|David Schwartz]], meant both sides had effectively said that matter did not involve attorney-client communications.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/04/10/how-trump-may-have-invited-investigators-to-go-after-michael-cohen/ |title=How Trump may have unwittingly invited the Michael Cohen raid |last=Blake |first=Aaron |date=April 10, 2018 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=April 11, 2018 |issn=0190-8286 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180411064731/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/04/10/how-trump-may-have-invited-investigators-to-go-after-michael-cohen/ |archive-date=April 11, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen and his lawyers argued that all of the thousands of items seized during the FBI raid should be protected by attorney-client privilege and thus withheld from the prosecutors. U.S. District Judge [[Kimba M. Wood]], appointed a [[special master]], former federal judge [[Barbara S. Jones]], to review all of the seized materials for attorney-client privilege. She found that only 14 of the 639 paper documents were privileged, and out of the 291,770 electronic files seized, only 148 files were withheld from the prosecution.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/04/nyregion/cohen-special-master-review.html |title=Special Master in Cohen Case Finds Few Seized Materials Are Privileged |access-date=September 5, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180905215031/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/04/nyregion/cohen-special-master-review.html |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The search warrant itself has been sealed, making it unavailable to the public.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://lawandcrime.com/high-profile/why-the-fbi-raid-suggests-michael-cohen-should-be-really-really-scared-that-hes-next/ |first1=Rachel |last1=Stockman |title=Analysis: The FBI Raid Means Michael Cohen Should Be Really, Really Scared He's Next |publisher=[[Law & Crime]] |date=April 9, 2018 |access-date=April 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180410201850/https://lawandcrime.com/high-profile/why-the-fbi-raid-suggests-michael-cohen-should-be-really-really-scared-that-hes-next/ |archive-date=April 10, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The FBI also sought documents pertaining to Cohen's ownership of [[taxi medallion]]s.<ref name=\"ShearRecords\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/382482-fbi-search-warrant-on-cohen-inquired-into-taxi-medallion-ownership |title=FBI search warrant on Cohen covered taxi medallion ownership |last=Delk |first=Josh |date=April 10, 2018 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=April 10, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180411025811/http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/382482-fbi-search-warrant-on-cohen-inquired-into-taxi-medallion-ownership |archive-date=April 11, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen's taxi fleet is operated by [[Gene Freidman]], who is facing legal trouble for alleged [[tax evasion]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/04/what-exactly-was-michael-cohen-doing-for-donald-trump/557801/ |title= What Exactly Was Michael Cohen Doing for Donald Trump? |work=[[The Atlantic]]|first=David A.|last=Graham|date=April 12, 2018|accessdate=April 12, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180413043706/https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/04/what-exactly-was-michael-cohen-doing-for-donald-trump/557801/ |archive-date=April 13, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nA few days after the raid, [[The McClatchy Company|McClatchy]] reported that the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Mueller investigation]] was in possession of evidence that Cohen traveled to [[Prague]] in August or September 2016. If true, the report bolsters similar claims in 3 of 17 reports from the [[Trump\u2013Russia dossier]]. According to McClatchy's confidential sources, Cohen traveled to Prague via Germany, a passage that would not have required use of a passport due to both countries being within the [[Schengen Area]].<ref name=\"Stone_Gordon_4/13/2018\">{{cite news |url= http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/white-house/article208870264.html |title=Sources: Mueller has evidence Cohen was in Prague in 2016, confirming part of dossier |publisher=[[The McClatchy Company|McClatchy DC Bureau]] |date=April 13, 2018 |last=Stone |first=Peter |last2=Gordon |first2=Greg |accessdate=April 16, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180413234700/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/white-house/article208870264.html |archive-date=April 13, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=Bump>{{cite news |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/politics/wp/2018/04/14/michael-cohen-visiting-prague-would-be-a-huge-development-in-the-russia-investigation/ |title=Michael Cohen's visiting Prague would be a huge development in the Russia investigation |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=April 14, 2018 |last=Bump |first=Philip |accessdate=April 16, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180415084835/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/politics/wp/2018/04/14/michael-cohen-visiting-prague-would-be-a-huge-development-in-the-russia-investigation/ |archive-date=April 15, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=Reuters-180414>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-russia-prague/special-counsel-has-evidence-michael-cohen-traveled-to-prague-mcclatchy-idUSKBN1HL00J |title=Special counsel has evidence Michael Cohen traveled to Prague: McClatchy |work=[[Reuters]] |date=April 14, 2018 |accessdate=April 16, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180416052343/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-russia-prague/special-counsel-has-evidence-michael-cohen-traveled-to-prague-mcclatchy-idUSKBN1HL00J |archive-date=April 16, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In reaction, Cohen denied having ever been to Prague, as he had done in his January 2017 denial following the dossier's release.<ref name=\"CBS_News_4/14/2018\" /><ref name=Porter>{{cite news |url=http://www.newsweek.com/mueller-has-evidence-back-russia-dossiers-claims-about-trump-attorney-cohen-886152 |title=Trump Attorney Lied About Prague Trip, Mueller Investigation Reveals, As New Evidence Comes To Light |work=[[Newsweek]] |date=April 14, 2018 |last=Porter |first=Tom |accessdate=April 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180415224129/http://www.newsweek.com/mueller-has-evidence-back-russia-dossiers-claims-about-trump-attorney-cohen-886152 |archive-date=April 15, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''Mother Jones'' reported that Cohen had told them \"I was in Prague for one afternoon 14 years ago,\" contradicting later statements that he had never visited.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2018/04/michael-cohen-says-hes-never-been-to-prague-he-told-me-a-different-story/|title=Michael Cohen says he's \"never\" been to Prague. He told me a different story.|work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]|access-date=July 4, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181230005649/https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2018/04/michael-cohen-says-hes-never-been-to-prague-he-told-me-a-different-story/|archive-date=December 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, [[NBC]] reported that Cohen's phone calls had been monitored by [[pen register]], which logs the origins and destinations of calls but not the contents.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/feds-tapped-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-s-phones-n871011 |title=Feds monitored Trump lawyer Michael Cohen's phones |first=Tom |last=Winter |first2=Julia |last2=Ainsley |date=May 3, 2018 |accessdate=May 3, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180503165933/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/feds-tapped-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-s-phones-n871011 |archive-date=May 3, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.mediaite.com/tv/nbc-issues-major-correction-feds-monitored-michael-cohens-calls-did-not-wiretap/ |title=Breaking: NBC News Issues Major Correction, Michael Cohen Was Not Wiretapped |first=Aidan |last=McLaughlin |publisher=[[Mediaite]] |accessdate=May 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504091618/https://www.mediaite.com/tv/nbc-issues-major-correction-feds-monitored-michael-cohens-calls-did-not-wiretap/ |archive-date=May 4, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n''The Wall Street Journal'' reported on July 26, 2018, that longtime [[Trump Organization]] CFO [[Allen Weisselberg]] had been subpoenaed to testify before a federal grand jury regarding the Cohen investigation.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.cnbc.com/2018/07/26/trump-org-cfo-called-to-grand-jury-to-testify-wsj.html |title=Trump Org. CFO mentioned in Michael Cohen tape called by grand jury to testify: WSJ |first1=Dan |last1=Mangan |first2=Kevin |last2=Breuninger |date=July 26, 2018 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180821202057/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/07/26/trump-org-cfo-called-to-grand-jury-to-testify-wsj.html |archive-date=August 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Conviction on campaign finance, tax evasion, and other charges===\nIn August 2018, it was reported that investigators were in the final stages of their investigation.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://nypost.com/2018/08/19/michael-cohen-reportedly-under-investigation-for-20m-in-bank-fraud/ |title=Michael Cohen reportedly under investigation for $20M in bank fraud |date=August 19, 2018 |work=New York Post |access-date=August 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820011819/https://nypost.com/2018/08/19/michael-cohen-reportedly-under-investigation-for-20m-in-bank-fraud/|archive-date=August 20, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen officially surrendered to the FBI on August 21, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-michael-cohen-plea-deal-fraud-case-20180821-story.html |title=Ex-Trump lawyer Cohen pleads guilty in hush-money scheme, campaign finance violations |agency=Associated Press |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |first=Larry |last=Neumeister |first2=Tom |last2=Hays |access-date=August 21, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180821223256/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-michael-cohen-plea-deal-fraud-case-20180821-story.html |archive-date=August 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> That afternoon, Cohen pleaded guilty to eight criminal<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/trump-michael-cohen-crimes-not-crimes-talking-point-2018-8 |title=Trump is latching on to a popular right-wing talking point about Michael Cohen that experts say is 'nonsense' |website=[[Business Insider]] |accessdate=August 25, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180826093407/http://uk.businessinsider.com/trump-michael-cohen-crimes-not-crimes-talking-point-2018-8 |archive-date=August 26, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> charges: five counts of [[tax evasion]], one count of making false statements to a financial institution, one count of willfully causing an unlawful corporate contribution, and one count of making an excessive campaign contribution at the request of a candidate (Trump) for the \"principal purpose of influencing [the] election\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/michael-cohen-to-plead-guilty-to-criminal-charges-1534875978 |title=Michael Cohen Pleads Guilty, Says He Acted at Trump's Direction |first1=Nicole |last1=Hong |first2=Rebecca |last2=Ballhaus|date=August 21, 2018 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |access-date=August 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821205500/https://www.wsj.com/articles/michael-cohen-to-plead-guilty-to-criminal-charges-1534875978 |archive-date=August 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Ex-Trump lawyer\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-45265546 |title=Ex-Trump lawyer admits campaign violation |date=August 21, 2018 |work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=August 21, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180821180933/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-45265546 |archive-date=August 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Ex-Trump lawyer\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/08/21/trumps-ex-lawyer-michael-cohen-strikes-plea-deal-nbc-news.html |title=Trump's former lawyer Michael Cohen pleads guilty, admits to making illegal payments at direction of candidate to influence election |first1=Tucker |last1=Higgins|first2=Kevin |last2=Breuninger |date=August 21, 2018 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |access-date=August 21, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180821211608/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/08/21/trumps-ex-lawyer-michael-cohen-strikes-plea-deal-nbc-news.html |archive-date=August 21, 2018 |url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter Cohen's conviction, his personal lawyer [[Lanny Davis]] stated that Cohen was ready to \"tell everything about Donald Trump that he knows\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-45270339 |title=Trump ex-lawyer 'happy' to aid Russia probe |date=August 22, 2018 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=August 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180822115807/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-45270339 |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Davis alluded to Cohen's knowledge that could be used against Trump, and hinted that Cohen had knowledge of whether Trump knew in advance about the computer hacking that was detrimental to [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2016|Hillary Clinton's presidential campaign]], as well as knowledge of the [[Trump Tower meeting|meeting at Trump Tower]] in June 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Becker |first1=Isaac |title=Cohen lawyer Lanny Davis suggests his client has knowledge implicating Trump in 'criminal conspiracy' to hack Democratic emails |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2018/08/22/cohen-lawyer-lanny-davis-suggests-his-client-has-knowledge-implicating-trump-in-criminal-conspiracy-to-hack-democratic-emails/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180822084903/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2018/08/22/cohen-lawyer-lanny-davis-suggests-his-client-has-knowledge-implicating-trump-in-criminal-conspiracy-to-hack-democratic-emails/ |archive-date= August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> He later added that he believed Cohen would agree to testify before Congress, even without immunity.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/22/politics/lanny-davis-michael-cohen-testify-no-immunity-cnntv/index.html |title=Cohen lawyer says he would testify to Congress about Trump without immunity |last=Vazquez |first=Maegan |date=August 22, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=August 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180822175008/https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/22/politics/lanny-davis-michael-cohen-testify-no-immunity-cnntv/index.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nResponding to speculation that President Trump might issue a [[Presidential pardon|pardon]] for Cohen, lawyer Davis said on [[NPR]], \"I know that Mr. Cohen would never accept a pardon from a man that he considers to be both corrupt and a dangerous person in the oval office. And [Cohen] has flatly authorized me to say under no circumstances would he accept a pardon from Mr. Trump.\"<ref>{{cite news |publisher=[[NPR]] |work=[[Morning Edition]] |first=Colin |last=Dwyer |first2=Ryan |last2=Lucas |title=Michael Cohen's Lawyer Says His Client Would Never Accept Pardon From 'Corrupt' Trump |url= https://www.npr.org/2018/08/22/640795902/michael-cohens-lawyer-says-hed-never-accept-a-pardon-from-president-trump |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180822150154/https://www.npr.org/2018/08/22/640795902/michael-cohens-lawyer-says-hed-never-accept-a-pardon-from-president-trump |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In his interview to Sky News, Davis said the turning point for his client's attitude toward Trump was the [[2018 Russia\u2013United States summit|Helsinki summit]] in July 2018, which caused him to doubt Trump's loyalty to the U.S.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://news.sky.com/story/putin-news-conference-drove-michael-cohen-away-from-trump-11479458 |title=Putin news conference drove Michael Cohen away from Trump|publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=August 22, 2018 |accessdate=August 22, 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180823005921/https://news.sky.com/story/putin-news-conference-drove-michael-cohen-away-from-trump-11479458|archive-date=August 23, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n''The New York Times'' reported on August 22, 2018, that Cohen court documents revealed that two senior [[Trump Organization]] executives were also involved in the [[hush money]] payments, and that Cohen \"coordinated with one or more members of the campaign, including through meetings and phone calls\" about the payments.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/22/nyregion/cohen-trump-organization-campaign-hush-money.html |title=Cohen Wasn't Alone: Records Suggest Others in Trump Circle Had Role in Hush Money Arrangements|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 22, 2018 |first=William K. |last=Rashbaum |accessdate=August 22, 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180823012340/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/22/nyregion/cohen-trump-organization-campaign-hush-money.html|archive-date=August 23, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nBy mid-October 2018, Cohen had sat for at least 50 hours of interviews with Mueller's investigators and other investigators, although he had no formal cooperation agreement with prosecutors.<ref>[[Emily Jane Fox|Fox, Emily Jane]] (October 15, 2018). [https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2018/10/michael-cohen-trump-investigation \"He Is Trying to Make It Right\": As the Midterms Approach, Michael Cohen Is Doubling Down on His Civic Duty] {{Webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181128175341/https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2018/10/michael-cohen-trump-investigation |date=November 28, 2018}}, ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''.</ref> Cohen also cooperated in a separate investigation by New York State investigators regarding the Trump Organization and Trump Foundation.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/michael-cohen-spoke-mueller-team-hours-asked-russia/story?id=57959664 |title=Michael Cohen spoke to Mueller team for hours; asked about Russia, possible collusion |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=September 20, 2018 |access-date=September 20, 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180921000523/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/michael-cohen-spoke-mueller-team-hours-asked-russia/story?id=57959664 |archive-date=September 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn December 12, 2018, U.S. District Judge [[William H. Pauley III]] sentenced Cohen to three years in prison and a $50,000 fine, and additionally ordered Cohen to pay $1.4&nbsp;million in restitution and to [[criminal forfeiture|forfeit]] $500,000.<ref name=\"UPI\">Cone, Allen; Adamczyk, Ed (December 13, 2018). [https://www.upi.com/Michael-Cohen-sentenced-to-3-years-in-prison-stemming-from-plea-deal/5891544588060 Michael Cohen sentenced to 3 years in prison stemming from plea deal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215224102/https://www.upi.com/Michael-Cohen-sentenced-to-3-years-in-prison-stemming-from-plea-deal/5891544588060 |date=December 15, 2018}}, [[United Press International]].</ref><ref>\nHamilton, Colby (December 12, 2018). [https://www.law.com/2018/12/12/cohen-sentenced-to-36-months-in-prison-in-sdny-mueller-prosecutions/?slreturn=20181112163109 Cohen's 'Blind Loyalty' Leads to 3-Year Prison Term] {{Webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181215224824/https://www.law.com/2018/12/12/cohen-sentenced-to-36-months-in-prison-in-sdny-mueller-prosecutions/?slreturn=20181112163109 |date=December 15, 2018}}, ''[[New York Law Journal]]''.</ref><ref name=\"BBC 12/12/2018\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-46546238 |title=Ex-Trump lawyer Cohen jailed for 36 months |date=December 12, 2018 |work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=December 12, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181212193446/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-46546238 |archive-date=December 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> At his sentencing hearing, Cohen stated: \"I take full responsibility for each act that I pled guilty to: The personal ones to me and those involving the president of the United States of America.\"<ref name=\"UPI\" /> Cohen said Trump was \"the man that caused me to choose the path of darkness\" and do \"dirty deeds\".<ref name=\"BBC 12/12/2018\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/12/12/former-donald-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-sentenced-blind-loyalty/2274755002/|title=Michael Cohen, Trump's former lawyer, is sentenced to three years in prison for 'dirty deeds' |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=December 12, 2018 |access-date=December 12, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181212175530/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/12/12/former-donald-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-sentenced-blind-loyalty/2274755002/ |archive-date=December 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Before passing sentence, Judge Pauley said, \"each of these crimes is a serious offense against the United States. Mr. Cohen pled guilty to a veritable smorgasbord of fraudulent conduct.\"<ref name=\"UPI\" />\n\n===Conviction for perjury in congressional testimony===\nOn November 29, 2018, Cohen pleaded guilty to lying to the [[Senate Intelligence Committee]] and [[House Intelligence Committee]] in 2017 regarding the proposed [[Trump Tower Moscow]] deal that he spearheaded in 2015 and 2016.<ref name=\"GuiltyMoscowProject\" /><ref name=\"CongPerjury\">{{cite news |first=Devlin |last=Barrett |first2=Matt |last2=Zapotosky |author3link=Rosalind Helderman |first3=Rosalind S. |last3=Helderman |title=Michael Cohen, Trump's former lawyer, pleads guilty to lying to Congress about Moscow project |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/michael-cohen-trumps-former-lawyer-pleads-guilty-to-lying-to-congress/2018/11/29/5fac986a-f3e0-11e8-bc79-68604ed88993_story.html |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=November 29, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129161726/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/michael-cohen-trumps-former-lawyer-pleads-guilty-to-lying-to-congress/2018/11/29/5fac986a-f3e0-11e8-bc79-68604ed88993_story.html |archive-date=November 29, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Cohen had told Congress that the deal ceased in January 2016 when it actually ended in June 2016, and that he had not received a response about the deal from the office of a senior Russian official when he actually had.<ref name=\"CongPerjury\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-46390368 |title=Trump ex-lawyer admits lying to Congress |date=November 29, 2018 |accessdate=December 1, 2018 |work=[[BBC News]]|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181130122304/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-46390368 |archive-date=November 30, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen said that he had given the false testimony in order to be consistent with Trump's \"repeated disavowals of commercial and political ties between himself and Russia\" and out of loyalty to Trump.<ref name=\"CongPerjury\" /> Cohen received a two-month sentence, to be served concurrently with his three-year sentence for tax fraud, for the false testimony.<ref name=\"CNBC Cohen Sentenced\" />\n\nThis charge was brought directly by [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Robert Mueller's investigation]], rather than the United States Attorney for the SDNY, who brought the previous charges against Cohen.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/11/29/michael-cohen-robert-mueller-trump-plea-deal/2147323002/ |title=Robert Mueller probe: Ex-Trump lawyer Michael Cohen pleads guilty to lying to Congress |date=November 29, 2018 |work=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=November 30, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181130011357/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/11/29/michael-cohen-robert-mueller-trump-plea-deal/2147323002/ |archive-date=November 30, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In a sentencing memorandum filed the following day, Cohen's attorneys stated he kept Trump \"apprised\" of the \"substantive conversation\" Cohen had in January 2016 with a Russian official, and discussed with Trump traveling to Russia to advance the project during the summer of 2016. The filing also stated Cohen \"remained in close and regular contact with White House-based staff and legal counsel\" as he prepared to provide false testimony to Congress.<ref>{{cite news |date=December 1, 2018 |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-russia/ex-lawyer-says-he-told-trump-about-kremlin-contact-court-filing-idUSKCN1O03E0 |title=Ex-lawyer says he told Trump about Kremlin contact: court filing |work=[[Reuters]] |accessdate= December 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181201193414/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-russia/ex-lawyer-says-he-told-trump-about-kremlin-contact-court-filing-idUSKCN1O03E0 |archive-date=December 1, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a [[BuzzFeed]] report on January 17, 2019, President [[Donald Trump]] personally directed Cohen to lie to Congress about the [[Trump Tower Moscow]] project.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sullivan |first=Kate |authorlink=Kate Sullivan |publisher=[[CNN]] |title=BuzzFeed: Sources say Trump directed Michael Cohen to lie to Congress about proposed Moscow project |date=January 18, 2019 |accessdate=January 18, 2018 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/17/politics/buzzfeed-trump-cohen-lie-congress-moscow/index.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190118050831/https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/17/politics/buzzfeed-trump-cohen-lie-congress-moscow/index.html |archive-date=January 18, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Elfrink |first=Tim |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |title=Democrats demand investigation after report that Trump ordered Michael Cohen to lie to Congress |date=January 18, 2019 |accessdate=January 18, 2019 |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/01/18/democrats-demand-investigation-after-report-that-trump-ordered-michael-cohen-lie-congress-about-russian-project/ |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190118082548/https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/01/18/democrats-demand-investigation-after-report-that-trump-ordered-michael-cohen-lie-congress-about-russian-project/ |archive-date=January 18, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> However, a spokesman for the Special Counsel investigation later said the report was \"not accurate\", but did not specify \"which parts of the BuzzFeed story they were calling untrue\".<ref name=\"Polantz Kelly 2019\">{{cite news |last=Polantz |first=Katelyn |last2=Kelly |first2=Caroline |title=Mueller's office disputes BuzzFeed report that Trump directed Michael Cohen to lie to Congress |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=January 19, 2019 |url= https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/18/politics/mueller-statement-buzzfeed/index.html |access-date=January 19, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190119012435/https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/18/politics/mueller-statement-buzzfeed/index.html |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn February 26, 2019, he was officially [[Disbarment|disbarred]] by the [[New York State Bar Association]].<ref name=\":0\">https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/justice-department/michael-cohen-has-been-disbarred-n976436</ref>\n\n==State of New York's investigations==\n{{Anchor|State investigations}}\nOn August 22, 2018, it was announced that the [[New York State Department of Taxation and Finance]] had subpoenaed Cohen in connection with its investigation into whether the [[Donald J. Trump Foundation]] had violated [[New York tax law]]s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/22/politics/michael-cohen-trump-foundation-subpoena/ |title=New York tax investigators subpoena Michael Cohen in Trump Foundation probe |last1=Orden |first1=Erica |last2=Tatum |first2=Sophie |date= August 22, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180822224534/https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/22/politics/michael-cohen-trump-foundation-subpoena/ }}</ref> This investigation is separate from the [[New York Attorney General]]'s lawsuit alleging that the foundation and its directors violated state and federal laws about the operation of charities.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/14/politics/new-york-lawsuit-trump-foundation/ |title=New York attorney general sues Trump Foundation |last1=Isidore |first1=Chris |last2=Schuman |first2=Melanie |date=June 14, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate= August 23, 2018 |archive-date=August 24, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180824002227/https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/14/politics/new-york-lawsuit-trump-foundation/ }}\n</ref>\n\n==Congressional investigations==\nOn January 10, 2019, Cohen agreed to testify publicly before the [[House Oversight Committee]] to give a \"full and credible account\" of his work on behalf of Trump.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/10/us/politics/michael-cohen-testify-trump-congress.html |title=Michael Cohen Agrees to Testify to Congress About Work for Trump|last=Haberman |first=Maggie |authorlink=Maggie Haberman |date=January 10, 2019|work=[[The New York Times]] |last2=Fandos|first2=Nicholas |access-date=January 10, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190110202807/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/10/us/politics/michael-cohen-testify-trump-congress.html|archive-date=January 10, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On January 12, Fox News\u00a0contributor and legal analyst\u00a0[[Jeanine Pirro]]\u00a0took a 20-minute, on-air phone call from Trump in which he claimed Cohen had fabricated stories to reduce the length of his expected sentence. Trump suggested that investigations should instead focus on Cohen's father-in-law, saying \"that's the one people want to look at.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/beta-story-container/Politics/michael-cohen-fears-trump-rhetoric-place-family-risk/story?id=60430893 |title=Michael Cohen fears Trump rhetoric could put his family at risk: Sources |last1=Larramendia |first1=Eliana |last2=Hill |first2=James |date=January 16, 2019 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |accessdate=January 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227223857/https://abcnews.go.com/beta-story-container/Politics/michael-cohen-fears-trump-rhetoric-place-family-risk/story?id=60430893 |archive-date=February 27, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The father-in-law, Fima Shusterman, owned condos both at Trump Tower and in a Trump development near Miami.<ref>Gualtieri, Allison Elyse. [https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/who-is-michael-cohens-father-in-law-trump-says-he-should-be-investigated Who is Michael Cohen's father-in-law? Trump says he should be investigated] {{Webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190124203949/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/who-is-michael-cohens-father-in-law-trump-says-he-should-be-investigated |date=January 24, 2019}}, ''[[Washington Examiner]]'', January 12, 2019. Retrieved January 24, 2019.</ref> According to former federal investigators, Shusterman actually introduced Trump to Cohen.<ref name=\"Rolling Stone Brief History of Criminal Ties\">Hettena, Seth. [https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/a-brief-history-of-michael-cohens-criminal-ties-628875/ A Brief History of Michael Cohen's Criminal Ties From the Russian mob to money launderers, Trump's personal attorney has long been a subject of interest to federal investigators] {{Webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190116175418/https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/a-brief-history-of-michael-cohens-criminal-ties-628875/ |date=January 16, 2019}}, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', April 10, 2018. Retrieved January 24, 2019.</ref>\u00a0On several subsequent occasions Trump hinted publicly that Cohen's father-in-law, or possibly even Cohen's wife, could be tied to criminal activity. On January 20 Trump's attorney Rudy Giuliani suggested on CNN that the father-in-law \"may have ties to something called organized crime\".<ref name=\"explained\">{{cite news |url= https://www.vox.com/2019/1/23/18194719/trump-michael-cohen-father-in-law-threat |title=Michael Cohen's claim that President Trump is threatening his family, explained |last=Prokop |first=Andrew |date=January 24, 2019 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |accessdate=January 25, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190125005548/https://www.vox.com/2019/1/23/18194719/trump-michael-cohen-father-in-law-threat |archive-date=January 25, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn January 23, Cohen announced through his attorney that he would postpone his testimony to a later date, citing \"ongoing threats against his family from President Trump\" and Giuliani.<ref name=\"explained\"/> Some legal analysts asserted that these comments by Trump and Giuliani constituted intimidation and witness tampering;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abajournal.com/news/article/following-fox-news-interview-some-wonder-if-president-engaged-in-obstruction/?icn=most_read |title=Legal experts weigh in on Trump's Cohen comments and whether they amount to witness intimidation |last=Ward |first=Stephanie Francis |date=January 15, 2019 |work=[[ABA Journal]] |accessdate=January 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190126061131/http://www.abajournal.com/news/article/following-fox-news-interview-some-wonder-if-president-engaged-in-obstruction/?icn=most_read|archive-date=January 26, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> House Oversight Committee chairman [[Elijah Cummings]] and [[House Intelligence Committee]] chairman [[Adam Schiff]] said that threatening a witness's family is \"textbook mob tactics\".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/23/us/politics/michael-cohen-testimony-postponed-congress.html |title=Michael Cohen Indefinitely Postpones Testimony to Congress, Citing Fears of Family's Safety|first=Maggie|last=Haberman |authorlink=Maggie Haberman |date=January 23, 2019|work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=January 24, 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190124011634/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/23/us/politics/michael-cohen-testimony-postponed-congress.html|archive-date=January 24, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/01/23/michael-cohen-says-trump-giuliani-threatened-him-does-that-amount-witness-tampering/|title=Analysis &#124; Michael Cohen says Trump and Giuliani threatened him. Does that amount to witness tampering?|work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=January 24, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190124010656/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/01/23/michael-cohen-says-trump-giuliani-threatened-him-does-that-amount-witness-tampering/ |archive-date=January 24, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter several scheduling delays, Cohen testified before three congressional committees in late February. First was a February 26, 2019, closed-door hearing before the Senate Intelligence Committee. He testified for more than seven hours.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/michael-cohen-testimony-lawmakers-to-grill-cohen-on-trump-tower-deal-during-closed-door-hearing/|title=Cohen to face questions on Trump Tower deal, BuzzFeed report at closed-door hearing|last=Montoya-Galvez|first=Camilo|date=February 25, 2019|work=CBS News|accessdate=4 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306042706/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/michael-cohen-testimony-lawmakers-to-grill-cohen-on-trump-tower-deal-during-closed-door-hearing/|archive-date=March 6, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAlso on February 26, [[Florida's 1st congressional district|Florida Republican Congressman]] [[Matt Gaetz]] directly threatened Cohen via Twitter, hinting about unspecified disclosures to Cohen's wife and father-in-law.<ref>{{cite news |title=A high-profile Trump ally in Congress just straight-up threatened Michael Cohen |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/26/politics/matt-gaetz-tweet-michael-cohen/index.html |date=2019-02-27 |publisher=[[CNN]] |authorlink=Chris Cillizza |first=Chris |last=Cillizza |accessdate=2019-02-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228002541/https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/26/politics/matt-gaetz-tweet-michael-cohen/index.html |archive-date=February 28, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=GOP Congressman Threatens Michael Cohen on Twitter, Then Apologizes |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/02/gop-congressman-may-have-threatened-michael-cohen-on-twitter.html |date=2019-02-27 |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |first=Matt |last=Stieb |accessdate=2019-02-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228191835/http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/02/gop-congressman-may-have-threatened-michael-cohen-on-twitter.html |archive-date=February 28, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The [[Florida Bar Association]] plans to investigate the incident.<ref>{{cite news |title=Florida Bar Will Investigate Matt Gaetz's Threat Against Cohen |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/27/us/politics/matt-gaetz-cohen.html |date=2019-02-27 |work=[[The New York Times]] |first=Nicholas |last=Fandos |accessdate=2019-02-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227230212/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/27/us/politics/matt-gaetz-cohen.html |archive-date=February 27, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe following day, February 27, Cohen gave 10 hours of public, televised testimony before the House Oversight Committee, during which he described Trump as a \"racist,\" a \"con man\", and a \"cheat\", and expressed remorse and shame for the things he had done for Trump. He said the president had reimbursed him for illegal hush money payments, suggested that he should lie to Congress and the public about the Trump Tower Moscow negotiations, and filed false financial statements with banks and insurance companies. Republicans hammered on his previous false testimony, asking why he should be believed now.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/02/27/ex-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-testify-house-oversight-committee/2995659002/|title='I am not protecting Mr. Trump anymore.' Michael Cohen ties the president to ongoing criminal probes|date=February 27, 2019|work=USA Today|accessdate=4 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301151914/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/02/27/ex-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-testify-house-oversight-committee/2995659002/|archive-date=March 1, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/02/27/696752450/michael-cohen-to-testify-publicly-before-congress-on-alleged-trump-lawbreaking|title=Michael Cohen Calls Trump A 'Racist' And A 'Con Man' In Scathing Testimony|last=Ewing|first=Philip|date=February 27, 2019|work=NPR|accessdate=4 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190304002320/https://www.npr.org/2019/02/27/696752450/michael-cohen-to-testify-publicly-before-congress-on-alleged-trump-lawbreaking|archive-date=March 4, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn February 28, Cohen testified behind closed doors to the House Intelligence Committee for more than seven hours. Cohen returned to that committee for more questioning on March 6.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/28/politics/michael-cohen-testimony-house-intelligence-committee/index.html|title=Michael Cohen will return to Congress March 6, Felix Sater to testify March 14|date=February 28, 2019|work=CNN|accessdate=4 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190304042611/https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/28/politics/michael-cohen-testimony-house-intelligence-committee/index.html|archive-date=March 4, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCohen married [[Ukrainians|Ukrainian]]-born Laura Shusterman in 1994.<ref name=\"FootSoldier\" /><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/michael-cohens-ties-to-russia-crime-and-trump-w518941 |title=A Brief History of Michael Cohen's Criminal Ties|last=Hettena|first=Seth|date=April 10, 2018|work=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=August 23, 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180616205156/https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/michael-cohens-ties-to-russia-crime-and-trump-w518941|archive-date=June 16, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT180504\">{{cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/05/business/michael-cohen-lawyer-trump.html |title=How Michael Cohen, Trump's Fixer, Built a Shadowy Business Empire|last1=Rashbaum|first1=William K.|date=May 5, 2018|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |last2=Hakim |first2=Danny |last3=Rosenthal |first3=Brian M. |last4=Flitter |first4=Emily |last5=Drucker |first5=Jesse |access-date=May 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180505203455/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/05/business/michael-cohen-lawyer-trump.html|archive-date=May 5, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Laura Shusterman's father, Fima Shusterman, left [[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic|Soviet Ukraine]] for New York in 1975.<ref name=\"NYT180504\" /> They have a daughter, Samantha, and a son, Jake.<ref name=\"LAT20181213\">{{Cite news|first1=Chris|last1=Megerian|first2=Sonja|last2=Sharp |title= Michael Cohen, Trump's longtime lawyer, sentenced to three years in prison|date=December 12, 2018|url= https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-michael-cohen-sentencing-20181212-story.html|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=December 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181213023808/https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-michael-cohen-sentencing-20181212-story.html|archive-date=December 13, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen's father-in-law was the person who introduced him to Trump, according to a Trump biographer.<ref name=\"Rolling Stone Brief History of Criminal Ties\" /><ref>Kwong, Jessica. (December 3, 2018). \"Who is Michael Cohen's wife? Laura Shusterman never charged though prosecutors had evidence implicating her, according to report.\" [https://www.newsweek.com/who-michael-cohen-wife-laura-shusterman-1242311 Newsweek website] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116065334/https://www.newsweek.com/who-michael-cohen-wife-laura-shusterman-1242311 |date=January 16, 2019}} ''[[Newsweek]]''. Retrieved December 16, 2018.</ref> Cohen's uncle is a doctor who treated members of the [[Lucchese crime family]].<ref name=\"NYT180504\" /> The uncle owned \"El Caribe Country Club\", known to be frequented by individuals associated with the [[Russian mafia]]: [[Evsei Agron]], [[Marat Balagula]], and [[Boris Nayfeld]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Hettena |first=Seth |date=May 2018 |title=Trump / Russia: A Definitive History |url= https://www.mhpbooks.com/books/trump-russia |publisher=Melville House |page=80 |isbn=978-1612197395 |access-date= December 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131232058/https://www.mhpbooks.com/books/trump-russia/ |archive-date=January 31, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nCohen served as chairman of the board of directors of [[Columbia Grammar & Preparatory School]] through late 2016.\n\nBefore joining the Trump Organization, Cohen had purchased several homes in Trump's buildings.<ref name=\"Falcone\" /> A 2017 ''New York Times'' article reported that Cohen is known for having \"a penchant for [[luxury goods|luxury]]\"; he was married at [[The Pierre]], drove a [[Porsche]] while attending college, and once owned a [[Bentley]].<ref name=\"FootSoldier\" />\n\n==In popular culture==\nAs the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|investigation surrounding Donald Trump]] was in the daily news headlines, the story became fodder for parody on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', with Trump being portrayed by [[Alec Baldwin]] and Cohen by [[Ben Stiller]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cadenas |first1=Kerensa |title=Alec Baldwin Returns to S.N.L. as Trump with Ben Stiller as Michael Cohen |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/12/alec-baldwin-snl-trump-ben-stiller-michael-cohen |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=December 2, 2018 |access-date=December 13, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227223857/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/12/alec-baldwin-snl-trump-ben-stiller-michael-cohen |archive-date=February 27, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]]\n*[[Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections (July 2016\u2013election day)]]\n*[[Timeline of post-election transition following Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]]\n*[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (January\u2013June 2017)]]\n*[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (July\u2013December 2017)]]\n*[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (January\u2013June 2018)]]\n*[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (July\u2013December 2018)]]\n*[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (2019\u20132020)]]\n*[[Legal teams involved in the Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Michael D. Cohen}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Michael Cohen04}}\n*{{IMDb name}}\n\n{{Trump businesses}}\n{{Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cohen, Michael Dean}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:21st-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:American male criminals]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of campaign finance violations]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of tax crimes]]\n[[Category:American University alumni]]\n[[Category:Children of Holocaust survivors]]\n[[Category:Criminals from New York City]]\n[[Category:Disbarred American lawyers]]\n[[Category:Donald Trump litigation]]\n[[Category:Jewish American attorneys]]\n[[Category:Jews and Judaism in Nassau County, New York]]\n[[Category:Jews and Judaism in New York City]]\n[[Category:Lawrence Woodmere Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Mixed martial arts executives]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Lawrence, Nassau County, New York]]\n[[Category:People convicted of making false statements]]\n[[Category:The Trump Organization employees]]\n[[Category:Thomas M. Cooley Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:American chief operating officers]]\n[[Category:Trump administration controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the former lawyer of Donald Trump and The Trump Organization|the lawyer, author, and former Harvard professor|Michael H. Cohen}}\n{{short description|American former attorney}}\n{{use American English|date=September 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = Michael Cohen\n| image = File:Michael Cohen headshot.jpg\n| caption = Cohen in 2011\n| birth_name = Michael Dean Cohen\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1966|8|25}}\n| birth_place = [[Lawrence, Nassau County, New York]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| education = {{plainlist|\n*[[American University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n*[[Western Michigan University Cooley Law School|Cooley Law School]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\n| party = {{plainlist|\n*{{nowrap|[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]}} {{nowrap|(before 2002;}} {{nowrap|2004\u20132017;}} {{nowrap|2018\u2013present)}}\n*{{nowrap|[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]}} {{nowrap|(2002\u20132004; 2017\u20132018)}}}}\n| spouse = {{marriage|Laura Shusterman|1995}}\n| children = 2\n| module = '''Criminal information'''{{Infobox criminal\n | child = yes\n | conviction = [[Fraud]]; [[perjury]]\n | criminal_charge = {{Bulleted list |5 counts of [[tax evasion]]| 1 count of making false statements to a financial institution |1 count of willfully causing an unlawful corporate contribution |1 count of making an excessive campaign contribution at the request of a candidate or campaign |1 count of making false statements to a congressional committee}}\n | conviction_penalty = {{nowrap|3 years in federal prison;}} {{nowrap|fines;}} {{nowrap|[[asset forfeiture]];}} {{nowrap|[[disbarment]]}}\n | conviction_status = Currently incarcerated at [[Federal Correctional Institution, Otisville]] #86067-054.\n}}\n}}\n'''Michael Dean Cohen''' (born August 25, 1966) is an American former attorney.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2017/01/19/michael-cohen-special-counsel-to-donald-trump-will-follow-him-to-washington/ |title=Michael Cohen will stay Trump's personal attorney\u2014even in the White House |last=Helderman |first=Rosalind |authorlink=Rosalind Helderman |date=January 19, 2017 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=February 1, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170129230446/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2017/01/19/michael-cohen-special-counsel-to-donald-trump-will-follow-him-to-washington/ |archive-date=January 29, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/11/michael-cohen-not-trump-attorney-583902 |title= Giuliani: Cohen is not Trump's lawyer anymore 'as far as we know' |last=Samuelsohn |first=Darren |date=May 11, 2018 |work=[[Politico]] |accessdate=January 29, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190129010907/https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/11/michael-cohen-not-trump-attorney-583902 |archive-date=January 29, 2019 |url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nCohen was a vice-president of [[The Trump Organization]], and the personal counsel to Trump, and was often described by media as Trump's \"[[fixer (person)|fixer]]\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/dec/12/michael-cohen-sentence-trump-loyalty |title=From fixer to inmate: Michael Cohen reckons with his 'blind loyalty' to Trump |last=Durkin |first=Erin |date=December 12, 2018 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=December 14, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181213194232/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/dec/12/michael-cohen-sentence-trump-loyalty |archive-date=December 13, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Stracqualursi |first=Veronica |title=Michael Cohen says Donald Trump knew hush payments were wrong |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=December 14, 2018 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/14/politics/michael-cohen-abc-interview/index.html |access-date= December 15, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181214211037/https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/14/politics/michael-cohen-abc-interview/index.html |archive-date=December 14, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> He previously served as co-president of [[Trump Entertainment]] and was a board member of the [[Eric Trump Foundation]], a children's health charity.<ref name=\"Nathan-Kazis\">{{cite news |url=http://forward.com/news/312123/meet-michael-cohen-donald-trumps-jewish-wingman/ |title=Meet Michael Cohen, Donald Trump's Jewish Wingman |last=Nathan-Kazis |first=Josh |date=July 20, 2015 |newspaper=[[The Forward]] |access-date=January 15, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160108172407/http://forward.com/news/312123/meet-michael-cohen-donald-trumps-jewish-wingman/ |archive-date=January 8, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> From 2017 to 2018, Cohen was deputy finance chairman of the [[Republican National Committee]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-rnc-finance-executive-2017-4 |title=Trump's personal lawyer will serve as key RNC finance executive |last=Sheth |first=Sonam |website=[[Business Insider]] |access-date=August 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180822050010/https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-rnc-finance-executive-2017-4 |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC News Cohen Resigns RNC\">{{Cite news |url= https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/michael-cohen-resigns-rnc-committee-post/story?id=56033406 |title=Michael Cohen resigns from RNC committee post, sources say |last=Larramendia |first=Eliana |first2=Zunaira |last2=Zaki |date=June 20, 2018 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |access-date=August 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180821202114/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/michael-cohen-resigns-rnc-committee-post/story?id=56033406 |archive-date=August 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nTrump employed Cohen until May 2018, a year after the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Special Counsel investigation]] into [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]] began, where nothing was proven, nor found. The investigation led him to plead guilty on August 21, 2018, to eight counts including [[campaign finance]] violations, [[tax fraud]], and [[bank fraud]]. <ref name=\"CNBC Cohen Sentenced\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/12/12/trumps-ex-lawyer-and-fixer-michael-cohen-sentenced-to-3-years.html |title=Trump's ex-lawyer and fixer Michael Cohen sentenced to 3 years |first1=Dan |last1=Mangan |first2=Kevin |last2=Breuninger |date=December 12, 2018 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |access-date=December 12, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181212171703/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/12/12/trumps-ex-lawyer-and-fixer-michael-cohen-sentenced-to-3-years.html |archive-date=December 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen said he violated campaign finance laws at the direction of Trump and \"for the principal purpose of influencing\" the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/21/nyregion/michael-cohen-plea-deal-trump.html |title= Michael Cohen Says He Arranged Payments to Women at Trump's Direction |date=August 21, 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |first=William K. |last=Rashbaum |first2=Maggie |last2=Haberman |author2link=Maggie Haberman |first3=Ben |last3=Protess |first4=Jim |last4=Rutenberg |author4link=Jim Rutenberg |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180821234039/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/21/nyregion/michael-cohen-plea-deal-trump.html |archive-date=August 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In November 2018, Cohen entered a second guilty plea for lying to a Senate committee about efforts to build a [[Trump Tower Moscow|Trump Tower in Moscow]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/cohen-new-charge-trump-1.4925270 |title=Michael Cohen pleads guilty to lying to Senate about Trump Tower project in Russia |date=November 29, 2018 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] |accessdate=December 13, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211134921/https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/cohen-new-charge-trump-1.4925270 |archive-date=December 11, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"GuiltyMoscowProject\">{{cite news |url= https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/29/politics/michael-cohen-guilty-plea-misleading-congress/ |title=Michael Cohen pleads guilty, says he lied about Trump's knowledge of Moscow project |first=Erica |last=Orden |first2=Kara |last2=Scannell |first3=Pamela |last3=Brown |author3link=Pamela Brown (journalist) |first4=Stephen |last4=Collinson |first5=Gloria |last5=Borger |author5link=Gloria Borger |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=November 29, 2018 |access-date=November 29, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181129173824/https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/29/politics/michael-cohen-guilty-plea-misleading-congress/ |archive-date=November 29, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn December 12, 2018, he was sentenced to three years in [[federal prison]] and ordered to pay a $50,000 fine after making a deal to falsely make claims about President Trump to aid in a faulty, and flimsy impeachment hearing. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://politi.co/2rwGkYV|title=Michael Cohen sentenced to 3 years in prison|last=Nahmias|first=Laura|last2=Samuelsohn|first2=Darren|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2019-12-25}}</ref> On February 26, 2019, he was officially [[Disbarment|disbarred]] by the [[New York State Bar Association]].<ref name=\":0\" /> He reported to [[Federal Correctional Institution, Otisville|the federal prison near Otisville, New York]], on May 6, 2019.{{r|\"CNBC Cohen Sentenced\"}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/former-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-sentenced-prison-asked-lockup-otisville-n947101 |title=Former Trump lawyer Michael Cohen, sentenced to prison, asked for this lockup |publisher=[[NBC News]] |access-date=February 5, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190116220735/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/former-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-sentenced-prison-asked-lockup-otisville-n947101 |archive-date=January 16, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sisak |first1=Michael R. |last2=Mustian |first2=Jim |title=Ex-Trump lawyer Michael Cohen arrives at prison |url=https://www.sfgate.com/news/crime/article/Michael-Cohen-heads-to-prison-in-Trump-hush-money-13821472.php |accessdate=6 May 2019 |work=SFGate |agency=Associated Press |date=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn April 16, 2020, it was reported that Cohen will be released from prison early due to the threats of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], to serve the rest of his sentence under [[house arrest]]. <ref>https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/16/politics/michael-cohen-to-be-released-prison-coronavirus/index.html</ref><ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-cohen/ex-trump-lawyer-cohen-to-be-released-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak-sources-idUSKBN21Z0EJ</ref><ref>https://thehill.com/homenews/news/493275-michael-cohen-to-be-released-early-from-prison-amid-coronavirus-pandemic-report</ref>\n{{toclimit|3}}\n\n==Early life and education==\nCohen grew up in the town of [[Lawrence, Nassau County, New York|Lawrence]] on [[Long Island]], New York.<ref name=\"Nathan-Kazis\" /> His mother was a nurse, and his father, who [[Holocaust survivor|survived]] the [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]], was a surgeon.<ref name=\"Nathan-Kazis\" /><ref name=\"Falcone\">{{cite news |last=Falcone |first=Michael |title=Donald Trump's Political 'Pit Bull': Meet Michael Cohen |date=April 16, 2011 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/donald-trumps-political-pit-bull-meet-michael-cohen/story?id=13386747 |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227180415/http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/donald-trumps-political-pit-bull-meet-michael-cohen/story?id=13386747 |archive-date=February 27, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Cohen is [[Jewish]].<ref name=\"heritage\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-news-and-politics/207978/trumps-jews |title=Trump's Jews |last=Rosen |first=Armin |date=July 15, 2016 |magazine=[[Tablet (magazine)|Tablet]] |access-date=March 9, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170312040858/http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-news-and-politics/207978/trumps-jews |archive-date= March 12, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> He attended [[Woodmere Academy]]<ref name=\"NYC Studios Cohen Company\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wnycstudios.org/story/trump-inc-podcast-company-michael-cohen-kept |title=The Company Michael Cohen Kept |first=Meg |last=Cramer |publisher=[[New York Public Radio]] |date=April 18, 2018 |access-date=May 2, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180502184853/https://www.wnycstudios.org/story/trump-inc-podcast-company-michael-cohen-kept/ |archive-date=May 2, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> and received his BA from [[American University]] in 1988 and his [[Juris Doctor|JD]] from [[Western Michigan University Cooley Law School|Thomas M. Cooley Law School]] in 1991.<ref name=\"NizerCohenBio\" />\n\n==Career==\n===Legal career===\nCohen began practicing personal injury law in New York in 1992, working for Melvyn Estrin in [[Manhattan]].<ref name=\"NYC Studios Cohen Company\" /><ref name=\"FootSoldier\" /> As of 2003, Cohen was an attorney in private practice and CEO of MLA Cruises, Inc., and of the Atlantic Casino.<ref name=\"NYCCFB Statement\">{{cite web |title=4th City Council District, Michael D. Cohen, Republican |work=2003 Voter Guide |url=http://www.nyccfb.info/public/voter-guide/general_2003/cd_statement/CD04_Cohen_769.htm |publisher=[[New York City Campaign Finance Board]] |access-date=April 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413034135/http://www.nyccfb.info/public/voter-guide/general_2003/cd_statement/CD04_Cohen_769.htm |archive-date=April 13, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Cohen was a partner at the law firm Phillips, Nizer, Benjamin, Krim & Ballon.<ref name=\"NizerCohenBio\">{{cite web |title=Michael D. Cohen \u2013 Attorney Bio |url= http://www.phillipsnizer.com/attorneys/cohenmichael_bio.cfm |publisher=Phillips Nizer |accessdate=April 10, 2018 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20061023023606/http://www.phillipsnizer.com/attorneys/cohenmichael_bio.cfm |archivedate=October 23, 2006}}</ref> He practiced law at the firm for about a year before joining The Trump Organization.<ref name=\"FootSoldier\">{{cite news |last1=Schwirtz |first1=Michael |title=Trump Foot Soldier Sidelined Under Glare of Russia Inquiry |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/02/us/politics/michael-cohen-donald-trump.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 2, 2017 |access-date=July 3, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170703045200/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/02/us/politics/michael-cohen-donald-trump.html |archive-date=July 3, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Following his 2018 felony convictions, Cohen was automatically disbarred in New York.<ref>{{cite news |title=New York law mandates ex-Trump lawyer Michael Cohen be disbarred for felonies |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/08/22/michael-cohen-new-york-possible-disbarment/1067364002/ |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=December 27, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181227230342/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/08/22/michael-cohen-new-york-possible-disbarment/1067364002/ |archive-date=December 27, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Business ventures===\nIn 2003, Cohen was a candidate for [[New York City Council]] when he provided a biography to the New York City Campaign Finance Board for inclusion in its voters' guide. The guide listed him as co-owner of Taxi Funding Corp. and a fleet of [[taxicabs of New York City|New York City taxicabs]] numbering over 200.<ref name=\"NYCCFB Statement\" /><ref name=\"ShearRecords\">{{cite news |first=Michael D. |last=Shear |authorlink=Michael D. Shear |authorlink2=Matt Apuzzo |first2=Matt |last2=Apuzzo |authorlink3=Sharon LaFraniere |first3=Sharon |last3=LaFraniere |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/10/us/politics/trump-russia-mueller-rosenstein.html |title=Raids on Trump's Lawyer Sought Records of Payments to Women |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 10, 2018 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180412041228/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/10/us/politics/trump-russia-mueller-rosenstein.html |archive-date=April 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Brenzel\">{{cite magazine |first=Kathryn |last=Brenzel |url=https://therealdeal.com/2018/02/27/meet-trump-attorney-michael-cohens-nemesis-uber/ |title=Meet Trump attorney Michael Cohen's nemesis: Uber |magazine=[[The Real Deal (magazine)|The Real Deal]] |date=February 27, 2018 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825021636/https://therealdeal.com/2018/02/27/meet-trump-attorney-michael-cohens-nemesis-uber/ |archive-date=August 25, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> At the time, Cohen was a business partner in the taxi business with \"taxi king\" [[Simon Garber]].<ref name=\"Brenzel\" /> As of 2017, Cohen was estimated to own at least 34 [[taxicabs of New York City#Medallions|taxi medallions]] through 17 [[limited liability companies]] (LLCs).<ref name=\"Brenzel\" /> Until April 2017, another \"taxi king\", disbarred attorney and convicted [[felon]] [[Gene Freidman]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/evgeny-freidman-michael-cohens-business-partner-known-as-the-taxi-king-pleads-guilty-to-fraud/ |title=Michael Cohen's business partner, known as \"Taxi King\", pleads guilty in deal |publisher=[[CBS News]] |accessdate=September 20, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181116151750/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/evgeny-freidman-michael-cohens-business-partner-known-as-the-taxi-king-pleads-guilty-to-fraud/ |archive-date=November 16, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> managed the medallions still held by Cohen; this arrangement ended after the city's [[Taxi and Limousine Commission]] decided not to renew Freidman's licenses.<ref name=\"Brenzel\" /> Between April and June 2017, the [[New York State Department of Taxation and Finance]] filed seven tax warrants against Cohen and his wife for $37,434 in unpaid taxi taxes due to the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|MTA]].<ref>Dan Rivoli & Reuven Blau, [http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/trump-personal-lawyer-owes-40g-unpaid-taxi-taxes-article-1.3392192 Trump's personal lawyer owes New York State nearly $40G in unpaid taxi taxes] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411111548/http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/trump-personal-lawyer-owes-40g-unpaid-taxi-taxes-article-1.3392192 |date=April 11, 2018}}, ''[[New York Daily News]]'' (August 8, 2017).</ref>\n\nCohen has been involved in real estate ventures in Manhattan, including the purchase and sale of four apartment buildings between 2011 and 2014. The total purchase price of the four buildings was $11&nbsp;million and the total sales price was $32&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"FootSoldier\" /><ref name=\"StoneGordonTax\">{{Cite news |first=Peter|last=Stone |first2=Greg |last2=Gordon |url= http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/national/article181133596.html |title=Michael Cohen says Americans paid cash for NY properties to get tax breaks |publisher=[[McClatchyDC]] |date=October 26, 2017 |access-date=April 14, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180415064055/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/national/article181133596.html |archive-date=April 15, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen sold the four properties at above their assessed values, in all-cash transactions, to [[limited liability company|LLCs]] owned by persons whose identities are not public.<ref name=\"StoneGordonMysterious\">{{Cite news |first=Peter|last=Stone |first2=Greg |last2=Gordon|url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/congress/article180701541.html |title=Trump associate Cohen sold four NY buildings for cash to mysterious buyers |publisher=[[McClatchyDC]] |date=October 25, 2017 |access-date= October 25, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171025163903/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/congress/article180701541.html |archive-date=October 25, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> After this was reported by [[McClatchy DC]] in October 2017, Cohen said that all four properties were purchased by an American-owned \"New York real estate family fund\" that paid cash for the properties in order to obtain a [[like-kind exchange|tax deferred (Section 1031) exchange]], but did not specifically identify the buyer.<ref name=\"StoneGordonTax\" />\n\nIn 2015, Cohen purchased an [[Upper East Side]] apartment building for $58&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"FootSoldier\" />\n\n===Politics===\nCohen volunteered for the 1988 presidential campaign of [[Michael Dukakis]].<ref name=\"Nathan-Kazis\" /> He was also an intern for Congressman [[Joe Moakley]]<ref name=\"Falcone\" /> and voted for [[Barack Obama]] in 2008, although he later became disappointed with Obama.<ref name=\"Nathan-Kazis\" />{{Tweet|name=Michael Cohen|username=MichaelCohen212|date=March 9, 2017|text=Made the official move today and joined the #RepublicanParty! It took a great man ([[@POTUS]]) to get me to make the switch. [[Make America Great Again|#MAGA]]|ref=<ref name=\"tweetRep\" />}}\n\nIn 2003, he unsuccessfully ran as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] for the [[New York City Council]] from the Fourth Council District<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://maps.nyc.gov/doitt/nycitymap/?searchType=AreaSearch&featureTypeName=CITY_COUNCIL_DISTRICT&featureName=4 |title=Archived copy |access-date=February 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228205720/http://maps.nyc.gov/doitt/nycitymap/?searchType=AreaSearch&featureTypeName=CITY_COUNCIL_DISTRICT&featureName=4 |archive-date=February 28, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> (a [[Murray Hill, Manhattan|Manhattan district]]).<ref name=\"NYCCFB Statement\" /> Cohen received 4,205 votes and was defeated by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] candidate [[Eva S. Moskowitz]], who received 13,745 votes.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://vote.nyc.ny.us/downloads/pdf/results/2003/general/g2003recaps.pdf |title=2003 General Election, New York County: Statement and Return of the Votes for the Office of Member of the City Council 4th Council District |publisher=[[New York City Board of Elections]] |date=December 5, 2003 |page=9 |access-date=April 11, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160303230946/http://vote.nyc.ny.us/downloads/pdf/results/2003/general/g2003recaps.pdf |archive-date=March 3, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2010, Cohen briefly campaigned for a seat in the [[New York State Senate]].<ref name=\"Falcone\" /><ref name=\"TRD\">{{cite news |url=http://therealdeal.com/new-research/topics/people/michael-d-cohen/ |title=Michael D. Cohen |newspaper=[[The Real Deal (magazine)|The Real Deal]] |access-date=January 15, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151201020629/http://therealdeal.com/new-research/topics/people/michael-d-cohen/ |archive-date=December 1, 2015 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> He was a registered Democrat until he officially registered as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] on March 9, 2017.<ref name=\"tweetRep\">{{Cite tweet |first=Michael |last=Cohen |user=MichaelCohen212 |number=839850609247469568 |date=March 9, 2017 |title=Made the official move today and joined the #RepublicanParty! It took a great man (@POTUS ) to get me to make the switch. #MAGA |access-date=March 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Howell |first=Kellan |date=April 14, 2016 |title=Michael Cohen, top Trump surrogate, can't vote for him because he's a registered Democrat |url= http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/apr/14/michael-cohen-top-trump-surrogate-cant-vote-him-be/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Times]] |access-date=November 11, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161111061328/http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/apr/14/michael-cohen-top-trump-surrogate-cant-vote-him-be/ |archive-date=November 11, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> On October 11, 2018, Cohen re-registered as a Democrat in an effort to distance \"himself from the values of the current\" administration.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/oct/11/michael-cohen-registers-democrat-trump |title=Michael Cohen re-registers as Democrat as he distances himself from Trump |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=October 11, 2018 |accessdate=October 11, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181012011243/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/oct/11/michael-cohen-registers-democrat-trump |archive-date=October 12, 2018 |url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/411030-michael-cohen-re-registers-as-a-democrat-lawyer-says |title=Michael Cohen re-registers as a Democrat, lawyer says |first=Brett |last=Samuels |date=October 11, 2018 |newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|accessdate=October 11, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011222750/https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/411030-michael-cohen-re-registers-as-a-democrat-lawyer-says|archive-date=October 11, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2006===\nCohen joined [[the Trump Organization]] in 2006.<ref name=\"WhoisCBS2018\" /> Trump hired him in part because he was already an admirer of Trump, having read Trump's ''Art of the Deal'' twice. He had purchased several Trump properties and convinced his own parents and in-laws, as well as a business partner, to buy condominiums in [[Trump World Tower]].<ref name=\"FootSoldier\" /> Cohen aided Trump in his struggle with the condominium board at the Trump World Tower, which led Trump to obtain control of the board.<ref name=\"FootSoldier\" /> Cohen became a close confidant to Trump, maintaining an office near Trump at [[Trump Tower]].<ref name=\"FootSoldier\" />\n\n===2008===\nCohen was named COO of [[mixed martial arts]] promotion company [[Affliction Entertainment]] in which Trump held a significant financial stake.<ref>{{cite web |title=Michael Cohen Named COO of Affliction |url= http://www.sherdog.com/news/pressreleases/Michael-Cohen-Named-COO-of-Affliction-13158 |publisher=sherdog.com |accessdate=May 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180528052545/http://www.sherdog.com/news/pressreleases/Michael-Cohen-Named-COO-of-Affliction-13158 |archive-date=May 28, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2011===\n[[File:Trump executive Michael Cohen 012 (5506031001) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Michael Cohen in 2011]]\nWhile Cohen was an executive at the organization, he was known as Trump's \"pit bull\". In late 2011, when Trump was publicly speculating about running for the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2012|2012 Republican Party presidential nomination]], Cohen co-founded the website \"Should Trump Run?\" to draft Trump into entering the race.<ref name=\"Falcone\" />\n\nIn an interview with [[ABC News]] in 2011, Cohen stated, \"If somebody does something Mr. Trump doesn't like, I do everything in my power to resolve it to Mr. Trump's benefit. If you do something wrong, I'm going to come at you, grab you by the neck and I'm not going to let you go until I'm finished.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/world/article-fbis-probe-of-presidential-lawyer-michael-cohen-enhances-trumps/ |title=FBI's probe of presidential lawyer Michael Cohen increases Trump's exposure |first=Joanna |last=Slater |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |date=April 10, 2018 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427085618/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/world/article-fbis-probe-of-presidential-lawyer-michael-cohen-enhances-trumps/ |archive-date=April 27, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2013===\nIn 2013, Cohen sent an email to the satirical news website ''[[The Onion]]'', demanding that an article ''The Onion'' had published that mocked Donald Trump (\"When You're Feeling Low, Just Remember I'll Be Dead In About 15 or 20 Years\")<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theonion.com/when-youre-feeling-low-just-remember-ill-be-dead-in-ab-1819584806 |publisher=[[The Onion]] |title=When You're Feeling Low, Just Remember I'll Be Dead In About 15 Or 20 Years |date=January 23, 2013 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180831220817/https://www.theonion.com/when-youre-feeling-low-just-remember-ill-be-dead-in-ab-1819584806 |archive-date=August 31, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> be removed with an apology, claiming it was [[defamation|defamatory]].<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[Politico]] |title=How Trump changed everything for The Onion |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/20/donald-trump-onion-stories-597809 |first=Andrew |last=Restuccia |date=May 20, 2018 |quote=Cohen was fuming over a satirical article published under Trump's name with the headline, \"When You're Feeling Low, Just Remember I'll Be Dead In About 15 Or 20 Years.\" On Trump's behalf, Cohen demanded that [[The Onion]] immediately remove the article and apologize. \"This commentary goes way beyond defamation and, if not immediately removed, I will take all actions necessary to ensure your actions do not go without consequence,\" Cohen wrote, according to a copy of the email provided to Politico. \"Guide yourself accordingly.\" |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709163849/https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/20/donald-trump-onion-stories-597809 |archive-date=July 9, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\nIn 2015, in response to an inquiry by reporter Tim Mak of ''[[The Daily Beast]]'' concerning rape allegations (later recanted) by [[Ivana Trump]] about her then-husband Donald Trump, Cohen said, \"I'm warning you, tread very fucking lightly, because what I'm going to do to you is going to be fucking disgusting.\"<ref name=\"WhoisCBS2018\">{{cite news |title=Who is Michael Cohen? |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/michael-cohen-trump-personal-lawyer/ |publisher=[[CBS News]] |date=March 26, 2018 |accessdate=March 28, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180328231504/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/michael-cohen-trump-personal-lawyer/ |archive-date=March 28, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nIn January 2016, according to the ''Washington Post'', Cohen sent an e-mail to Dmitry Peskov which was the \"most direct outreach documented by a top Trump aide to a similarly senior member of Putin\u2019s government.\" <ref>{{cite news |last1=Rosalind S. Helderman |last2=Carol D. Leonnig |last3=Tom Hamburger |title=Top Trump Organization executive asked Putin aide for help on business deal |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/top-trump-organization-executive-reached-out-to-putin-aide-for-help-on-business-deal/2017/08/28/095aebac-8c16-11e7-84c0-02cc069f2c37_story.html |accessdate=25 April 2019 |work=Washington Post |date=28 August 2017 |quote=Cohen\u2019s email marks the most direct outreach documented by a top Trump aide to a similarly senior member of Putin\u2019s government [...] he did not recall receiving a response from Peskov [...] The email, addressed to Peskov, appeared to have been sent to a general Kremlin press account.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=[[Matt Taibbi]] |title=The Press Will Learn Nothing From the Russiagate Fiasco |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/russiagate-fiasco-taibbi-news-media-826246/amp/ |accessdate=25 April 2019 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=23 April 2019 |quote=an email Trump lawyer Michael Cohen sent to Kremlin press secretary Dmitry Peskov. They called it \u201cthe most direct interaction yet of a top Trump aide and a senior member of Putin\u2019s government.\u201d The report shows the whole episode was a joke. In order to further the Trump Tower project-that-never-was, Cohen literally cold-emailed the Kremlin. More than that, he entered the email incorrectly, so the letter initially didn\u2019t even arrive. When he finally fixed the mistake, Peskov didn\u2019t answer back.}}</ref>\n\nA video of an interview of Cohen by CNN's [[Brianna Keilar]] went [[viral video|viral]], in which Cohen said \"Says who?\" several times in response to Keilar's statement that Trump was behind in all of the polls.<ref>{{cite news |title=Exchange between Trump attorney, CNN anchor goes viral |url=http://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2016/08/19/michael-cohen-brianna-keilar-says-who-all-of-them-moos-pkg-erin.cnn |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate=November 15, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161116020401/http://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2016/08/19/michael-cohen-brianna-keilar-says-who-all-of-them-moos-pkg-erin.cnn |archive-date=November 16, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"WashPost\">{{cite news |last=Wemple |first=Erik |authorlink=Erik Wemple |date=November 15, 2016 |title=An apology for Trump lawyer Michael Cohen |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2016/11/15/an-apology-for-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=January 28, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170124024115/https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2016/11/15/an-apology-for-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen/ |archive-date=January 24, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nCohen defended Trump against charges of [[antisemitism]].<ref name=\"heritage\" />\n\nIn 2016, he was a co-founder, along with [[Darrell C. Scott]], of the [[National Diversity Coalition for Trump]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vitali |first1=Ali |title=Trump 'Diversity Coalition' Holds Hectic First Meeting |url= https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2016-election/trump-diversity-coalition-holds-hectic-first-meeting-n557911|date=April 18, 2016|publisher=[[NBC News]]|access-date=August 22, 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180722071256/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2016-election/trump-diversity-coalition-holds-hectic-first-meeting-n557911|archive-date=July 22, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://thehill.com/latino/347027-trump-diversity-council-in-spotlight-after-charlottesville-remarks |title=Trump diversity council in spotlight after Charlottesville remarks |last1=Bernal |first1=Rafael |date=August 18, 2017 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180709094313/http://thehill.com/latino/347027-trump-diversity-council-in-spotlight-after-charlottesville-remarks |archive-date=July 9, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Peter J. Gleason, a lawyer who filed for protection of documents pertaining to two women with sexual abuse allegations against [[Eric Schneiderman|Eric T. Schneiderman]], stated\u2014without offering details or corroborating evidence\u2014that Cohen told him that if Trump had been elected governor of New York in 2013, the latter would have helped bring the accusations to public attention.<ref name=\"NYTEricSchneiderman\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/11/nyregion/eric-schneiderman-michael-cohen.html |title=Lawyer for 2 Schneiderman Accusers Brought Their Claims to Michael Cohen |date=May 11, 2018 |first=Alan |last=Feuer |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=May 12, 2018 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180512002007/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/11/nyregion/eric-schneiderman-michael-cohen.html |archive-date=May 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\n[[File:Michael D. Cohen.png|thumb|upright|Cohen in 2017]]\nThe [[Trump\u2013Russia dossier#Key roles of Manafort, Cohen, and Page|Trump\u2013Russia dossier]], published in January 2017, alleges that Cohen met with Russian officials in [[Prague]], [[Czech Republic]], in 2016 with the objective of paying those who had [[Democratic National Committee cyber attacks|hacked the DNC]] and to \"cover up all traces of the hacking operation\". The dossier contains raw intelligence, and is thought to be a mix of accurate and inaccurate information.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/nov/15/christopher-steele-trump-russia-dossier-accurate |title=Christopher Steele believes his dossier on Trump-Russia is 70-90% accurate |first=Julian |last=Borger |authorlink=Julian Borger |date=November 15, 2017 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180821033332/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/nov/15/christopher-steele-trump-russia-dossier-accurate |archive-date=August 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.cbsnews.com/amp/news/some-questions-in-trump-russia-dossier-now-finding-answers/|title=Some questions in Trump-Russia dossier now finding answers|publisher=[[CBS News]]|date=June 29, 2018|accessdate=August 22, 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180822014957/https://www.cbsnews.com/amp/news/some-questions-in-trump-russia-dossier-now-finding-answers/|archive-date=August 22, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen denied the allegations against him,<ref name=\"Harding_5/10/2017\">{{cite news |last=Harding |first=Luke |authorlink=Luke Harding |title=What do we know about alleged links between Trump and Russia? |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=May 10, 2017 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/may/10/qa-what-we-know-about-alleged-links-between-trump-and-russia |access-date=December 26, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180121172204/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/may/10/qa-what-we-know-about-alleged-links-between-trump-and-russia |archive-date=January 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Borger_4/28/2017\">{{cite news |last=Borger |first=Julian |authorlink=Julian Borger |title=UK was given details of alleged contacts between Trump campaign and Moscow |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=April 28, 2017 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/apr/28/trump-russia-intelligence-uk-government-m16-kremlin |access-date=December 26, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171226141900/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/apr/28/trump-russia-intelligence-uk-government-m16-kremlin |archive-date=December 26, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Cormier_5/5/2017\">{{cite news |last=Cormier |first=Anthony |authorlink=Anthony Cormier |title=This Is The Inside of Trump's Lawyer's Passport |publisher=[[BuzzFeed]] |date=May 5, 2017 |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/anthonycormier/trumps-lawyer-showed-you-the-cover-of-his-passport-heres |access-date= December 24, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171223204907/https://www.buzzfeed.com/anthonycormier/trumps-lawyer-showed-you-the-cover-of-his-passport-heres |archive-date=December 23, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> stating that he was in Los Angeles between August 23 and 29, and in New York for the entire month of September.<ref name=\"Gray_1/10/2017\">{{cite magazine |last=Gray |first=Rosie |authorlink=Rosie Gray |title=Michael Cohen: 'It Is Fake News Meant to Malign Mr. Trump' |magazine=[[The Atlantic]] |date=January 10, 2017 |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/01/michael-cohen-it-is-fake-news-meant-to-malign-mr-trump/512762/ |access-date=December 24, 2017 |quote=I'm telling you emphatically that I've not been to Prague, I've never been to Czech [Republic], I've not been to Russia. |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171212123015/https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/01/michael-cohen-it-is-fake-news-meant-to-malign-mr-trump/512762/ |archive-date=December 12, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> According to a Czech intelligence source, there is no record of him entering Prague by plane, but ''[[Respekt]]'' magazine and ''Politico'' pointed out that he could have theoretically entered by car or train from a neighboring country within the [[Schengen Area]], for example [[Italy]]. In the latter case, a record of Cohen entering the Schengen zone from a non-Schengen country should exist, if it occurred.<ref name=\"RFE/RL_1/11/2017\">{{cite news |author=RFE/RL|authorlink=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |title=Report: Czech Intelligence Says No Evidence Trump Lawyer Traveled To Prague |publisher=[[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]] |date=January 11, 2017 |url= https://www.rferl.org/a/czech-intelligence-trump-lawyer-prague-meeting/28226228.html |access-date=January 19, 2018 |quote=According to [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]], 'A Czech intelligence source told the ''[[Respekt]]'' magazine that there is no record of Cohen arriving in Prague by plane, although the news weekly pointed out he could have traveled by car or train from a nearby EU country, avoiding passport control under [[Schengen zone]] travel rules.' |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180223043351/https://www.rferl.org/a/czech-intelligence-trump-lawyer-prague-meeting/28226228.html |archive-date=February 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Meyer_12/6/2017\">{{cite news |last=Meyer |first=Josh |authorlink=Josh Meyer |title=Investigators probe European travel of Trump associates |newspaper=[[Politico]] |date=December 6, 2017 |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/12/06/trump-europe-russia-travel-281134 |access-date=February 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227214001/https://www.politico.com/story/2017/12/06/trump-europe-russia-travel-281134 |archive-date=February 27, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nHowever, on April 13, 2018, the DC Bureau of [[The McClatchy Company|McClatchy Newspapers]] reported that Special Counsel [[Robert Mueller]] has evidence that Cohen did travel to Prague during the late summer of 2016, with two sources having confirmed this secret trip. The evidence is said to show that Cohen entered the Czech Republic from [[Germany]], and since both countries are in the European Union's [[Schengen Area|Schengen passport area]], Cohen would not have needed to receive a passport stamp to enter Czech territory.<ref name=\"Prague allegations\">{{cite news |date=April 13, 2018 |url= https://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/white-house/article208870264.html |title=Sources: Mueller has evidence Cohen was in Prague in 2016 |last=Stone |first=Peter |last2=Gordon |first2=Greg |publisher=[[McClatchy DC Bureau]] |accessdate=April 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413234700/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/white-house/article208870264.html |archive-date=April 13, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The following day, Cohen again denied he has \"ever been to Prague\".<ref name=\"CBS_News_4/14/2018\">{{cite news |title=Trump lawyer Michael Cohen denies traveling to Prague |publisher=[[CBS News]] |date=April 14, 2018 |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-denies-traveling-to-prague/ |access-date=April 15, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180415051044/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-denies-traveling-to-prague/ |archive-date=April 15, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen also said that he didn't travel to the [[European Union]] in August 2016.<ref name=\"CBS_News_4/14/2018\" /> McClatchy reported in December 2018 that a mobile phone traced to Cohen had \"pinged\" cellphone towers around Prague in late summer 2016. McClatchy also reported that during that time an eastern European intelligence agency had intercepted communications between Russians, one of whom mentioned that Cohen was in Prague.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/investigations/article219016820.html |title=Cell signal puts Cohen outside Prague around time of purported Russian meeting |last=Stone |first=Peter |date=December 27, 2018 |publisher=[[McClatchyDC]] |last2=Gordon |first2=Greg |access-date=February 27, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181227184142/https://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/investigations/article219016820.html |archive-date=December 27, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> However, the ''[[Mueller Report]]'' states \u201cCohen had never traveled to Prague and was not concerned about those allegations, which he believed were provably false\"<ref>https://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/investigations/article229424084.html</ref><ref>''[https://www.justice.gov/storage/report.pdf Mueller Report]'', vol.2, p.139</ref>\n\nIn late January 2017, Cohen met with Ukrainian opposition politician [[Andrey Artemenko]] and [[Felix Sater]] at the [[Loews Hotels|Loews Regency]] in Manhattan to discuss a plan to lift [[international sanctions during the Ukrainian crisis|sanctions against Russia]]. The proposed plan would require that Russian forces withdraw from eastern Ukraine and that Ukraine hold a referendum on whether [[Crimea]] should be \"leased\" to Russia for 50 or 100 years. Cohen was given a written proposal in a sealed envelope that he delivered to then-National Security Advisor [[Michael Flynn]] in early February.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Twohey |first1=Megan |authorlink=Megan Twohey |authorlink2=Scott Shane |last2=Shane |first2=Scott |title=A Back-Channel Plan for Ukraine and Russia, Courtesy of Trump Associates |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/19/us/politics/donald-trump-ukraine-russia.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 19, 2017 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180823054448/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/19/us/politics/donald-trump-ukraine-russia.html |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn April 3, 2017, Cohen was appointed as national deputy finance chairman of the [[Republican National Committee]].<ref>{{cite web |title=RNC Announces Additions To RNC Finance Leadership Team |url=https://gop.com/rnc-announces-additions-to-rnc-finance-leadership-team/ |publisher=[[Republican National Committee]] |date=April 3, 2017 |accessdate=October 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026054418/https://gop.com/rnc-announces-additions-to-rnc-finance-leadership-team/ |archive-date=October 26, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Sheth |first1=Sonam |title=Trump's personal lawyer will serve as key RNC finance executive |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-rnc-finance-executive-2017-4 |website=[[Business Insider]] |date=April 3, 2017 |accessdate=October 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024035318/http://www.businessinsider.com/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-rnc-finance-executive-2017-4 |archive-date=October 24, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In April 2017, Cohen also formed an alliance with [[Squire Patton Boggs]] for legal and lobbying counsel on behalf of Trump.<ref>{{Cite web |first=C. Ryan |last=Barber |first2=Katelyn |last2=Polantz |url=http://www.legalweek.com/sites/legalweek/2017/04/04/trump-lawyer-salaries-revealed-as-squire-patton-boggs-seals-alliance-with-presidents-personal-adviser/ |title=Trump lawyer salaries revealed as Squire Patton Boggs seals alliance with president's personal adviser |publisher=[[Legal Week]] |date=April 4, 2017 |access-date=April 11, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180412082011/http://www.legalweek.com/sites/legalweek/2017/04/04/trump-lawyer-salaries-revealed-as-squire-patton-boggs-seals-alliance-with-presidents-personal-adviser/ |archive-date=April 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, amidst expanding inquiries into alleged [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Russian interference in the 2016 U.S. election]], two congressional panels asked Cohen to provide information about any communications he had with people connected to the Russian government.<ref name=\"FootSoldier\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-40098658 |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=May 30, 2017 |title=Russia inquiry expands to Trump lawyer Michael Cohen |access-date=May 30, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531121809/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-40098658 |archive-date=May 31, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC_Cohen_Russia_2017\">{{cite news |url= https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/russia-investigation-expands-include-donald-trumps-personal-attorney/story?id=47646601 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=May 30, 2017 |title=Congress expands Russia investigation to include Trump's personal attorney |first1=Brian |last1=Ross |authorlink=Brian Ross (journalist) |first2=Matthew |last2=Mosk |access-date=May 30, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170530162834/http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/russia-investigation-expands-include-donald-trumps-personal-attorney/story?id=47646601 |archive-date=May 30, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://soundcloud.com/the-intercept/donald-trump-fundraiser |title=Donald Trump fundraiser June 29, 2017 |publisher=[[SoundCloud]]|accessdate=July 3, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170703055009/https://soundcloud.com/the-intercept/donald-trump-fundraiser |archive-date=July 3, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://theintercept.com/2017/06/30/heres-the-audio-of-donald-trumps-private-rnc-fundraiser-at-his-own-hotel/ |title=Here's the Audio of Donald Trump's Private RNC Fundraiser at His Own Hotel |first1=Ryan |last1=Grim |authorlink=Ryan Grim |first2=Lee |last2=Fang |author2link=Lee Fang |date=June 30, 2017 |website=[[The Intercept]] |accessdate=July 3, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170703011612/https://theintercept.com/2017/06/30/heres-the-audio-of-donald-trumps-private-rnc-fundraiser-at-his-own-hotel/ |archive-date=July 3, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> He was a subject of the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Mueller investigation]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.axios.com/robert-muller-questions-list-trump-russia-54d00d1c-f008-457c-b304-ee601a98d78c.html |first=Jonathan |last=Swan |authorlink=Jonathan Swan |title=Scoop: Mueller's hit list |publisher=[[Axios (website)|Axios]] |date=March 4, 2018 |accessdate=March 5, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180305003347/https://www.axios.com/robert-muller-questions-list-trump-russia-54d00d1c-f008-457c-b304-ee601a98d78c.html |archive-date=March 5, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/national/article208090764.html |date=April 6, 2018 |title=Mueller probe tracking down Trump business partners, with Cohen a focus of queries |publisher=[[The McClatchy Company|McClatchy]] |accessdate=April 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180406014835/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/national/article208090764.html |archive-date=April 6, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/special-counsel-has-examined-episodes-involving-michael-cohen-trumps-longtime-lawyer/2018/03/06/4a2bd064-1b37-11e8-b2d9-08e748f892c0_story.html |title=Special counsel has examined episodes involving Michael Cohen, Trump's longtime lawyer |first1=Rosalind S. |last1=Helderman |authorlink=Rosalind Helderman |first2=Tom |last2=Hamburger |first3=Josh |last3=Dawsey |author3link=Josh Dawsey |date=March 6, 2018 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=March 6, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180306195701/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/special-counsel-has-examined-episodes-involving-michael-cohen-trumps-longtime-lawyer/2018/03/06/4a2bd064-1b37-11e8-b2d9-08e748f892c0_story.html |archive-date=March 6, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\n[[File:Michael Cohen in 2019.png|thumb|upright|Cohen at a court hearing]]\nIn May 2018, [[BBC News]] falsely reported that Cohen had received a secret payment of between $400,000 and $600,000 from intermediaries for Ukrainian President [[Petro Poroshenko]] to arrange a meeting between Poroshenko and Trump, though Cohen was not registered as a [[foreign agent]].<ref name=\"BBC Ukraine\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-44215656 |title=Ukraine 'paid Trump lawyer for talks' |first=Paul |last=Wood |authorlink=Paul Wood (journalist) |date=May 23, 2018 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=August 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725173526/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-44215656|archive-date=July 25, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Paul Wood |title=Trump lawyer 'paid by Ukraine' to arrange White House talks |url=http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-44215656 |accessdate=29 March 2019 |work=BBC |date=23 May 2018 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/Eyw9x |archivedate=24 May 2018 |quote=Donald Trump's personal lawyer, Michael Cohen, received a secret payment of at least $400,000 (\u00a3300,000) to fix talks between the Ukrainian president and President Trump}}</ref> Cohen and the Ukrainian president's office denied the allegations.<ref name=\"BBC Ukraine\" />  The BBC ended up having to state the allegation was untrue, apologizing to Poroshenko, deleting the article from its website, paying legal costs, and paying damages to Poroshenko.<ref>{{cite news |title=BBC pays damages to Ukraine President Petro Poroshenko over report |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-47719166 |accessdate=29 March 2019 |work=BBC |date=28 March 2019 |quote=\"We apologise to Mr Poroshenko for any distress caused and have agreed to pay him damages, legal costs and have participated in a joint statement in open court,\" the broadcaster said.}}</ref><ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/bbc-ukraine-poroshenko-trump-michael-cohen-defamation-a8844061.html \"Jane Phillips, counsel for the BBC, said: \u201cThe BBC is happy to acknowledge that these claims about the claimant are completely untrue, and it is here, through me, to apologise to the claimant for any distress and embarrassment caused to him by the article and the broadcast.\u201d\"</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, [[Rudy Giuliani]] announced that Cohen was no longer Trump's lawyer.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/business/rudy-giuliani-michael-cohen-is-no-longer-trumps-attorney |title=Rudy Giuliani: Michael Cohen is no longer Trump's attorney |date=May 6, 2018 |work=[[The Washington Examiner]] |access-date=May 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180522112540/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/business/rudy-giuliani-michael-cohen-is-no-longer-trumps-attorney |archive-date=May 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In July, seized tapes secretly recorded by Cohen of his conversations with Trump about [[hush payment]]s to Karen McDougal were disclosed to ''The New York Times'', seemingly contradicting earlier statements by Trump denying knowledge of the payments,<ref name=\"NYT Tapes\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/20/us/politics/michael-cohen-trump-tape.html |title=Michael Cohen Secretly Taped Trump Discussing Payment to Playboy Model |date=July 20, 2018 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |quote=The recording's existence appears to undercut the Trump campaign's denial of any knowledge of payments to the model. |access-date=July 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180722165154/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/20/us/politics/michael-cohen-trump-tape.html |archive-date=July 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> and raising questions about campaign finance ethics.<ref name=\"NYT Tapes\" /> Cohen also asserted that then-candidate Trump knew in advance about the [[Trump campaign\u2013Russian meetings|June 2016 Trump Tower meeting]] between his son [[Donald Trump Jr.|Donald Jr.]], and other Trump campaign officials with Russians who claimed to possess information damaging to the Hillary Clinton campaign, contradicting the President's repeated insistence that he was not aware of the meeting until long after it had taken place.<ref name=\"sciutto\">{{cite news |first1=Jim |last1=Sciutto |author1link=Jim Sciutto |first2=Carl |last2=Bernstein |author2link=Carl Bernstein |first3=Marshall |last3=Cohen |title=Cohen claims Trump knew in advance of 2016 Trump Tower meeting |url= https://www.cnn.com/2018/07/26/politics/michael-cohen-donald-trump-june-2016-meeting-knowledge/index.html |publisher=[[CNN Politics]] |accessdate=July 28, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180727011123/https://www.cnn.com/2018/07/26/politics/michael-cohen-donald-trump-june-2016-meeting-knowledge/index.html |archive-date=July 27, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, Cohen resigned as deputy finance chairman of the [[Republican National Committee]]. His resignation letter cited the ongoing investigations and also criticized the Trump administration's policy of [[Trump administration family separation policy|separating undocumented families]] at the border.<ref name=\"ABC News Cohen Resigns RNC\" />\n\n====Payment to Stormy Daniels====\n{{Main|Stormy Daniels\u2013Donald Trump scandal}}\nIn the fall of 2016, adult film actress [[Stormy Daniels]] ([[legal name]] Stephanie Clifford) was speaking to some reporters and said that she had had a sexual affair with Trump in 2006. In October, Cohen and Daniels' attorney [[Keith M. Davidson]] negotiated a [[non-disclosure agreement]] under which she was to be paid $130,000 [[hush money]]. Cohen created a Delaware LLC called Essential Consultants and used it to pay the $130,000.<ref name=\"LLC\">{{cite news |url= https://www.vox.com/2018/3/24/17151786/stormy-daniels-explained |title=The definitive guide to the Stormy Daniels scandal |last=Matthews |first=Dylan |authorlink=Dylan Matthews |date=April 6, 2018 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |accessdate=July 26, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180726234153/https://www.vox.com/2018/3/24/17151786/stormy-daniels-explained |archive-date=July 26, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The arrangement was reported by ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' in January 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Twohey |first1=Megan |authorlink=Megan Twohey |last2=Rutenberg |first2=Jim |author2link=Jim Rutenberg |title=Porn Star Was Reportedly Paid to Stay Quiet About Trump |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/12/us/trump-stephanie-clifford-stormy-daniels.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=January 12, 2018 |accessdate=February 14, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180214105249/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/12/us/trump-stephanie-clifford-stormy-daniels.html |archive-date=February 14, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-lawyer-used-private-company-pseudonyms-to-pay-porn-star-stormy-daniels-1516315731 |title=Trump Lawyer Used Private Company, Pseudonyms to Pay Adult film Star 'Stormy Daniels'; Michael Cohen created limited liability company just before $130,000 payment |first=Joe|last=Palazzolo|first2=Michael|last2=Rothfeld |date=January 18, 2018 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |access-date=January 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124233946/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-lawyer-used-private-company-pseudonyms-to-pay-porn-star-stormy-daniels-1516315731 |archive-date=January 24, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nCohen told ''[[The New York Times]]'' in February 2018 that he paid the $130,000 to Daniels from his own pocket; he also said that the payment was not a campaign contribution and he was not reimbursed by either the Trump Organization or [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|the Trump campaign]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Haberman |first=Maggie |authorlink=Maggie Haberman |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/13/us/politics/stormy-daniels-michael-cohen-trump.html |title=Trump's Longtime Lawyer Says He Paid Stormy Daniels Out of His Own Pocket |date=February 13, 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=February 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214023312/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/13/us/politics/stormy-daniels-michael-cohen-trump.html |archive-date=February 14, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' later noted that, by stating that he used his own money to \"facilitate\" the payment, Cohen was not ruling out the possibility that Trump, as an individual, reimbursed Cohen for the payment.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/02/14/trumps-lawyer-confirmed-the-stormy-daniels-payment-whats-conspicuously-absent-any-denial-that-trump-was-involved/ |title=Analysis {{!}} Did Trump's lawyer just implicate Trump in the Stormy Daniels payment? |last=Blake |first=Aaron |date=February 14, 2018 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=February 15, 2018 |issn=0190-8286 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214202706/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/02/14/trumps-lawyer-confirmed-the-stormy-daniels-payment-whats-conspicuously-absent-any-denial-that-trump-was-involved/ |archive-date=February 14, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In April 2018, Trump acknowledged for the first time that Cohen has represented him in the Stormy Daniels case, after previously having denied knowledge of the $130,000 payment.<ref>{{cite news |first=Philip |last=Rucker |authorlink=Philip Rucker |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-says-for-first-time-that-cohen-represented-him-in-stormy-daniels-case/2018/04/26/43c48962-4951-11e8-827e-190efaf1f1ee_story.html |title=Trump says for first time that Cohen represented him in Stormy Daniels case |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=April 26, 2018 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822204335/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-says-for-first-time-that-cohen-represented-him-in-stormy-daniels-case/2018/04/26/43c48962-4951-11e8-827e-190efaf1f1ee_story.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn March 5, ''The Wall Street Journal'' cited anonymous sources recounting Cohen as saying he missed two deadlines to pay Daniels because Cohen \"couldn't reach Mr. Trump in the hectic final days of the presidential campaign\", and that after Trump's election, Cohen had complained that he had not been reimbursed for the payment. Cohen described this report as \"[[fake news]]\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Palazzolo |first1=Joe |last2=Rothfeld |first2=Michael |title=Trump Lawyer's Payment to Stormy Daniels Was Reported as Suspicious by Bank |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-lawyers-payment-to-porn-star-was-reported-as-suspicious-by-bank-1520273701?tesla=y&mod=e2tw |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=March 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180310200019/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-lawyers-payment-to-porn-star-was-reported-as-suspicious-by-bank-1520273701?tesla=y&mod=e2tw |archive-date=March 10, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn March 9, [[NBC News]] reported that Cohen had used his Trump Organization email to negotiate with Daniels regarding her nondisclosure agreement, and that Cohen had used the same Trump Organization email to arrange for a transfer for funds that would eventually lead to Daniels' payment.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fitzpatrick |first1=Sarah |last2=Connor |first2=Tracy |title=Michael Cohen used Trump company email in Stormy Daniels arrangements |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/michael-cohen-used-trump-org-email-stormy-daniels-arrangements-n855021 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |accessdate=March 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180310233230/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/michael-cohen-used-trump-org-email-stormy-daniels-arrangements-n855021 |archive-date=March 10, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In response, Cohen acknowledged that he had transferred funds from his [[home equity line of credit]] to the LLC and from the LLC to Daniels' attorney.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Llamas |first1=Tom |authorlink=Tom Llamas |last2=Zaki |first2=Zunaira |last3=Faulders |first3=Katherine |last4=Peck |first4=Christina |title=Michael Cohen dismisses claims of email as proof that Trump knew about payment to porn star to buy her silence |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/michael-cohen-dismisses-claims-email-proof-trump-knew/story?id=53642094 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |accessdate=March 11, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180310205756/http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/michael-cohen-dismisses-claims-email-proof-trump-knew/story?id=53642094 |archive-date=March 10, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn a March 25, 2018, interview with ''[[60 Minutes]]'', Daniels said that she and Trump had sex once, and that later she had been threatened in front of her infant daughter and felt pressured to later sign a [[non-disclosure agreement]].<ref name=\"60m-transcript\">{{cite news |url= https://www.cbsnews.com/news/stormy-daniels-describes-her-alleged-affair-with-donald-trump-60-minutes-interview/ |title=Stormy Daniels describes her alleged affair with Donald Trump |work=[[60 Minutes]] |publisher=[[CBS News]] |date=March 25, 2018 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180326002719/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/stormy-daniels-describes-her-alleged-affair-with-donald-trump-60-minutes-interview/ |archivedate=March 26, 2018 |url-status=live |access-date=March 26, 2018}} Includes video and transcript.</ref><ref name=\"npr-graphic-details\">{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2018/03/25/596868354/stormy-daniels-shares-graphic-details-about-alleged-affair-with-trump |title=Stormy Daniels Shares Graphic Details About Alleged Affair With Trump |first=Miles |last=Parks |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=March 25, 2018 |accessdate=March 26, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180326012144/https://www.npr.org/2018/03/25/596868354/stormy-daniels-shares-graphic-details-about-alleged-affair-with-trump |archive-date=March 26, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, David Schwarz, a lawyer for Cohen, told [[ABC Studios|ABC's]] ''[[Good Morning America]]'' that Daniels was lying in the ''60 Minutes'' interview. Cohen's lawyer sent a cease-and-desist letter claiming Daniels' statements constituted \"libel per se and intentional infliction of emotional distress\" to Cohen.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.cbsnews.com/news/lawyers-for-trump-attorney-say-stormy-daniels-lied-in-60-minutes-interview/ |title=Lawyers for Trump attorney say Stormy Daniels lied in '60 Minutes' interview |publisher=[[CBS News]] |access-date=March 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326165445/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/lawyers-for-trump-attorney-say-stormy-daniels-lied-in-60-minutes-interview/ |archive-date=March 26, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nCohen initiated a private arbitration case against Daniels in February 2018, based on an October 2016 non-disclosure agreement signed by Daniels in October 2016, in exchange for $130,000. Cohen obtained an order from an arbitrator barring Daniels from publicly discussing her alleged relationship with Trump.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fitzpatrick |first1=Sarah |title=Trump lawyer Michael Cohen tries to silence adult-film star Stormy Daniels |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-tries-silence-stormy-daniels-n854646 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |accessdate=March 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308000908/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-tries-silence-stormy-daniels-n854646 |archive-date=March 8, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"ReutersForce\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-daniels/trump-attorney-seeks-to-force-porn-stars-lawsuit-into-arbitration-idUSKCN1HA058 |title=Trump attorney seeks to force porn star's lawsuit into arbitration |work=[[Reuters]] |date=April 2, 2018 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180914122314/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-daniels/trump-attorney-seeks-to-force-porn-stars-lawsuit-into-arbitration-idUSKCN1HA058 |archive-date=September 14, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Daniels subsequently brought a lawsuit in federal court against Trump and Cohen, arguing that the non-disclosure agreement is legally invalid because Trump never signed it,<ref>{{cite news |date=April 2, 2018 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-daniels/trump-attorney-seeks-to-force-porn-star-lawsuit-into-arbitration-idUSKCN1HA058 |title=Trump attorney seeks to force porn star's lawsuit into arbitration |first=Eric |last=Beech |first2=Karen |last2=Freifeld |work=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=May 9, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180823174123/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-daniels/trump-attorney-seeks-to-force-porn-star-lawsuit-into-arbitration-idUSKCN1HA058 |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen responded by seeking to compel arbitration, which would avoid public proceedings.<ref name=\"ReutersForce\" /> In April 2018, Cohen filed a [[affidavit|declaration]] in the court saying that he would invoke his [[Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifth Amendment]] right not to [[self-incrimination|incriminate himself]] in the Daniels lawsuit.<ref>{{cite news |first=Alan |last=Feuer |first2=Benjamin |last2=Weiser |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/25/nyregion/michael-cohen-stormy-daniels.html |title=Michael Cohen to Take Fifth Amendment in Stormy Daniels Lawsuit |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 25, 2018 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180822205018/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/25/nyregion/michael-cohen-stormy-daniels.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Emma |last=Brown |first2=Rosalind S. |last2=Helderman |author2link=Rosalind Helderman |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/cohen-says-he-would-invoke-his-fifth-amendment-right-in-stormy-daniels-case/2018/04/25/c72a5c5a-48d9-11e8-827e-190efaf1f1ee_story.html |title=Michael Cohen to invoke Fifth Amendment right in Stormy Daniels case |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=April 25, 2018 |access-date=April 27, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180427122215/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/cohen-says-he-would-invoke-his-fifth-amendment-right-in-stormy-daniels-case/2018/04/25/c72a5c5a-48d9-11e8-827e-190efaf1f1ee_story.html |archive-date=April 27, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn May 18, lawyers for Cohen filed an [[objection (United States law)|objection]] to Daniel's lawyer Michael Avenatti being allowed to represent her in a case involving Cohen, claiming it (the objection) was based on the violations of ethical rules and local court rules, among other issues.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/05/18/michael-cohen-objects-to-stormy-daniels-lawyer-being-admitted-to-case.html |title=Cohen lawyers object to Stormy Daniels' attorney Michael Avenatti intervening in New York case |last2=Breuninger |first1=Dan |last1=Mangan |first2=Kevin |date=May 18, 2018 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |access-date=May 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180519224307/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/05/18/michael-cohen-objects-to-stormy-daniels-lawyer-being-admitted-to-case.html |archive-date=May 19, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> After Cohen's August 2018 conviction, Trump stated that the payment to Daniels came from him personally and not from the campaign during a [[Fox & Friends]] interview.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-45279047 |title=Trump: Hush money payments came from me |date=August 23, 2018 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823042305/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-45279047 |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Recording of discussion regarding Karen McDougal====\nIn 2016, [[Karen McDougal]], a former ''[[Playboy]]'' model, claimed that she and Trump had an affair from 2006 until 2007, a claim that Trump has since denied.<ref name=\"clientprivilege\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/07/21/politics/trump-cohen-recording-privilege/index.html |title=Trump attorneys waive privilege on secret recording about ex-Playmate payment |first=Gloria |last=Borger |authorlink=Gloria Borger |first2=Erica |last2=Orden |first3=Dana |last3=Bash |author3link=Dana Bash |first4=Evan |last4=Perez |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=July 22, 2018 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180822203651/https://www.cnn.com/2018/07/21/politics/trump-cohen-recording-privilege/index.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The ''[[National Enquirer]]'' paid McDougal $150,000 for her story but never published it, a practice known as [[catch and kill]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://money.cnn.com/2018/02/16/media/trump-catch-and-kill/index.html |date=February 16, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |title= 'Catch and kill': How a tabloid shields Trump from troublesome stories |first=Brian |last=Shelter |authorlink=Brian Stelter |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823234417/https://money.cnn.com/2018/02/16/media/trump-catch-and-kill/index.html |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> On September 30, 2016, Cohen created Resolution Consultants LLC, a [[Delaware]] shell company, to purchase the rights to McDougal's story from the ''National Enquirer'', though the rights to the story were ultimately never purchased.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/trumps-former-lawyer-michael-cohen-formed-delaware-company-to-pay-playboy-model-1532526807 |title=Trump's Former Lawyer Michael Cohen Formed Delaware Company to Purchase Ex-Playboy Model's Story |archive-url= https://archive.today/20180725193109/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trumps-former-lawyer-michael-cohen-formed-delaware-company-to-pay-playboy-model-1532526807 |archive-date=July 25, 2018 |date=July 25, 2018 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |first=Joe |last=Palazzolo |first2=Michael |last2=Rothfeld |first3=Rebecca |last3=Ballhaus |accessdate=August 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Resolution_Consultants_LLC_01_12_18.pdf |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180118230907/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Resolution_Consultants_LLC_01_12_18.pdf |archive-date=January 18, 2018 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |title=State of Delaware Limited Liability Company Certificate of Formation: Resolution Consultants LLC |date=September 30, 2016 |first=Michael |last=Cohen |publisher=[[Secretary of State of Delaware]] ([[Jeffrey W. Bullock]])}}</ref>\n\nCohen had been known to record conversations and phone calls with other people.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/382951-trump-advisers-fear-fbi-seized-trump-lawyers-recordings-of |title=Trump allies fear feds seized lawyer's recordings of conversations: report |last=Thomsen |first=Jacqueline |date=April 12, 2018 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |accessdate=July 21, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180722011510/http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/382951-trump-advisers-fear-fbi-seized-trump-lawyers-recordings-of |archive-date=July 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> According to his lawyer Lanny Davis, \"Michael Cohen had the habit of using his phone to record conversations instead of taking notes.\"<ref name=\"voxseized\">{{Cite news |first=Li |last=Zhou |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/7/26/17616548/michael-cohen-trump-recordings |title=Report: federal authorities have seized more than 100 Michael Cohen tapes |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=July 26, 2018 |access-date=July 27, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180726175435/https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/7/26/17616548/michael-cohen-trump-recordings |archive-date=July 26, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Altogether the prosecutors have been given more than one hundred audio recordings from the material seized from Cohen in the April raid, after the Trump team withdrew their claims of [[privilege (law)|privilege]] for those items; reportedly only one of them features a substantive conversation with Trump.<ref name=\"voxseized\" /> The existence of that tape was revealed on July 20 and the actual recording was released on July 25.<ref name=\"clientprivilege\" /><ref name=\"tape\" />\n\nOn July 20, it was revealed that Cohen secretly recorded a conversation between Trump and him. The discussion involved a potential hush payment to the publisher of the ''National Enquirer''. The recording had been classified as a [[attorney\u2013client privilege|privileged attorney-client communication]] by the Special Master reviewing the Cohen material, but Trump's attorneys waived that claim, meaning that prosecutors can have it and use it. The conversation in that tape occurred in September 2016, two months before the election and weeks after the ''Enquirer'' paid McDougal the $150,000. In the conversation, Trump and Cohen discuss whether to buy the rights to her story from the ''Enquirer'', and Trump appears to approve the idea. Trump's lawyer, Rudy Giuliani, initially claimed that the tape shows Trump saying \"make sure it's done correctly, and make sure it's done by check.\" Giuliani also noted that no payment was ultimately made, and asserted that Trump's team waived privilege and allowed the recording to be revealed because it shows no violation of law.<ref name=\"clientprivilege\" /> The recording appears to contradict [[Hope Hicks]], then Trump's spokeswoman, who said when the story of the ''Enquirer'' payment came out a few days before the election that the Trump campaign had \"no knowledge of any of this\".<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Tucker|first1=Eric |last2=Peltz|first2=Jennifer |url= https://apnews.com/3faf47db59054b3c9c8dd414b943c9ea/Trump-was-taped-talking-of-paying-for-Playboy-model's-story |title=Trump was taped talking of paying for Playboy model's story |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |date=July 20, 2018 |access-date= October 19, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180722164507/https://www.apnews.com/3faf47db59054b3c9c8dd414b943c9ea/Trump-was-taped-talking-of-paying-for-Playboy-model's-story |archive-date=July 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn July 25, Cohen's attorney [[Lanny Davis]] released the actual recording to [[CNN]], which played it on the air on the ''[[Cuomo Prime Time]]'' program. On it, Trump can be heard concluding a telephone conversation with an unidentified person and then discussing several items of business with Cohen. Cohen mentions that he needs to \"open up a company for the transfer of all of that info regarding our friend David\", interpreted as meaning [[David Pecker]], the head of [[American Media, Inc.|American Media]], which publishes the ''National Enquirer''. Later when they discuss financing, Trump is heard saying something about \"pay with cash\", to which Cohen responds \"no, no, no\", but the tape is unclear and it is disputed what is said next; the word \"check\" can be heard.<ref name=\"tape\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/07/24/politics/michael-cohen-donald-trump-tape/index.html |title=Exclusive: CNN obtains secret Trump-Cohen tape |date=July 25, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate=July 25, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180725010902/https://www.cnn.com/2018/07/24/politics/michael-cohen-donald-trump-tape/index.html |archive-date=July 25, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> A transcript provided by Trump's attorneys has Trump saying \"Don't pay with cash ... check.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/trump-cohen-secret-audio-tape-made-public/story?id=56798373 |title=Trump-Cohen secret audio tape made public |last=Faulders |first=Katherine |date=July 25, 2018 |work=[[ABC News]] |accessdate=July 25, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180725025936/https://abcnews.go.com/US/trump-cohen-secret-audio-tape-made-public/story?id=56798373 |archive-date=July 25, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The tape cuts off abruptly at that point.<ref name=\"first\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/07/24/the-trump-michael-cohen-tape-transcript-annotated/ |title=The Trump-Michael Cohen tape transcript, annotated |last=Blake |first=Aaron |date=July 24, 2018 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=July 25, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180725020958/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/07/24/the-trump-michael-cohen-tape-transcript-annotated/|archive-date=July 25, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A lawyer for the Trump Organization said that any reference to \"cash\" would not have meant \"green currency\", but a one-time payment (\"cash\") vs. extended payments (\"[[funding|financing]]\"), in either case accompanied by documents.<ref name=\"tape\" /> According to Aaron Blake at ''The Washington Post'', \"the tape provides the first evidence that Trump spoke with Cohen about purchasing the rights to women's stories\u2014apparently to silence them\u2014before the [[United States elections, 2016|2016 election]].\"<ref name=\"first\" /> He also notes that Cohen speaks in \"somewhat coded language\", which Trump understands, suggesting that he is already familiar with the issue.{{citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n\nDespite the taped conversation, on August 23, in a [[Fox News]] interview Trump stated that he was not aware of the hush-money payments until \"later on\": \"Later on I knew. Later on. What he did\u2014and they weren't taken out of the campaign finance, that's the big thing.\" He added: \"In fact, my first question when I heard about it was, did they come out of the campaign, because that could be a little dicey. And they didn't come out of the campaign and that's big. But they weren't ... that's not even a campaign violation.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singman |first1=Brooke |title=Trump rips Cohen for 'flipping,' praises Manafort in exclusive FNC interview |date=August 23, 2018 |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2018/08/23/trump-rips-cohen-for-flipping-praises-manafort-in-exclusive-fnc-interview.html |publisher=[[Fox News]] |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823110631/http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2018/08/23/trump-rips-cohen-for-flipping-praises-manafort-in-exclusive-fnc-interview.html |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> According to U.S. election rules, any payments intended to influence an election vote must be reported.<ref name=\"auto1\" />\n\n====Payment to Shera Bechard====\n{{See also|Keith M. Davidson#Shera Bechard}}\nIn April 2018, ''The Wall Street Journal'' reported that [[Shera Bechard]], a former [[Playboy Playmate|''Playboy'' Playmate]], had an affair with married Republican fundraiser [[Elliott Broidy]]. She became pregnant by him, had an abortion, and was to be paid $1.6 million [[hush money]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-negotiated-1-6-million-settlement-for-top-republican-fundraiser-1523638726 |title=Trump Lawyer Michael Cohen Negotiated $1.6 Million Settlement for Top Republican Fundraiser |last1= Palazzolo |first1=Joe |last2=Rothfeld |first2=Michael |date=April 13, 2018 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate= April 13, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413175435/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-negotiated-1-6-million-settlement-for-top-republican-fundraiser-1523638726 |archive-date=April 13, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ruiz |first1=Rebecca R. |last2=Rutenberg |first2=Jim |author2link=Jim Rutenberg |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/13/us/politics/elliott-broidy-michael-cohen-payout.html |title=R.N.C. Official Who Agreed to Pay Playboy Model $1.6 Million Resigns |date=April 13, 2018 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=April 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416015815/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/13/us/politics/elliott-broidy-michael-cohen-payout.html |archive-date=April 16, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Broidy is a Republican fundraiser and deputy finance chair of the [[Republican National Committee]].\n\nIn a 2018 court proceeding, Cohen said he had given legal advice to only three clients in 2017: Donald Trump, [[Sean Hannity]], and Elliott Broidy.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-04-16/cohen-says-he-gave-legal-advice-to-three-clients-in-past-year |title=Cohen Says He Gave Legal Advice to Three Clients in Past Year |last= Voreacos |first=David |date=April 16, 2018 |publisher=[[Bloomberg News]] |accessdate=May 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180513165311/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-04-16/cohen-says-he-gave-legal-advice-to-three-clients-in-past-year |archive-date=May 13, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In late 2017, Cohen arranged the $1.6 million payment by Broidy to Bechard as part of a nondisclosure agreement requiring Bechard to keep silent about the matter.<ref name=\"CNN Cohen facilitated\">{{Cite news |date=April 13, 2018 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/13/politics/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-settlement/index.html |title=Michael Cohen facilitated $1.6 million agreement on behalf of GOP fundraiser |first1=MJ |last1=Lee |last2=Sara |first2=Sidner |author2link=Sara Sidner |first3=Kara |last3=Scannell |first4=Clare |last4=Foran |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=April 13, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180413204522/https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/13/politics/trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-settlement/index.html |archive-date=April 13, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen was Broidy's attorney and [[Keith M. Davidson]] represented Bechard.<ref name=\"CNN Cohen facilitated\" /> Davidson had previously been the attorney for Stormy Daniels and Karen McDougal.<ref name=\"CNN Cohen facilitated\" /> The Bechard nondisclosure agreement used the same [[pseudonym]]s&nbsp;\u2013 David Dennison for the man and Peggy Peterson for the woman&nbsp;\u2013 as in the Daniels agreement.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/05/theory-playboy-model-had-affair-with-trump-not-broidy.html |title=Here's a Theory About That $1.6 Million Payout From a GOP Official to a Playboy Model |last=Campos |first=Paul |authorlink=Paul Campos |date=May 8, 2018 |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |accessdate=July 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180812142316/http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/05/theory-playboy-model-had-affair-with-trump-not-broidy.html |archive-date=August 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The payments were to be made in installments.\n\nOn July 6, 2018, Bechard filed a lawsuit against Broidy, Davidson, and Daniels' attorney [[Michael Avenatti]], claiming the three had breached the agreement in relation to the cessation of the settlement payments.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.vox.com/2018/7/6/17542222/shera-bechard-broidy-trump-lawsuit-pregnancy |title=Shera Bechard lawsuit: Model who Trump donor paid hush money to sues - Vox |last=Prokop |first=Andrew |date=July 6, 2018 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |accessdate=July 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180723003718/https://www.vox.com/2018/7/6/17542222/shera-bechard-broidy-trump-lawsuit-pregnancy |archive-date=July 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Dillon |first=Nancy |url= http://www.nydailynews.com/news/ny-news-playmate-sues-broidy-avenatti-20180706-story.html |title=Ex-Playboy model sues Trump donor Elliott Broidy and Michael Avenatti over hush-money pact tied to secret pregnancy |work=[[New York Daily News]] |date=July 6, 2018 |accessdate=July 7, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180707010249/http://www.nydailynews.com/news/ny-news-playmate-sues-broidy-avenatti-20180706-story.html |archive-date=July 7, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/ex-playmate-files-suit-against-gop-donor-elliott-broidy-over-hush-money-deal-1530904576 |title=Ex-Playmate Files Suit Against GOP Donor Elliott Broidy Over Hush-Money Deal |first=Michael |last=Rothfeld |first2=Joe |last2=Palazzolo |date=July 6, 2018 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180706200055/https://www.wsj.com/articles/ex-playmate-files-suit-against-gop-donor-elliott-broidy-over-hush-money-deal-1530904576 |archive-date=July 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/2018_0706_bechard_vs_broidy_plaintffs_memorandum.pdf?mod=article_inline |format=[[PDF]] |first=Peter K. |last=Stris |first2=Elizabeth R. |last2=Brannen |first3=Dana |last3=Berkowitz |first4=John |last4=Stokes |first5=Shaun P. |last5=Martin |publisher=Stris & Maher LLP via [[The Wall Street Journal]] |archive-date= July 7, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180707154348/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/2018_0706_bechard_vs_broidy_plaintffs_memorandum.pdf?mod=article_inline |date=July 6, 2018 |title=Plaintiff's Memorandum of Points and Authorities in Support of Ex Parte Application to Conditionally Seal the Complaint for 45 Days}}</ref>\n\n====Essential Consultants LLC====\nEssential Consultants LLC is a [[Delaware]] shell company created by Cohen in October 2016 to facilitate payment of hush money to Stormy Daniels.<ref name=\"LLC\" /> For many months thereafter, Cohen used the LLC<ref>{{Cite news |last=Cohen |first=Michael |date=October 17, 2016 |title=State of Delaware Limited Liability Company Certificate of Formation |url= https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Essential_Consultants_01_12_17.pdf |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |publisher=[[Secretary of State of Delaware]] ([[Jeffrey W. Bullock]]) |access-date=May 9, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180417150531/http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/Essential_Consultants_01_12_17.pdf |archive-date=April 17, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> for an array of business activities largely unknown to the public, with at least $4.4 million moving through the LLC between Trump's election to the presidency and January 2018.<ref name=\"NYTShellCompanyPayments\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/08/us/politics/michael-cohen-shell-company-payments.html |title=Firm Tied to Russian Oligarch Made Payments to Michael Cohen |last=McIntire |first=Mike |date=May 8, 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |last2=Protess |first2=Ben |last3=Rutenberg |first3=Jim |author3link=Jim Rutenberg |access-date=May 9, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180509001006/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/08/us/politics/michael-cohen-shell-company-payments.html |archive-date=May 9, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In May 2018, Stormy Daniels' lawyer [[Michael Avenatti]] posted a seven-page report to [[Twitter]] detailing what he said were financial transactions involving Essential Consultants and Cohen. Avenatti did not reveal the source of his information, which was later largely confirmed by ''The New York Times'' and other publications.<ref name=\"NYTShellCompanyPayments\" /> The data showed that hundreds of thousands of dollars were given to Cohen, via Essential Consultants, from Fortune 500 firms such as [[Novartis]] and [[AT&T]], which had business before the Trump administration. It was also revealed that Essential Consultants had received at least $500,000 from a New York-based investment firm called [[Columbus Nova]], which is linked to a [[Russian oligarch]]. The firm's largest client is a company controlled by [[Viktor Vekselberg]], a Ukrainian-born Russian oligarch.<ref name=\"NYTShellCompanyPayments\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-05-08/oligarch-steered-cash-to-trump-lawyer-s-account-avenatti-says |title=Russian Oligarch Tied to Trump Lawyer in Stormy Bombshell |first=Erik |last=Larson |authorlink=Erik Larson (author) |first2=Andrew |last2=Martin |date=May 8, 2018 |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |accessdate=May 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180508235733/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-05-08/oligarch-steered-cash-to-trump-lawyer-s-account-avenatti-says |archive-date=May 8, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}<br>{{cite news|url= https://assets.bwbx.io/s3/readings/P8GBAG6TTDSH1525865905564.mp3 |title=Russian Oligarch Tied to Trump Lawyer in Stormy Bombshell |first=Erik |last=Larson |authorlink=Erik Larson (author) |first2=Andrew |last2=Martin |date=May 8, 2018 |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |accessdate=March 2, 2019 |type=audio|format=[[MP3]]|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180510212404/https://assets.bwbx.io/s3/readings/P8GBAG6TTDSH1525865905564.mp3 |archive-date=May 10, 2018 |url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=May 8, 2018 |url=https://www.newyorker.com/current/michael-cohen-essential-consulting |title=Why the Revelations About Michael Cohen's Business Dealings Could Be a Very Big Deal |first=Eric |last=Lach |work=[[The New Yorker]] |accessdate=May 9, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180509035833/https://www.newyorker.com/current/michael-cohen-essential-consulting |archive-date=May 9, 2018 |url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"lat Firm paid $500,000\" /> Vekselberg is a business partner of Soviet-born billionaire and major [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] donor, [[Leonard Blavatnik]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=May |first1=Ruth |title=GOP campaigns took $7.35&nbsp;million from oligarch linked to Russia |url= https://www.dallasnews.com/opinion/commentary/2017/08/03/tangled-web-connects-russian-oligarch-money-gop-campaigns |newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |date=August 3, 2017 |access-date=May 9, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180518034059/https://www.dallasnews.com/opinion/commentary/2017/08/03/tangled-web-connects-russian-oligarch-money-gop-campaigns |archive-date=May 18, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> A spokesperson for Columbus Nova said that the payment was a consulting fee that had nothing to do with Vekselberg.<ref name=\"NYTShellCompanyPayments\" />\n\nQuestions were raised about many of the payments, such as four totaling $200,000 that [[AT&T]] paid to the LLC between October 2017 and January 2018,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scribd.com/document/378627744/Executive-Summary |title= Executive Summary|first=Michael|last=Avenatti|authorlink=Michael Avenatti|via=[[Scribd]]|accessdate=May 9, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180612074312/https://www.scribd.com/document/378627744/Executive-Summary |archive-date=June 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2018/politics/news/att-trump-michael-cohen-1202803819/ |title=AT&T Says It Paid Michael Cohen's Firm for 'Insights' Into Trump Administration |first=Ted |last=Johnson |date=May 9, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=May 9, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180509023512/http://variety.com/2018/politics/news/att-trump-michael-cohen-1202803819/ |archive-date=May 9, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> while at the same time the proposed merger between the company and [[Time Warner Cable|Time Warner]] was pending before the Justice Department. AT&T claimed that the money was paid to the LLC and other firms that were used to provide insights into understanding the new administration, and that the LLC did no legal or lobbying work for AT&T.<ref name=\"NYTShellCompanyPayments\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/michael-cohen-took-cash-from-russian-oligarch-after-election |title=Michael Cohen Took Cash From Oligarch-Connected Firm After Election |first1=Noah|last1=Shachtman |authorlink=Noah Shachtman |first2=Kate |last2=Briquelet |date=May 8, 2018 |work=[[The Daily Beast]] |accessdate=May 9, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180508225248/https://www.thedailybeast.com/michael-cohen-took-cash-from-russian-oligarch-after-election |archive-date=May 8, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn May 11, 2018, the CEO of AT&T stated that in early 2017 it was approached by Cohen to provide \"his opinion on the new president and his administration\". Cohen was paid $600,000 ($50,000 per month) over the year, which its CEO described as \"a big mistake\". Novartis was also approached by Cohen and was offered similar services.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://money.cnn.com/2018/05/11/media/att-michael-cohen-randall-stephenson/index.html |title=AT&T CEO says hiring Michael Cohen 'was a big mistake' |first=Brian |last=Stelter |authorlink=Brian Stelter |first2=Hadas |last2=Gold |author2link=Hadas Gold |publisher=[[CNNMoney]] |date=May 11, 2018 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180824002302/https://money.cnn.com/2018/05/11/media/att-michael-cohen-randall-stephenson/index.html |archive-date=August 24, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nNovartis, a [[Switzerland]]&ndash;based pharmaceutical giant paid the LLC nearly $1.2 million in separate payments.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=https://www.fiercepharma.com/pharma/during-davos-trip-trump-takes-meeting-novartis-bayer-ceos-and-other-execs |title=Novartis, Bayer CEOs get time with Trump as he meets with EU business leaders during Davos trip |first=Eric |last= Sagonowsky |publisher=FiercePharma |accessdate=May 9, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180509150956/https://www.fiercepharma.com/pharma/during-davos-trip-trump-takes-meeting-novartis-bayer-ceos-and-other-execs |archive-date=May 9, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Novartis released a statement May 9, 2018, that it hired the LLC to help the company understand the \"health care policy\" of the new administration, but it actually did not receive benefit for its investment. The statement continued that Novartis made a decision to not engage Essential Consultants further, but it could not terminate the contract for \"cause\", raising concerns on why the company did not pursue reimbursement.<ref name=\"WashPostSwampThing\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/05/10/michael-cohen-swamp-thing/ |title=Analysis {{!}} Michael Cohen epitomizes just how much the swamp has thrived under Trump |last=Blake |first=Aaron |date=May 10, 2018 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=May 10, 2018 |issn=0190-8286 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510144426/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/05/10/michael-cohen-swamp-thing/ |archive-date=May 10, 2018 |url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Korea Aerospace Industries]] paid $150,000,<ref name=\"lat Firm paid $500,000\">{{cite news |url= https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-cohen-russia-vekselberg-20180508-story.html |title=Firm linked to Russian mogul paid $500,000 to Trump attorney Michael Cohen |first=Michael |last=Finnegan |date=May 9, 2018 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=May 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509021213/http://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-cohen-russia-vekselberg-20180508-story.html |archive-date=May 9, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> ostensibly for advice on \"cost accounting standards\".<ref name=\"WashPostSwampThing\"/>\n\nFranklin L. Haney agreed to pay Cohen $10 million if he successfully lobbied for the [[United States Department of Energy]] to finance the [[Bellefonte Nuclear Generating Station]], or a reduced fee if the funding targets were only partially met.<ref name=\"nuke\">{{cite news |title=Top Trump Donor Agreed to Pay Michael Cohen $10 Million for Nuclear Project Push |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |first=Michael |last=Rothfeld |first2=Rebecca |last2=Ballhaus |first3=Joe |last3=Palazzolo |date=August 2, 2018 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/top-trump-donor-agreed-to-pay-michael-cohen-10-million-for-nuclear-project-push-sources-say-1533245330 |archive-url= https://archive.today/20180802225217/https://www.wsj.com/articles/top-trump-donor-agreed-to-pay-michael-cohen-10-million-for-nuclear-project-push-sources-say-1533245330 |archive-date=August 2, 2018 |first4=Nicole |last4=Hong}}</ref>\n\n==Federal investigations==\n[[File:Cohen-v-US-Govt-Opposition-to-TRO-Request.pdf|thumb|Cohen v US \u2013 Govt Opposition to TRO Request]]\nAs of April 2018, Cohen was under federal criminal investigation by the [[United States Attorney for the Southern District of New York]] (SDNY).<ref name=\"Winter\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-wants-review-some-materials-seized-cohen-fbi-raid-n866226 |title=Fox News host Sean Hannity revealed as Michael Cohen's mystery client |last1=Winter |first1=Tom |last2=Edelman |first2=Adam |date=April 16, 2018 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |accessdate=April 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416122620/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-wants-review-some-materials-seized-cohen-fbi-raid-n866226 |archive-date=April 16, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"29investigations\" >{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/05/13/us/politics/trump-investigations.html |title=Tracking 29 Investigations Related to Trump |authors=Larry Buchanan and Karen Yourish |date=May 20, 2019 |website=nytimes.com |access-date=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn April 9, 2018, the [[FBI]] raided Cohen's office at the law firm of [[Squire Patton Boggs]], as well as his home and his hotel room in the Loews Regency Hotel in New York City, pursuant to a federal [[search warrant]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Strobel |first1=Warren |last2=Walcott |first2=John |title=FBI raids offices, home of Trump's personal lawyer: sources |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-cohen-raid/fbi-raids-offices-home-of-trumps-personal-lawyer-sources-idUSKBN1HG336 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=April 10, 2018 |accessdate=April 10, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180410012921/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-cohen-raid/fbi-raids-offices-home-of-trumps-personal-lawyer-sources-idUSKBN1HG336 |archive-date=April 10, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/09/politics/michael-cohen-fbi/index.html |title=FBI raids Trump lawyer Michael Cohen's office |first=Eli |last=Watkins |accessdate=May 3, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181006115044/https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/09/politics/michael-cohen-fbi/index.html |archive-date=October 6, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The warrant was obtained by the U.S. Attorney's Office for the SDNY, whose [[public corruption]] unit was conducting an investigation.<ref name=\"ShearRecords\" /> Seeking the warrant required high-level approval from the Department of Justice.<ref name=\"nytimes2018\">{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/09/us/politics/fbi-raids-office-of-trumps-longtime-lawyer-michael-cohen.html |title=F.B.I. Raids Office of Trump's Longtime Lawyer Michael Cohen |first=Matt |last=Apuzzo |authorlink=Matt Apuzzo |date=April 9, 2018 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180409201609/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/09/us/politics/fbi-raids-office-of-trumps-longtime-lawyer-michael-cohen.html |archive-date=April 9, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The Interim U.S. Attorney, [[Geoffrey Berman]], was recused.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/us-attorney-trump-appointee-recused-michael-cohen-investigation/story?id=54365546 |first=Jonathan |last=Karl |authorlink=Jonathan Karl |first2=Josh |last2=Margolin |title=Trump-appointed US attorney recused from Michael Cohen investigation |date=April 10, 2018 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |access-date=April 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411001510/http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/us-attorney-trump-appointee-recused-michael-cohen-investigation/story?id=54365546 |archive-date=April 11, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Deputy Attorney General [[Rod Rosenstein]] and FBI Director [[Christopher A. Wray|Christopher Wray]]\u2014both of whom are Trump appointees\u2014had supervisory roles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/michael-cohen-justice-department-raid-on-trump-lawyer-2018-4 |title=The Justice Department had to go to extraordinary lengths to conduct a raid on top Trump lawyer Michael Cohen |website=[[Business Insider]] |first=Allan |last=Smith |date=April 10, 2018 |accessdate=May 3, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180502230213/http://www.businessinsider.com/michael-cohen-justice-department-raid-on-trump-lawyer-2018-4 |archive-date=May 2, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The FBI obtained the warrant after a referral from [[Robert Mueller]]'s [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Special Counsel investigation]] into [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]], although underlying reasons for the raid were not revealed.<ref name=\"nytimes2018\" /><ref>{{cite news |first1=Erica |last1=Orden |first2=Rebecca |last2=Ballhaus |first3=Michael |last3=Rothfeld |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/fbi-raids-trump-lawyers-office-1523306297 |title=Agents Raid Office of Trump Lawyer Michael Cohen in Connection With Stormy Daniels Payments |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=April 9, 2018 |accessdate=April 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411035157/https://www.wsj.com/articles/fbi-raids-trump-lawyers-office-1523306297 |archive-date=April 11, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Following the raid, Squire Patton Boggs law firm ended its formal working relationship with Cohen.<ref>{{cite web |last=Lovelace |first=Ryan |url=https://www.law.com/nationallawjournal/2018/04/09/after-fbi-raid-squire-says-it-severed-ties-to-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen/ |title=After FBI Raid, Squire Says It Severed Ties to Trump Lawyer Michael Cohen |work=[[The National Law Journal]] |date=April 9, 2018 |accessdate=April 11, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180411145941/https://www.law.com/nationallawjournal/2018/04/09/after-fbi-raid-squire-says-it-severed-ties-to-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen/ |archive-date=April 11, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAgents seized emails, tax records, business records, and other matter related to several topics, including payments made by Cohen to Stormy Daniels,<ref name=\"nytimes2018\" /> and records related to [[Donald Trump Access Hollywood tape|Trump's ''Access Hollywood'' controversy]].<ref>{{cite news |authorlink=Maggie Haberman |last1=Haberman |first1=Maggie |last2=Apuzzo |first2=Matt |author2link=Matt Apuzzo |last3=Schmidt |first3=Michael S. |authorlink3=Michael S. Schmidt |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/11/us/politics/michael-cohen-trump-access-hollywood.html |title=Raid on Trump's Lawyer Sought Records on 'Access Hollywood' Tape |date=April 11, 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=April 11, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180411183333/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/11/us/politics/michael-cohen-trump-access-hollywood.html |archive-date=April 11, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Recordings of phone conversations Cohen made were also obtained.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/13/politics/fbi-phone-recordings-cohen-daniels-mcdougal/index.html |first=Gloria |last=Borger |authorlink=Gloria Borger |first2=Sara |last2=Sidner |author2link=Sara Sidner |first3=Scott |last3=Glover |title=Exclusive: FBI seized recordings between Trump's lawyer and Stormy Daniels' former lawyer |date=April 13, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=April 14, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180414003708/https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/13/politics/fbi-phone-recordings-cohen-daniels-mcdougal/index.html |archive-date=April 14, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> According to Stormy Daniels' attorney [[Michael Avenatti]] and civil rights attorney [[Lisa Bloom]], some of the recordings may have included participants located in California, which would make the recordings illegal, as California is a \"[[telephone recording laws#Two-party consent states|two party consent]]\" state.<ref>{{cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n1f4-vZby88&t=1m19s |date=April 14, 2018 |people=[[Joy Reid]] (interviewer), [[Michael Avenatti]] & [[Lisa Bloom]] (interviewees) |title=Avenatti and Bloom on ''A.M. Joy'' |work=[[A.M. Joy]] |publisher=[[MSNBC]] |access-date=December 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227223857/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n1f4-vZby88&t=1m19s |archive-date=February 27, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nSince Cohen is an attorney, the search included the seizure of materials normally protected by [[attorney-client privilege]], which is subject to a [[crime-fraud exception]] if a crime is suspected.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.lawfareblog.com/michael-cohen-attorney-client-privilege-and-crime-fraud-exception |first=Paul |last=Rosenzweig |title=Michael Cohen, Attorney-Client Privilege and the Crime-Fraud Exception |date=April 10, 2018 |publisher=[[Lawfare (blog)|Lawfare]]|access-date=April 11, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180411094135/https://www.lawfareblog.com/michael-cohen-attorney-client-privilege-and-crime-fraud-exception |archive-date=April 11, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Some legal scholars opined that Trump's denial that he had knowledge of the Daniels payment, combined with denials by Cohen and his lawyer [[David Schwartz (lawyer)|David Schwartz]], meant both sides had effectively said that matter did not involve attorney-client communications.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/04/10/how-trump-may-have-invited-investigators-to-go-after-michael-cohen/ |title=How Trump may have unwittingly invited the Michael Cohen raid |last=Blake |first=Aaron |date=April 10, 2018 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=April 11, 2018 |issn=0190-8286 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180411064731/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/04/10/how-trump-may-have-invited-investigators-to-go-after-michael-cohen/ |archive-date=April 11, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen and his lawyers argued that all of the thousands of items seized during the FBI raid should be protected by attorney-client privilege and thus withheld from the prosecutors. U.S. District Judge [[Kimba M. Wood]], appointed a [[special master]], former federal judge [[Barbara S. Jones]], to review all of the seized materials for attorney-client privilege. She found that only 14 of the 639 paper documents were privileged, and out of the 291,770 electronic files seized, only 148 files were withheld from the prosecution.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/04/nyregion/cohen-special-master-review.html |title=Special Master in Cohen Case Finds Few Seized Materials Are Privileged |access-date=September 5, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180905215031/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/04/nyregion/cohen-special-master-review.html |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The search warrant itself has been sealed, making it unavailable to the public.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://lawandcrime.com/high-profile/why-the-fbi-raid-suggests-michael-cohen-should-be-really-really-scared-that-hes-next/ |first1=Rachel |last1=Stockman |title=Analysis: The FBI Raid Means Michael Cohen Should Be Really, Really Scared He's Next |publisher=[[Law & Crime]] |date=April 9, 2018 |access-date=April 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180410201850/https://lawandcrime.com/high-profile/why-the-fbi-raid-suggests-michael-cohen-should-be-really-really-scared-that-hes-next/ |archive-date=April 10, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The FBI also sought documents pertaining to Cohen's ownership of [[taxi medallion]]s.<ref name=\"ShearRecords\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/382482-fbi-search-warrant-on-cohen-inquired-into-taxi-medallion-ownership |title=FBI search warrant on Cohen covered taxi medallion ownership |last=Delk |first=Josh |date=April 10, 2018 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=April 10, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180411025811/http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/382482-fbi-search-warrant-on-cohen-inquired-into-taxi-medallion-ownership |archive-date=April 11, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen's taxi fleet is operated by [[Gene Freidman]], who is facing legal trouble for alleged [[tax evasion]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/04/what-exactly-was-michael-cohen-doing-for-donald-trump/557801/ |title= What Exactly Was Michael Cohen Doing for Donald Trump? |work=[[The Atlantic]]|first=David A.|last=Graham|date=April 12, 2018|accessdate=April 12, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180413043706/https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/04/what-exactly-was-michael-cohen-doing-for-donald-trump/557801/ |archive-date=April 13, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nA few days after the raid, [[The McClatchy Company|McClatchy]] reported that the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Mueller investigation]] was in possession of evidence that Cohen traveled to [[Prague]] in August or September 2016. If true, the report bolsters similar claims in 3 of 17 reports from the [[Trump\u2013Russia dossier]]. According to McClatchy's confidential sources, Cohen traveled to Prague via Germany, a passage that would not have required use of a passport due to both countries being within the [[Schengen Area]].<ref name=\"Stone_Gordon_4/13/2018\">{{cite news |url= http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/white-house/article208870264.html |title=Sources: Mueller has evidence Cohen was in Prague in 2016, confirming part of dossier |publisher=[[The McClatchy Company|McClatchy DC Bureau]] |date=April 13, 2018 |last=Stone |first=Peter |last2=Gordon |first2=Greg |accessdate=April 16, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180413234700/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/white-house/article208870264.html |archive-date=April 13, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=Bump>{{cite news |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/politics/wp/2018/04/14/michael-cohen-visiting-prague-would-be-a-huge-development-in-the-russia-investigation/ |title=Michael Cohen's visiting Prague would be a huge development in the Russia investigation |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=April 14, 2018 |last=Bump |first=Philip |accessdate=April 16, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180415084835/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/politics/wp/2018/04/14/michael-cohen-visiting-prague-would-be-a-huge-development-in-the-russia-investigation/ |archive-date=April 15, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=Reuters-180414>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-russia-prague/special-counsel-has-evidence-michael-cohen-traveled-to-prague-mcclatchy-idUSKBN1HL00J |title=Special counsel has evidence Michael Cohen traveled to Prague: McClatchy |work=[[Reuters]] |date=April 14, 2018 |accessdate=April 16, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180416052343/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-russia-prague/special-counsel-has-evidence-michael-cohen-traveled-to-prague-mcclatchy-idUSKBN1HL00J |archive-date=April 16, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In reaction, Cohen denied having ever been to Prague, as he had done in his January 2017 denial following the dossier's release.<ref name=\"CBS_News_4/14/2018\" /><ref name=Porter>{{cite news |url=http://www.newsweek.com/mueller-has-evidence-back-russia-dossiers-claims-about-trump-attorney-cohen-886152 |title=Trump Attorney Lied About Prague Trip, Mueller Investigation Reveals, As New Evidence Comes To Light |work=[[Newsweek]] |date=April 14, 2018 |last=Porter |first=Tom |accessdate=April 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180415224129/http://www.newsweek.com/mueller-has-evidence-back-russia-dossiers-claims-about-trump-attorney-cohen-886152 |archive-date=April 15, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''Mother Jones'' reported that Cohen had told them \"I was in Prague for one afternoon 14 years ago,\" contradicting later statements that he had never visited.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2018/04/michael-cohen-says-hes-never-been-to-prague-he-told-me-a-different-story/|title=Michael Cohen says he's \"never\" been to Prague. He told me a different story.|work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]|access-date=July 4, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181230005649/https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2018/04/michael-cohen-says-hes-never-been-to-prague-he-told-me-a-different-story/|archive-date=December 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, [[NBC]] reported that Cohen's phone calls had been monitored by [[pen register]], which logs the origins and destinations of calls but not the contents.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/feds-tapped-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-s-phones-n871011 |title=Feds monitored Trump lawyer Michael Cohen's phones |first=Tom |last=Winter |first2=Julia |last2=Ainsley |date=May 3, 2018 |accessdate=May 3, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180503165933/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/feds-tapped-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-s-phones-n871011 |archive-date=May 3, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.mediaite.com/tv/nbc-issues-major-correction-feds-monitored-michael-cohens-calls-did-not-wiretap/ |title=Breaking: NBC News Issues Major Correction, Michael Cohen Was Not Wiretapped |first=Aidan |last=McLaughlin |publisher=[[Mediaite]] |accessdate=May 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504091618/https://www.mediaite.com/tv/nbc-issues-major-correction-feds-monitored-michael-cohens-calls-did-not-wiretap/ |archive-date=May 4, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n''The Wall Street Journal'' reported on July 26, 2018, that longtime [[Trump Organization]] CFO [[Allen Weisselberg]] had been subpoenaed to testify before a federal grand jury regarding the Cohen investigation.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.cnbc.com/2018/07/26/trump-org-cfo-called-to-grand-jury-to-testify-wsj.html |title=Trump Org. CFO mentioned in Michael Cohen tape called by grand jury to testify: WSJ |first1=Dan |last1=Mangan |first2=Kevin |last2=Breuninger |date=July 26, 2018 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180821202057/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/07/26/trump-org-cfo-called-to-grand-jury-to-testify-wsj.html |archive-date=August 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Conviction on campaign finance, tax evasion, and other charges===\nIn August 2018, it was reported that investigators were in the final stages of their investigation.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://nypost.com/2018/08/19/michael-cohen-reportedly-under-investigation-for-20m-in-bank-fraud/ |title=Michael Cohen reportedly under investigation for $20M in bank fraud |date=August 19, 2018 |work=New York Post |access-date=August 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820011819/https://nypost.com/2018/08/19/michael-cohen-reportedly-under-investigation-for-20m-in-bank-fraud/|archive-date=August 20, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen officially surrendered to the FBI on August 21, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-michael-cohen-plea-deal-fraud-case-20180821-story.html |title=Ex-Trump lawyer Cohen pleads guilty in hush-money scheme, campaign finance violations |agency=Associated Press |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |first=Larry |last=Neumeister |first2=Tom |last2=Hays |access-date=August 21, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180821223256/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-michael-cohen-plea-deal-fraud-case-20180821-story.html |archive-date=August 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> That afternoon, Cohen pleaded guilty to eight criminal<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/trump-michael-cohen-crimes-not-crimes-talking-point-2018-8 |title=Trump is latching on to a popular right-wing talking point about Michael Cohen that experts say is 'nonsense' |website=[[Business Insider]] |accessdate=August 25, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180826093407/http://uk.businessinsider.com/trump-michael-cohen-crimes-not-crimes-talking-point-2018-8 |archive-date=August 26, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> charges: five counts of [[tax evasion]], one count of making false statements to a financial institution, one count of willfully causing an unlawful corporate contribution, and one count of making an excessive campaign contribution at the request of a candidate (Trump) for the \"principal purpose of influencing [the] election\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/michael-cohen-to-plead-guilty-to-criminal-charges-1534875978 |title=Michael Cohen Pleads Guilty, Says He Acted at Trump's Direction |first1=Nicole |last1=Hong |first2=Rebecca |last2=Ballhaus|date=August 21, 2018 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |access-date=August 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821205500/https://www.wsj.com/articles/michael-cohen-to-plead-guilty-to-criminal-charges-1534875978 |archive-date=August 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Ex-Trump lawyer\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-45265546 |title=Ex-Trump lawyer admits campaign violation |date=August 21, 2018 |work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=August 21, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180821180933/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-45265546 |archive-date=August 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Ex-Trump lawyer\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/08/21/trumps-ex-lawyer-michael-cohen-strikes-plea-deal-nbc-news.html |title=Trump's former lawyer Michael Cohen pleads guilty, admits to making illegal payments at direction of candidate to influence election |first1=Tucker |last1=Higgins|first2=Kevin |last2=Breuninger |date=August 21, 2018 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |access-date=August 21, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180821211608/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/08/21/trumps-ex-lawyer-michael-cohen-strikes-plea-deal-nbc-news.html |archive-date=August 21, 2018 |url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter Cohen's conviction, his personal lawyer [[Lanny Davis]] stated that Cohen was ready to \"tell everything about Donald Trump that he knows\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-45270339 |title=Trump ex-lawyer 'happy' to aid Russia probe |date=August 22, 2018 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=August 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180822115807/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-45270339 |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Davis alluded to Cohen's knowledge that could be used against Trump, and hinted that Cohen had knowledge of whether Trump knew in advance about the computer hacking that was detrimental to [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2016|Hillary Clinton's presidential campaign]], as well as knowledge of the [[Trump Tower meeting|meeting at Trump Tower]] in June 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Becker |first1=Isaac |title=Cohen lawyer Lanny Davis suggests his client has knowledge implicating Trump in 'criminal conspiracy' to hack Democratic emails |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2018/08/22/cohen-lawyer-lanny-davis-suggests-his-client-has-knowledge-implicating-trump-in-criminal-conspiracy-to-hack-democratic-emails/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180822084903/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2018/08/22/cohen-lawyer-lanny-davis-suggests-his-client-has-knowledge-implicating-trump-in-criminal-conspiracy-to-hack-democratic-emails/ |archive-date= August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> He later added that he believed Cohen would agree to testify before Congress, even without immunity.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/22/politics/lanny-davis-michael-cohen-testify-no-immunity-cnntv/index.html |title=Cohen lawyer says he would testify to Congress about Trump without immunity |last=Vazquez |first=Maegan |date=August 22, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=August 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180822175008/https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/22/politics/lanny-davis-michael-cohen-testify-no-immunity-cnntv/index.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nResponding to speculation that President Trump might issue a [[Presidential pardon|pardon]] for Cohen, lawyer Davis said on [[NPR]], \"I know that Mr. Cohen would never accept a pardon from a man that he considers to be both corrupt and a dangerous person in the oval office. And [Cohen] has flatly authorized me to say under no circumstances would he accept a pardon from Mr. Trump.\"<ref>{{cite news |publisher=[[NPR]] |work=[[Morning Edition]] |first=Colin |last=Dwyer |first2=Ryan |last2=Lucas |title=Michael Cohen's Lawyer Says His Client Would Never Accept Pardon From 'Corrupt' Trump |url= https://www.npr.org/2018/08/22/640795902/michael-cohens-lawyer-says-hed-never-accept-a-pardon-from-president-trump |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180822150154/https://www.npr.org/2018/08/22/640795902/michael-cohens-lawyer-says-hed-never-accept-a-pardon-from-president-trump |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In his interview to Sky News, Davis said the turning point for his client's attitude toward Trump was the [[2018 Russia\u2013United States summit|Helsinki summit]] in July 2018, which caused him to doubt Trump's loyalty to the U.S.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://news.sky.com/story/putin-news-conference-drove-michael-cohen-away-from-trump-11479458 |title=Putin news conference drove Michael Cohen away from Trump|publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=August 22, 2018 |accessdate=August 22, 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180823005921/https://news.sky.com/story/putin-news-conference-drove-michael-cohen-away-from-trump-11479458|archive-date=August 23, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n''The New York Times'' reported on August 22, 2018, that Cohen court documents revealed that two senior [[Trump Organization]] executives were also involved in the [[hush money]] payments, and that Cohen \"coordinated with one or more members of the campaign, including through meetings and phone calls\" about the payments.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/22/nyregion/cohen-trump-organization-campaign-hush-money.html |title=Cohen Wasn't Alone: Records Suggest Others in Trump Circle Had Role in Hush Money Arrangements|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 22, 2018 |first=William K. |last=Rashbaum |accessdate=August 22, 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180823012340/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/22/nyregion/cohen-trump-organization-campaign-hush-money.html|archive-date=August 23, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nBy mid-October 2018, Cohen had sat for at least 50 hours of interviews with Mueller's investigators and other investigators, although he had no formal cooperation agreement with prosecutors.<ref>[[Emily Jane Fox|Fox, Emily Jane]] (October 15, 2018). [https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2018/10/michael-cohen-trump-investigation \"He Is Trying to Make It Right\": As the Midterms Approach, Michael Cohen Is Doubling Down on His Civic Duty] {{Webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181128175341/https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2018/10/michael-cohen-trump-investigation |date=November 28, 2018}}, ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''.</ref> Cohen also cooperated in a separate investigation by New York State investigators regarding the Trump Organization and Trump Foundation.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/michael-cohen-spoke-mueller-team-hours-asked-russia/story?id=57959664 |title=Michael Cohen spoke to Mueller team for hours; asked about Russia, possible collusion |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=September 20, 2018 |access-date=September 20, 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180921000523/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/michael-cohen-spoke-mueller-team-hours-asked-russia/story?id=57959664 |archive-date=September 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn December 12, 2018, U.S. District Judge [[William H. Pauley III]] sentenced Cohen to three years in prison and a $50,000 fine, and additionally ordered Cohen to pay $1.4&nbsp;million in restitution and to [[criminal forfeiture|forfeit]] $500,000.<ref name=\"UPI\">Cone, Allen; Adamczyk, Ed (December 13, 2018). [https://www.upi.com/Michael-Cohen-sentenced-to-3-years-in-prison-stemming-from-plea-deal/5891544588060 Michael Cohen sentenced to 3 years in prison stemming from plea deal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215224102/https://www.upi.com/Michael-Cohen-sentenced-to-3-years-in-prison-stemming-from-plea-deal/5891544588060 |date=December 15, 2018}}, [[United Press International]].</ref><ref>\nHamilton, Colby (December 12, 2018). [https://www.law.com/2018/12/12/cohen-sentenced-to-36-months-in-prison-in-sdny-mueller-prosecutions/?slreturn=20181112163109 Cohen's 'Blind Loyalty' Leads to 3-Year Prison Term] {{Webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181215224824/https://www.law.com/2018/12/12/cohen-sentenced-to-36-months-in-prison-in-sdny-mueller-prosecutions/?slreturn=20181112163109 |date=December 15, 2018}}, ''[[New York Law Journal]]''.</ref><ref name=\"BBC 12/12/2018\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-46546238 |title=Ex-Trump lawyer Cohen jailed for 36 months |date=December 12, 2018 |work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=December 12, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181212193446/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-46546238 |archive-date=December 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> At his sentencing hearing, Cohen stated: \"I take full responsibility for each act that I pled guilty to: The personal ones to me and those involving the president of the United States of America.\"<ref name=\"UPI\" /> Cohen said Trump was \"the man that caused me to choose the path of darkness\" and do \"dirty deeds\".<ref name=\"BBC 12/12/2018\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/12/12/former-donald-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-sentenced-blind-loyalty/2274755002/|title=Michael Cohen, Trump's former lawyer, is sentenced to three years in prison for 'dirty deeds' |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=December 12, 2018 |access-date=December 12, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181212175530/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/12/12/former-donald-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-sentenced-blind-loyalty/2274755002/ |archive-date=December 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Before passing sentence, Judge Pauley said, \"each of these crimes is a serious offense against the United States. Mr. Cohen pled guilty to a veritable smorgasbord of fraudulent conduct.\"<ref name=\"UPI\" />\n\n===Conviction for perjury in congressional testimony===\nOn November 29, 2018, Cohen pleaded guilty to lying to the [[Senate Intelligence Committee]] and [[House Intelligence Committee]] in 2017 regarding the proposed [[Trump Tower Moscow]] deal that he spearheaded in 2015 and 2016.<ref name=\"GuiltyMoscowProject\" /><ref name=\"CongPerjury\">{{cite news |first=Devlin |last=Barrett |first2=Matt |last2=Zapotosky |author3link=Rosalind Helderman |first3=Rosalind S. |last3=Helderman |title=Michael Cohen, Trump's former lawyer, pleads guilty to lying to Congress about Moscow project |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/michael-cohen-trumps-former-lawyer-pleads-guilty-to-lying-to-congress/2018/11/29/5fac986a-f3e0-11e8-bc79-68604ed88993_story.html |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=November 29, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129161726/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/michael-cohen-trumps-former-lawyer-pleads-guilty-to-lying-to-congress/2018/11/29/5fac986a-f3e0-11e8-bc79-68604ed88993_story.html |archive-date=November 29, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Cohen had told Congress that the deal ceased in January 2016 when it actually ended in June 2016, and that he had not received a response about the deal from the office of a senior Russian official when he actually had.<ref name=\"CongPerjury\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-46390368 |title=Trump ex-lawyer admits lying to Congress |date=November 29, 2018 |accessdate=December 1, 2018 |work=[[BBC News]]|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181130122304/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-46390368 |archive-date=November 30, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen said that he had given the false testimony in order to be consistent with Trump's \"repeated disavowals of commercial and political ties between himself and Russia\" and out of loyalty to Trump.<ref name=\"CongPerjury\" /> Cohen received a two-month sentence, to be served concurrently with his three-year sentence for tax fraud, for the false testimony.<ref name=\"CNBC Cohen Sentenced\" />\n\nThis charge was brought directly by [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Robert Mueller's investigation]], rather than the United States Attorney for the SDNY, who brought the previous charges against Cohen.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/11/29/michael-cohen-robert-mueller-trump-plea-deal/2147323002/ |title=Robert Mueller probe: Ex-Trump lawyer Michael Cohen pleads guilty to lying to Congress |date=November 29, 2018 |work=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=November 30, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181130011357/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/11/29/michael-cohen-robert-mueller-trump-plea-deal/2147323002/ |archive-date=November 30, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In a sentencing memorandum filed the following day, Cohen's attorneys stated he kept Trump \"apprised\" of the \"substantive conversation\" Cohen had in January 2016 with a Russian official, and discussed with Trump traveling to Russia to advance the project during the summer of 2016. The filing also stated Cohen \"remained in close and regular contact with White House-based staff and legal counsel\" as he prepared to provide false testimony to Congress.<ref>{{cite news |date=December 1, 2018 |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-russia/ex-lawyer-says-he-told-trump-about-kremlin-contact-court-filing-idUSKCN1O03E0 |title=Ex-lawyer says he told Trump about Kremlin contact: court filing |work=[[Reuters]] |accessdate= December 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181201193414/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-russia/ex-lawyer-says-he-told-trump-about-kremlin-contact-court-filing-idUSKCN1O03E0 |archive-date=December 1, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a [[BuzzFeed]] report on January 17, 2019, President [[Donald Trump]] personally directed Cohen to lie to Congress about the [[Trump Tower Moscow]] project.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sullivan |first=Kate |authorlink=Kate Sullivan |publisher=[[CNN]] |title=BuzzFeed: Sources say Trump directed Michael Cohen to lie to Congress about proposed Moscow project |date=January 18, 2019 |accessdate=January 18, 2018 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/17/politics/buzzfeed-trump-cohen-lie-congress-moscow/index.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190118050831/https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/17/politics/buzzfeed-trump-cohen-lie-congress-moscow/index.html |archive-date=January 18, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Elfrink |first=Tim |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |title=Democrats demand investigation after report that Trump ordered Michael Cohen to lie to Congress |date=January 18, 2019 |accessdate=January 18, 2019 |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/01/18/democrats-demand-investigation-after-report-that-trump-ordered-michael-cohen-lie-congress-about-russian-project/ |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190118082548/https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/01/18/democrats-demand-investigation-after-report-that-trump-ordered-michael-cohen-lie-congress-about-russian-project/ |archive-date=January 18, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> However, a spokesman for the Special Counsel investigation later said the report was \"not accurate\", but did not specify \"which parts of the BuzzFeed story they were calling untrue\".<ref name=\"Polantz Kelly 2019\">{{cite news |last=Polantz |first=Katelyn |last2=Kelly |first2=Caroline |title=Mueller's office disputes BuzzFeed report that Trump directed Michael Cohen to lie to Congress |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=January 19, 2019 |url= https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/18/politics/mueller-statement-buzzfeed/index.html |access-date=January 19, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190119012435/https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/18/politics/mueller-statement-buzzfeed/index.html |archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn February 26, 2019, he was officially [[Disbarment|disbarred]] by the [[New York State Bar Association]].<ref name=\":0\">https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/justice-department/michael-cohen-has-been-disbarred-n976436</ref>\n\n==State of New York's investigations==\n{{Anchor|State investigations}}\nOn August 22, 2018, it was announced that the [[New York State Department of Taxation and Finance]] had subpoenaed Cohen in connection with its investigation into whether the [[Donald J. Trump Foundation]] had violated [[New York tax law]]s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/22/politics/michael-cohen-trump-foundation-subpoena/ |title=New York tax investigators subpoena Michael Cohen in Trump Foundation probe |last1=Orden |first1=Erica |last2=Tatum |first2=Sophie |date= August 22, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180822224534/https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/22/politics/michael-cohen-trump-foundation-subpoena/ }}</ref> This investigation is separate from the [[New York Attorney General]]'s lawsuit alleging that the foundation and its directors violated state and federal laws about the operation of charities.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/14/politics/new-york-lawsuit-trump-foundation/ |title=New York attorney general sues Trump Foundation |last1=Isidore |first1=Chris |last2=Schuman |first2=Melanie |date=June 14, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate= August 23, 2018 |archive-date=August 24, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180824002227/https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/14/politics/new-york-lawsuit-trump-foundation/ }}\n</ref>\n\n==Congressional investigations==\nOn January 10, 2019, Cohen agreed to testify publicly before the [[House Oversight Committee]] to give a \"full and credible account\" of his work on behalf of Trump.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/10/us/politics/michael-cohen-testify-trump-congress.html |title=Michael Cohen Agrees to Testify to Congress About Work for Trump|last=Haberman |first=Maggie |authorlink=Maggie Haberman |date=January 10, 2019|work=[[The New York Times]] |last2=Fandos|first2=Nicholas |access-date=January 10, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190110202807/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/10/us/politics/michael-cohen-testify-trump-congress.html|archive-date=January 10, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On January 12, Fox News\u00a0contributor and legal analyst\u00a0[[Jeanine Pirro]]\u00a0took a 20-minute, on-air phone call from Trump in which he claimed Cohen had fabricated stories to reduce the length of his expected sentence. Trump suggested that investigations should instead focus on Cohen's father-in-law, saying \"that's the one people want to look at.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/beta-story-container/Politics/michael-cohen-fears-trump-rhetoric-place-family-risk/story?id=60430893 |title=Michael Cohen fears Trump rhetoric could put his family at risk: Sources |last1=Larramendia |first1=Eliana |last2=Hill |first2=James |date=January 16, 2019 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |accessdate=January 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227223857/https://abcnews.go.com/beta-story-container/Politics/michael-cohen-fears-trump-rhetoric-place-family-risk/story?id=60430893 |archive-date=February 27, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The father-in-law, Fima Shusterman, owned condos both at Trump Tower and in a Trump development near Miami.<ref>Gualtieri, Allison Elyse. [https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/who-is-michael-cohens-father-in-law-trump-says-he-should-be-investigated Who is Michael Cohen's father-in-law? Trump says he should be investigated] {{Webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190124203949/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/who-is-michael-cohens-father-in-law-trump-says-he-should-be-investigated |date=January 24, 2019}}, ''[[Washington Examiner]]'', January 12, 2019. Retrieved January 24, 2019.</ref> According to former federal investigators, Shusterman actually introduced Trump to Cohen.<ref name=\"Rolling Stone Brief History of Criminal Ties\">Hettena, Seth. [https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/a-brief-history-of-michael-cohens-criminal-ties-628875/ A Brief History of Michael Cohen's Criminal Ties From the Russian mob to money launderers, Trump's personal attorney has long been a subject of interest to federal investigators] {{Webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190116175418/https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/a-brief-history-of-michael-cohens-criminal-ties-628875/ |date=January 16, 2019}}, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', April 10, 2018. Retrieved January 24, 2019.</ref>\u00a0On several subsequent occasions Trump hinted publicly that Cohen's father-in-law, or possibly even Cohen's wife, could be tied to criminal activity. On January 20 Trump's attorney Rudy Giuliani suggested on CNN that the father-in-law \"may have ties to something called organized crime\".<ref name=\"explained\">{{cite news |url= https://www.vox.com/2019/1/23/18194719/trump-michael-cohen-father-in-law-threat |title=Michael Cohen's claim that President Trump is threatening his family, explained |last=Prokop |first=Andrew |date=January 24, 2019 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |accessdate=January 25, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190125005548/https://www.vox.com/2019/1/23/18194719/trump-michael-cohen-father-in-law-threat |archive-date=January 25, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn January 23, Cohen announced through his attorney that he would postpone his testimony to a later date, citing \"ongoing threats against his family from President Trump\" and Giuliani.<ref name=\"explained\"/> Some legal analysts asserted that these comments by Trump and Giuliani constituted intimidation and witness tampering;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abajournal.com/news/article/following-fox-news-interview-some-wonder-if-president-engaged-in-obstruction/?icn=most_read |title=Legal experts weigh in on Trump's Cohen comments and whether they amount to witness intimidation |last=Ward |first=Stephanie Francis |date=January 15, 2019 |work=[[ABA Journal]] |accessdate=January 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190126061131/http://www.abajournal.com/news/article/following-fox-news-interview-some-wonder-if-president-engaged-in-obstruction/?icn=most_read|archive-date=January 26, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> House Oversight Committee chairman [[Elijah Cummings]] and [[House Intelligence Committee]] chairman [[Adam Schiff]] said that threatening a witness's family is \"textbook mob tactics\".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/23/us/politics/michael-cohen-testimony-postponed-congress.html |title=Michael Cohen Indefinitely Postpones Testimony to Congress, Citing Fears of Family's Safety|first=Maggie|last=Haberman |authorlink=Maggie Haberman |date=January 23, 2019|work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=January 24, 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190124011634/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/23/us/politics/michael-cohen-testimony-postponed-congress.html|archive-date=January 24, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/01/23/michael-cohen-says-trump-giuliani-threatened-him-does-that-amount-witness-tampering/|title=Analysis &#124; Michael Cohen says Trump and Giuliani threatened him. Does that amount to witness tampering?|work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=January 24, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190124010656/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/01/23/michael-cohen-says-trump-giuliani-threatened-him-does-that-amount-witness-tampering/ |archive-date=January 24, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter several scheduling delays, Cohen testified before three congressional committees in late February. First was a February 26, 2019, closed-door hearing before the Senate Intelligence Committee. He testified for more than seven hours.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/michael-cohen-testimony-lawmakers-to-grill-cohen-on-trump-tower-deal-during-closed-door-hearing/|title=Cohen to face questions on Trump Tower deal, BuzzFeed report at closed-door hearing|last=Montoya-Galvez|first=Camilo|date=February 25, 2019|work=CBS News|accessdate=4 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306042706/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/michael-cohen-testimony-lawmakers-to-grill-cohen-on-trump-tower-deal-during-closed-door-hearing/|archive-date=March 6, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAlso on February 26, [[Florida's 1st congressional district|Florida Republican Congressman]] [[Matt Gaetz]] directly threatened Cohen via Twitter, hinting about unspecified disclosures to Cohen's wife and father-in-law.<ref>{{cite news |title=A high-profile Trump ally in Congress just straight-up threatened Michael Cohen |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/26/politics/matt-gaetz-tweet-michael-cohen/index.html |date=2019-02-27 |publisher=[[CNN]] |authorlink=Chris Cillizza |first=Chris |last=Cillizza |accessdate=2019-02-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228002541/https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/26/politics/matt-gaetz-tweet-michael-cohen/index.html |archive-date=February 28, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=GOP Congressman Threatens Michael Cohen on Twitter, Then Apologizes |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/02/gop-congressman-may-have-threatened-michael-cohen-on-twitter.html |date=2019-02-27 |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |first=Matt |last=Stieb |accessdate=2019-02-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228191835/http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/02/gop-congressman-may-have-threatened-michael-cohen-on-twitter.html |archive-date=February 28, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The [[Florida Bar Association]] plans to investigate the incident.<ref>{{cite news |title=Florida Bar Will Investigate Matt Gaetz's Threat Against Cohen |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/27/us/politics/matt-gaetz-cohen.html |date=2019-02-27 |work=[[The New York Times]] |first=Nicholas |last=Fandos |accessdate=2019-02-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227230212/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/27/us/politics/matt-gaetz-cohen.html |archive-date=February 27, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe following day, February 27, Cohen gave 10 hours of public, televised testimony before the House Oversight Committee, during which he described Trump as a \"racist,\" a \"con man\", and a \"cheat\", and expressed remorse and shame for the things he had done for Trump. He said the president had reimbursed him for illegal hush money payments, suggested that he should lie to Congress and the public about the Trump Tower Moscow negotiations, and filed false financial statements with banks and insurance companies. Republicans hammered on his previous false testimony, asking why he should be believed now.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/02/27/ex-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-testify-house-oversight-committee/2995659002/|title='I am not protecting Mr. Trump anymore.' Michael Cohen ties the president to ongoing criminal probes|date=February 27, 2019|work=USA Today|accessdate=4 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301151914/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/02/27/ex-trump-lawyer-michael-cohen-testify-house-oversight-committee/2995659002/|archive-date=March 1, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/02/27/696752450/michael-cohen-to-testify-publicly-before-congress-on-alleged-trump-lawbreaking|title=Michael Cohen Calls Trump A 'Racist' And A 'Con Man' In Scathing Testimony|last=Ewing|first=Philip|date=February 27, 2019|work=NPR|accessdate=4 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190304002320/https://www.npr.org/2019/02/27/696752450/michael-cohen-to-testify-publicly-before-congress-on-alleged-trump-lawbreaking|archive-date=March 4, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn February 28, Cohen testified behind closed doors to the House Intelligence Committee for more than seven hours. Cohen returned to that committee for more questioning on March 6.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/28/politics/michael-cohen-testimony-house-intelligence-committee/index.html|title=Michael Cohen will return to Congress March 6, Felix Sater to testify March 14|date=February 28, 2019|work=CNN|accessdate=4 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190304042611/https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/28/politics/michael-cohen-testimony-house-intelligence-committee/index.html|archive-date=March 4, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCohen married [[Ukrainians|Ukrainian]]-born Laura Shusterman in 1994.<ref name=\"FootSoldier\" /><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/michael-cohens-ties-to-russia-crime-and-trump-w518941 |title=A Brief History of Michael Cohen's Criminal Ties|last=Hettena|first=Seth|date=April 10, 2018|work=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=August 23, 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180616205156/https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/michael-cohens-ties-to-russia-crime-and-trump-w518941|archive-date=June 16, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT180504\">{{cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/05/business/michael-cohen-lawyer-trump.html |title=How Michael Cohen, Trump's Fixer, Built a Shadowy Business Empire|last1=Rashbaum|first1=William K.|date=May 5, 2018|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |last2=Hakim |first2=Danny |last3=Rosenthal |first3=Brian M. |last4=Flitter |first4=Emily |last5=Drucker |first5=Jesse |access-date=May 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180505203455/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/05/business/michael-cohen-lawyer-trump.html|archive-date=May 5, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Laura Shusterman's father, Fima Shusterman, left [[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic|Soviet Ukraine]] for New York in 1975.<ref name=\"NYT180504\" /> They have a daughter, Samantha, and a son, Jake.<ref name=\"LAT20181213\">{{Cite news|first1=Chris|last1=Megerian|first2=Sonja|last2=Sharp |title= Michael Cohen, Trump's longtime lawyer, sentenced to three years in prison|date=December 12, 2018|url= https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-michael-cohen-sentencing-20181212-story.html|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=December 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181213023808/https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-michael-cohen-sentencing-20181212-story.html|archive-date=December 13, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cohen's father-in-law was the person who introduced him to Trump, according to a Trump biographer.<ref name=\"Rolling Stone Brief History of Criminal Ties\" /><ref>Kwong, Jessica. (December 3, 2018). \"Who is Michael Cohen's wife? Laura Shusterman never charged though prosecutors had evidence implicating her, according to report.\" [https://www.newsweek.com/who-michael-cohen-wife-laura-shusterman-1242311 Newsweek website] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116065334/https://www.newsweek.com/who-michael-cohen-wife-laura-shusterman-1242311 |date=January 16, 2019}} ''[[Newsweek]]''. Retrieved December 16, 2018.</ref> Cohen's uncle is a doctor who treated members of the [[Lucchese crime family]].<ref name=\"NYT180504\" /> The uncle owned \"El Caribe Country Club\", known to be frequented by individuals associated with the [[Russian mafia]]: [[Evsei Agron]], [[Marat Balagula]], and [[Boris Nayfeld]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Hettena |first=Seth |date=May 2018 |title=Trump / Russia: A Definitive History |url= https://www.mhpbooks.com/books/trump-russia |publisher=Melville House |page=80 |isbn=978-1612197395 |access-date= December 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131232058/https://www.mhpbooks.com/books/trump-russia/ |archive-date=January 31, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nCohen served as chairman of the board of directors of [[Columbia Grammar & Preparatory School]] through late 2016.\n\nBefore joining the Trump Organization, Cohen had purchased several homes in Trump's buildings.<ref name=\"Falcone\" /> A 2017 ''New York Times'' article reported that Cohen is known for having \"a penchant for [[luxury goods|luxury]]\"; he was married at [[The Pierre]], drove a [[Porsche]] while attending college, and once owned a [[Bentley]].<ref name=\"FootSoldier\" />\n\n==In popular culture==\nAs the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|investigation surrounding Donald Trump]] was in the daily news headlines, the story became fodder for parody on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', with Trump being portrayed by [[Alec Baldwin]] and Cohen by [[Ben Stiller]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cadenas |first1=Kerensa |title=Alec Baldwin Returns to S.N.L. as Trump with Ben Stiller as Michael Cohen |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/12/alec-baldwin-snl-trump-ben-stiller-michael-cohen |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=December 2, 2018 |access-date=December 13, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227223857/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/12/alec-baldwin-snl-trump-ben-stiller-michael-cohen |archive-date=February 27, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]]\n*[[Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections (July 2016\u2013election day)]]\n*[[Timeline of post-election transition following Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]]\n*[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (January\u2013June 2017)]]\n*[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (July\u2013December 2017)]]\n*[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (January\u2013June 2018)]]\n*[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (July\u2013December 2018)]]\n*[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (2019\u20132020)]]\n*[[Legal teams involved in the Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Michael D. Cohen}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Michael Cohen04}}\n*{{IMDb name}}\n\n{{Trump businesses}}\n{{Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cohen, Michael Dean}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:21st-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:American male criminals]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of campaign finance violations]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of tax crimes]]\n[[Category:American University alumni]]\n[[Category:Children of Holocaust survivors]]\n[[Category:Criminals from New York City]]\n[[Category:Disbarred American lawyers]]\n[[Category:Donald Trump litigation]]\n[[Category:Jewish American attorneys]]\n[[Category:Jews and Judaism in Nassau County, New York]]\n[[Category:Jews and Judaism in New York City]]\n[[Category:Lawrence Woodmere Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Mixed martial arts executives]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Lawrence, Nassau County, New York]]\n[[Category:People convicted of making false statements]]\n[[Category:The Trump Organization employees]]\n[[Category:Thomas M. Cooley Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:American chief operating officers]]\n[[Category:Trump administration controversies]]\n", "name_user": "Iamthecheese44", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor copyedit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Cohen_(lawyer)"}
{"title_page": "Lou Reed", "text_new": "{{for|the Welsh rugby player|Lou Reed (rugby player)}}\n{{Redirect|Lewis Reed|the St. Louis alderman|Lewis E. Reed}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| image               = Lou Reed 1977.JPG\n<!-- NOTE: Do not replace Lou Reed 1977.JPG unless it is with a photo under a public domain or free license (meaning NOT fair use). Any fair use photos (i.e. 'promotional photos') violate the Fair Use Policy and will be deleted. See [[Wikipedia:Fair]] use criteria. -->\n| alt                 =\n| caption             = Reed in 1977\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Lewis Allan Reed\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1942|3|2}}\n| birth_place         = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.<!--No boroughs/neighborhoods, just cities per format.-->\n| origin              = [[Freeport, New York]], U.S.\n| death_date          = {{Death date and age|2013|10|27|1942|3|2}}\n| death_place         = {{nowrap|[[East Hampton (town), New York|East Hampton]], New York, U.S.}}\n| genre               = {{hlist|[[Rock music|Rock]]|[[experimental music|experimental]]|[[proto-punk]]|[[glam rock]]|[[art rock]]|[[noise rock]]}}\n| occupation          = {{hlist|Musician|singer|songwriter|composer|photographer}}<!--Please do not add to this list without first discussing your proposal on the talk page. -->\n| instrument          = {{hlist|Vocals|guitar}}<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed or removed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| years_active        = 1958\u20132013\n| label               = {{hlist|[[Pickwick Records|Pickwick]]|[[Verve Records|Verve]]|[[MGM Records|MGM]]|[[Cotillion Records|Cotillion]]|[[RCA Records|RCA]]|[[Arista Records|Arista]]|[[Sire Records|Sire]]|[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]}}\n| associated_acts     = {{hlist|[[The Velvet Underground]]|[[John Cale]]|[[Nico]]|[[David Bowie]]|[[John Zorn]]|[[Laurie Anderson]]|[[Metal Machine Trio]]|[[Metallica]]}}<!--Please do not add to this list without first discussing your proposal on the talk page. -->\n}}\n<!-- PER WP:LEADCITE NOTHING CITED IN THE REST OF THE ARTICLE NEEDS TO BE CITED HERE -->\n'''Lewis Allan Reed''' (March 2, 1942 \u2013 October 27, 2013) was an American musician, singer, songwriter and poet. He was the rhythm/lead guitarist, singer and principal songwriter for the rock band [[The Velvet Underground]] and had a solo career that spanned five decades. The Velvet Underground was not a commercial success during its existence, but became regarded as one of the most influential bands in the history of [[underground music|underground]] and [[alternative rock]] music.\n\nAfter leaving the band in 1970, Reed released twenty solo [[Album#Studio|studio albums]]. His second, ''[[Transformer (Lou Reed album)|Transformer]]'' (1972), was produced by [[David Bowie]] and arranged by [[Mick Ronson]], and brought mainstream recognition. The album is considered an influential landmark of the [[glam rock]] genre, anchored by Reed's most successful single, \"[[Walk on the Wild Side (Lou Reed song)|Walk on the Wild Side]]\". After ''Transformer'', the less commercial but critically acclaimed ''[[Berlin (Lou Reed album)|Berlin]]'' reached No. 7 on the [[UK Albums Chart]]. ''[[Rock 'n' Roll Animal]]'' (a live album released in 1974) sold strongly, and ''[[Sally Can't Dance]]'' (1974) peaked at No. 10 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]; but for a long period after, Reed's work did not translate into sales, leading him deeper into drug addiction and alcoholism. Reed cleaned up in the early 1980s, and gradually returned to prominence with ''[[New Sensations]]'' (1984), reaching a critical and commercial career peak with his 1989 album ''[[New York (album)|New York]]''.\n\nReed participated in the reformation of the Velvet Underground in the 1990s, and made several more albums, including a collaboration album with [[John Cale]] titled ''[[Songs for Drella]]'' which was a tribute to their former mentor [[Andy Warhol]]. ''[[Magic and Loss]]'' (1992) would become Reed's highest-charting album on the UK Albums Chart, peaking at No. 6.\n\nHe contributed music to two theatrical interpretations of 19th century writers, one of which he developed into an album titled ''[[The Raven (Lou Reed album)|The Raven]]''. He married his third wife [[Laurie Anderson]] in 2008, and recorded the collaboration album ''[[Lulu (Lou Reed and Metallica album)|Lulu]]'' with [[Metallica]]. He died in 2013 of [[liver disease]]. Reed's distinctive deadpan voice, poetic lyrics and experimental guitar playing were trademarks throughout his long career. Reed has been inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] twice; as a member of the Velvet Underground in 1996 and as a solo act in 2015.\n\n==Biography==\n===1942\u201357: Early life ===\nLewis Allan Reed was born on March 2, 1942, at Beth El Hospital (later [[Brookdale University Hospital and Medical Center|Brookdale]]) in [[Brooklyn]] and grew up in [[Freeport, New York|Freeport, Long Island]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-10-27/lou-reed-rocker-who-sang-walk-on-the-wild-side-dies-at-71.html |title=Lou Reed, 'Walk on the Wild Side' Rocker, Dies at 71 |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |accessdate=October 28, 2013}}</ref>{{refn|Contrary to some sources, his birth name was Lewis Allan Reed, not Louis Firbanks, a name that was coined as a joke by [[Lester Bangs]] in ''[[Creem]]'' magazine.{{sfnp|Roberts|Reed|2004|p=18}}|group=nb}} Reed was the son of Toby (n\u00e9e Futterman) (1920\u20132013) and Sidney Joseph Reed (1913\u20132005), an accountant.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/Lou_Reed.aspx |title=Lou Reed Facts, information, pictures|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia.com|accessdate=December 24, 2012}}</ref> His family was [[Jews|Jewish]];{{sfnp|Beeber|2006|p=11}} his father had changed his name from Rabinowitz to Reed.{{sfnp|DeCurtis|2017|p=}} Reed said that although he was Jewish, his real god was rock 'n' roll.<ref name=\"NYROCK1998\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyrock.com/interviews/loureed_int.htm|title=The Gospel According to Lou: Interview with Lou Reed|author=Gabriella|website=Nyrock.com|date=November 1998|accessdate=October 27, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031184208/http://www.nyrock.com/interviews/loureed_int.htm|archivedate=October 31, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/lou-reeds-contradictory-jewishness/|title=Lou Reed's paradoxical Jewishness|work=The Times of Israel|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\nReed attended Atkinson Elementary School in Freeport and went on to Freeport Junior High School. His sister Merrill, born Margaret Reed, said that as an adolescent, he suffered [[panic attack]]s, became socially awkward and \"possessed a fragile temperament\" but was highly focused on things that he liked, mainly music.<ref name=medium>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/cuepoint/a-family-in-peril-lou-reed-s-sister-sets-the-record-straight-about-his-childhood-20e8399f84a3|title=A Family in Peril: Lou Reed's Sister Sets the Record Straight About His Childhood|first=Merrill Reed|last=Weiner|date=April 11, 2015|website=Medium.com|accessdate=June 6, 2017}}</ref> Having learned to play the guitar from the radio, he developed an early interest in [[rock and roll]] and [[rhythm and blues]], and during high school played in several bands.<ref name=\"Costello interview\">{{cite episode|title=Lou Reed and Julian Schnabel|url=http://www.sundancechannel.com/films/500328617|series=Spectacle|airdate=2008|season=1|number=2|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090415182218/http://www.sundancechannel.com/films/500328617|archivedate=April 15, 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lou Reed HS Yearbook (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|upright|Reed as a high school senior, 1959]]\nHe began experimenting with drugs at the age of 16.<ref name=medium/> \n\n===1958-64: Early recordings & education===\nReed's first recording was as a member of a [[doo-wop]] three-piece group called The Jades, with Reed providing guitar accompaniment & singing backup vocals. After participating at a talent show at Freeport Junior High School in early 1958, and receiving an enthusiastic response from the audience,<ref>olivier.landemaine.free.fr/loureed/thejades/jades.html</ref> the group was given the chance to record an original single \"So Blue\" with the B-side \"Leave Her For Me\" later that year. While the single didn't chart, notable saxophonist [[King Curtis]] was brought in as a session musician by the producer Bob Shad to play on both songs,<ref>olivier.landemaine.free.fr/loureed/thejades/jades.html</ref> and the single was played by [[Murray The K]], which gave Reed his first-ever airplay. <ref>olivier.landemaine.free.fr/loureed/thejades/jades.html</ref>  Reed's love for playing music and his desire to play gigs brought him into confrontation with his anxious and unaccommodating parents.<ref name=medium/> His sister recalled that during his first year in college he was brought home one day, having had a [[mental breakdown]], after which he remained \"depressed, anxious, and socially unresponsive\" for a time, and that his parents were having difficulty coping. Visiting a psychologist, Reed's parents were made to feel guilty as inadequate parents, and consented to [[electroconvulsive therapy]] (ECT).<ref name=medium/> Reed appeared to blame his father for the treatment to which he had been subjected.<ref name=medium/> He wrote about the experience in his 1974 song, \"Kill Your Sons\".<ref name=\"Fatherhood\">{{cite web|url=http://fatherhoodchannel.com/2013/10/27/lou-reed-lived-and-died-with-a-broken-heart-027/|title=Lou Reed Lived and Died with a Broken Heart|work=Fatherhood Channel|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Salon.com_LouReed_Syracuse_BA\">{{cite web|url=http://dir.salon.com/people/bc/2000/05/16/reed|title=Lou Reed|last=Colin|first=Chris|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|accessdate=June 23, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101107125917/http://dir.salon.com/people/bc/2000/05/16/reed|archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> Reed later recalled the experience as having been traumatic and leading to memory loss. He believed that he was treated to dispel his feelings of homosexuality.{{sfnp|McNeil|McCain|2006|p=4}} After Reed's death, his sister denied the ECT treatments were intended to suppress his \"homosexual urges\", asserting that their parents were not homophobic but had been told by his doctors that ECT was necessary to treat Reed's mental and behavioral issues.<ref name=medium/>\n\nUpon his recovery from his illness and associated treatment, Reed resumed his education at [[Syracuse University]] in 1960,<ref name=medium/> studying journalism, film directing, and [[creative writing]]. He was a [[platoon leader]] in [[Reserve Officers' Training Corps|ROTC]]; he said he was later expelled from the program for holding an unloaded gun to his superior's head.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,916140,00.html|title=Music: Lou Reed's Nightshade Carnival|date=April 24, 1978|author=Cocks, Jay|work=Time|location=New York|accessdate=October 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1961, he began hosting a late-night radio program on [[WAER]] called ''Excursions on a Wobbly Rail''.<ref name=\"Costello interview\"/> Named after a song by pianist [[Cecil Taylor]], the program typically featured doo wop, rhythm and blues, and [[jazz]], particularly the [[free jazz]] developed in the mid-1950s.<ref>{{Cite AV media notes|first=David|last=Fricke|type=liner notes|title=Peel Slowly and See|publisher=Polydor|year=1995}}</ref> Reed said that when he started out he was inspired by such musicians as [[Ornette Coleman]], who had \"always been a great influence\" on him; he said that his guitar on \"[[European Son]]\" was his way of trying to imitate the jazz saxophonist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.furious.com/perfect/jazzpunk.html|title=The Jazz-Punk Connection|work=furious.com|accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> Reed's sister said that during her brother's time at [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]], the university authorities had tried unsuccessfully to expel him because they did not approve of his extracurricular activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.loureed.com/inmemoriam|title=Lou Reed, 1942-2013|work=loureed.com|accessdate=January 18, 2017|quote=[He] started a band, he had his own radio show. He reportedly libeled some student on his radio show; the kid's family tried to sue my father. And there were other extracurricular possibly illegal activities of which the university didn't approve. I believe they tried to kick him out. But he was a genius; what could they do? He stayed and he graduated.}}</ref> At Syracuse University, he studied under poet [[Delmore Schwartz]], who he said was \"the first great person I ever met\", and they became friends. He credited Schwartz with showing him how \"with the simplest language imaginable, and very short, you can accomplish the most astonishing heights.\"<ref name=documentary>\"Rock and Roll Heart\", documentary on the life of Lou Reed, ''American Masters''</ref> One of Reed's fellow students at Syracuse in the early 1960s (who also studied under Schwartz) was the musician [[Garland Jeffreys]]; they remained close friends until the end of Reed's life.<ref name=\"syracuse.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2014/01/garland_jeffreys_le_moyne_lou_reed.html|title=Garland Jeffreys remembers his friend, Lou Reed|work=syracuse.com|accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJeffreys recalled Reed's time at Syracuse: \"At four in the afternoon we'd all meet at [the bar] ''The Orange Grove.'' Me, Delmore and Lou. That would often be the center of the crew. And Delmore was the leader - our quiet leader.\"<ref name=\"syracuse.com\"/> While at Syracuse, Reed was also introduced to intravenous drug use for the first time, and quickly contracted [[hepatitis]].{{sfnp|Clapton|2012|p=}} [[Sterling Morrison]] was not attending Syracuse at the time, but met Reed while he was visiting mutual friend Jim Tucker, the older brother of Velvet Underground drummer [[Moe Tucker]], who was attending school there. Reed later dedicated the song \"European Son\", from the first Velvet Underground album, to Schwartz.<ref>{{Cite AV media notes |title=The Velvet Underground & Nico |year=1967 |type=album cover notes and record label}}</ref> In 1982, Reed recorded \"My House\" from his album ''[[The Blue Mask]]'' as a tribute to his late mentor. He later said that his goals as a writer were \"to bring the sensitivities of the novel to rock music\" or to write the [[Great American Novel]] in a record album.<ref>Interview in ''Rolling Stone'' Nov/Dec 1987: Twentieth Anniversary Issue.</ref> Reed graduated from Syracuse University's [[Syracuse University College of Arts and Sciences|College of Arts and Sciences]] with a [[B.A.]] ''[[cum laude]]'' in English in June 1964.<ref name=\"Salon.com_LouReed_Syracuse_BA\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.syr.edu/statement-from-syracuse-university-regarding-the-passing-of-lou-reed-59708|title=Statement from Syracuse University Regarding the Passing of Lou Reed|accessdate=October 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===1964\u201370: Pickwick and the Velvet Underground===\n[[File:Velvet Underground 1968 by Billy Name.png|thumb|upright|left|The Velvet Underground, 1968]]\nIn 1964, Reed moved to New York City to work as an in-house songwriter for [[Pickwick Records]]. That year he wrote and recorded the single \"The Ostrich\", a parody of popular [[dance music|dance songs]] of the time, which included lines such as \"put your head on the floor and have somebody step on it\". His employers felt that the song had hit potential, and assembled a supporting band to help promote the recording. The ''ad hoc'' band, called \"the Primitives\", included Welsh musician [[John Cale]], who had recently moved to New York to study music and was playing viola in composer [[La Monte Young]]'s [[Theatre of Eternal Music]], along with [[Tony Conrad]]. Cale and Conrad were surprised to find that for \"The Ostrich\", Reed tuned each string of his guitar to the same note, which they began to call his \"[[ostrich guitar]]\" tuning. This technique created a [[drone (music)|drone]] effect similar to their experimentation in Young's [[avant-garde]] ensemble. Disappointed with Reed's performance, Cale was nevertheless impressed by Reed's early repertoire (including \"[[Heroin (The Velvet Underground song)|Heroin]]\"), and a partnership began to evolve.<ref name=documentary/>\n\nReed and Cale (who played viola, keyboards and bass guitar) lived together on the [[Lower East Side]], and invited Reed's college acquaintance guitarist Sterling Morrison and Cale's neighbor drummer [[Angus MacLise]] to join the band, thus forming [[the Velvet Underground]]. When the opportunity came to play their first paying gig at [[Summit High School (New Jersey)|Summit High School]] in [[Summit, New Jersey]], MacLise quit because he believed that accepting money for art was a [[selling out|sellout]] and did not want to participate in a structured gig. He was replaced on drums by [[Moe Tucker]], initially for that one show, but she soon became a full-time member with her drumming an integral part of the band's sound, despite Cale's initial objections. Though it had little commercial success, the band is considered one of the most influential in rock history.<ref name=\"nrr-loc\">{{cite web |title=News from the Library of Congress |url=https://www.loc.gov/today/pr/2007/07-039.html |website=National Recording Registry |publisher=Library of Congress |date=March 6, 2007 |quote=For decades this album has cast a huge shadow over nearly every sub-variety of avant-garde rock, from 1970s art-rock to No Wave, New Wave and Punk. Referring to their sway over the rock music of the '70s and '80s, critic Lester Bangs stated, 'Modern music starts with the Velvets, and the implications and influence of what they did seem to go on forever.'}}</ref><ref name=rrhallbio>{{cite web |title=The Velvet Underground Biography |url=https://rockhall.com/inductees/the-velvet-underground/bio/ |website=Rock & Roll Hall of Fame |quote=The influence of the Velvet Underground on rock greatly exceeds their sales figures and chart numbers. They are one of the most important rock and roll bands of all time, laying the groundwork in the Sixties for many tangents rock music would take in ensuing decades.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20131125-do-the-velvets-beat-the-beatles |title=The Velvet Underground: As influential as The Beatles? |last=Kot |first=Greg |publisher=BBC |date=October 21, 2014 |accessdate=November 25, 2016}}</ref> Reed was the main singer and songwriter in the band.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |last1=Unterberger |first1=Richie |title=The Velvet Underground \u2013 Biography & History |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-velvet-underground-mn0000840402/biography |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=March 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box|width=30em|align=right|quote=Had he accomplished nothing else, his work with the Velvet Underground in the late sixties would assure him a place in anyone's rock & roll pantheon; those remarkable songs still serve as an articulate aural nightmare of men and women caught in the beauty and terror of sexual, street and drug paranoia, unwilling or unable to move. The message is that urban life is tough stuff\u2014it will kill you; Reed, the poet of destruction, knows it but never looks away and somehow finds holiness as well as perversity in both his sinners and his quest. ... [H]e is still one of a handful of American artists capable of the spiritual home run.|source= \u2014''[[Rolling Stone]]'', 1975<ref>Nelson, Paul. ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', June 5, 1975. p. 60.</ref>}}\n\nThe band soon came to the attention of [[Andy Warhol]]. One of Warhol's first contributions was to integrate them into the [[Exploding Plastic Inevitable]]. Warhol's associates inspired many of Reed's songs as he fell into a thriving, multifaceted artistic scene.{{sfnp|Reed|1991|pp=22, 38, 42}}{{sfnp|Thompson|2009|p=18}} Reed rarely gave an interview without paying homage to Warhol as a mentor. Warhol pushed the band to take on a [[chanteuse]], the German former model and singer [[Nico]]. Despite his initial resistance, Reed wrote several songs for Nico to sing, and the two were briefly lovers.{{sfnp|Bockris|1994|pp=104, 106, 107}}\n\n''[[The Velvet Underground & Nico]]'' reached No. 171 on the charts.<ref name=rrhallbio /> Much later, ''Rolling Stone'' listed it as the 13th greatest album of all time; [[Brian Eno]] once stated that although few people bought the album, most of them were inspired to form their own bands.<ref>{{cite web |author=Jones, Chris |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/fq4h |archivedate= April 30, 2012 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120430223626/http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/fq4h/ |title=Review of The Velvet Underground - The Velvet Underground & Nico (Deluxe Edition) |publisher=BBC Music |year=2002 |accessdate=October 28, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[V\u00e1clav Havel]] credited the album, which he bought while visiting the US, with inspiring him to become president of [[Czechoslovakia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/lou-reed-and-vaclav-havel-vs-communism-2013-10|title=The True Story Of How Lou Reed Helped Overthrow Communism In Eastern Europe|date=October 27, 2013|work=Business Insider|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBy the time the band recorded ''[[White Light/White Heat]]'', Nico had quit and Warhol had been fired, both against Cale's wishes. Warhol's replacement as manager was [[Steve Sesnick]]. In September 1968, Cale left the band at Reed's behest.{{sfnp|Bockris|1994|p=160}} Morrison and Tucker were discomfited by Reed's tactics but continued with the band. Cale's replacement was [[Boston]]-based musician [[Doug Yule]], who played bass guitar, keyboards and who would soon share lead vocal duties in the band with Reed.{{sfnp|Bockris|1994|pp=164, 167}} The band now took on a more pop-oriented sound and acted more as a vehicle for Reed to develop his songwriting craft.{{sfnp|Bockris|1994|p=164, 166}} They released two studio albums with this line-up: 1969's ''[[The Velvet Underground (album)|The Velvet Underground]]'' and 1970's ''[[Loaded (The Velvet Underground album)|Loaded]]''. Reed left the Velvet Underground in August 1970.{{sfnp|Bockris|1994|p=177}} The band disintegrated after Morrison and Tucker departed in 1971.{{sfnp|Unterberger|2009|pp=307, 317}}\n\n===1970\u201375: Glam rock and commercial breakthrough===\nAfter leaving the Velvet Underground, Reed moved to his parents' home on [[Long Island]], and took a job at his father's tax accounting firm as a typist, by his own account earning $40 a week (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|40|1970}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}).<ref name=Unterberger2009>{{cite web|last=Unterberger|first=Richie|title=White Light / White Heat|url=http://www.well.com/conf/inkwell.vue/topics/354/Richie-Unterberger-White-Light-W-page03.html#post58|work=The WELL|publisher=The Well Group|accessdate=November 4, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121202055654/http://www.well.com/conf/inkwell.vue/topics/354/Richie-Unterberger-White-Light-W-page03.html#post58|archivedate=December 2, 2012|page=3|date=May 30, 2009}}</ref> In 1971, he signed a recording contract with [[RCA Records]] and recorded his first solo album at [[Morgan Studios]] in [[Willesden]], London with session musicians including [[Steve Howe (musician)|Steve Howe]] and [[Rick Wakeman]] from the band [[Yes (band)|Yes]]. The album, ''[[Lou Reed (album)|Lou Reed]]'', contained versions of unreleased Velvet Underground songs, some of which had originally been recorded for ''Loaded'' but shelved.{{refn|Some later appeared on the ''[[Peel Slowly and See]]'' box set.|group=nb}} This album was overlooked by most pop music critics and did not sell well, although music critic [[Stephen Holden]], in ''Rolling Stone'', called it an \"almost perfect album. ... which embodied the spirit of the Velvets.\" Holden went on to compare Reed's voice with those of [[Mick Jagger]] and [[Bob Dylan]] and to praise the poetic quality of his lyrics.<ref>Holden, Stephen (May 25, 1972). ''Rolling Stone''. p. 68</ref>\n\nReed's commercial breakthrough album, ''[[Transformer (Lou Reed album)|Transformer]]'', was released in November 1972. ''Transformer'' was co-produced by [[David Bowie]] and [[Mick Ronson]], and it introduced Reed to a wider audience, especially in the UK. The single \"[[Walk on the Wild Side (Lou Reed song)|Walk on the Wild Side]]\" was a salute to the misfits and hustlers who once surrounded Andy Warhol in the late '60s and appeared in his films. Each of the song's five verses describes a person who had been a fixture at [[The Factory]] during the mid-to-late 1960s: (1) [[Holly Woodlawn]], (2) [[Candy Darling]], (3) [[Joe Dallesandro|\"Little Joe\" Dallesandro]], (4) \"Sugar Plum Fairy\" [[Joe Campbell (actor)|Joe Campbell]] and (5) [[Jackie Curtis]]. The song's transgressive lyrics evaded radio censorship. Though the jazzy arrangement (courtesy of bassist [[Herbie Flowers]] and saxophonist [[Ronnie Ross]]) was musically atypical for Reed, it eventually became his signature song.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wiener|first1=John|title=Beatles Buy-Out|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/music/beatles-buy-out|website=The New Republic|date=May 11, 1987}}</ref> It came about as a result of a commission to compose a soundtrack to a theatrical adaptation of [[Nelson Algren]]'s novel of the same name; the play failed to materialize.{{sfnp|Reed|1991|p=42}} \"Walk on the Wild Side\" was Reed's only entry in the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] singles chart, at number 16.<ref name=\"Caulfield\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5770575/lou-reed-billboard-chart-history|title=Lou Reed's 'Perfect' Billboard Chart History|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=October 27, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nRonson's arrangements brought out new aspects of Reed's songs. \"[[Perfect Day (Lou Reed song)|Perfect Day]]\", for example, features delicate strings and soaring dynamics. It was rediscovered in the 1990s and allowed Reed to drop \"Walk on the Wild Side\" from his concerts.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/blurred-vision-at-the-beeb-1235724.html|last1=Walker|first1=Nick|date=October 13, 1997|title=Blurred vision at the Beeb|website=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nBowie and Reed fell out during a late-night meeting which led to Reed hitting Bowie. Bowie had told Reed that he would have to \"clean up his act\" if they were to work together again.{{sfnp|DeCurtis|2017|p=}}{{refn|The two reconciled years later, and Reed performed with Bowie at the latter's 50th birthday concert at [[Madison Square Garden]] in 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesound.co.nz/home/music/2018/01/david-bowie-s-50th-birthday-performance-with-lou-reed.html|title=David Bowie's 50th birthday performance with Lou Reed|accessdate=February 16, 2018}}</ref>|group=nb}} Reed hired a local New York bar-band, The Tots, to tour in support of ''Transformer'' and spent much of 1972 and early 1973 on the road with them. Though they improved over the months, Reed (with producer [[Bob Ezrin]]'s encouragement) decided to recruit a new backing band in anticipation of the upcoming ''[[Berlin (Lou Reed album)|Berlin]]'' album. He chose keyboardist [[Moogy Klingman]] to come up with a new five-member band on barely a week's notice.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.wolfgangsvault.com/lou-reed-and-moogy-klingman-band/concerts/kansas-city-memorial-hall-may-02-1973.html | work=Wolfgangs Vault | title=Concert Summary: May 2, 1973 | last=Bershaw | accessdate=March 2, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523090717/http://www.wolfgangsvault.com/lou-reed-and-moogy-klingman-band/concerts/kansas-city-memorial-hall-may-02-1973.html | archive-date=May 23, 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nReed married Bettye Kronstad in 1973. She later said he had been a violent drunk when on tour.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/01/fashion/who-was-the-real-lou-reed.html |first=Alex |last=Williams |date=November 1, 2015 |title=Who Was the Real Lou Reed? |work=The New York Times }}</ref> ''[[Berlin (Lou Reed album)|Berlin]]'' (July 1973) was a [[concept album]] about two [[addiction|junkies]] in love in the city. The songs variously concern [[domestic violence]] (\"Caroline Says I\", \"Caroline Says II\"), drug addiction (\"How Do You Think It Feels\"), adultery and prostitution (\"The Kids\"), and suicide (\"The Bed\"). Reed's late 1973 European tour, featuring lead guitarists [[Steve Hunter]] and [[Dick Wagner]], mixed his ''Berlin'' material with older numbers. Response to ''Berlin'' at the time of its release was negative, with ''Rolling Stone'' pronouncing it \"a disaster\".{{sfnp|Bockris|1994|p=221}} Reed found the poor reviews it received very frustrating.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/8e40a4de-4245-11e3-bb85-00144feabdc0|title=Lou Reed: rock 'n' roll animal|last=Morley|first=Paul|date=November 1, 2013|work=[[Financial Times]]|accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref> Since then the album has been critically reevaluated, and in 2003 ''Rolling Stone'' included it in their list of the 500 greatest albums of all time.<ref>{{cite web|title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time: 344. Lou Reed, Berlin|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-20120531/lou-reed-berlin-20120524|website=Rolling Stone}}</ref> ''Berlin'' made number 7 in the UK charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/14017/lou-reed/|title=Lou Reed full Official Chart History|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the commercial disappointment of ''Berlin'', Reed befriended [[Steve Katz (musician)|Steve Katz]] of [[Blood, Sweat & Tears]] (who was the brother of his then-manager Dennis Katz), who suggested Reed put together a \"great live band\" and release a live album of Velvet Underground songs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bedfordandbowery.com/2013/10/he-treads-kind-of-softly-musicians-remember-working-with-lou-reed/|title='He Treads Kind of Softly': Two Musicians Remember Working With Lou Reed|date=October 28, 2013|website=Bedfordandbowery.com}}</ref> Katz would come on board as producer, and the album ''[[Rock 'n' Roll Animal]]'' (February 1974) contained live performances of the Velvet Underground songs \"Sweet Jane\", \"Heroin\", \"White Light/White Heat\", and \"Rock and Roll\". Wagner's live arrangements, and Hunter's intro to \"[[Sweet Jane]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vintageguitar.com/2795/dick-wagner-and-steve-hunter/|title=Dick Wagner and Steve Hunter|first=Greg|last=Pedersen|date=May 15, 2001|website=Vintageguitar.com}}</ref> which opened the album, gave Reed's songs the live rock sound he was looking for, and the album peaked at #45 on the Top 200 [[Billboard Chart]] for 28 weeks and soon became Reed's biggest selling album.{{refn|''Rock 'n' Roll Animal'' and its follow-up ''[[Lou Reed Live]]'' (1975) were both recorded at the [[Palladium (New York City)|Academy of Music]], New York City, on December 21, 1973.|group=nb}} It went gold in 1978, with 500,000 certified sales.<ref name=\"riaa\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=lou+reed#search_section|title=RIAA|website=Riaa.com|accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''[[Sally Can't Dance]]'' which was released later that year (in August 1974), became Reed's highest-charting album in the United States, peaking at number 10 during a 14-week stay on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] album chart in October 1974.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/lou-reed/chart-history/billboard-200/song/830856 |title=Sally Can't Dance Chart History |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=February 9, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, an audio tape of publicly unknown music by Reed, based on Warhols' 1975 book, \u201c''[[The Philosophy of Andy Warhol|The Philosophy of Andy Warhol: From A to B and Back Again]]''\u201d, was reported to have been discovered in an archive at the [[Andy Warhol Museum]] in Pittsburgh.<ref name=\"NYT-20191030\">{{cite news |last=Sisaro |first=Ben |title=A Long-Lost Lou Reed Tape With a Surprise: Andy Warhol Lyrics - The cassette, discovered at the Andy Warhol Museum, finds the Velvet Underground musician performing snippets from his mentor's 1975 book. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/30/arts/music/lou-reed-andy-warhol-tape.html |date=October 30, 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=October 30, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===1975\u201379: Addiction and creative work===\n[[File:Chuck Hammer and Lou Reed.jpg|thumb|240px| Lou Reed on stage with guitarist Chuck Hammer, June 1979, The Bottom Line, NYC]] Throughout the 1970s, Reed was a heavy user of [[methamphetamine]] and [[alcohol (drug)|alcohol]].<ref name=\"nyt\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopmusic/10092969/Lou-Reed-saved-by-liver-transplant-after-years-of-drugs-and-alcohol-take-their-toll.html|title=Lou Reed saved by liver transplant after years of drugs and alcohol take their toll - Telegraph|last=Sawer|first=Patrick|date=June 1, 2011|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''[[Metal Machine Music]]'' (1975) was an hour of modulated feedback and guitar effects. Described by Rolling Stone as the \"tubular groaning of a galactic refrigerator\",<ref name=\"Dayal2013\">{{cite news |author1=Geeta Dayal |title=Lou Reed Was a Rock God and the Epitome of Cool. He Was Also a Big Nerd. |url=https://slate.com/culture/2013/10/lou-reeds-metal-machine-music-the-artist-was-a-rock-god-he-was-also-a-big-nerd.html |accessdate=November 16, 2019 |work=Slate Magazine |date=October 28, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190311073715/https://slate.com/culture/2013/10/lou-reeds-metal-machine-music-the-artist-was-a-rock-god-he-was-also-a-big-nerd.html |archivedate=April 14, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> many critics interpreted it as a gesture of contempt, an attempt to break his contract with RCA or to alienate his less sophisticated fans. Reed claimed that the album was a genuine artistic effort, even suggesting that quotations of classical music could be found buried in the feedback,<ref name=\"Little2018\">{{cite news |author1=Michael H. Little |title=Graded on a Curve: Lou Reed, Metal Machine Music |url=http://www.thevinyldistrict.com/storefront/2018/03/graded-on-a-curve-lou-reed-metal-machine-music/ |accessdate=November 16, 2019 |work=The Vinyl District |date=March 9, 2018}}</ref> but he also said, \"Well, anyone who gets to side four is dumber than I am.\"<ref name=\"BogdanovWoodstra2002\">{{cite book|editor1=Vladimir Bogdanov |editor2=Chris Woodstra |editor3=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|title=All Music Guide to Rock: The Definitive Guide to Rock, Pop, and Soul|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1-pH4i3jXvAC&pg=PA927|year=2002|publisher=Backbeat Books|isbn=978-0-87930-653-3|page=927}}</ref><ref name=\"McPadden2012\">{{cite book|author=Mike McPadden|title=If You Like Metallica...: Here Are Over 200 Bands, CDs, Movies and Other Oddities That You Will Love|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RtGGDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT61|date=May 1, 2012|publisher=Backbeat|isbn=978-1-4768-1358-5|page=61}}</ref> Lester Bangs declared it \"genius\", though also psychologically disturbing. The album, now regarded as a visionary textural guitar masterpiece by some music critics,<ref name=\"McGonigal2015\">{{cite news |author1=Mike McGonigal |title=Coming to Cranbrook Nov. 21: '3-D installation' of Lou Reed's 1975 feedback masterpiece 'Metal Machine Music' |url=https://www.metrotimes.com/city-slang/archives/2015/09/04/coming-to-cranbrook-nov-21-3-d-installation-of-lou-reeds-1975-feedback-masterpiece-metal-machine-music |accessdate=November 16, 2019 |work=Detroit Metro Times |date=September 4, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116160623/https://www.metrotimes.com/city-slang/archives/2015/09/04/coming-to-cranbrook-nov-21-3-d-installation-of-lou-reeds-1975-feedback-masterpiece-metal-machine-music |archivedate=November 16, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> was reportedly returned to stores by the thousands and was withdrawn after a few weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://92yondemand.org/lou-reed-with-anthony-decurtis|title=Lou Reed with Anthony DeCurtis - 92Y On Demand|date=September 18, 2006|accessdate=February 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/wzwx/|title=Review of Lou Reed - Metal Machine Music: Re-mastered|work=[[BBC Online]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box|width=30em|align=left|quote=Lou Reed doesn't just write about squalid characters, he allows them to leer and breathe in their own voices, and he colors familiar landscapes through their own eyes. In the process, Reed has created a body of music that comes as close to disclosing the parameters of human loss and recovery as we're likely to find. That qualifies him, in my opinion, as one of the few real heroes rock & roll has raised.|source=\u2014[[Mikal Gilmore]], ''Rolling Stone'', (1979)<ref name=Gilmore/>}}\n\n1975's ''[[Coney Island Baby]]'' was dedicated to Reed's then-partner Rachel, a [[transgender]] woman Reed dated and lived with for three years.<ref>DeCurtis, Anthony. Lou Reed: A Life. New York: Little Brown. p. 180. {{ISBN|978-0-316-37654-9}}.</ref> Rachel also appears in the photos on the cover of Reed's 1977 \"best of\" album, ''[[Walk on the Wild Side: The Best of Lou Reed]]''. ''[[Rock and Roll Heart]]'' was his 1976 debut for his new record label [[Arista Records|Arista]], and ''[[Street Hassle]]'' (1978) was released in the midst of the punk scene he had helped to inspire. Reed took on a watchful, competitive and sometimes dismissive attitude towards punk. Aware that he had inspired them, he regularly attended shows at [[CBGB]] to track the artistic and commercial development of numerous punk bands, and a cover illustration and interview of Reed appeared in the first issue of ''[[Punk (magazine)|Punk]]'' by [[Legs McNeil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://13thdimension.com/punk-magazine-began-with-lou-reed-comic/|title=PUNK Magazine Began With Lou Reed Comic|date=October 28, 2013|website=13thdimension.com}}</ref>\n\nReed released his third live album, ''[[Live: Take No Prisoners]]'', in 1978; some critics thought it was his \"bravest work yet\", while others considered it his \"silliest\".<ref name=Gilmore>{{cite magazine |last=Gilmore |first=Mikal |title=Lou Reed's heart of darkness |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=March 22, 1979 |pages=8, 12|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/lou-reeds-heart-of-darkness-19790322}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' described it as \"one of the funniest live albums ever recorded\" and compared Reed's monologues with those of [[Lenny Bruce]].<ref name=Gilmore/> Reed felt it was his best album to date.<ref name=Gilmore/> ''[[The Bells (Lou Reed album)|The Bells]]'' (1979) featured jazz trumpeter [[Don Cherry (trumpeter)|Don Cherry]]. During 1979 Reed toured extensively in Europe and throughout the United States performing a wide range of songs including a suite of core songs from his Berlin album and the title track from the Bells with [[Chuck Hammer]] on guitar-synth. Around this time Reed also appeared as a record producer in [[Paul Simon]]'s film ''[[One-Trick Pony (film)|One-Trick Pony]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=One-Trick Pony (1980)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0081280/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|website=IMDb.com}}</ref> From around 1979 Reed began to wean himself off drugs.<ref name=\"nyt\"/>\n\n===1980\u201389: Marriage and mid-period===\n[[File:Lou Reed-Conspiracy of Hope-by Steven Toole.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.85|Reed performing live during a benefit concert for [[A Conspiracy of Hope]] at [[Giants Stadium]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]], 1986]]\nReed married British designer Sylvia Morales in 1980.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/bettye-kronstad-speaks-for-the-first-time-about-her-marriage-to-lou-reed-fame-is-a-fiend-it-turns-10166659.html|title=Bettye Kronstad has spoken about her marriage to Lou Reed for the first time|work=[[The Independent]]|date=April 10, 2015|accessdate=November 8, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"timesonline\">{{cite news |first=Robert |last=Sandall |title=Lou Reed: Walk on the mild side |url= http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/article860207.ece |work=[[The Sunday Times]]|date=February 9, 2003 |accessdate=December 20, 2008 |location=London}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Morales inspired Reed to write several songs, particularly \"Think It Over\" from 1980's ''[[Growing Up in Public (Lou Reed album)|Growing Up in Public]]''{{sfnp|Reed|1991|p=71}} and \"Heavenly Arms\" from 1982's ''[[The Blue Mask]]''.<ref name=carson>{{cite journal|last1=Carson|first1=Tom|title=The Blue Mask|journal=Rolling Stone|date=April 15, 1982|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/the-blue-mask-19820415}}</ref> After ''[[Legendary Hearts]]'' (1983) and ''[[New Sensations]]'' (1984), Reed was sufficiently reestablished as a public figure to become spokesman for [[Honda]] motorcycles.{{sfnp|Bockris|1994|p=351}} In the early 1980s, Reed worked with guitarists including [[Chuck Hammer]] on ''Growing Up in Public'', and [[Robert Quine]] on ''The Blue Mask'' and ''Legendary Hearts''.\n\nReed's 1984 album ''[[New Sensations]]'' marked the first time that Reed had charted within the US Top 100 since 1978's ''[[Street Hassle]]'', and the first time that Reed had charted in the UK altogether since 1976's ''[[Coney Island Baby]]''. Although its [[lead single]] \"[[I Love You, Suzanne]]\" only charted at No. 78 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] it did receive light rotation on [[MTV]]. Two more singles were released from the album: \"[[My Red Joystick]]\" and the Dutch-only release \"[[High in the City]]\" but they both failed to chart.\n\nIn 1998, ''[[The New York Times]]'' observed that in the 1970s, Reed had a distinctive persona: \"Back then he was publicly gay, pretended to shoot heroin onstage, and cultivated a 'Dachau panda' look, with cropped peroxide hair and black circles painted under his eyes.\"<ref name=\"Lewis\">{{Cite news|last=Lewis|first=Randy|date= October 28, 2013|title= Lou Reed, 1942 - 2013 Influential pioneer of punk, art rock|work= [[Los Angeles Times]] |page=1 |url=https://www.latimes.com/obituaries/la-me-lou-reed-20131028,0,347074.story?page=2 |accessdate=December 7, 2013}}</ref> The newspaper wrote that in 1980, \"Reed renounced druggy theatrics, even swore off intoxicants themselves, and became openly heterosexual, openly married.\"<ref name=\"Lewis\"/>\n\nOn September 22, 1985, Reed performed at the first [[Farm Aid]] concert in [[Champaign, Illinois]]. He performed \"Doin' the Things That We Want To\", \"I Love You, Suzanne\", \"New Sensations\" and \"Walk on the Wild Side\" as his solo set, later playing bass for [[Roy Orbison]] during his set. In June 1986, Reed released ''[[Mistrial (album)|Mistrial]]'' (co-produced with Fernando Saunders). To support the album, he released two music videos: \"[[No Money Down]]\" and \"[[The Original Wrapper]]\". In the same year, he joined [[Amnesty International]]'s [[A Conspiracy of Hope]] short tour and was outspoken about New York City's political issues and personalities.\n\nThe 1989 album ''[[New York (album)|New York]]'', which commented on crime, [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]], civil rights activist [[Jesse Jackson]], then-President of Austria [[Kurt Waldheim]] and [[Pope John Paul II]], became his second gold-certified work when it passed 500,000 sales in 1997.<ref name=\"riaa\"/> Reed was nominated for a Grammy Award for best male rock vocal performance for the album.<ref name=\"Caulfield\"/>\n\n===1990\u201399: Velvet Underground reunion and various projects===\nReed met John Cale for the first time in decades at Warhol's funeral in 1987. They worked together on the album ''[[Songs for Drella]]'' (April 1990), a [[song cycle]] about Warhol.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2013/10/28/lou-reed-dead-john-cale-statement/|title=Lou Reed remembered by VU bandmate John Cale|last=Anderson|first=Kyle|date=October 28, 2013|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> On the album, Reed sings of his love for his late friend, and criticizes both the doctors who were unable to save Warhol's life and Warhol's would-be assassin, [[Valerie Solanas]]. In 1990, the first Velvet Underground lineup reformed for a [[Fondation Cartier pour l'Art Contemporain|Fondation Cartier]] benefit show in France.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/see-velvet-underground-play-heroin-at-1990-reunion-w446616|title=See Velvet Underground Play 'Heroin' at 1990 Reunion - Rolling Stone|last=Greene|first=Andy|date=October 25, 2016|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In June and July 1993, the Velvet Underground again reunited and toured Europe, including an appearance at the [[Glastonbury Festival]]; plans for a North American tour were cancelled following a dispute between Reed and Cale.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/06/05/arts/older-but-still-hip-the-velvet-underground-rocks-again.html|title=Older but Still Hip, the Velvet Underground Rocks Again|last=Rockwell|first=John|date=June 5, 1993|accessdate=February 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://dangerousminds.net/comments/the_velvet_underground_live_paris_1993|title=Their Last Tour: The Velvet Underground - Live in Paris, 1993|work=Dangerous Minds|accessdate=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nReed had released his sixteenth solo album, ''[[Magic and Loss]]'', in January 1992. The album is preoccupied with mortality, inspired by the death of two close friends from [[cancer]]. In 1994, he appeared in ''[[A Celebration: The Music of Pete Townshend and The Who]]''. In the same year, he and Morales were divorced.{{sfnp|Brown|2013|p=98}} In 1995, Reed made a cameo appearance in the unreleased [[video game]] ''[[Penn & Teller's Smoke and Mirrors]]''. If the player selects the \"impossible\" difficulty setting, Reed appears shortly after the game begins as an unbeatable [[boss (video gaming)|boss]] who murders the player with his laser beam eyes. Reed then pops up on the screen and says to the player, \"This is the impossible level, boys. Impossible doesn't mean very difficult, very difficult is winning the [[Nobel Prize]], impossible is eating the sun.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MWlbzdaJJ|title=YouTube|website=Youtube.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, the Velvet Underground were inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]. At the ceremony, Reed, Cale and Tucker performed a song titled \"Last Night I Said Goodbye to My Friend\", dedicated to Sterling Morrison, who had died the previous August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/26-rock-and-roll-hall-of-fame-reunions-that-actually-happened-20140407/7-the-velvet-underground-1996-0317341|title=7. The Velvet Underground (1996)|last=Greene|first=Andy|date=April 7, 2014|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=February 15, 2018}}</ref> In February 1996 Reed released ''[[Set the Twilight Reeling]]'', and later that year, Reed contributed songs and music to ''Time Rocker'', a theatrical interpretation of [[H. G. Wells]]' ''[[The Time Machine]]'' by experimental director [[Robert Wilson (director)|Robert Wilson]]. The piece premiered in the [[Thalia Theater (Hamburg)|Thalia Theater, Hamburg]], and was later also shown at the [[Brooklyn Academy of Music]] in New York.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9404E5D81738F937A25752C1A961958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=1 |work=The New York Times |title=Next Wave Festival: Echoes of H. G. Wells, Rhythms of Lou Reed |first=Jon |last=Pareles |date=November 14, 1997}}</ref>\n\nFrom the late 1990s, Reed was romantically linked to musician, [[multimedia]] and performance artist [[Laurie Anderson]], and the two worked together on several recordings. They married on April 12, 2008.<ref>{{cite news |last=Aleksander |first=Irina |url= http://observer.com/2008/04/morning-memo-lou-reed-and-laurie-anderson-make-it-legal-suri-cruises-100000-birthday/ |title=Morning Memo: Lou Reed and Laurie Anderson Make it Legal |work=The New York Observer |date=April 23, 2008 |accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2000\u201312: Rock and ambient experimentation===\n[[File:Lou reed.jpg|thumb|left|Reed performing live at Schnitzer Concert Hall in [[Portland, Oregon]], 2004]]\nIn February 2000, Reed worked with Robert Wilson at the Thalia Theater again, on POEtry, another production inspired by the works of a 19th-century writer, this time [[Edgar Allan Poe]]. In April 2000, Reed released ''[[Ecstasy (Lou Reed album)|Ecstasy]]''. In January 2003, Reed released a two-CD set, ''[[The Raven (Lou Reed album)|The Raven]]'', based on POEtry. The album consists of songs written by Reed and spoken-word performances of reworked and rewritten texts of Edgar Allan Poe by the actors, set to electronic music composed by Reed. It features David Bowie and [[Ornette Coleman]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/news/1459300/20021226/reed_lou.jhtml |website=Vh1.com |title=Lou Reed's Obsession With Edgar Allan Poe Spawns ''The Raven'' |date=December 27, 2002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605030102/http://www.vh1.com/artists/news/1459300/20021226/reed_lou.jhtml |archivedate=June 5, 2011 }}</ref> A single disc CD version of the album, focusing on the music, was also released.{{refn|In 2011, Reed developed the CD into an illustrated book, with art by [[Lorenzo Mattotti]], published by [[Fantagraphics Books|Fantagraphics]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/ravenous-reed?mobify=0#slide_ss_0=1|title=Ravenous Reed|newspaper=[[The New Yorker]]|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref>|group=nb}}\n\nIn May 2000, Reed performed before Pope John Paul II at the Great Jubilee Concert in [[Rome]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1499424/pope-john-paul-ii-friend-of-bono-fan-of-pop-culture/|title=Pope John Paul II: Friend Of Bono, Fan Of Pop Culture|work=[[MTV]]|accessdate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In 2001, Reed made a cameo appearance in the [[Prozac Nation (film)|movie adaptation]] of ''[[Prozac Nation]]''. On October 6, 2001, ''the New York Times'' published a Reed poem called \"Laurie Sadly Listening\" in which he reflects on the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bushwatch.com/auden.htm |title=War Poems |website=Bushwatch.com |accessdate=March 26, 2010}}</ref> [[List of premature obituaries|Incorrect reports]] of Reed's death were broadcast by numerous US radio stations in 2001, caused by a hoax email (purporting to be from [[Reuters]]) which said he had died of a [[drug overdose]].<ref>[http://www.museumofhoaxes.com/day/05_09_2001.html \"Death of Lou Reed\"], Museum of Hoaxes web site</ref> In April 2003, Reed began a world tour featuring the cellist [[Jane Scarpantoni]] and singer [[Anohni]].\n\nIn 2003, Reed released a book of photographs, ''Emotions in Action''. This comprised an [[A4 paper size|A4]]-sized book called ''Emotions'' and a smaller one called ''Actions'' laid into its hard cover. In January 2006, he released a second book of photographs, ''Lou Reed's New York''.<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.artbook.com/3865211526.html |title=Lou Reed's New York |via=Artbook.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090908102734/http://www.artbook.com/3865211526.html |archivedate=September 8, 2009}}</ref> A third volume, ''Romanticism'', was released in 2009.{{sfnp|DeCurtis|2017|p=}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/features/lou-reed-photographer-1817676.html|title=Lou Reed: Photographer|date=November 10, 2009|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lou Reed Malaga, Spain 1.jpg|thumb|upright|Reed performing in [[M\u00e1laga]], Spain, 2008]]\nIn 2004, a Groovefinder [[remix]] of his song \"[[Satellite of Love]]\", called \"Satellite of Love '04\", was released. It reached No. 10 in the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/14017/lou-reed/|title=Lou Reed full Official Chart History|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=February 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2006, Reed appeared at Hal Willner's [[Leonard Cohen]] tribute show \"Came So Far for Beauty\" in [[Dublin]], along with Laurie Anderson, [[Nick Cave]], Anohni, [[Jarvis Cocker]], and [[Beth Orton]]. He played a [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] version of Cohen's \"The Stranger Song\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leonardcohenfiles.com/dublin.html|title=\"Came so far for Beauty\" in Dublin|website=Leonardcohenfiles.com|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn December that year, Reed played a series of shows at [[St. Ann's Warehouse]], Brooklyn, based on ''Berlin''. Reed played with guitarist [[Steve Hunter]], who played on the original album and ''Rock 'n' Roll Animal'', and was joined by singers Anohni and [[Sharon Jones]]. The show was produced by [[Bob Ezrin]], who also produced the original album, and Hal Willner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/shows/spectacle-elvis-costello-with/watch/lou-reed-and-julian-schnabel-1243213/|title=Watch Spectacle: Elvis Costello With ... - Lou Reed and Julian Schnabel Online |website=TV.com}}</ref> The show played at the [[Sydney Festival]] in January 2007 and in Europe during June and July 2007. The album version of the concert, entitled ''[[Berlin: Live at St. Ann's Warehouse]]'', and a live film recording of these concerts were both released in 2008. In April 2007, he released ''[[Hudson River Wind Meditations]]'', an album of [[ambient music|ambient]] [[meditation]]al music. It was released on the [[Sounds True]] record label. In June 2007, he performed at the Traffic Festival 2007 in [[Turin]], Italy, a five-day free event organized by the city. In the same month \"[[Pale Blue Eyes]]\" was included in the soundtrack of the French-language film, ''[[The Diving Bell and the Butterfly (film)|The Diving Bell and the Butterfly]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0401383/soundtrack?ref_=tt_ql_trv_7|title=The Diving Bell and the Butterfly (2007) - Soundtracks|website=IMDb.com}}</ref> In August 2007, Reed recorded \"[[Tranquilize]]\" with [[the Killers]] in New York City, a duet with [[Brandon Flowers]] for the B-side/rarities album ''[[Sawdust (album)|Sawdust]]''.\n\n[[File:Lou Reed at the Hop Farm Music Festival.jpg|thumb|170px|left|upright|Reed performing at the<br />[[Hop Farm Festival]] in [[Paddock Wood]], Kent, 2011]]\n\nOn October 2 and 3, 2008, he introduced his new group, which was later named [[Metal Machine Trio]], at the [[REDCAT|Walt Disney Concert Hall Complex]] in Los Angeles. The trio featured Ulrich Krieger (saxophone) and [[Sarth Calhoun]] (electronics), and played improvised instrumental music inspired by ''Metal Machine Music''. Recordings of the concerts were released under the title ''[[The Creation of the Universe]]''. The trio played at New York's [[Gramercy Theatre]] in April 2009, and appeared as part of Reed's band at the 2009 [[Lollapalooza]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2009/04/24/lou-reed-brings-controversial-metal-machine-music-to-new-york/ |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090427042824/http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2009/04/24/lou-reed-brings-controversial-metal-machine-music-to-new-york/ |archivedate= April 27, 2009 |title=Rolling Stone review of the Metal Machine Trio concert at the Gramercy in New York |work=Rolling Stone |date=April 24, 2009}}</ref>\n\nReed provided the voice of Maltazard, the villain in the 2009 [[Luc Besson]] animated/live-action feature film ''[[Arthur and the Revenge of Maltazard]]'' and appeared as himself in [[Wim Wenders]]' 2008 film ''[[Palermo Shooting]]''.\n\nReed played \"Sweet Jane\" and \"White Light/White Heat\" with [[Metallica]] at Madison Square Garden during the twenty-fifth anniversary celebration of the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame on October 30, 2009. In 2010 Lou Reed featured on the song \"Some Kind of Nature\" with Gorillaz, from their album Plastic Beach.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://2009.lollapalooza.com/band/lou-reed |title=Lou Reed at Lollapalooza 2009 |publisher=Lollapalooza 2009 |accessdate=March 26, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328163729/http://2009.lollapalooza.com/band/lou-reed |archivedate=March 28, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=129623 |title=Metallica with Ozzy, Lou Reed, Ray Davies at Rock Hall Concert: More Video Footage Available |publisher= Roadrunner Records |accessdate=March 26, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104034032/http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/metallica-with-ozzy-lou-reed-ray-davies-at-rock-hall-concert-more-video-footage-available/ |archivedate=November 4, 2013}}</ref> In October 2011, Metallica and Reed released the collaboration album [[Lulu (Lou Reed and Metallica album)|''Lulu'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metallica.com/news/20110615_news.asp |title=Secret Recording Project? |date=June 15, 2010 |website=Metallica.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110619190555/http://www.metallica.com/news/20110615_news.asp |archivedate=June 19, 2011 |accessdate=June 18, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It was based on the \"Lulu\" plays by the German playwright [[Frank Wedekind]] (1864\u20131918). The album received mixed and mainly negative reviews from music critics.<ref name=\"meta\">{{cite web| title = ''Lulu'' Reviews, Ratings, Credits, and More| work = [[Metacritic]]| publisher = [[CBS Interactive]]| url = http://www.metacritic.com/music/lulu |accessdate=January 28, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Sputnik\">{{cite web|url=http://sputnikmusic.com/review/46170/Lou-Reed-and-Metallica-Lulu/ |title=Lou Reed and Metallica - Lulu (staff review) |website=Sputnikmusic |date=October 21, 2011 |accessdate=October 25, 2011}}</ref> Reed joked that he had no fans left.<ref name=\"usatoday-genrebender\">{{cite news |last=Gundersen |first=Edna |title=Metallica, Lou Reed go on a genre bender with 'Lulu' |work=[[USA Today]] |publisher=[[Gannett Company]] |date=November 1, 2011 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/story/2011-11-25/lou-reed-metallica/51021572/1 |accessdate=November 4, 2011}}</ref> The album debuted at number 36 on the ''Billboard'' 200 with first-week sales of 13,000 copies.<ref name=\"Billboard200\">{{cite web|last=Greene|first=Andy|title=On The Charts: Justin Bieber Annihilates Loutallica|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/on-the-charts-justin-bieber-annihilates-loutallica-20111109|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=November 10, 2011|date=November 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Reed collaborated with [[indie rock]] band [[Metric (band)|Metric]] on \"The Wanderlust\", the tenth track on their fifth studio album '' [[Synthetica]]''. This was to be the last original composition he worked on.<ref>{{cite news|title=Metric On Recording Lou Reed Duet 'The Wanderlust'|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2013/10/28/metric-lou-reed-wanderlust_n_4170594.html|accessdate=December 12, 2013|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=October 28, 2013|author=Joshua Ostroff}}</ref>\n\n==Death, legacy, and honors==\nReed had suffered from [[hepatitis]] and [[Diabetes mellitus|diabetes]] for several years. He practiced [[tai chi]] during the last part of his life.<ref name=\"nyt\"/><ref name=\"andersonrs\"/> He was treated with [[interferon]] but developed [[liver cancer]].<ref name=\"andersonrs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/laurie-andersons-farewell-to-lou-reed-a-rolling-stone-exclusive-20131106|title=Laurie Anderson, \"For 21 years we tangled our minds and hearts together\"|date=November 6, 2013|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref> In May 2013, he underwent a [[Liver transplantation|liver transplant]] at the [[Cleveland Clinic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/lou-reed-recovering-from-liver-transplant-20130601|title=Lou Reed Recovering From Liver Transplant|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref><ref>Feran, Tom (June 11, 2013).[http://www.cleveland.com/metro/index.ssf/2013/06/cleveland_clinic_confirms_rock.html \"Cleveland Clinic confirms rock legend Lou Reed underwent liver transplant at hospital\"]. ''[[The Plain Dealer]]'' (Cleveland). Retrieved October 31, 2013.</ref> Afterwards, on his website, he wrote of feeling \"bigger and stronger\" than ever, but on October 27, 2013, he died from liver disease<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.verbicidemagazine.com/2013/10/29/lou-reed-cause-of-death-liver-disease-transplant/|title=Lou Reed's Cause of Death Confirmed|work=Verbicide Magazine|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref> at his home in [[East Hampton (town), New York|East Hampton]], New York, at the age of 71. He was cremated and the ashes were given to his family.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/28/arts/music/lou-reed-dies-at-71.html|title=Outsider Whose Dark, Lyrical Vision Helped Shape Rock 'n' Roll |work=The New York Times |date=October 27, 2013 |accessdate=October 28, 2013 |author=Ratliff, Ben}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/lou-reed-velvet-underground-leader-and-rock-pioneer-dead-at-71-20131027 |title=Lou Reed, Velvet Underground Leader and Rock Pioneer, Dead at 71 |work=Rolling Stone |date= October 27, 2013 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHis widow [[Laurie Anderson]] said his last days were peaceful, and described him as a \"prince and a fighter\".<ref name=\"andersonrs\"/> [[David Byrne]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/david-byrne-remembers-the-brave-lou-reed-20131028|title=David Byrne Remembers the 'Brave' Lou Reed|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref> [[Patti Smith]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/patti-smith-lou-reed-was-a-very-special-poet-20131028|title=Patti Smith: 'Lou Reed Was a Very Special Poet|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref> [[David Bowie]], [[Morrissey]], [[Iggy Pop]], [[Courtney Love]], [[Lenny Kravitz]] and many others also paid tribute to Reed.<ref name=\"BBC-Bowie\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-24703353|title=David Bowie leads tributes to 'master' Lou Reed|work=BBC News|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/just-wild-about-lou-tributes-pour-in-for-rock-pioneer-reed-8909458.html|work=The Independent|title=Just wild about Lou: Tributes pour in for rock pioneer Lou Reed|date=October 28, 2013|accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://pitchfork.com/news/52786-david-bowie-morrissey-john-cale-release-statements-on-lou-reeds-death/ | title=David Bowie, Morrissey, John Cale Release Statements on Lou Reed's Death | work=[[Pitchfork Media]] | date=October 28, 2013 | accessdate=October 29, 2013 |author=Battan, Carrie}}</ref> Former Velvet Underground members Moe Tucker<ref>{{cite news |author1=Almasy, Steve |author2=Smith, Matt |url= http://www.cnn.com/2013/10/27/showbiz/lou-reed-obit/index.html |title=Rock legend Lou Reed dies at 71 |publisher=CNN |date= October 28, 2013 |accessdate=October 28, 2013}}</ref> and John Cale made statements on Reed's death,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/earshot/lou-reed-remembered-by-john-cale-651146 |title=John Cale Remembers Friend Lou Reed: 'We Have the Best of Our Fury Laid Out on Vinyl' |date=October 27, 2013 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=October 28, 2013}}</ref> and notables from far outside the music industry paid their respects such as [[Gianfranco Ravasi|Cardinal Gianfranco Ravasi]].<ref name=tributes>Runcie, Charlotte (October 28, 2013). [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/10408554/Vatican-leads-tributes-to-Lou-Reed.html \"Vatican leads tributes to Lou Reed\"], ''The Daily Telegraph'' (London).</ref>\n\nOn October 27, 2013, the day of Reed's death, [[Pearl Jam]] dedicated their song \"[[Man of the Hour]]\" to him at their show in [[Baltimore]] and then played \"[[I'm Waiting for the Man]]\".<ref name=\"Baltimore\">Case, Wesley (October 28, 2013).[http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/music/midnight-sun-blog/bal-after-23-years-pearl-jam-finally-comes-to-baltimore-20131028,0,7370922.story \"After 23 Years Pearl Jam Finally Comes to Baltimore\"]. ''The Sun'' (Baltimore). Retrieved October 28, 2013</ref> On the day of his death, the Killers dedicated their rendition of \"Pale Blue Eyes\" to Reed at the Life Is Beautiful festival in [[Las Vegas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/the-killers/73527 |title=The Killers cover Lou Reed's 'Pale Blue Eyes' at Las Vegas gig \u2013 watch |work=NME |date=October 30, 2013 |accessdate=December 10, 2013}}</ref> [[My Morning Jacket]] performed a cover of \"Oh! Sweet Nuthin'\" in California<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hogan |first1=Marc |title=See Pearl Jam, My Morning Jacket Pay Musical Tribute to Lou Reed |url=https://www.spin.com/2013/10/lou-reed-pearl-jam-my-morning-jacket-live-covers/ |accessdate=August 19, 2018 |work=Spin |date=October 28, 2013}}</ref> while [[Arctic Monkeys]] performed \"Walk on the Wild Side\" in Liverpool.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ayers |first1=Mike |title=Arctic Monkeys Honor Lou Reed |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/arctic-monkeys-cover-lou-reeds-walk-on-the-wild-side-67816/ |accessdate=August 19, 2018 |work=Rolling Stone |date=October 29, 2013}}</ref> That same night, [[Phish]] opened their show in Hartford, CT with the Velvet Underground's \"[[Rock & Roll (The Velvet Underground song)|Rock & Roll]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://phish.in/2013-10-27|title=phish.in'|website=phish.in|access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> On November 14, 2013, a three-hour public memorial was held near [[Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts|Lincoln Center]]'s [[Paul Milstein]] Pool and Terrace. Billed as \"New York: Lou Reed at Lincoln Center\", the ceremony featured favorite Reed recordings selected by family and friends.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chiu|first=David|title=Lou Reed's Memorial Lets the Music Speak for Itself|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/lou-reeds-memorial-lets-the-music-speak-for-itself-20131114|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=November 14, 2013|date=March 4, 2014}}</ref> On March 14, 2014, [[Richard Barone]] and [[Alejandro Escovedo]] produced and hosted the first full-scale tribute to Lou Reed at the [[SXSW]] Music Festival in Austin, Texas, with over twenty international acts performing Reed's music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5930169/lou-reed-tribute-concert-sxsw-lineup-spandau-ballet-sean-lennon|title=Inside the Lou Reed Tribute at SXSW: 20-Plus Acts, All-Star House Band to Create 'Austin Meets New York Street Vibe'|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nReed's estate was valued at $30 million, $20 million of which accrued after his death. He left everything to his wife and his sister.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/jul/01/lou-reed-leaves-30m-fortune|title=Lou Reed leaves $30m fortune|date=July 1, 2014|work=[[TheGuardian.com]]|accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nReed's induction into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] as a solo artist was announced on December 16, 2014.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2014/12/16/2015-rock-hall-of-fame-inductees/20310347/ \"Green Day, Lou Reed among Rock Hall inductees\"], ''[[USA Today]]''. December 16, 2014. Retrieved December 18, 2014</ref> He was inducted by Patti Smith at a ceremony in Cleveland on April 18, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Read Patti Smith's Poignant Lou Reed Rock Hall Induction|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/read-patti-smiths-poignant-lou-reed-rock-hall-induction-20150419|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=April 19, 2015}}</ref> In 2017, ''Lou Reed: A Life'' was published by the ''Rolling Stone'' critic [[Anthony DeCurtis]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/oct/01/my-brilliant-troubled-friend-lou-reed-a-life-anthony-decurtis-berlin|title=My brilliant and troubled friend Lou Reed|date=October 1, 2017|work=[[TheGuardian.com]]|accessdate=February 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAsteroid [[270553 Loureed]], discovered by [[Maik Meyer]] at [[Palomar Observatory]] in 2002, was named in his honor.<ref name=\"MPC-object\" /> The official {{MoMP|270553|naming citation}} was published by the [[Minor Planet Center]] on June 2, 2015 ({{small|[[Minor Planet Circulars|M.P.C.]] 94391}}).<ref name=\"MPC-Circulars-Archive\" /> Spiders with furry bodies are known as [[velvet spider]]s and one which was recently discovered in Spain is named ''[[Loureedia]]'', because it has a velvet body and lives underground.<ref>{{cite web |title=Velvet spider named after Lou Reed found in Europe for the first time |url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/discover/news/2019/january/velvet-spider-named-after-lou-reed-found-in-europe-for-the-first.html |website=Natural History Museum |accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAn archive of his letters and other personal effects was donated to The New York Public Library for the Performing Arts, where it can be viewed by members of the public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nypl.org/loureed|title=Lou Reed Archive at The New York Public Library for the Performing Arts|website=The New York Public Library|access-date=April 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Equipment==\n\n===Guitars===\n* [[Fender Telecaster]]\n* [[Carl Thompson (luthier)|Carl Thompson]] six-string guitar\n* Steve Klein electric guitar\n* [[Epiphone]] Riviera electric guitar\n* [[Gretsch]] Country Gentleman\n* [[Gibson ES-335]]TD electric guitar\n* [[Steinberger]] Synapse Transcale ST-2FPA Custom\n* [[Fender Electric XII]] twelve-string\n* [[Gibson SG]] Standard electric guitar\n* Rick Kelly electric guitar (silver sparkle [[Telecaster]] style)\n\n===Amplifiers===\n* [[Jim Kelley Amplifiers]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vintageguitar.com/26365/jim-kelley-reverb-model/|title=Jim Kelley Reverb Model|first=Bob|last=Dragich|website=Vintageguitar.com|date=December 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guitarworld.com/magazine/lou-reed-talks-about-velvet-underground-songwriting-and-gear-1998-guitar-world-interview|title=Lou Reed Talks About the Velvet Underground, Songwriting and Gear in 1998 Guitar World Interview|author=Alan di Perna|website=Guitarworld.com}}</ref>\n* [[Fender Deluxe|Fender 'wide panel tweed' Deluxe Amp 5C3]]\n* [[Soldano Custom Amplification|Soldano]] SLO 100 100-Watt Tube guitar amplifier\n* [[Tone King]] Imperial 1x12 Combo guitar amplifier\n* [[Sears]] [[Silvertone (brand)|Silvertone]] 1484 Twin-Twelve\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Lou Reed discography}}\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n:: '''The Velvet Underground'''\n* ''[[The Velvet Underground & Nico]]'' (1967)\n* ''[[White Light/White Heat]]'' (1968)\n* ''[[The Velvet Underground (album)|The Velvet Underground]]'' (1969)\n* ''[[Loaded (The Velvet Underground album)|Loaded]]'' (1970)\n:: '''Solo'''\n* ''[[Lou Reed (album)|Lou Reed]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Transformer (Lou Reed album)|Transformer]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Berlin (Lou Reed album)|Berlin]]'' (1973)\n* ''[[Sally Can't Dance]]'' (1974)\n* ''[[Metal Machine Music]]'' (1975)\n* ''[[Coney Island Baby]]'' (1975)\n* ''[[Rock and Roll Heart]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[Street Hassle]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[The Bells (Lou Reed album)|The Bells]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Growing Up in Public (Lou Reed album)|Growing Up in Public]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[The Blue Mask]]'' (1982)\n* ''[[Legendary Hearts]]'' (1983)\n* ''[[New Sensations]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[Mistrial (album)|Mistrial]]'' (1986)\n{{col-break}}\n* ''[[New York (album)|New York]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Magic and Loss]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Set the Twilight Reeling]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Ecstasy (Lou Reed album)|Ecstasy]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[The Raven (Lou Reed album)|The Raven]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Hudson River Wind Meditations]]'' (2007)\n\n:: '''Collaborations'''\n* ''[[Songs for Drella]]'' (1990) <small>(with [[John Cale]])</small>\n* ''[[Lulu (Lou Reed and Metallica album)|Lulu]]'' (2011) <small>(with [[Metallica]])</small>\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"|Year\n! scope=\"col\"|Title\n! scope=\"col\"|Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1980\n| ''[[One-Trick Pony (film)|One-Trick Pony]]''\n| Steve Kunelian\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"| 1983\n| ''[[Get Crazy]]''\n| Auden\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Rock & Rule]]''\n| Mok's singing voice\n| \"My Name is Mok\" and \"Triumph\"; third song \"Pain and Suffering\" was sung by [[Iggy Pop]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1988\n| ''[[Permanent Record (film)|Permanent Record]]''\n| Himself\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1993\n| ''[[Faraway, So Close!]]''\n| Himself\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1995\n| ''[[Blue in the Face]]''\n| Man with Strange Glasses\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1995\n| ''[[Penn & Teller's Smoke and Mirrors]]''\n| Himself\n| Unreleased video game; Appears as an unbeatable [[Boss (video gaming)|Boss]] if the player sets the game's difficulty to \"Impossible\".\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1997\n| ''[[Closure (video)|Closure]]''\n| Himself\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1998\n| ''[[Lulu on the Bridge]]''\n| Not Lou Reed\n| Cameo\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2001\n| ''[[Prozac Nation (film)|Prozac Nation]]''\n| Himself\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"| 2008\n| ''[[Berlin: Live at St. Ann's Warehouse]]''\n| Himself\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Palermo Shooting]]''\n| Himself\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2009\n| ''[[Arthur and the Revenge of Maltazard]]''\n| Emperor Maltazard (voice)\n| Replaced [[David Bowie]], who voiced the character in the first installment.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2010\n| ''[[Arthur 3: The War of the Two Worlds]]''\n| Emperor Maltazard (voice)\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2010\n| ''[[Red Shirley]]''\n| Director, Interviewer\n| Documentary, 28 mins.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2016\n| ''[[Danny Says (film)|Danny Says]]''\n| Subject\n| Documentary, 104 mins. Features archival tape from 1975 of Lou Reed listening to the [[Ramones]] for the first time with music manager [[Danny Fields]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Arts|Music|Film|LGBT}}\n* [[Loureedia]], a genus of (underground) velvet spiders named for Lou Reed\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"MPC-object\">{{cite web\n  |title      = 270553 Loureed (2002 GG178)\n  |work       = Minor Planet Center\n  |url        = https://www.minorplanetcenter.net/db_search/show_object?object_id=270553\n  |accessdate = September 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MPC-Circulars-Archive\">{{cite web\n  |title      = MPC/MPO/MPS Archive\n  |work       = Minor Planet Center\n  |url        = https://www.minorplanetcenter.net/iau/ECS/MPCArchive/MPCArchive_TBL.html\n  |accessdate = September 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n}} <!-- end of reflist -->\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Beeber|first1=Steven Lee|title=The Heebie-Jeebies at CBGB's: A Secret History of Jewish Punk|url=https://books.google.com/?id=tDk6FuQcxpoC&pg=PA11&lpg=PA11&dq=Toby+Futterman+Sidney+Joseph+Reed|isbn=9781556527616|year=2006|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Bockris|first1=Victor|title=Transformer: The Lou Reed Story|year=1994|isbn=0-684-80366-6|authorlink=Victor Bockris|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/transformerlour000bock}}\n* {{cite book|last=Brown|first=Bill|title=Words and Guitar: A History of Lou Reed's Music|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6JIpBgAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=Colossal Books|isbn=9780615933771|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=DeCurtis|first=Anthony|title=Lou Reed: A Life|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VdIpDgAAQBAJ|year=2017|publisher=Hodder & Stoughton|isbn=9781444794595|authorlink=Anthony DeCurtis|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Clapton|first=Diana|url=https://books.google.com/?id=cHb_AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT21&lpg=PT21&dq=Lou%20Reed%20hepatitis%20from%20a%20negro%20named%20jaw#v=onepage|title=Lou Reed & The Velvet Underground|year=2012|publisher=Music Sales Group|isbn=9780857127570|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=McNeil|first1=Legs|last2=McCain|first2=Gillian|title=Please Kill Me: The Uncensored Oral History of Punk|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mkG7Y6_J7pUC|year=2006|publisher=Grove Press|isbn=9780802142641|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Reed|first1=Lou|title=Between Thought and Expression: Selected Lyrics of Lou Reed|year=1991|publisher=Hyperion|isbn=1-56282-923-8|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/betweenthoughtex00lreed}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Roberts|first1=Chris|first2=Lou|last2=Reed|url=https://books.google.com/?id=SdiPJ8sPF18C&pg=PA18&lpg=PA18&dq=%22Lewis+Allan+Reed%22|title=Lou Reed: The Stories Behind the Songs|year=2004|publisher=Hal Leonard|isbn=0-634-08032-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Thompson|first1=Dave|title=Your Pretty Face Is Going to Hell: The Dangerous Glitter of David Bowie, Iggy Pop, and Lou Reed|year=2009|publisher=Backbeat Books|isbn=9781617134081|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rFJMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT18|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Unterberger|first1=Richie|title=White Light/White Heat: The Velvet Underground Day-by-Day|year=2009|publisher=Jawbone Press|location=London|isbn=978-1-906002-22-0|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Lou Reed}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{AllMusic|class=artist|id=mn0000233066}}\n* {{discogs artist}}\n* {{IMDb name|0715563}}\n* {{IBDB name|84104}}\n<!--\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. Wikipedia  |\n    | is not a collection of links nor should it be used for advertising. |\n    |                                                                     |\n    |           Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n    | See [[Wikipedia:External links]] & [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.  |\n    |                                                                     |\n-->\n{{Lou Reed}}\n{{The Velvet Underground}}\n{{2015 Rock and Roll Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reed, Lou}}\n[[Category:Lou Reed| ]]\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:American baritones]]\n[[Category:American street performers]]\n[[Category:American experimental guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American poets]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American rock singers]]\n[[Category:American rock songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Art rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Bisexual men]]\n[[Category:Bisexual musicians]]\n[[Category:Deaths from liver disease]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Glam rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Ivor Novello Award winners]]\n[[Category:Jewish American songwriters]]\n[[Category:Jewish American musicians]]\n[[Category:Jewish rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Jewish singers]]\n[[Category:Jews in punk rock]]\n[[Category:Rhythm guitarists]]\n[[Category:Lead guitarists]]\n[[Category:LGBT Jews]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers]]\n[[Category:LGBT songwriters]]\n[[Category:Liver transplant recipients]]\n[[Category:Matador Records artists]]\n[[Category:MGM Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Noise musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Freeport, New York]]\n[[Category:Photographers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Protopunk musicians]]\n[[Category:RCA Records artists]]\n[[Category:Reprise Records artists]]\n[[Category:Singers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Sire Records artists]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Syracuse University alumni]]\n[[Category:The Velvet Underground members]]\n[[Category:Warner Records artists]]\n[[Category:People from East Hampton (town), New York]]\n[[Category:People associated with The Factory]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Welsh rugby player|Lou Reed (rugby player)}}\n{{Redirect|Lewis Reed|the St. Louis alderman|Lewis E. Reed}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| image               = Lou Reed 1977.JPG\n<!-- NOTE: Do not replace Lou Reed 1977.JPG unless it is with a photo under a public domain or free license (meaning NOT fair use). Any fair use photos (i.e. 'promotional photos') violate the Fair Use Policy and will be deleted. See [[Wikipedia:Fair]] use criteria. -->\n| alt                 =\n| caption             = Reed in 1977\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Lewis Allan Reed\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1942|3|2}}\n| birth_place         = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.<!--No boroughs/neighborhoods, just cities per format.-->\n| origin              = [[Freeport, New York]], U.S.\n| death_date          = {{Death date and age|2013|10|27|1942|3|2}}\n| death_place         = {{nowrap|[[East Hampton (town), New York|East Hampton]], New York, U.S.}}\n| genre               = {{hlist|[[Rock music|Rock]]|[[experimental music|experimental]]|[[proto-punk]]|[[glam rock]]|[[art rock]]|[[noise rock]]}}\n| occupation          = {{hlist|Musician|singer|songwriter|composer|photographer}}<!--Please do not add to this list without first discussing your proposal on the talk page. -->\n| instrument          = {{hlist|Vocals|guitar}}<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed or removed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| years_active        = 1958\u20132013\n| label               = {{hlist|[[Pickwick Records|Pickwick]]|[[Verve Records|Verve]]|[[MGM Records|MGM]]|[[Cotillion Records|Cotillion]]|[[RCA Records|RCA]]|[[Arista Records|Arista]]|[[Sire Records|Sire]]|[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]}}\n| associated_acts     = {{hlist|[[The Velvet Underground]]|[[John Cale]]|[[Nico]]|[[David Bowie]]|[[John Zorn]]|[[Laurie Anderson]]|[[Metal Machine Trio]]|[[Metallica]]}}<!--Please do not add to this list without first discussing your proposal on the talk page. -->\n}}\n<!-- PER WP:LEADCITE NOTHING CITED IN THE REST OF THE ARTICLE NEEDS TO BE CITED HERE -->\n'''Lewis Allan Reed''' (March 2, 1942 \u2013 October 27, 2013) was an American musician, singer, songwriter and poet. He was the rhythm/lead guitarist, singer and principal songwriter for the rock band [[The Velvet Underground]] and had a solo career that spanned five decades. The Velvet Underground was not a commercial success during its existence, but became regarded as one of the most influential bands in the history of [[underground music|underground]] and [[alternative rock]] music.\n\nAfter leaving the band in 1970, Reed released twenty solo [[Album#Studio|studio albums]]. His second, ''[[Transformer (Lou Reed album)|Transformer]]'' (1972), was produced by [[David Bowie]] and arranged by [[Mick Ronson]], and brought mainstream recognition. The album is considered an influential landmark of the [[glam rock]] genre, anchored by Reed's most successful single, \"[[Walk on the Wild Side (Lou Reed song)|Walk on the Wild Side]]\". After ''Transformer'', the less commercial but critically acclaimed ''[[Berlin (Lou Reed album)|Berlin]]'' reached No. 7 on the [[UK Albums Chart]]. ''[[Rock 'n' Roll Animal]]'' (a live album released in 1974) sold strongly, and ''[[Sally Can't Dance]]'' (1974) peaked at No. 10 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]; but for a long period after, Reed's work did not translate into sales, leading him deeper into drug addiction and alcoholism. Reed cleaned up in the early 1980s, and gradually returned to prominence with ''[[New Sensations]]'' (1984), reaching a critical and commercial career peak with his 1989 album ''[[New York (album)|New York]]''.\n\nReed participated in the reformation of the Velvet Underground in the 1990s, and made several more albums, including a collaboration album with [[John Cale]] titled ''[[Songs for Drella]]'' which was a tribute to their former mentor [[Andy Warhol]]. ''[[Magic and Loss]]'' (1992) would become Reed's highest-charting album on the UK Albums Chart, peaking at No. 6.\n\nHe contributed music to two theatrical interpretations of 19th century writers, one of which he developed into an album titled ''[[The Raven (Lou Reed album)|The Raven]]''. He married his third wife [[Laurie Anderson]] in 2008, and recorded the collaboration album ''[[Lulu (Lou Reed and Metallica album)|Lulu]]'' with [[Metallica]]. He died in 2013 of [[liver disease]]. Reed's distinctive deadpan voice, poetic lyrics and experimental guitar playing were trademarks throughout his long career. Reed has been inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] twice; as a member of the Velvet Underground in 1996 and as a solo act in 2015.\n\n==Biography==\n===1942\u201364: Early life===\nLewis Allan Reed was born on March 2, 1942, at Beth El Hospital (later [[Brookdale University Hospital and Medical Center|Brookdale]]) in [[Brooklyn]] and grew up in [[Freeport, New York|Freeport, Long Island]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-10-27/lou-reed-rocker-who-sang-walk-on-the-wild-side-dies-at-71.html |title=Lou Reed, 'Walk on the Wild Side' Rocker, Dies at 71 |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |accessdate=October 28, 2013}}</ref>{{refn|Contrary to some sources, his birth name was Lewis Allan Reed, not Louis Firbanks, a name that was coined as a joke by [[Lester Bangs]] in ''[[Creem]]'' magazine.{{sfnp|Roberts|Reed|2004|p=18}}|group=nb}} Reed was the son of Toby (n\u00e9e Futterman) (1920\u20132013) and Sidney Joseph Reed (1913\u20132005), an accountant.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/Lou_Reed.aspx |title=Lou Reed Facts, information, pictures|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia.com|accessdate=December 24, 2012}}</ref> His family was [[Jews|Jewish]];{{sfnp|Beeber|2006|p=11}} his father had changed his name from Rabinowitz to Reed.{{sfnp|DeCurtis|2017|p=}} Reed said that although he was Jewish, his real god was rock 'n' roll.<ref name=\"NYROCK1998\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyrock.com/interviews/loureed_int.htm|title=The Gospel According to Lou: Interview with Lou Reed|author=Gabriella|website=Nyrock.com|date=November 1998|accessdate=October 27, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031184208/http://www.nyrock.com/interviews/loureed_int.htm|archivedate=October 31, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/lou-reeds-contradictory-jewishness/|title=Lou Reed's paradoxical Jewishness|work=The Times of Israel|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\nReed attended Atkinson Elementary School in Freeport and went on to Freeport Junior High School. His sister Merrill, born Margaret Reed, said that as an adolescent, he suffered [[panic attack]]s, became socially awkward and \"possessed a fragile temperament\" but was highly focused on things that he liked, mainly music.<ref name=medium>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/cuepoint/a-family-in-peril-lou-reed-s-sister-sets-the-record-straight-about-his-childhood-20e8399f84a3|title=A Family in Peril: Lou Reed's Sister Sets the Record Straight About His Childhood|first=Merrill Reed|last=Weiner|date=April 11, 2015|website=Medium.com|accessdate=June 6, 2017}}</ref> Having learned to play the guitar from the radio, he developed an early interest in [[rock and roll]] and [[rhythm and blues]], and during high school played in several bands.<ref name=\"Costello interview\">{{cite episode|title=Lou Reed and Julian Schnabel|url=http://www.sundancechannel.com/films/500328617|series=Spectacle|airdate=2008|season=1|number=2|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090415182218/http://www.sundancechannel.com/films/500328617|archivedate=April 15, 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lou Reed HS Yearbook (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|upright|Reed as a high school senior, 1959]]\nHe began experimenting with drugs at the age of 16.<ref name=medium/> His first recording was as a member of a [[doo-wop]] band called the Jades. His love for playing music and his desire to play gigs brought him into confrontation with his anxious and unaccommodating parents.<ref name=medium/> His sister recalled that during his first year in college he was brought home one day, having had a [[mental breakdown]], after which he remained \"depressed, anxious, and socially unresponsive\" for a time, and that his parents were having difficulty coping. Visiting a psychologist, Reed's parents were made to feel guilty as inadequate parents, and consented to [[electroconvulsive therapy]] (ECT).<ref name=medium/> Reed appeared to blame his father for the treatment to which he had been subjected.<ref name=medium/> He wrote about the experience in his 1974 song, \"Kill Your Sons\".<ref name=\"Fatherhood\">{{cite web|url=http://fatherhoodchannel.com/2013/10/27/lou-reed-lived-and-died-with-a-broken-heart-027/|title=Lou Reed Lived and Died with a Broken Heart|work=Fatherhood Channel|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Salon.com_LouReed_Syracuse_BA\">{{cite web|url=http://dir.salon.com/people/bc/2000/05/16/reed|title=Lou Reed|last=Colin|first=Chris|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|accessdate=June 23, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101107125917/http://dir.salon.com/people/bc/2000/05/16/reed|archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> Reed later recalled the experience as having been traumatic and leading to memory loss. He believed that he was treated to dispel his feelings of homosexuality.{{sfnp|McNeil|McCain|2006|p=4}} After Reed's death, his sister denied the ECT treatments were intended to suppress his \"homosexual urges\", asserting that their parents were not homophobic but had been told by his doctors that ECT was necessary to treat Reed's mental and behavioral issues.<ref name=medium/>\n\nUpon his recovery from his illness and associated treatment, Reed resumed his education at [[Syracuse University]] in 1960,<ref name=medium/> studying journalism, film directing, and [[creative writing]]. He was a [[platoon leader]] in [[Reserve Officers' Training Corps|ROTC]]; he said he was later expelled from the program for holding an unloaded gun to his superior's head.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,916140,00.html|title=Music: Lou Reed's Nightshade Carnival|date=April 24, 1978|author=Cocks, Jay|work=Time|location=New York|accessdate=October 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1961, he began hosting a late-night radio program on [[WAER]] called ''Excursions on a Wobbly Rail''.<ref name=\"Costello interview\"/> Named after a song by pianist [[Cecil Taylor]], the program typically featured doo wop, rhythm and blues, and [[jazz]], particularly the [[free jazz]] developed in the mid-1950s.<ref>{{Cite AV media notes|first=David|last=Fricke|type=liner notes|title=Peel Slowly and See|publisher=Polydor|year=1995}}</ref> Reed said that when he started out he was inspired by such musicians as [[Ornette Coleman]], who had \"always been a great influence\" on him; he said that his guitar on \"[[European Son]]\" was his way of trying to imitate the jazz saxophonist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.furious.com/perfect/jazzpunk.html|title=The Jazz-Punk Connection|work=furious.com|accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> Reed's sister said that during her brother's time at [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]], the university authorities had tried unsuccessfully to expel him because they did not approve of his extracurricular activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.loureed.com/inmemoriam|title=Lou Reed, 1942-2013|work=loureed.com|accessdate=January 18, 2017|quote=[He] started a band, he had his own radio show. He reportedly libeled some student on his radio show; the kid's family tried to sue my father. And there were other extracurricular possibly illegal activities of which the university didn't approve. I believe they tried to kick him out. But he was a genius; what could they do? He stayed and he graduated.}}</ref> At Syracuse University, he studied under poet [[Delmore Schwartz]], who he said was \"the first great person I ever met\", and they became friends. He credited Schwartz with showing him how \"with the simplest language imaginable, and very short, you can accomplish the most astonishing heights.\"<ref name=documentary>\"Rock and Roll Heart\", documentary on the life of Lou Reed, ''American Masters''</ref> One of Reed's fellow students at Syracuse in the early 1960s (who also studied under Schwartz) was the musician [[Garland Jeffreys]]; they remained close friends until the end of Reed's life.<ref name=\"syracuse.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2014/01/garland_jeffreys_le_moyne_lou_reed.html|title=Garland Jeffreys remembers his friend, Lou Reed|work=syracuse.com|accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJeffreys recalled Reed's time at Syracuse: \"At four in the afternoon we'd all meet at [the bar] ''The Orange Grove.'' Me, Delmore and Lou. That would often be the center of the crew. And Delmore was the leader - our quiet leader.\"<ref name=\"syracuse.com\"/> While at Syracuse, Reed was also introduced to intravenous drug use for the first time, and quickly contracted [[hepatitis]].{{sfnp|Clapton|2012|p=}} [[Sterling Morrison]] was not attending Syracuse at the time, but met Reed while he was visiting mutual friend Jim Tucker, the older brother of Velvet Underground drummer [[Moe Tucker]], who was attending school there. Reed later dedicated the song \"European Son\", from the first Velvet Underground album, to Schwartz.<ref>{{Cite AV media notes |title=The Velvet Underground & Nico |year=1967 |type=album cover notes and record label}}</ref> In 1982, Reed recorded \"My House\" from his album ''[[The Blue Mask]]'' as a tribute to his late mentor. He later said that his goals as a writer were \"to bring the sensitivities of the novel to rock music\" or to write the [[Great American Novel]] in a record album.<ref>Interview in ''Rolling Stone'' Nov/Dec 1987: Twentieth Anniversary Issue.</ref> Reed graduated from Syracuse University's [[Syracuse University College of Arts and Sciences|College of Arts and Sciences]] with a [[B.A.]] ''[[cum laude]]'' in English in June 1964.<ref name=\"Salon.com_LouReed_Syracuse_BA\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.syr.edu/statement-from-syracuse-university-regarding-the-passing-of-lou-reed-59708|title=Statement from Syracuse University Regarding the Passing of Lou Reed|accessdate=October 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===1964\u201370: Pickwick and the Velvet Underground===\n[[File:Velvet Underground 1968 by Billy Name.png|thumb|upright|left|The Velvet Underground, 1968]]\nIn 1964, Reed moved to New York City to work as an in-house songwriter for [[Pickwick Records]]. That year he wrote and recorded the single \"The Ostrich\", a parody of popular [[dance music|dance songs]] of the time, which included lines such as \"put your head on the floor and have somebody step on it\". His employers felt that the song had hit potential, and assembled a supporting band to help promote the recording. The ''ad hoc'' band, called \"the Primitives\", included Welsh musician [[John Cale]], who had recently moved to New York to study music and was playing viola in composer [[La Monte Young]]'s [[Theatre of Eternal Music]], along with [[Tony Conrad]]. Cale and Conrad were surprised to find that for \"The Ostrich\", Reed tuned each string of his guitar to the same note, which they began to call his \"[[ostrich guitar]]\" tuning. This technique created a [[drone (music)|drone]] effect similar to their experimentation in Young's [[avant-garde]] ensemble. Disappointed with Reed's performance, Cale was nevertheless impressed by Reed's early repertoire (including \"[[Heroin (The Velvet Underground song)|Heroin]]\"), and a partnership began to evolve.<ref name=documentary/>\n\nReed and Cale (who played viola, keyboards and bass guitar) lived together on the [[Lower East Side]], and invited Reed's college acquaintance guitarist Sterling Morrison and Cale's neighbor drummer [[Angus MacLise]] to join the band, thus forming [[the Velvet Underground]]. When the opportunity came to play their first paying gig at [[Summit High School (New Jersey)|Summit High School]] in [[Summit, New Jersey]], MacLise quit because he believed that accepting money for art was a [[selling out|sellout]] and did not want to participate in a structured gig. He was replaced on drums by [[Moe Tucker]], initially for that one show, but she soon became a full-time member with her drumming an integral part of the band's sound, despite Cale's initial objections. Though it had little commercial success, the band is considered one of the most influential in rock history.<ref name=\"nrr-loc\">{{cite web |title=News from the Library of Congress |url=https://www.loc.gov/today/pr/2007/07-039.html |website=National Recording Registry |publisher=Library of Congress |date=March 6, 2007 |quote=For decades this album has cast a huge shadow over nearly every sub-variety of avant-garde rock, from 1970s art-rock to No Wave, New Wave and Punk. Referring to their sway over the rock music of the '70s and '80s, critic Lester Bangs stated, 'Modern music starts with the Velvets, and the implications and influence of what they did seem to go on forever.'}}</ref><ref name=rrhallbio>{{cite web |title=The Velvet Underground Biography |url=https://rockhall.com/inductees/the-velvet-underground/bio/ |website=Rock & Roll Hall of Fame |quote=The influence of the Velvet Underground on rock greatly exceeds their sales figures and chart numbers. They are one of the most important rock and roll bands of all time, laying the groundwork in the Sixties for many tangents rock music would take in ensuing decades.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20131125-do-the-velvets-beat-the-beatles |title=The Velvet Underground: As influential as The Beatles? |last=Kot |first=Greg |publisher=BBC |date=October 21, 2014 |accessdate=November 25, 2016}}</ref> Reed was the main singer and songwriter in the band.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |last1=Unterberger |first1=Richie |title=The Velvet Underground \u2013 Biography & History |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-velvet-underground-mn0000840402/biography |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=March 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box|width=30em|align=right|quote=Had he accomplished nothing else, his work with the Velvet Underground in the late sixties would assure him a place in anyone's rock & roll pantheon; those remarkable songs still serve as an articulate aural nightmare of men and women caught in the beauty and terror of sexual, street and drug paranoia, unwilling or unable to move. The message is that urban life is tough stuff\u2014it will kill you; Reed, the poet of destruction, knows it but never looks away and somehow finds holiness as well as perversity in both his sinners and his quest. ... [H]e is still one of a handful of American artists capable of the spiritual home run.|source= \u2014''[[Rolling Stone]]'', 1975<ref>Nelson, Paul. ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', June 5, 1975. p. 60.</ref>}}\n\nThe band soon came to the attention of [[Andy Warhol]]. One of Warhol's first contributions was to integrate them into the [[Exploding Plastic Inevitable]]. Warhol's associates inspired many of Reed's songs as he fell into a thriving, multifaceted artistic scene.{{sfnp|Reed|1991|pp=22, 38, 42}}{{sfnp|Thompson|2009|p=18}} Reed rarely gave an interview without paying homage to Warhol as a mentor. Warhol pushed the band to take on a [[chanteuse]], the German former model and singer [[Nico]]. Despite his initial resistance, Reed wrote several songs for Nico to sing, and the two were briefly lovers.{{sfnp|Bockris|1994|pp=104, 106, 107}}\n\n''[[The Velvet Underground & Nico]]'' reached No. 171 on the charts.<ref name=rrhallbio /> Much later, ''Rolling Stone'' listed it as the 13th greatest album of all time; [[Brian Eno]] once stated that although few people bought the album, most of them were inspired to form their own bands.<ref>{{cite web |author=Jones, Chris |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/fq4h |archivedate= April 30, 2012 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120430223626/http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/fq4h/ |title=Review of The Velvet Underground - The Velvet Underground & Nico (Deluxe Edition) |publisher=BBC Music |year=2002 |accessdate=October 28, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[V\u00e1clav Havel]] credited the album, which he bought while visiting the US, with inspiring him to become president of [[Czechoslovakia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/lou-reed-and-vaclav-havel-vs-communism-2013-10|title=The True Story Of How Lou Reed Helped Overthrow Communism In Eastern Europe|date=October 27, 2013|work=Business Insider|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBy the time the band recorded ''[[White Light/White Heat]]'', Nico had quit and Warhol had been fired, both against Cale's wishes. Warhol's replacement as manager was [[Steve Sesnick]]. In September 1968, Cale left the band at Reed's behest.{{sfnp|Bockris|1994|p=160}} Morrison and Tucker were discomfited by Reed's tactics but continued with the band. Cale's replacement was [[Boston]]-based musician [[Doug Yule]], who played bass guitar, keyboards and who would soon share lead vocal duties in the band with Reed.{{sfnp|Bockris|1994|pp=164, 167}} The band now took on a more pop-oriented sound and acted more as a vehicle for Reed to develop his songwriting craft.{{sfnp|Bockris|1994|p=164, 166}} They released two studio albums with this line-up: 1969's ''[[The Velvet Underground (album)|The Velvet Underground]]'' and 1970's ''[[Loaded (The Velvet Underground album)|Loaded]]''. Reed left the Velvet Underground in August 1970.{{sfnp|Bockris|1994|p=177}} The band disintegrated after Morrison and Tucker departed in 1971.{{sfnp|Unterberger|2009|pp=307, 317}}\n\n===1970\u201375: Glam rock and commercial breakthrough===\nAfter leaving the Velvet Underground, Reed moved to his parents' home on [[Long Island]], and took a job at his father's tax accounting firm as a typist, by his own account earning $40 a week (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|40|1970}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}).<ref name=Unterberger2009>{{cite web|last=Unterberger|first=Richie|title=White Light / White Heat|url=http://www.well.com/conf/inkwell.vue/topics/354/Richie-Unterberger-White-Light-W-page03.html#post58|work=The WELL|publisher=The Well Group|accessdate=November 4, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121202055654/http://www.well.com/conf/inkwell.vue/topics/354/Richie-Unterberger-White-Light-W-page03.html#post58|archivedate=December 2, 2012|page=3|date=May 30, 2009}}</ref> In 1971, he signed a recording contract with [[RCA Records]] and recorded his first solo album at [[Morgan Studios]] in [[Willesden]], London with session musicians including [[Steve Howe (musician)|Steve Howe]] and [[Rick Wakeman]] from the band [[Yes (band)|Yes]]. The album, ''[[Lou Reed (album)|Lou Reed]]'', contained versions of unreleased Velvet Underground songs, some of which had originally been recorded for ''Loaded'' but shelved.{{refn|Some later appeared on the ''[[Peel Slowly and See]]'' box set.|group=nb}} This album was overlooked by most pop music critics and did not sell well, although music critic [[Stephen Holden]], in ''Rolling Stone'', called it an \"almost perfect album. ... which embodied the spirit of the Velvets.\" Holden went on to compare Reed's voice with those of [[Mick Jagger]] and [[Bob Dylan]] and to praise the poetic quality of his lyrics.<ref>Holden, Stephen (May 25, 1972). ''Rolling Stone''. p. 68</ref>\n\nReed's commercial breakthrough album, ''[[Transformer (Lou Reed album)|Transformer]]'', was released in November 1972. ''Transformer'' was co-produced by [[David Bowie]] and [[Mick Ronson]], and it introduced Reed to a wider audience, especially in the UK. The single \"[[Walk on the Wild Side (Lou Reed song)|Walk on the Wild Side]]\" was a salute to the misfits and hustlers who once surrounded Andy Warhol in the late '60s and appeared in his films. Each of the song's five verses describes a person who had been a fixture at [[The Factory]] during the mid-to-late 1960s: (1) [[Holly Woodlawn]], (2) [[Candy Darling]], (3) [[Joe Dallesandro|\"Little Joe\" Dallesandro]], (4) \"Sugar Plum Fairy\" [[Joe Campbell (actor)|Joe Campbell]] and (5) [[Jackie Curtis]]. The song's transgressive lyrics evaded radio censorship. Though the jazzy arrangement (courtesy of bassist [[Herbie Flowers]] and saxophonist [[Ronnie Ross]]) was musically atypical for Reed, it eventually became his signature song.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wiener|first1=John|title=Beatles Buy-Out|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/music/beatles-buy-out|website=The New Republic|date=May 11, 1987}}</ref> It came about as a result of a commission to compose a soundtrack to a theatrical adaptation of [[Nelson Algren]]'s novel of the same name; the play failed to materialize.{{sfnp|Reed|1991|p=42}} \"Walk on the Wild Side\" was Reed's only entry in the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] singles chart, at number 16.<ref name=\"Caulfield\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5770575/lou-reed-billboard-chart-history|title=Lou Reed's 'Perfect' Billboard Chart History|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=October 27, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nRonson's arrangements brought out new aspects of Reed's songs. \"[[Perfect Day (Lou Reed song)|Perfect Day]]\", for example, features delicate strings and soaring dynamics. It was rediscovered in the 1990s and allowed Reed to drop \"Walk on the Wild Side\" from his concerts.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/blurred-vision-at-the-beeb-1235724.html|last1=Walker|first1=Nick|date=October 13, 1997|title=Blurred vision at the Beeb|website=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nBowie and Reed fell out during a late-night meeting which led to Reed hitting Bowie. Bowie had told Reed that he would have to \"clean up his act\" if they were to work together again.{{sfnp|DeCurtis|2017|p=}}{{refn|The two reconciled years later, and Reed performed with Bowie at the latter's 50th birthday concert at [[Madison Square Garden]] in 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesound.co.nz/home/music/2018/01/david-bowie-s-50th-birthday-performance-with-lou-reed.html|title=David Bowie's 50th birthday performance with Lou Reed|accessdate=February 16, 2018}}</ref>|group=nb}} Reed hired a local New York bar-band, The Tots, to tour in support of ''Transformer'' and spent much of 1972 and early 1973 on the road with them. Though they improved over the months, Reed (with producer [[Bob Ezrin]]'s encouragement) decided to recruit a new backing band in anticipation of the upcoming ''[[Berlin (Lou Reed album)|Berlin]]'' album. He chose keyboardist [[Moogy Klingman]] to come up with a new five-member band on barely a week's notice.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.wolfgangsvault.com/lou-reed-and-moogy-klingman-band/concerts/kansas-city-memorial-hall-may-02-1973.html | work=Wolfgangs Vault | title=Concert Summary: May 2, 1973 | last=Bershaw | accessdate=March 2, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523090717/http://www.wolfgangsvault.com/lou-reed-and-moogy-klingman-band/concerts/kansas-city-memorial-hall-may-02-1973.html | archive-date=May 23, 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nReed married Bettye Kronstad in 1973. She later said he had been a violent drunk when on tour.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/01/fashion/who-was-the-real-lou-reed.html |first=Alex |last=Williams |date=November 1, 2015 |title=Who Was the Real Lou Reed? |work=The New York Times }}</ref> ''[[Berlin (Lou Reed album)|Berlin]]'' (July 1973) was a [[concept album]] about two [[addiction|junkies]] in love in the city. The songs variously concern [[domestic violence]] (\"Caroline Says I\", \"Caroline Says II\"), drug addiction (\"How Do You Think It Feels\"), adultery and prostitution (\"The Kids\"), and suicide (\"The Bed\"). Reed's late 1973 European tour, featuring lead guitarists [[Steve Hunter]] and [[Dick Wagner]], mixed his ''Berlin'' material with older numbers. Response to ''Berlin'' at the time of its release was negative, with ''Rolling Stone'' pronouncing it \"a disaster\".{{sfnp|Bockris|1994|p=221}} Reed found the poor reviews it received very frustrating.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/8e40a4de-4245-11e3-bb85-00144feabdc0|title=Lou Reed: rock 'n' roll animal|last=Morley|first=Paul|date=November 1, 2013|work=[[Financial Times]]|accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref> Since then the album has been critically reevaluated, and in 2003 ''Rolling Stone'' included it in their list of the 500 greatest albums of all time.<ref>{{cite web|title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time: 344. Lou Reed, Berlin|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-20120531/lou-reed-berlin-20120524|website=Rolling Stone}}</ref> ''Berlin'' made number 7 in the UK charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/14017/lou-reed/|title=Lou Reed full Official Chart History|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the commercial disappointment of ''Berlin'', Reed befriended [[Steve Katz (musician)|Steve Katz]] of [[Blood, Sweat & Tears]] (who was the brother of his then-manager Dennis Katz), who suggested Reed put together a \"great live band\" and release a live album of Velvet Underground songs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bedfordandbowery.com/2013/10/he-treads-kind-of-softly-musicians-remember-working-with-lou-reed/|title='He Treads Kind of Softly': Two Musicians Remember Working With Lou Reed|date=October 28, 2013|website=Bedfordandbowery.com}}</ref> Katz would come on board as producer, and the album ''[[Rock 'n' Roll Animal]]'' (February 1974) contained live performances of the Velvet Underground songs \"Sweet Jane\", \"Heroin\", \"White Light/White Heat\", and \"Rock and Roll\". Wagner's live arrangements, and Hunter's intro to \"[[Sweet Jane]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vintageguitar.com/2795/dick-wagner-and-steve-hunter/|title=Dick Wagner and Steve Hunter|first=Greg|last=Pedersen|date=May 15, 2001|website=Vintageguitar.com}}</ref> which opened the album, gave Reed's songs the live rock sound he was looking for, and the album peaked at #45 on the Top 200 [[Billboard Chart]] for 28 weeks and soon became Reed's biggest selling album.{{refn|''Rock 'n' Roll Animal'' and its follow-up ''[[Lou Reed Live]]'' (1975) were both recorded at the [[Palladium (New York City)|Academy of Music]], New York City, on December 21, 1973.|group=nb}} It went gold in 1978, with 500,000 certified sales.<ref name=\"riaa\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=lou+reed#search_section|title=RIAA|website=Riaa.com|accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''[[Sally Can't Dance]]'' which was released later that year (in August 1974), became Reed's highest-charting album in the United States, peaking at number 10 during a 14-week stay on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] album chart in October 1974.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/lou-reed/chart-history/billboard-200/song/830856 |title=Sally Can't Dance Chart History |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=February 9, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, an audio tape of publicly unknown music by Reed, based on Warhols' 1975 book, \u201c''[[The Philosophy of Andy Warhol|The Philosophy of Andy Warhol: From A to B and Back Again]]''\u201d, was reported to have been discovered in an archive at the [[Andy Warhol Museum]] in Pittsburgh.<ref name=\"NYT-20191030\">{{cite news |last=Sisaro |first=Ben |title=A Long-Lost Lou Reed Tape With a Surprise: Andy Warhol Lyrics - The cassette, discovered at the Andy Warhol Museum, finds the Velvet Underground musician performing snippets from his mentor's 1975 book. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/30/arts/music/lou-reed-andy-warhol-tape.html |date=October 30, 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=October 30, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===1975\u201379: Addiction and creative work===\n[[File:Chuck Hammer and Lou Reed.jpg|thumb|240px| Lou Reed on stage with guitarist Chuck Hammer, June 1979, The Bottom Line, NYC]] Throughout the 1970s, Reed was a heavy user of [[methamphetamine]] and [[alcohol (drug)|alcohol]].<ref name=\"nyt\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopmusic/10092969/Lou-Reed-saved-by-liver-transplant-after-years-of-drugs-and-alcohol-take-their-toll.html|title=Lou Reed saved by liver transplant after years of drugs and alcohol take their toll - Telegraph|last=Sawer|first=Patrick|date=June 1, 2011|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''[[Metal Machine Music]]'' (1975) was an hour of modulated feedback and guitar effects. Described by Rolling Stone as the \"tubular groaning of a galactic refrigerator\",<ref name=\"Dayal2013\">{{cite news |author1=Geeta Dayal |title=Lou Reed Was a Rock God and the Epitome of Cool. He Was Also a Big Nerd. |url=https://slate.com/culture/2013/10/lou-reeds-metal-machine-music-the-artist-was-a-rock-god-he-was-also-a-big-nerd.html |accessdate=November 16, 2019 |work=Slate Magazine |date=October 28, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190311073715/https://slate.com/culture/2013/10/lou-reeds-metal-machine-music-the-artist-was-a-rock-god-he-was-also-a-big-nerd.html |archivedate=April 14, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> many critics interpreted it as a gesture of contempt, an attempt to break his contract with RCA or to alienate his less sophisticated fans. Reed claimed that the album was a genuine artistic effort, even suggesting that quotations of classical music could be found buried in the feedback,<ref name=\"Little2018\">{{cite news |author1=Michael H. Little |title=Graded on a Curve: Lou Reed, Metal Machine Music |url=http://www.thevinyldistrict.com/storefront/2018/03/graded-on-a-curve-lou-reed-metal-machine-music/ |accessdate=November 16, 2019 |work=The Vinyl District |date=March 9, 2018}}</ref> but he also said, \"Well, anyone who gets to side four is dumber than I am.\"<ref name=\"BogdanovWoodstra2002\">{{cite book|editor1=Vladimir Bogdanov |editor2=Chris Woodstra |editor3=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|title=All Music Guide to Rock: The Definitive Guide to Rock, Pop, and Soul|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1-pH4i3jXvAC&pg=PA927|year=2002|publisher=Backbeat Books|isbn=978-0-87930-653-3|page=927}}</ref><ref name=\"McPadden2012\">{{cite book|author=Mike McPadden|title=If You Like Metallica...: Here Are Over 200 Bands, CDs, Movies and Other Oddities That You Will Love|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RtGGDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT61|date=May 1, 2012|publisher=Backbeat|isbn=978-1-4768-1358-5|page=61}}</ref> Lester Bangs declared it \"genius\", though also psychologically disturbing. The album, now regarded as a visionary textural guitar masterpiece by some music critics,<ref name=\"McGonigal2015\">{{cite news |author1=Mike McGonigal |title=Coming to Cranbrook Nov. 21: '3-D installation' of Lou Reed's 1975 feedback masterpiece 'Metal Machine Music' |url=https://www.metrotimes.com/city-slang/archives/2015/09/04/coming-to-cranbrook-nov-21-3-d-installation-of-lou-reeds-1975-feedback-masterpiece-metal-machine-music |accessdate=November 16, 2019 |work=Detroit Metro Times |date=September 4, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116160623/https://www.metrotimes.com/city-slang/archives/2015/09/04/coming-to-cranbrook-nov-21-3-d-installation-of-lou-reeds-1975-feedback-masterpiece-metal-machine-music |archivedate=November 16, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> was reportedly returned to stores by the thousands and was withdrawn after a few weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://92yondemand.org/lou-reed-with-anthony-decurtis|title=Lou Reed with Anthony DeCurtis - 92Y On Demand|date=September 18, 2006|accessdate=February 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/wzwx/|title=Review of Lou Reed - Metal Machine Music: Re-mastered|work=[[BBC Online]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box|width=30em|align=left|quote=Lou Reed doesn't just write about squalid characters, he allows them to leer and breathe in their own voices, and he colors familiar landscapes through their own eyes. In the process, Reed has created a body of music that comes as close to disclosing the parameters of human loss and recovery as we're likely to find. That qualifies him, in my opinion, as one of the few real heroes rock & roll has raised.|source=\u2014[[Mikal Gilmore]], ''Rolling Stone'', (1979)<ref name=Gilmore/>}}\n\n1975's ''[[Coney Island Baby]]'' was dedicated to Reed's then-partner Rachel, a [[transgender]] woman Reed dated and lived with for three years.<ref>DeCurtis, Anthony. Lou Reed: A Life. New York: Little Brown. p. 180. {{ISBN|978-0-316-37654-9}}.</ref> Rachel also appears in the photos on the cover of Reed's 1977 \"best of\" album, ''[[Walk on the Wild Side: The Best of Lou Reed]]''. ''[[Rock and Roll Heart]]'' was his 1976 debut for his new record label [[Arista Records|Arista]], and ''[[Street Hassle]]'' (1978) was released in the midst of the punk scene he had helped to inspire. Reed took on a watchful, competitive and sometimes dismissive attitude towards punk. Aware that he had inspired them, he regularly attended shows at [[CBGB]] to track the artistic and commercial development of numerous punk bands, and a cover illustration and interview of Reed appeared in the first issue of ''[[Punk (magazine)|Punk]]'' by [[Legs McNeil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://13thdimension.com/punk-magazine-began-with-lou-reed-comic/|title=PUNK Magazine Began With Lou Reed Comic|date=October 28, 2013|website=13thdimension.com}}</ref>\n\nReed released his third live album, ''[[Live: Take No Prisoners]]'', in 1978; some critics thought it was his \"bravest work yet\", while others considered it his \"silliest\".<ref name=Gilmore>{{cite magazine |last=Gilmore |first=Mikal |title=Lou Reed's heart of darkness |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=March 22, 1979 |pages=8, 12|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/lou-reeds-heart-of-darkness-19790322}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' described it as \"one of the funniest live albums ever recorded\" and compared Reed's monologues with those of [[Lenny Bruce]].<ref name=Gilmore/> Reed felt it was his best album to date.<ref name=Gilmore/> ''[[The Bells (Lou Reed album)|The Bells]]'' (1979) featured jazz trumpeter [[Don Cherry (trumpeter)|Don Cherry]]. During 1979 Reed toured extensively in Europe and throughout the United States performing a wide range of songs including a suite of core songs from his Berlin album and the title track from the Bells with [[Chuck Hammer]] on guitar-synth. Around this time Reed also appeared as a record producer in [[Paul Simon]]'s film ''[[One-Trick Pony (film)|One-Trick Pony]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=One-Trick Pony (1980)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0081280/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|website=IMDb.com}}</ref> From around 1979 Reed began to wean himself off drugs.<ref name=\"nyt\"/>\n\n===1980\u201389: Marriage and mid-period===\n[[File:Lou Reed-Conspiracy of Hope-by Steven Toole.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.85|Reed performing live during a benefit concert for [[A Conspiracy of Hope]] at [[Giants Stadium]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]], 1986]]\nReed married British designer Sylvia Morales in 1980.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/bettye-kronstad-speaks-for-the-first-time-about-her-marriage-to-lou-reed-fame-is-a-fiend-it-turns-10166659.html|title=Bettye Kronstad has spoken about her marriage to Lou Reed for the first time|work=[[The Independent]]|date=April 10, 2015|accessdate=November 8, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"timesonline\">{{cite news |first=Robert |last=Sandall |title=Lou Reed: Walk on the mild side |url= http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/article860207.ece |work=[[The Sunday Times]]|date=February 9, 2003 |accessdate=December 20, 2008 |location=London}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Morales inspired Reed to write several songs, particularly \"Think It Over\" from 1980's ''[[Growing Up in Public (Lou Reed album)|Growing Up in Public]]''{{sfnp|Reed|1991|p=71}} and \"Heavenly Arms\" from 1982's ''[[The Blue Mask]]''.<ref name=carson>{{cite journal|last1=Carson|first1=Tom|title=The Blue Mask|journal=Rolling Stone|date=April 15, 1982|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/the-blue-mask-19820415}}</ref> After ''[[Legendary Hearts]]'' (1983) and ''[[New Sensations]]'' (1984), Reed was sufficiently reestablished as a public figure to become spokesman for [[Honda]] motorcycles.{{sfnp|Bockris|1994|p=351}} In the early 1980s, Reed worked with guitarists including [[Chuck Hammer]] on ''Growing Up in Public'', and [[Robert Quine]] on ''The Blue Mask'' and ''Legendary Hearts''.\n\nReed's 1984 album ''[[New Sensations]]'' marked the first time that Reed had charted within the US Top 100 since 1978's ''[[Street Hassle]]'', and the first time that Reed had charted in the UK altogether since 1976's ''[[Coney Island Baby]]''. Although its [[lead single]] \"[[I Love You, Suzanne]]\" only charted at No. 78 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] it did receive light rotation on [[MTV]]. Two more singles were released from the album: \"[[My Red Joystick]]\" and the Dutch-only release \"[[High in the City]]\" but they both failed to chart.\n\nIn 1998, ''[[The New York Times]]'' observed that in the 1970s, Reed had a distinctive persona: \"Back then he was publicly gay, pretended to shoot heroin onstage, and cultivated a 'Dachau panda' look, with cropped peroxide hair and black circles painted under his eyes.\"<ref name=\"Lewis\">{{Cite news|last=Lewis|first=Randy|date= October 28, 2013|title= Lou Reed, 1942 - 2013 Influential pioneer of punk, art rock|work= [[Los Angeles Times]] |page=1 |url=https://www.latimes.com/obituaries/la-me-lou-reed-20131028,0,347074.story?page=2 |accessdate=December 7, 2013}}</ref> The newspaper wrote that in 1980, \"Reed renounced druggy theatrics, even swore off intoxicants themselves, and became openly heterosexual, openly married.\"<ref name=\"Lewis\"/>\n\nOn September 22, 1985, Reed performed at the first [[Farm Aid]] concert in [[Champaign, Illinois]]. He performed \"Doin' the Things That We Want To\", \"I Love You, Suzanne\", \"New Sensations\" and \"Walk on the Wild Side\" as his solo set, later playing bass for [[Roy Orbison]] during his set. In June 1986, Reed released ''[[Mistrial (album)|Mistrial]]'' (co-produced with Fernando Saunders). To support the album, he released two music videos: \"[[No Money Down]]\" and \"[[The Original Wrapper]]\". In the same year, he joined [[Amnesty International]]'s [[A Conspiracy of Hope]] short tour and was outspoken about New York City's political issues and personalities.\n\nThe 1989 album ''[[New York (album)|New York]]'', which commented on crime, [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]], civil rights activist [[Jesse Jackson]], then-President of Austria [[Kurt Waldheim]] and [[Pope John Paul II]], became his second gold-certified work when it passed 500,000 sales in 1997.<ref name=\"riaa\"/> Reed was nominated for a Grammy Award for best male rock vocal performance for the album.<ref name=\"Caulfield\"/>\n\n===1990\u201399: Velvet Underground reunion and various projects===\nReed met John Cale for the first time in decades at Warhol's funeral in 1987. They worked together on the album ''[[Songs for Drella]]'' (April 1990), a [[song cycle]] about Warhol.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2013/10/28/lou-reed-dead-john-cale-statement/|title=Lou Reed remembered by VU bandmate John Cale|last=Anderson|first=Kyle|date=October 28, 2013|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> On the album, Reed sings of his love for his late friend, and criticizes both the doctors who were unable to save Warhol's life and Warhol's would-be assassin, [[Valerie Solanas]]. In 1990, the first Velvet Underground lineup reformed for a [[Fondation Cartier pour l'Art Contemporain|Fondation Cartier]] benefit show in France.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/see-velvet-underground-play-heroin-at-1990-reunion-w446616|title=See Velvet Underground Play 'Heroin' at 1990 Reunion - Rolling Stone|last=Greene|first=Andy|date=October 25, 2016|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In June and July 1993, the Velvet Underground again reunited and toured Europe, including an appearance at the [[Glastonbury Festival]]; plans for a North American tour were cancelled following a dispute between Reed and Cale.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/06/05/arts/older-but-still-hip-the-velvet-underground-rocks-again.html|title=Older but Still Hip, the Velvet Underground Rocks Again|last=Rockwell|first=John|date=June 5, 1993|accessdate=February 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://dangerousminds.net/comments/the_velvet_underground_live_paris_1993|title=Their Last Tour: The Velvet Underground - Live in Paris, 1993|work=Dangerous Minds|accessdate=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nReed had released his sixteenth solo album, ''[[Magic and Loss]]'', in January 1992. The album is preoccupied with mortality, inspired by the death of two close friends from [[cancer]]. In 1994, he appeared in ''[[A Celebration: The Music of Pete Townshend and The Who]]''. In the same year, he and Morales were divorced.{{sfnp|Brown|2013|p=98}} In 1995, Reed made a cameo appearance in the unreleased [[video game]] ''[[Penn & Teller's Smoke and Mirrors]]''. If the player selects the \"impossible\" difficulty setting, Reed appears shortly after the game begins as an unbeatable [[boss (video gaming)|boss]] who murders the player with his laser beam eyes. Reed then pops up on the screen and says to the player, \"This is the impossible level, boys. Impossible doesn't mean very difficult, very difficult is winning the [[Nobel Prize]], impossible is eating the sun.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MWlbzdaJJ|title=YouTube|website=Youtube.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, the Velvet Underground were inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]. At the ceremony, Reed, Cale and Tucker performed a song titled \"Last Night I Said Goodbye to My Friend\", dedicated to Sterling Morrison, who had died the previous August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/26-rock-and-roll-hall-of-fame-reunions-that-actually-happened-20140407/7-the-velvet-underground-1996-0317341|title=7. The Velvet Underground (1996)|last=Greene|first=Andy|date=April 7, 2014|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=February 15, 2018}}</ref> In February 1996 Reed released ''[[Set the Twilight Reeling]]'', and later that year, Reed contributed songs and music to ''Time Rocker'', a theatrical interpretation of [[H. G. Wells]]' ''[[The Time Machine]]'' by experimental director [[Robert Wilson (director)|Robert Wilson]]. The piece premiered in the [[Thalia Theater (Hamburg)|Thalia Theater, Hamburg]], and was later also shown at the [[Brooklyn Academy of Music]] in New York.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9404E5D81738F937A25752C1A961958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=1 |work=The New York Times |title=Next Wave Festival: Echoes of H. G. Wells, Rhythms of Lou Reed |first=Jon |last=Pareles |date=November 14, 1997}}</ref>\n\nFrom the late 1990s, Reed was romantically linked to musician, [[multimedia]] and performance artist [[Laurie Anderson]], and the two worked together on several recordings. They married on April 12, 2008.<ref>{{cite news |last=Aleksander |first=Irina |url= http://observer.com/2008/04/morning-memo-lou-reed-and-laurie-anderson-make-it-legal-suri-cruises-100000-birthday/ |title=Morning Memo: Lou Reed and Laurie Anderson Make it Legal |work=The New York Observer |date=April 23, 2008 |accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2000\u201312: Rock and ambient experimentation===\n[[File:Lou reed.jpg|thumb|left|Reed performing live at Schnitzer Concert Hall in [[Portland, Oregon]], 2004]]\nIn February 2000, Reed worked with Robert Wilson at the Thalia Theater again, on POEtry, another production inspired by the works of a 19th-century writer, this time [[Edgar Allan Poe]]. In April 2000, Reed released ''[[Ecstasy (Lou Reed album)|Ecstasy]]''. In January 2003, Reed released a two-CD set, ''[[The Raven (Lou Reed album)|The Raven]]'', based on POEtry. The album consists of songs written by Reed and spoken-word performances of reworked and rewritten texts of Edgar Allan Poe by the actors, set to electronic music composed by Reed. It features David Bowie and [[Ornette Coleman]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/news/1459300/20021226/reed_lou.jhtml |website=Vh1.com |title=Lou Reed's Obsession With Edgar Allan Poe Spawns ''The Raven'' |date=December 27, 2002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605030102/http://www.vh1.com/artists/news/1459300/20021226/reed_lou.jhtml |archivedate=June 5, 2011 }}</ref> A single disc CD version of the album, focusing on the music, was also released.{{refn|In 2011, Reed developed the CD into an illustrated book, with art by [[Lorenzo Mattotti]], published by [[Fantagraphics Books|Fantagraphics]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/ravenous-reed?mobify=0#slide_ss_0=1|title=Ravenous Reed|newspaper=[[The New Yorker]]|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref>|group=nb}}\n\nIn May 2000, Reed performed before Pope John Paul II at the Great Jubilee Concert in [[Rome]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1499424/pope-john-paul-ii-friend-of-bono-fan-of-pop-culture/|title=Pope John Paul II: Friend Of Bono, Fan Of Pop Culture|work=[[MTV]]|accessdate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In 2001, Reed made a cameo appearance in the [[Prozac Nation (film)|movie adaptation]] of ''[[Prozac Nation]]''. On October 6, 2001, ''the New York Times'' published a Reed poem called \"Laurie Sadly Listening\" in which he reflects on the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bushwatch.com/auden.htm |title=War Poems |website=Bushwatch.com |accessdate=March 26, 2010}}</ref> [[List of premature obituaries|Incorrect reports]] of Reed's death were broadcast by numerous US radio stations in 2001, caused by a hoax email (purporting to be from [[Reuters]]) which said he had died of a [[drug overdose]].<ref>[http://www.museumofhoaxes.com/day/05_09_2001.html \"Death of Lou Reed\"], Museum of Hoaxes web site</ref> In April 2003, Reed began a world tour featuring the cellist [[Jane Scarpantoni]] and singer [[Anohni]].\n\nIn 2003, Reed released a book of photographs, ''Emotions in Action''. This comprised an [[A4 paper size|A4]]-sized book called ''Emotions'' and a smaller one called ''Actions'' laid into its hard cover. In January 2006, he released a second book of photographs, ''Lou Reed's New York''.<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.artbook.com/3865211526.html |title=Lou Reed's New York |via=Artbook.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090908102734/http://www.artbook.com/3865211526.html |archivedate=September 8, 2009}}</ref> A third volume, ''Romanticism'', was released in 2009.{{sfnp|DeCurtis|2017|p=}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/features/lou-reed-photographer-1817676.html|title=Lou Reed: Photographer|date=November 10, 2009|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lou Reed Malaga, Spain 1.jpg|thumb|upright|Reed performing in [[M\u00e1laga]], Spain, 2008]]\nIn 2004, a Groovefinder [[remix]] of his song \"[[Satellite of Love]]\", called \"Satellite of Love '04\", was released. It reached No. 10 in the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/14017/lou-reed/|title=Lou Reed full Official Chart History|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=February 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2006, Reed appeared at Hal Willner's [[Leonard Cohen]] tribute show \"Came So Far for Beauty\" in [[Dublin]], along with Laurie Anderson, [[Nick Cave]], Anohni, [[Jarvis Cocker]], and [[Beth Orton]]. He played a [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] version of Cohen's \"The Stranger Song\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leonardcohenfiles.com/dublin.html|title=\"Came so far for Beauty\" in Dublin|website=Leonardcohenfiles.com|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn December that year, Reed played a series of shows at [[St. Ann's Warehouse]], Brooklyn, based on ''Berlin''. Reed played with guitarist [[Steve Hunter]], who played on the original album and ''Rock 'n' Roll Animal'', and was joined by singers Anohni and [[Sharon Jones]]. The show was produced by [[Bob Ezrin]], who also produced the original album, and Hal Willner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/shows/spectacle-elvis-costello-with/watch/lou-reed-and-julian-schnabel-1243213/|title=Watch Spectacle: Elvis Costello With ... - Lou Reed and Julian Schnabel Online |website=TV.com}}</ref> The show played at the [[Sydney Festival]] in January 2007 and in Europe during June and July 2007. The album version of the concert, entitled ''[[Berlin: Live at St. Ann's Warehouse]]'', and a live film recording of these concerts were both released in 2008. In April 2007, he released ''[[Hudson River Wind Meditations]]'', an album of [[ambient music|ambient]] [[meditation]]al music. It was released on the [[Sounds True]] record label. In June 2007, he performed at the Traffic Festival 2007 in [[Turin]], Italy, a five-day free event organized by the city. In the same month \"[[Pale Blue Eyes]]\" was included in the soundtrack of the French-language film, ''[[The Diving Bell and the Butterfly (film)|The Diving Bell and the Butterfly]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0401383/soundtrack?ref_=tt_ql_trv_7|title=The Diving Bell and the Butterfly (2007) - Soundtracks|website=IMDb.com}}</ref> In August 2007, Reed recorded \"[[Tranquilize]]\" with [[the Killers]] in New York City, a duet with [[Brandon Flowers]] for the B-side/rarities album ''[[Sawdust (album)|Sawdust]]''.\n\n[[File:Lou Reed at the Hop Farm Music Festival.jpg|thumb|170px|left|upright|Reed performing at the<br />[[Hop Farm Festival]] in [[Paddock Wood]], Kent, 2011]]\n\nOn October 2 and 3, 2008, he introduced his new group, which was later named [[Metal Machine Trio]], at the [[REDCAT|Walt Disney Concert Hall Complex]] in Los Angeles. The trio featured Ulrich Krieger (saxophone) and [[Sarth Calhoun]] (electronics), and played improvised instrumental music inspired by ''Metal Machine Music''. Recordings of the concerts were released under the title ''[[The Creation of the Universe]]''. The trio played at New York's [[Gramercy Theatre]] in April 2009, and appeared as part of Reed's band at the 2009 [[Lollapalooza]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2009/04/24/lou-reed-brings-controversial-metal-machine-music-to-new-york/ |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090427042824/http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2009/04/24/lou-reed-brings-controversial-metal-machine-music-to-new-york/ |archivedate= April 27, 2009 |title=Rolling Stone review of the Metal Machine Trio concert at the Gramercy in New York |work=Rolling Stone |date=April 24, 2009}}</ref>\n\nReed provided the voice of Maltazard, the villain in the 2009 [[Luc Besson]] animated/live-action feature film ''[[Arthur and the Revenge of Maltazard]]'' and appeared as himself in [[Wim Wenders]]' 2008 film ''[[Palermo Shooting]]''.\n\nReed played \"Sweet Jane\" and \"White Light/White Heat\" with [[Metallica]] at Madison Square Garden during the twenty-fifth anniversary celebration of the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame on October 30, 2009. In 2010 Lou Reed featured on the song \"Some Kind of Nature\" with Gorillaz, from their album Plastic Beach.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://2009.lollapalooza.com/band/lou-reed |title=Lou Reed at Lollapalooza 2009 |publisher=Lollapalooza 2009 |accessdate=March 26, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328163729/http://2009.lollapalooza.com/band/lou-reed |archivedate=March 28, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=129623 |title=Metallica with Ozzy, Lou Reed, Ray Davies at Rock Hall Concert: More Video Footage Available |publisher= Roadrunner Records |accessdate=March 26, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104034032/http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/metallica-with-ozzy-lou-reed-ray-davies-at-rock-hall-concert-more-video-footage-available/ |archivedate=November 4, 2013}}</ref> In October 2011, Metallica and Reed released the collaboration album [[Lulu (Lou Reed and Metallica album)|''Lulu'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metallica.com/news/20110615_news.asp |title=Secret Recording Project? |date=June 15, 2010 |website=Metallica.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110619190555/http://www.metallica.com/news/20110615_news.asp |archivedate=June 19, 2011 |accessdate=June 18, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It was based on the \"Lulu\" plays by the German playwright [[Frank Wedekind]] (1864\u20131918). The album received mixed and mainly negative reviews from music critics.<ref name=\"meta\">{{cite web| title = ''Lulu'' Reviews, Ratings, Credits, and More| work = [[Metacritic]]| publisher = [[CBS Interactive]]| url = http://www.metacritic.com/music/lulu |accessdate=January 28, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Sputnik\">{{cite web|url=http://sputnikmusic.com/review/46170/Lou-Reed-and-Metallica-Lulu/ |title=Lou Reed and Metallica - Lulu (staff review) |website=Sputnikmusic |date=October 21, 2011 |accessdate=October 25, 2011}}</ref> Reed joked that he had no fans left.<ref name=\"usatoday-genrebender\">{{cite news |last=Gundersen |first=Edna |title=Metallica, Lou Reed go on a genre bender with 'Lulu' |work=[[USA Today]] |publisher=[[Gannett Company]] |date=November 1, 2011 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/story/2011-11-25/lou-reed-metallica/51021572/1 |accessdate=November 4, 2011}}</ref> The album debuted at number 36 on the ''Billboard'' 200 with first-week sales of 13,000 copies.<ref name=\"Billboard200\">{{cite web|last=Greene|first=Andy|title=On The Charts: Justin Bieber Annihilates Loutallica|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/on-the-charts-justin-bieber-annihilates-loutallica-20111109|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=November 10, 2011|date=November 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Reed collaborated with [[indie rock]] band [[Metric (band)|Metric]] on \"The Wanderlust\", the tenth track on their fifth studio album '' [[Synthetica]]''. This was to be the last original composition he worked on.<ref>{{cite news|title=Metric On Recording Lou Reed Duet 'The Wanderlust'|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2013/10/28/metric-lou-reed-wanderlust_n_4170594.html|accessdate=December 12, 2013|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=October 28, 2013|author=Joshua Ostroff}}</ref>\n\n==Death, legacy, and honors==\nReed had suffered from [[hepatitis]] and [[Diabetes mellitus|diabetes]] for several years. He practiced [[tai chi]] during the last part of his life.<ref name=\"nyt\"/><ref name=\"andersonrs\"/> He was treated with [[interferon]] but developed [[liver cancer]].<ref name=\"andersonrs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/laurie-andersons-farewell-to-lou-reed-a-rolling-stone-exclusive-20131106|title=Laurie Anderson, \"For 21 years we tangled our minds and hearts together\"|date=November 6, 2013|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref> In May 2013, he underwent a [[Liver transplantation|liver transplant]] at the [[Cleveland Clinic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/lou-reed-recovering-from-liver-transplant-20130601|title=Lou Reed Recovering From Liver Transplant|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref><ref>Feran, Tom (June 11, 2013).[http://www.cleveland.com/metro/index.ssf/2013/06/cleveland_clinic_confirms_rock.html \"Cleveland Clinic confirms rock legend Lou Reed underwent liver transplant at hospital\"]. ''[[The Plain Dealer]]'' (Cleveland). Retrieved October 31, 2013.</ref> Afterwards, on his website, he wrote of feeling \"bigger and stronger\" than ever, but on October 27, 2013, he died from liver disease<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.verbicidemagazine.com/2013/10/29/lou-reed-cause-of-death-liver-disease-transplant/|title=Lou Reed's Cause of Death Confirmed|work=Verbicide Magazine|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref> at his home in [[East Hampton (town), New York|East Hampton]], New York, at the age of 71. He was cremated and the ashes were given to his family.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/28/arts/music/lou-reed-dies-at-71.html|title=Outsider Whose Dark, Lyrical Vision Helped Shape Rock 'n' Roll |work=The New York Times |date=October 27, 2013 |accessdate=October 28, 2013 |author=Ratliff, Ben}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/lou-reed-velvet-underground-leader-and-rock-pioneer-dead-at-71-20131027 |title=Lou Reed, Velvet Underground Leader and Rock Pioneer, Dead at 71 |work=Rolling Stone |date= October 27, 2013 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHis widow [[Laurie Anderson]] said his last days were peaceful, and described him as a \"prince and a fighter\".<ref name=\"andersonrs\"/> [[David Byrne]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/david-byrne-remembers-the-brave-lou-reed-20131028|title=David Byrne Remembers the 'Brave' Lou Reed|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref> [[Patti Smith]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/patti-smith-lou-reed-was-a-very-special-poet-20131028|title=Patti Smith: 'Lou Reed Was a Very Special Poet|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref> [[David Bowie]], [[Morrissey]], [[Iggy Pop]], [[Courtney Love]], [[Lenny Kravitz]] and many others also paid tribute to Reed.<ref name=\"BBC-Bowie\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-24703353|title=David Bowie leads tributes to 'master' Lou Reed|work=BBC News|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/just-wild-about-lou-tributes-pour-in-for-rock-pioneer-reed-8909458.html|work=The Independent|title=Just wild about Lou: Tributes pour in for rock pioneer Lou Reed|date=October 28, 2013|accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://pitchfork.com/news/52786-david-bowie-morrissey-john-cale-release-statements-on-lou-reeds-death/ | title=David Bowie, Morrissey, John Cale Release Statements on Lou Reed's Death | work=[[Pitchfork Media]] | date=October 28, 2013 | accessdate=October 29, 2013 |author=Battan, Carrie}}</ref> Former Velvet Underground members Moe Tucker<ref>{{cite news |author1=Almasy, Steve |author2=Smith, Matt |url= http://www.cnn.com/2013/10/27/showbiz/lou-reed-obit/index.html |title=Rock legend Lou Reed dies at 71 |publisher=CNN |date= October 28, 2013 |accessdate=October 28, 2013}}</ref> and John Cale made statements on Reed's death,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/earshot/lou-reed-remembered-by-john-cale-651146 |title=John Cale Remembers Friend Lou Reed: 'We Have the Best of Our Fury Laid Out on Vinyl' |date=October 27, 2013 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=October 28, 2013}}</ref> and notables from far outside the music industry paid their respects such as [[Gianfranco Ravasi|Cardinal Gianfranco Ravasi]].<ref name=tributes>Runcie, Charlotte (October 28, 2013). [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/10408554/Vatican-leads-tributes-to-Lou-Reed.html \"Vatican leads tributes to Lou Reed\"], ''The Daily Telegraph'' (London).</ref>\n\nOn October 27, 2013, the day of Reed's death, [[Pearl Jam]] dedicated their song \"[[Man of the Hour]]\" to him at their show in [[Baltimore]] and then played \"[[I'm Waiting for the Man]]\".<ref name=\"Baltimore\">Case, Wesley (October 28, 2013).[http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/music/midnight-sun-blog/bal-after-23-years-pearl-jam-finally-comes-to-baltimore-20131028,0,7370922.story \"After 23 Years Pearl Jam Finally Comes to Baltimore\"]. ''The Sun'' (Baltimore). Retrieved October 28, 2013</ref> On the day of his death, the Killers dedicated their rendition of \"Pale Blue Eyes\" to Reed at the Life Is Beautiful festival in [[Las Vegas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/the-killers/73527 |title=The Killers cover Lou Reed's 'Pale Blue Eyes' at Las Vegas gig \u2013 watch |work=NME |date=October 30, 2013 |accessdate=December 10, 2013}}</ref> [[My Morning Jacket]] performed a cover of \"Oh! Sweet Nuthin'\" in California<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hogan |first1=Marc |title=See Pearl Jam, My Morning Jacket Pay Musical Tribute to Lou Reed |url=https://www.spin.com/2013/10/lou-reed-pearl-jam-my-morning-jacket-live-covers/ |accessdate=August 19, 2018 |work=Spin |date=October 28, 2013}}</ref> while [[Arctic Monkeys]] performed \"Walk on the Wild Side\" in Liverpool.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ayers |first1=Mike |title=Arctic Monkeys Honor Lou Reed |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/arctic-monkeys-cover-lou-reeds-walk-on-the-wild-side-67816/ |accessdate=August 19, 2018 |work=Rolling Stone |date=October 29, 2013}}</ref> That same night, [[Phish]] opened their show in Hartford, CT with the Velvet Underground's \"[[Rock & Roll (The Velvet Underground song)|Rock & Roll]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://phish.in/2013-10-27|title=phish.in'|website=phish.in|access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> On November 14, 2013, a three-hour public memorial was held near [[Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts|Lincoln Center]]'s [[Paul Milstein]] Pool and Terrace. Billed as \"New York: Lou Reed at Lincoln Center\", the ceremony featured favorite Reed recordings selected by family and friends.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chiu|first=David|title=Lou Reed's Memorial Lets the Music Speak for Itself|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/lou-reeds-memorial-lets-the-music-speak-for-itself-20131114|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=November 14, 2013|date=March 4, 2014}}</ref> On March 14, 2014, [[Richard Barone]] and [[Alejandro Escovedo]] produced and hosted the first full-scale tribute to Lou Reed at the [[SXSW]] Music Festival in Austin, Texas, with over twenty international acts performing Reed's music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5930169/lou-reed-tribute-concert-sxsw-lineup-spandau-ballet-sean-lennon|title=Inside the Lou Reed Tribute at SXSW: 20-Plus Acts, All-Star House Band to Create 'Austin Meets New York Street Vibe'|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nReed's estate was valued at $30 million, $20 million of which accrued after his death. He left everything to his wife and his sister.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/jul/01/lou-reed-leaves-30m-fortune|title=Lou Reed leaves $30m fortune|date=July 1, 2014|work=[[TheGuardian.com]]|accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nReed's induction into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] as a solo artist was announced on December 16, 2014.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2014/12/16/2015-rock-hall-of-fame-inductees/20310347/ \"Green Day, Lou Reed among Rock Hall inductees\"], ''[[USA Today]]''. December 16, 2014. Retrieved December 18, 2014</ref> He was inducted by Patti Smith at a ceremony in Cleveland on April 18, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Read Patti Smith's Poignant Lou Reed Rock Hall Induction|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/read-patti-smiths-poignant-lou-reed-rock-hall-induction-20150419|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=April 19, 2015}}</ref> In 2017, ''Lou Reed: A Life'' was published by the ''Rolling Stone'' critic [[Anthony DeCurtis]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/oct/01/my-brilliant-troubled-friend-lou-reed-a-life-anthony-decurtis-berlin|title=My brilliant and troubled friend Lou Reed|date=October 1, 2017|work=[[TheGuardian.com]]|accessdate=February 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAsteroid [[270553 Loureed]], discovered by [[Maik Meyer]] at [[Palomar Observatory]] in 2002, was named in his honor.<ref name=\"MPC-object\" /> The official {{MoMP|270553|naming citation}} was published by the [[Minor Planet Center]] on June 2, 2015 ({{small|[[Minor Planet Circulars|M.P.C.]] 94391}}).<ref name=\"MPC-Circulars-Archive\" /> Spiders with furry bodies are known as [[velvet spider]]s and one which was recently discovered in Spain is named ''[[Loureedia]]'', because it has a velvet body and lives underground.<ref>{{cite web |title=Velvet spider named after Lou Reed found in Europe for the first time |url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/discover/news/2019/january/velvet-spider-named-after-lou-reed-found-in-europe-for-the-first.html |website=Natural History Museum |accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAn archive of his letters and other personal effects was donated to The New York Public Library for the Performing Arts, where it can be viewed by members of the public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nypl.org/loureed|title=Lou Reed Archive at The New York Public Library for the Performing Arts|website=The New York Public Library|access-date=April 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Equipment==\n\n===Guitars===\n* [[Fender Telecaster]]\n* [[Carl Thompson (luthier)|Carl Thompson]] six-string guitar\n* Steve Klein electric guitar\n* [[Epiphone]] Riviera electric guitar\n* [[Gretsch]] Country Gentleman\n* [[Gibson ES-335]]TD electric guitar\n* [[Steinberger]] Synapse Transcale ST-2FPA Custom\n* [[Fender Electric XII]] twelve-string\n* [[Gibson SG]] Standard electric guitar\n* Rick Kelly electric guitar (silver sparkle [[Telecaster]] style)\n\n===Amplifiers===\n* [[Jim Kelley Amplifiers]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vintageguitar.com/26365/jim-kelley-reverb-model/|title=Jim Kelley Reverb Model|first=Bob|last=Dragich|website=Vintageguitar.com|date=December 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guitarworld.com/magazine/lou-reed-talks-about-velvet-underground-songwriting-and-gear-1998-guitar-world-interview|title=Lou Reed Talks About the Velvet Underground, Songwriting and Gear in 1998 Guitar World Interview|author=Alan di Perna|website=Guitarworld.com}}</ref>\n* [[Fender Deluxe|Fender 'wide panel tweed' Deluxe Amp 5C3]]\n* [[Soldano Custom Amplification|Soldano]] SLO 100 100-Watt Tube guitar amplifier\n* [[Tone King]] Imperial 1x12 Combo guitar amplifier\n* [[Sears]] [[Silvertone (brand)|Silvertone]] 1484 Twin-Twelve\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Lou Reed discography}}\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n:: '''The Velvet Underground'''\n* ''[[The Velvet Underground & Nico]]'' (1967)\n* ''[[White Light/White Heat]]'' (1968)\n* ''[[The Velvet Underground (album)|The Velvet Underground]]'' (1969)\n* ''[[Loaded (The Velvet Underground album)|Loaded]]'' (1970)\n:: '''Solo'''\n* ''[[Lou Reed (album)|Lou Reed]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Transformer (Lou Reed album)|Transformer]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Berlin (Lou Reed album)|Berlin]]'' (1973)\n* ''[[Sally Can't Dance]]'' (1974)\n* ''[[Metal Machine Music]]'' (1975)\n* ''[[Coney Island Baby]]'' (1975)\n* ''[[Rock and Roll Heart]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[Street Hassle]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[The Bells (Lou Reed album)|The Bells]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Growing Up in Public (Lou Reed album)|Growing Up in Public]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[The Blue Mask]]'' (1982)\n* ''[[Legendary Hearts]]'' (1983)\n* ''[[New Sensations]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[Mistrial (album)|Mistrial]]'' (1986)\n{{col-break}}\n* ''[[New York (album)|New York]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Magic and Loss]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Set the Twilight Reeling]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Ecstasy (Lou Reed album)|Ecstasy]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[The Raven (Lou Reed album)|The Raven]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Hudson River Wind Meditations]]'' (2007)\n\n:: '''Collaborations'''\n* ''[[Songs for Drella]]'' (1990) <small>(with [[John Cale]])</small>\n* ''[[Lulu (Lou Reed and Metallica album)|Lulu]]'' (2011) <small>(with [[Metallica]])</small>\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"|Year\n! scope=\"col\"|Title\n! scope=\"col\"