{"title_page": "Panga (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|Hindi-language sports drama film}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Panga\n| image          = Panga film poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari]]\n| producer       = [[Fox Star Studios]]\n| writer         = Nikhil Mehrohtra<br/>\nAshwiny Iyer Tiwari\n| screenplay     = [[Nitesh Tiwari]]\n| starring       = [[Kangana Ranaut]]<br />[[Jassi Gill]]<br />[[Richa Chadda]]<br />[[Neena Gupta]]<br/>Yagya Bhasin\n| music          = '''Songs:'''<br />[[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]]<br />'''Score:'''<br />[[Sanchit Balhara]]<br />Ankit Balhara\n| cinematography = Jay I. Patel\n| editing        = Ballu Saluja\n| studio         = [[Fox Star Studios]]\n| distributor    = Fox Star Studios\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|1|24|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 131 minutes<ref>{{cite web | url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/panga-2020 | title=Panga (2020) | website=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         = {{INR}} 24 crore<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Panga-(India)#tab=summary|title=Panga|publisher=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n| gross          = {{Estimation}} {{INR}}56.29 crore[https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Panga-(India)#tab=summary Panga Global Collections]\n\n'''''Panga''''' ({{translation|To mess with}}) is a 2020 Indian Hindi-language [[sports drama]] film directed by [[Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari]] and produced by [[Fox Star Studios]]. The film features [[Kangana Ranaut]], [[Jassi Gill]], [[Richa Chadda]] and [[Neena Gupta]]. The story depicts the jovial life of a [[kabaddi]] player.<ref name=\"ht\" />\nFilming took place from November 2018 to July 2019 in [[Panaji]], [[Bhopal]], [[Delhi]] and [[Kolkata]].<ref name=\"india_west\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/bollywood/no-panga-with-kangana-ranaut-director-ashwini-iyer-tiwari-on/article_d860b874-e434-11e8-8130-af274a856864.html|title=No 'Panga' with Kangana Ranaut: Director Ashwini Iyer Tiwari on Her Equation with Her Film's Star|publisher= India West|date=9 November 2018|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ranaut_heads\">{{Cite web|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/photo-kangana-ranaut-heads-for-the-shoot-of-her-upcoming-film-panga/articleshow/66559623.cms|title=Photo: Kangana Ranaut heads for the shoot of her upcoming film 'Panga'\n|publisher=Times of India|date=9 November 2018|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref> The film was released in India on 24 January 2020.<ref name=\"times_of_india\">{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/first-schedule-of-panga-wrapped-up/articleshow/66982371.cms|title=Kangana Ranaut wraps up the first schedule of Panga|date=7 December 2018|website=Times of India}}</ref><ref name=\"bollywood\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/features/panga-kangana-ranaut-ashwiny-iyer-tiwari-wrap-second-schedule/|title=Panga: Kangana Ranaut and Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari wrap up second schedule|date=28 February 2019|website= Bollywood Hungama|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref> The film received critical acclaim with critics highlighting Ranaut's performance and was a box office success globally grossing {{INR}}56.29 crore against a production budget of {{INR}}24 crore.\n\n== Synopsis ==\nRooted in the subculture of societal facts, Panga is an emotional roller coaster tale of a middle-class Indian woman, where a forgotten Kabaddi world champion catalyzes an inner desire to give a new meaning to her existing role as a wife and mother and takes an ingenious decision to come back to the sport despite the challenges of age stereotypes and new generation complexities which creates an upheaval in her life as she is torn between societal pressures of family responsibility and love for the sport.\n\nJaya Nigam is a former Kabaddi world champion and current railways ticketing staff who is married to Prashant Sachdeva, a railways sr.section engineer, and has a son, Aditya a.k.a. Adi. Currently living in Bhopal after Prashant's transfer to the city, she is propelled both by the arrival of her former teammate Meenu and a push from Adi, who learns of her achievements through Prashant, to return to the sport despite facing challenges of physical fitness and newer, more experienced players. Initially unable to deal with the pressures of a hectic job and the exercise routines that Adi's enthusiasm pushes her through, she finally regains composure and, with support from Prashant and Adi, goes on to mark her comeback to the sport as a mother of a 7-year-old after her story gets noticed again. How she gets back on her feet as the renewed player forms the rest of the story.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Kangana Ranaut]] as Jaya Nigam\n*[[Jassi Gill]] as Prashant Sachdeva, Jaya's husband\n*[[Richa Chadda]] as Meenal \"Meenu\" Singh, Jaya's friend and former teammate\n*[[Neena Gupta]] as Rachna Nigam, Jaya's mother\n*[[Yagya Bhasin]] as Aditya \"Adi\" Sachdeva, Jaya's and Prashant's son\n*[[Megha Burman]] as Nisha Das, Jaya's present teammate\n*[[Rajesh Tailang]] as National Coach\n*[[Smita Tambe]] as india captain\n\n==Production==\n=== Development ===\n''Panga'' was announced on 21 August 2018 with [[Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari]] sharing an emotional Instagram video montage of herself, [[Kangana Ranaut]], [[Jassi Gill]], [[Neena Gupta]] and their families, indicating that when your kin stands behind you, no one in the world can take \u2018panga\u2019 with you.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Bmua0nxnj43/|title=My existing reality is a reflection of my dear ones' belief in me. From the team backed by its families. Presenting Panga|publisher=Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari on Instagram|date=21 August 2018|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref> Ranaut told the Mumbai Mirror in an interview: \u201cWhen Ashwiny narrated the film's story, I was completely moved. My family has been my pillar of strength and have always stood by me through thick and thin. I could really relate to the emotions of the film. Plus, Ashwiny is known for her slice-of-life films and I loved her recent work in Bareilly Ki Barfi. Panga is even more special for me as, for the first time, I will be playing the role of a National-level Kabaddi player. That's going to be challenging for sure! I am looking forward to some exciting times with Ashwiny and the Fox Star team.\u201d<ref name=\"ht\"/>\n\nGill who is playing the role of the husband of Ranaut in this film told the Mumbai Mirror: \u201cI loved the script, especially the inspiring family angle. The film is a roller-coaster of emotions but to me the real Indian family feeling was the most heart-warming part of the subject. Since I come from a very close-knit family, I could identify with the story.\u201d<ref name=\"ht\">{{Cite web|url=https://m.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/panga-kangana-ranaut-s-kabaddi-movie-with-ashwiny-iyer-tiwari-gets-a-title/story-Sl5Q6YaMnwQRWHRspc1xmL.html|title=Panga, Kangana Ranaut's kabaddi film title announced with emotional Instagram video|publisher= Hindustani Times|date=21 August 2018|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Training ===\nThe actors appearing in the film as kabbadi players including Ranaut underwent training in kabaddi for over two months.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/bollywood/report-kangana-ranaut-ahwiny-iyer-tiwari-s-panga-first-look-out-movie-slated-to-release-next-year-2727345|title=Kangana Ranaut-Ahwiny Iyer Tiwari's 'Panga' first look out, movie slated to release next year|publisher=DNA India|date=7 March 2019|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n=== Filming ===\nThe film went on floor on 23 March 2017 in [[Panaji]].<ref name=\"india_west\" /><ref name=\"ranaut_heads\" /> The first schedule of the film was wrapped up on 7 December 2018.<ref name=\"times_of_india\" /> The second schedule of the film was wrapped up on 22 June 2019.<ref name=\"bollywood\" /> The director planned next schedule in a Delhi stadium in April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/panga-shoot-takes-ashwiny-iyer-tiwari-to-delhi/articleshow/68298930.cms|title=Panga shoot takes Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari to Delhi|date=7 March 2019|website=Times of India}}</ref> The third schedule of shooting began in April 2019 in [[Delhi]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/photo-kangana-ranaut-enjoys-gol-gappas-in-delhi/articleshow/68730683.cms|title=Photo: Kangana Ranaut enjoys 'Gol Gappas' in Delhi|date=5 April 2019|accessdate=6 April 2019|website=Times of India}}</ref> The Delhi schedule of the film was completed in mid April and next schedule of shooting to begin in Kolkata.<ref>{{cite web|title=Photos: Kangana Ranaut wraps up the Delhi schedule of her upcoming film 'Panga'|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/photo-features/movies-to-look-forward-to/photos-kangana-ranaut-wraps-up-the-delhi-schedule-of-her-upcoming-film-panga/photostory/68803460.cms|website=Times of India|date=10 April 2019|access-date=7 May 2019}}</ref> The filming was completed in mid July 2019, [[Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari]], the director of the film wrote on her Instagram account, \"My dearest Panga Humans are the sun. The sun that spread a ray of hope when things seem really impossible to achieve.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Panga' wrap-up: Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari thanks her team!|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/panga-wrap-up-ashwiny-iyer-tiwari-thanks-her-team-119071400164_1.html |work=Business Standard |date=14 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Marketing and release==\nFirst look of the film was shared by the director of the film [[Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari]] on 7 March 2019, a still photo in which leading pair is laughing while looking at the sunset.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/panga-first-look-kangana-ranaut-laughs-with-abandon-in-this-heartwarming-still-from-the-film/378578|title=Panga FIRST LOOK: Kangana Ranaut laughs with abandon in this heartwarming still from the film|publisher=Times Now News|date=7 March 2019|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first look poster of Ranaut was released on 19 December 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/movies/bollywood/story/panga-first-poster-out-jo-sapne-dekhte-hain-woh-panga-lete-hain-1629605-2019-12-19|title=Panga first poster out: Jo sapne dekhte hain woh panga lete hain|publisher=India Today|date=19 December 2019|access-date=19 December 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn December 23 official trailer of the film was launched by [[Fox Star Studios]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=QDP6tCC8zTo|title=Panga - Official Trailer - Kangana - Jassie - Richa - Dir: Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari - 24th Jan, 2020 |last=Fox Star Studios|via=YouTube|date=23 December 2019|accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe film was released in India on 24 January 2020.<ref name=\"reldate\">{{cite tweet|user=taran_adarsh| author=Taran Adarsh|date=7  March  2019|number=1103632637900582912?s=19|title=Release date finalised... Richa Chadha, Jassie Gill,  and Neena Gupta and Kangana,  ... #Panga to release on 10 Jan 2020... Directed by Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari... Produced by Fox Star Studios. https://t.co/njw129hxUw}}</ref>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Panga\n| type         = soundtrack\n| artist       = [[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]]\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = 21 January 2020<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jiosaavn.com/album/panga/zhK-fbskwwM_|title=Panga - Original Motion Picture Soundtrack |publisher=Jio Saavn}}</ref>\n| recorded     = 2018\u20132019\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length       = 23:55\n| language     = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| label        = [[Saregama]]\n| producer     = \n| prev_title   = [[Chhapaak]]\n| prev_year    = 2020\n| year         = 2020\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = {{External media\n | audio1     = {{YouTube|RHH6JXr5SKs|Official Audio Jukebox}}\n}}}}\n\nThe film's music is composed by [[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]] while lyrics are written by [[Javed Akhtar]].\n\n{{Tracklist\n| headline     = Track listing\n| total_length = 23:55\n| extra_column=Singer(s)\n| title1  = Panga - Title Track\n| extra1  = [[Harshdeep Kaur]], [[Divya Kumar (singer)|Divya Kumar]], [[Siddharth Mahadevan]]\n| length1 = 3:19\n| title2  = Dil Ne Kaha\n| extra2  = [[Shahid Mallya]], [[Asees Kaur]]\n| length2 = 4:46\n| title3  = Jugnu\n| extra3  = [[Sunny Hindustani]], [[Shankar Mahadevan]]\n| length3 = 4:40\n| title4  = Bibby Song\n| extra4  = [[Annu Kapoor]], Sherry\n| length4 = 2:50\n| title5  = Wahi Hai Raste\n| extra5  = Mohan Kannan, Asees Kaur\n| length5 = 4:28\n| title6  = Dil Ne Kaha\n| note6   = Reprise\n| extra6  = [[Jassi Gill]], Asees Kaur\n| length6 = 3:52\n}}\n\n==Box office==\n''Panga'' earned {{INR}}2.70 crore at the domestic box office on its opening day. On the second day, the film collected {{INR}}5.61 crore. On the third day, the film collected {{INR}}6.60 crore, taking total opening weekend collection to {{INR}}14.91 crore.<ref name=\"bo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/panga/box-office/#bh-movie-box-office|title=Panga Box Office|website=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2020|2|28}}, with a gross of {{INR}}34.43 crore in India and {{INR}}7.28 crore overseas, the film has a worldwide gross collection of {{INR}}41.71 crore.<ref name=\"bo\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|tt8983166}}\n* [https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/panga/ Panga] on [[Bollywood Hungama]]\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes|https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/panga_2020}}\n\n{{Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari}}\n\n{{Portal|India|Film|Bollywood}}\n\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:2020s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:2020s sports films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian sports films]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Fox Star Studios films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Delhi]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Goa]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Kolkata]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Madhya Pradesh]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Hindi-language sports drama film}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Panga\n| image          = Panga film poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari]]\n| producer       = [[Fox Star Studios]]\n| writer         = Nikhil Mehrohtra<br/>\nAshwiny Iyer Tiwari\n| screenplay     = [[Nitesh Tiwari]]\n| starring       = [[Kangana Ranaut]]<br />[[Jassi Gill]]<br />[[Richa Chadda]]<br />[[Neena Gupta]]<br/>Yagya Bhasin\n| music          = '''Songs:'''<br />[[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]]<br />'''Score:'''<br />[[Sanchit Balhara]]<br />Ankit Balhara\n| cinematography = Jay I. Patel\n| editing        = Ballu Saluja\n| studio         = [[Fox Star Studios]]\n| distributor    = Fox Star Studios\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|1|24|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 131 minutes<ref>{{cite web | url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/panga-2020 | title=Panga (2020) | website=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         = {{INR}} 24 crore<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Panga-(India)#tab=summary|title=Panga|publisher=[[The Numbers]]|accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n| gross          = {{Estimation}} {{INR}}56.29 crore[https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Panga-(India)#tab=summary Panga Global Collections]\n\n'''''Panga''''' ({{translation|To mess with}}) is a 2020 Indian Hindi-language [[sports drama]] film directed by [[Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari]] and produced by [[Fox Star Studios]]. The film features [[Kangana Ranaut]], [[Jassi Gill]], [[Richa Chadda]] and [[Neena Gupta]]. The story depicts the jovial life of a [[kabaddi]] player.<ref name=\"ht\" />\nFilming took place from November 2018 to July 2019 in [[Panaji]], [[Bhopal]], [[Delhi]] and [[Kolkata]].<ref name=\"india_west\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/bollywood/no-panga-with-kangana-ranaut-director-ashwini-iyer-tiwari-on/article_d860b874-e434-11e8-8130-af274a856864.html|title=No 'Panga' with Kangana Ranaut: Director Ashwini Iyer Tiwari on Her Equation with Her Film's Star|publisher= India West|date=9 November 2018|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ranaut_heads\">{{Cite web|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/photo-kangana-ranaut-heads-for-the-shoot-of-her-upcoming-film-panga/articleshow/66559623.cms|title=Photo: Kangana Ranaut heads for the shoot of her upcoming film 'Panga'\n|publisher=Times of India|date=9 November 2018|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref> The film was released in India on 24 January 2020.<ref name=\"times_of_india\">{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/first-schedule-of-panga-wrapped-up/articleshow/66982371.cms|title=Kangana Ranaut wraps up the first schedule of Panga|date=7 December 2018|website=Times of India}}</ref><ref name=\"bollywood\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/features/panga-kangana-ranaut-ashwiny-iyer-tiwari-wrap-second-schedule/|title=Panga: Kangana Ranaut and Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari wrap up second schedule|date=28 February 2019|website= Bollywood Hungama|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref> The film received critical acclaim with critics highlighting Ranaut's performance and was a box office success globally grossing {{INR}}56.29 crore against a production budget of {{INR}}24 crore.\n\n== Synopsis ==\nRooted in the subculture of societal facts, Panga is an emotional roller coaster tale of a middle-class Indian woman, where a forgotten Kabaddi world champion catalyzes an inner desire to give a new meaning to her existing role as a wife and mother and takes an ingenious decision to come back to the sport despite the challenges of age stereotypes and new generation complexities which creates an upheaval in her life as she is torn between societal pressures of family responsibility and love for the sport.\n\nJaya Nigam is a former Kabaddi world champion and current railways ticketing staff who is married to Prashant Sachdeva, a railways sr.section engineer, and has a son, Aditya a.k.a. Adi. Currently living in Bhopal after Prashant's transfer to the city, she is propelled both by the arrival of her former teammate Meenu and a push from Adi, who learns of her achievements through Prashant, to return to the sport despite facing challenges of physical fitness and newer, more experienced players. Initially unable to deal with the pressures of a hectic job and the exercise routines that Adi's enthusiasm pushes her through, she finally regains composure and, with support from Prashant and Adi, goes on to mark her comeback to the sport as a mother of a 7-year-old after her story gets noticed again. How she gets back on her feet as the renewed player forms the rest of the story.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Kangana Ranaut]] as Jaya Nigam\n*[[Jassi Gill]] as Prashant Sachdeva, Jaya's husband\n*[[Richa Chadda]] as Meenal \"Meenu\" Singh, Jaya's friend and former teammate\n*[[Neena Gupta]] as Rachna Nigam, Jaya's mother\n*[[Yagya Bhasin]] as Aditya \"Adi\" Sachdeva, Jaya's and Prashant's son\n*[[Megha Burman]] as Nisha Das, Jaya's present teammate\n*[[Rajesh Tailang]] as National Coach\n*[[Smita Tambe]] as india captain\n\n==Production==\n=== Development ===\n''Panga'' was announced on 21 August 2018 with [[Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari]] sharing an emotional Instagram video montage of herself, [[Kangana Ranaut]], [[Jassi Gill]], [[Neena Gupta]] and their families, indicating that when your kin stands behind you, no one in the world can take \u2018panga\u2019 with you.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Bmua0nxnj43/|title=My existing reality is a reflection of my dear ones' belief in me. From the team backed by its families. Presenting Panga|publisher=Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari on Instagram|date=21 August 2018|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref> Ranaut told the Mumbai Mirror in an interview: \u201cWhen Ashwiny narrated the film's story, I was completely moved. My family has been my pillar of strength and have always stood by me through thick and thin. I could really relate to the emotions of the film. Plus, Ashwiny is known for her slice-of-life films and I loved her recent work in Bareilly Ki Barfi. Panga is even more special for me as, for the first time, I will be playing the role of a National-level Kabaddi player. That's going to be challenging for sure! I am looking forward to some exciting times with Ashwiny and the Fox Star team.\u201d<ref name=\"ht\"/>\n\nGill who is playing the role of the husband of Ranaut in this film told the Mumbai Mirror: \u201cI loved the script, especially the inspiring family angle. The film is a roller-coaster of emotions but to me the real Indian family feeling was the most heart-warming part of the subject. Since I come from a very close-knit family, I could identify with the story.\u201d<ref name=\"ht\">{{Cite web|url=https://m.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/panga-kangana-ranaut-s-kabaddi-movie-with-ashwiny-iyer-tiwari-gets-a-title/story-Sl5Q6YaMnwQRWHRspc1xmL.html|title=Panga, Kangana Ranaut's kabaddi film title announced with emotional Instagram video|publisher= Hindustani Times|date=21 August 2018|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Training ===\nThe actors appearing in the film as kabbadi players including Ranaut underwent training in kabaddi for over two months.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/bollywood/report-kangana-ranaut-ahwiny-iyer-tiwari-s-panga-first-look-out-movie-slated-to-release-next-year-2727345|title=Kangana Ranaut-Ahwiny Iyer Tiwari's 'Panga' first look out, movie slated to release next year|publisher=DNA India|date=7 March 2019|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n=== Filming ===\nThe film went on floor on 23 March 2017 in [[Panaji]].<ref name=\"india_west\" /><ref name=\"ranaut_heads\" /> The first schedule of the film was wrapped up on 7 December 2018.<ref name=\"times_of_india\" /> The second schedule of the film was wrapped up on 22 June 2019.<ref name=\"bollywood\" /> The director planned next schedule in a Delhi stadium in April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/panga-shoot-takes-ashwiny-iyer-tiwari-to-delhi/articleshow/68298930.cms|title=Panga shoot takes Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari to Delhi|date=7 March 2019|website=Times of India}}</ref> The third schedule of shooting began in April 2019 in [[Delhi]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/photo-kangana-ranaut-enjoys-gol-gappas-in-delhi/articleshow/68730683.cms|title=Photo: Kangana Ranaut enjoys 'Gol Gappas' in Delhi|date=5 April 2019|accessdate=6 April 2019|website=Times of India}}</ref> The Delhi schedule of the film was completed in mid April and next schedule of shooting to begin in Kolkata.<ref>{{cite web|title=Photos: Kangana Ranaut wraps up the Delhi schedule of her upcoming film 'Panga'|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/photo-features/movies-to-look-forward-to/photos-kangana-ranaut-wraps-up-the-delhi-schedule-of-her-upcoming-film-panga/photostory/68803460.cms|website=Times of India|date=10 April 2019|access-date=7 May 2019}}</ref> The filming was completed in mid July 2019, [[Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari]], the director of the film wrote on her Instagram account, \"My dearest Panga Humans are the sun. The sun that spread a ray of hope when things seem really impossible to achieve.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Panga' wrap-up: Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari thanks her team!|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/panga-wrap-up-ashwiny-iyer-tiwari-thanks-her-team-119071400164_1.html |work=Business Standard |date=14 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Marketing and release==\nFirst look of the film was shared by the director of the film [[Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari]] on 7 March 2019, a still photo in which leading pair is laughing while looking at the sunset.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/panga-first-look-kangana-ranaut-laughs-with-abandon-in-this-heartwarming-still-from-the-film/378578|title=Panga FIRST LOOK: Kangana Ranaut laughs with abandon in this heartwarming still from the film|publisher=Times Now News|date=7 March 2019|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first look poster of Ranaut was released on 19 December 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/movies/bollywood/story/panga-first-poster-out-jo-sapne-dekhte-hain-woh-panga-lete-hain-1629605-2019-12-19|title=Panga first poster out: Jo sapne dekhte hain woh panga lete hain|publisher=India Today|date=19 December 2019|access-date=19 December 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn December 23 official trailer of the film was launched by [[Fox Star Studios]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=QDP6tCC8zTo|title=Panga - Official Trailer - Kangana - Jassie - Richa - Dir: Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari - 24th Jan, 2020 |last=Fox Star Studios|via=YouTube|date=23 December 2019|accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe film was released in India on 24 January 2020.<ref name=\"reldate\">{{cite tweet|user=taran_adarsh| author=Taran Adarsh|date=7  March  2019|number=1103632637900582912?s=19|title=Release date finalised... Richa Chadha, Jassie Gill,  and Neena Gupta and Kangana,  ... #Panga to release on 10 Jan 2020... Directed by Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari... Produced by Fox Star Studios. https://t.co/njw129hxUw}}</ref>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Panga\n| type         = soundtrack\n| artist       = [[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]]\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = 21 January 2020<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jiosaavn.com/album/panga/zhK-fbskwwM_|title=Panga - Original Motion Picture Soundtrack |publisher=Jio Saavn}}</ref>\n| recorded     = 2018\u20132019\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length       = 23:55\n| language     = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| label        = [[Saregama]]\n| producer     = \n| prev_title   = [[Chhapaak]]\n| prev_year    = 2020\n| year         = 2020\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = {{External media\n | audio1     = {{YouTube|RHH6JXr5SKs|Official Audio Jukebox}}\n}}}}\n\nThe film's music is composed by [[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]] while lyrics are written by [[Javed Akhtar]].\n\n{{Tracklist\n| headline     = Track listing\n| total_length = 23:55\n| extra_column=Singer(s)\n| title1  = Panga - Title Track\n| extra1  = [[Harshdeep Kaur]], [[Divya Kumar (singer)|Divya Kumar]], [[Siddharth Mahadevan]]\n| length1 = 3:19\n| title2  = Dil Ne Kaha\n| extra2  = [[Shahid Mallya]], [[Asees Kaur]]\n| length2 = 4:46\n| title3  = Jugnu\n| extra3  = [[Sunny Hindustani]], [[Shankar Mahadevan]]\n| length3 = 4:40\n| title4  = Bibby Song\n| extra4  = [[Annu Kapoor]], Sherry\n| length4 = 2:50\n| title5  = Wahi Hai Raste\n| extra5  = Mohan Kannan, Asees Kaur\n| length5 = 4:28\n| title6  = Dil Ne Kaha\n| note6   = Reprise\n| extra6  = [[Jassi Gill]], Asees Kaur\n| length6 = 3:52\n}}\n\n==Box office==\n''Panga'' earned {{INR}}2.70 crore at the domestic box office on its opening day. On the second day, the film collected {{INR}}5.61 crore. On the third day, the film collected {{INR}}6.60 crore, taking total opening weekend collection to {{INR}}14.91 crore.<ref name=\"bo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/panga/box-office/#bh-movie-box-office|title=Panga Box Office|website=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2020|2|28}}, with a gross of {{INR}}34.43 crore in India and {{INR}}7.28 crore overseas, the film has a worldwide gross collection of {{INR}}41.71 crore.<ref name=\"bo\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|tt8983166}}\n* [https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/panga/ Panga] on [[Bollywood Hungama]]\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes|https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/panga_2020}}\n\n{{Ashwiny Iyer Tiwari}}\n\n{{Portal|India|Film|Bollywood}}\n\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:2020s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:2020s sports films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian sports films]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Fox Star Studios films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Delhi]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Goa]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Kolkata]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Madhya Pradesh]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toNumber (disambiguation)(link changed toThe Numbers (website)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Panga_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Izvestia", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n|name = Izvestia<br />\u0418\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u044f\n|image = [[File:Izvestia-frontpage.jpg|200px|border]]\n|caption = Front page of the ''Izvestia'' newspaper from 15 June 2012.\n|type = Daily newspaper\n|format = [[Broadsheet]]\n|owners = [[National Media Group]]\n|publisher = Inews ([[News Media (company)|News Media]])\n|chiefeditor = Arseniy Ogenesyan\n|assoceditor =\n|staff =\n|foundation = {{Start date and age|df=y|1969\n|3|13}}\n|political = \n|language = Russian\n|headquarters = [[Begovoy District]], [[Moscow]], Russia\n|circulation = 234,500<ref>[http://www.mediaatlas.ru/editions/?a=view&id=2477 \u0410\u0442\u043b\u0430\u0441 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0441\u044b: \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \"\u0418\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u044f\"] Media Atlas</ref>\n|ISSN = 0233-4356\n|oclc = 427395058\n|website = {{URL|iz.ru}}\n}}\n'''''Izvestia''''' ({{lang-rus|\u0418\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u044f|p=\u026az\u02c8v\u02b2es\u02b2t\u02b2\u026aj\u0259}}) is a daily [[broadsheet]] newspaper in [[Russia]]. It was a [[Newspaper of record#Newspapers of record (by reputation)|newspaper of record]] in the [[Soviet Union]] from 1917 until the [[Dissolution of the Soviet Union|dissolution of the USSR]] in 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastview.com/Files/EVIzvestiiaDA.pdf|title=Izvestiia Digital Archive 1917\u20132010. Online access to the Kremlin's newspaper of record|publisher=East View Information Services |location=Minneapolis, MN|page=5|accessdate=18 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe word ''izvestiya'' in Russian means \"delivered messages\", derived from the verb ''izveshchat'' (\"to inform\", \"to notify\"). In the context of newspapers it is usually translated as \"news\" or \"reports\".\n\n==Origin==\nThe newspaper began as the ''News of the [[Petrograd Soviet]] of Workers Deputies'' on {{OldStyleDate|13 March|1917|28 February}} in [[Petrograd]]. Initially, the paper expressed [[Menshevik]] and [[Socialist-Revolutionary Party]] views.\n\nIn August 1917, it took the title ''News of the Central Executive Committee of the Petrograd Soviet of Workers' and Soldiers' Deputies''. By October 1917 it became ''News of the Central Executive Committee of the Soviets of Working and Military Deputies'', and was eventually re-titled ''News of the Soviets of People's Deputies''.\n\nAfter the Second All-Union Congress of Soviets, ''Izvestia'' became an official newspaper of the Soviet government (Central Executive Committee of the [[Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union]] and [[Sovnarkom]]).\n\n==History==\n===1917\u20131991===\n[[File:Izvestia logo old.png|thumb|right|200px|Old ''Izvestia'' logo. It uses two letters that are no longer used in the Russian language (see [[Reforms of Russian orthography]]).]]\nDuring the Soviet period, while ''[[Pravda]]'' served as the official mouthpiece of the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Communist Party]], ''Izvestia'' expressed the official views of the Soviet government as published by the [[Presidium of the Supreme Soviet]] of the USSR.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Andrei G. Richter|title=The Russian Press after Perestroika|journal=Canadian Journal of Communication|year=1995|volume=20|issue=1|url=http://www.cjc-online.ca/index.php/journal/article/view/842/748|accessdate=28 November 2014}}</ref> The full name was ''Izvestiya Sovetov Narodnykh Deputatov SSSR'' (in Russian, ''\u0418\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0434\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u0421\u0421\u0421\u0420'', the ''Reports of Soviets of Peoples' Deputies of the USSR'').\n\n===1992\u2013present===\nFollowing the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]], ''Izvestia'' now describes itself as a \"national\" newspaper of Russia. The newspaper was owned by a vast holding company of [[Vladimir Potanin]] which had close ties with the government.<ref name=gse>{{cite web|last=Bigg|first=Claire |title=Russia: State-Owned Gazprom Buys Leading Independent Daily 'Izvestiya'|work=GlobalSecurity|date=3 June 2005 |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/russia/2005/russia-050603-rferl01.htm|accessdate=4 September 2007}}</ref> A controlling stake in ''Izvestia'' was purchased by state-owned [[Gazprom]] on 3 June 2005, and included in the [[Gazprom Media]] holding.<ref name=gse/> According to the allegations of the [[Committee to Protect Journalists]], Raf Shakirov, editor-in-chief of ''Izvestia'', was forced to resign because the government officials did not like the paper's coverage of the [[Beslan school hostage crisis]].<ref>[http://www.cpj.org/attacks05/europe05/russia_05.html Attacks 2005: Europe and Central Asia]. [[Committee to Protect Journalists]]. 16 February 2006.</ref><ref>[http://www.cdi.org/russia/johnson/9167-14.cfm Russia, Media, Gazprom, Izvestia \u2013 JRL 6March 2005<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070204020150/http://cdi.org/russia/johnson/9167-14.cfm |date=4 February 2007 }}</ref> Other sources informed that Potanin had asked him to leave for fear the Kremlin would be riled by the explicit photographs of the massacre published by ''Izvestia''.<ref name=gse/> As of 2005, the circulation of ''Izvestia'' was 240,967. Its 2007 circulation certified by TNS Gallup Media was 371,000 copies.<ref name=bbc8>{{cite news|title=Main papers|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4315129.stm|accessdate=6 October 2013|publisher=BBC|date=16 May 2008}}</ref> Until his death on 1 October 2008, the chief artist was [[Boris Yefimov]], the centenarian illustrator who had worked as [[Joseph Stalin]]'s political cartoonist.\n\nIn 2008, Gazprom Media sold ''Izvestia'' to [[National Media Group]].<ref>[http://www.nm-g.ru/en/about/ \u2013 About Us] National Media Group</ref> The newspaper was relaunched in D2 ([[broadsheet]]) format after that and adopted a new slogan (\"Making ''Izvestia'' [i.e., reports] from the news\"), as well as extended simultaneously its business coverage. The paper's old business section, '''Finansovye Izvestia''' (Finance Izvestia), was closed, and '''Marker Weekly''' was launched instead in September 2011, distributed with ''Izvestia'' on Mondays. The Friday appendix '''Nedelya''' (The Week), devoted to culture and leisure activities, was relaunched as well.\n\n==References==\n<!--See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes for an explanation of how to generate footnotes using the <ref(erences/)> tags-->\n<!--to cite a web resource, use this template\n <ref>{{cite web|title= }}</ref>\n-->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Merrill, John C. and Harold A. Fisher. ''The world's great dailies: profiles of fifty newspapers'' (1980) pp 170-76\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n* [https://iz.ru/ Official ''Izvestia'' website] {{in lang|ru}}\n*{{twitter|izvestia_ru}} {{in lang|ru}}\n*{{Instagram|izvestia_ru}} {{in lang|ru}}\n* [https://www.google.com/custom?q=Izvestia&sa=Google+Search&cof=GALT%3A0000CC%3BS%3Ahttp%3A%2F%2FWORLDMEETS.US%3BGL%3A0%3BVLC%3A0000FF%3BAH%3Aleft%3BBGC%3AE9f9E9%3BLH%3A90%3BLC%3A0000CC%3BL%3Ahttp%3A%2F%2FWORLDMEETS.US%2Fimagesui%2Fwalogo_siteid.gif%3BALC%3A0000CC%3BBIMG%3Ahttp%3A%2F%2FWORLDMEETS.US%2Fimages%2FUSAbkgd.jpg%3BLW%3A213%3BT%3A00354F%3BAWFID%3A834a24b6e0f3e242%3B&domains=WORLDMEETS.US&sitesearch=WORLDMEETS.US English translations of ''Izvestia'' articles at nonprofit WorldMeets.US]\n*[http://nlr.ru/res/inv/ukazat55/record_full.php?record_ID=181482 \"Izvestia\" digital archives in \"Newspapers on the web and beyond\"], the digital resource of the [[National Library of Russia]]\n\n{{Eastern Bloc media}}\n{{Portal bar|Soviet Union}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Izvestia}}\n[[Category:Newspapers published in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Russian-language newspapers published in Russia]]\n[[Category:Eastern Bloc media]]\n[[Category:Gazprom subsidiaries]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1917]]\n[[Category:1917 establishments in Russia]]\n[[Category:Russian-language newspapers]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in the Russian Empire]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Russia]]\n[[Category:Media in Saint Petersburg]]\n[[Category:Media in Moscow]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n|name = Izvestia<br />\u0418\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u044f\n|image = [[File:Izvestia-frontpage.jpg|200px|border]]\n|caption = Front page of the ''Izvestia'' newspaper from 15 June 2012.\n|type = Daily newspaper\n|format = [[Broadsheet]]\n|owners = [[National Media Group]]\n|publisher = Inews ([[News Media (company)|News Media]])\n|chiefeditor = Arseniy Ogenesyan\n|assoceditor =\n|staff =\n|foundation = {{Start date and age|df=y|1969\n|3|13}}\n|political = \n|language = Russian\n|headquarters = [[Begovoy District]], [[Moscow]], Russia\n|circulation = 234,500<ref>[http://www.mediaatlas.ru/editions/?a=view&id=2477 \u0410\u0442\u043b\u0430\u0441 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0441\u044b: \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \"\u0418\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u044f\"] Media Atlas</ref>\n|ISSN = 0233-4356\n|oclc = 427395058\n|website = {{URL|iz.ru}}\n}}\n'''''Izvestia''''' ({{lang-rus|\u0418\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u044f|p=\u026az\u02c8v\u02b2es\u02b2t\u02b2\u026aj\u0259}}) is a daily [[broadsheet]] newspaper in [[Russia]]. It was a [[Newspaper of record#Newspapers of record (by reputation)|newspaper of record]] in the [[Soviet Union]] from 1917 until the [[Dissolution of the Soviet Union|dissolution of the USSR]] in 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastview.com/Files/EVIzvestiiaDA.pdf|title=Izvestiia Digital Archive 1917\u20132010. Online access to the Kremlin's newspaper of record|publisher=East View Information Services |location=Minneapolis, MN|page=5|accessdate=18 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe word ''izvestiya'' in Russian means \"delivered messages,\" derived from the verb ''izveshchat'' (\"to inform\", \"to notify\"). In the context of newspapers it is usually translated as \"news\" or \"reports\".\n\n==Origin==\nThe newspaper began as the ''News of the [[Petrograd Soviet]] of Workers Deputies'' on {{OldStyleDate|13 March|1917|28 February}} in [[Petrograd]]. Initially, the paper expressed [[Menshevik]] and [[Socialist-Revolutionary Party]] views.\n\nIn August 1917, it took the title ''News of the Central Executive Committee of the Petrograd Soviet of Workers' and Soldiers' Deputies''. By October 1917 it became ''News of the Central Executive Committee of the Soviets of Working and Military Deputies'', and was eventually re-titled ''News of the Soviets of People's Deputies''.\n\nAfter the Second All-Union Congress of Soviets, ''Izvestia'' became an official newspaper of the Soviet government (Central Executive Committee of the [[Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union]] and [[Sovnarkom]]).\n\n==History==\n===1917\u20131991===\n[[File:Izvestia logo old.png|thumb|right|200px|Old ''Izvestia'' logo. It uses two letters that are no longer used in the Russian language (see [[Reforms of Russian orthography]]).]]\nDuring the Soviet period, while ''[[Pravda]]'' served as the official mouthpiece of the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Communist Party]], ''Izvestia'' expressed the official views of the Soviet government as published by the [[Presidium of the Supreme Soviet]] of the USSR.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Andrei G. Richter|title=The Russian Press after Perestroika|journal=Canadian Journal of Communication|year=1995|volume=20|issue=1|url=http://www.cjc-online.ca/index.php/journal/article/view/842/748|accessdate=28 November 2014}}</ref> The full name was ''Izvestiya Sovetov Narodnykh Deputatov SSSR'' (in Russian, ''\u0418\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0434\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u0421\u0421\u0421\u0420'', the ''Reports of Soviets of Peoples' Deputies of the USSR'').\n\n===1992\u2013present===\nFollowing the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]], ''Izvestia'' now describes itself as a \"national\" newspaper of Russia. The newspaper was owned by a vast holding company of [[Vladimir Potanin]] which had close ties with the government.<ref name=gse>{{cite web|last=Bigg|first=Claire |title=Russia: State-Owned Gazprom Buys Leading Independent Daily 'Izvestiya'|work=GlobalSecurity|date=3 June 2005 |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/russia/2005/russia-050603-rferl01.htm|accessdate=4 September 2007}}</ref> A controlling stake in ''Izvestia'' was purchased by state-owned [[Gazprom]] on 3 June 2005, and included in the [[Gazprom Media]] holding.<ref name=gse/> According to the allegations of the [[Committee to Protect Journalists]], Raf Shakirov, editor-in-chief of ''Izvestia'', was forced to resign because the government officials did not like the paper's coverage of the [[Beslan school hostage crisis]].<ref>[http://www.cpj.org/attacks05/europe05/russia_05.html Attacks 2005: Europe and Central Asia]. [[Committee to Protect Journalists]]. 16 February 2006.</ref><ref>[http://www.cdi.org/russia/johnson/9167-14.cfm Russia, Media, Gazprom, Izvestia \u2013 JRL 6March 2005<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070204020150/http://cdi.org/russia/johnson/9167-14.cfm |date=4 February 2007 }}</ref> Other sources informed that Potanin had asked him to leave for fear the Kremlin would be riled by the explicit photographs of the massacre published by ''Izvestia''.<ref name=gse/> As of 2005, the circulation of ''Izvestia'' was 240,967. Its 2007 circulation certified by TNS Gallup Media was 371,000 copies.<ref name=bbc8>{{cite news|title=Main papers|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4315129.stm|accessdate=6 October 2013|publisher=BBC|date=16 May 2008}}</ref> Until his death on 1 October 2008, the chief artist was [[Boris Yefimov]], the centenarian illustrator who had worked as [[Joseph Stalin]]'s political cartoonist.\n\nIn 2008, Gazprom Media sold ''Izvestia'' to [[National Media Group]].<ref>[http://www.nm-g.ru/en/about/ \u2013 About Us] National Media Group</ref> The newspaper was relaunched in D2 ([[broadsheet]]) format after that and adopted a new slogan (\"Making ''Izvestia'' [i.e., reports] from the news\"), as well as extended simultaneously its business coverage. The paper's old business section, '''Finansovye Izvestia''' (Finance Izvestia), was closed, and '''Marker Weekly''' was launched instead in September 2011, distributed with ''Izvestia'' on Mondays. The Friday appendix '''Nedelya''' (The Week), devoted to culture and leisure activities, was relaunched as well.\n\n==References==\n<!--See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes for an explanation of how to generate footnotes using the <ref(erences/)> tags-->\n<!--to cite a web resource, use this template\n <ref>{{cite web|title= }}</ref>\n-->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Merrill, John C. and Harold A. Fisher. ''The world's great dailies: profiles of fifty newspapers'' (1980) pp 170-76\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n* [https://iz.ru/ Official ''Izvestia'' website] {{in lang|ru}}\n*{{twitter|izvestia_ru}} {{in lang|ru}}\n*{{Instagram|izvestia_ru}} {{in lang|ru}}\n* [https://www.google.com/custom?q=Izvestia&sa=Google+Search&cof=GALT%3A0000CC%3BS%3Ahttp%3A%2F%2FWORLDMEETS.US%3BGL%3A0%3BVLC%3A0000FF%3BAH%3Aleft%3BBGC%3AE9f9E9%3BLH%3A90%3BLC%3A0000CC%3BL%3Ahttp%3A%2F%2FWORLDMEETS.US%2Fimagesui%2Fwalogo_siteid.gif%3BALC%3A0000CC%3BBIMG%3Ahttp%3A%2F%2FWORLDMEETS.US%2Fimages%2FUSAbkgd.jpg%3BLW%3A213%3BT%3A00354F%3BAWFID%3A834a24b6e0f3e242%3B&domains=WORLDMEETS.US&sitesearch=WORLDMEETS.US English translations of ''Izvestia'' articles at nonprofit WorldMeets.US]\n*[http://nlr.ru/res/inv/ukazat55/record_full.php?record_ID=181482 \"Izvestia\" digital archives in \"Newspapers on the web and beyond\"], the digital resource of the [[National Library of Russia]]\n\n{{Eastern Bloc media}}\n{{Portal bar|Soviet Union}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Izvestia}}\n[[Category:Newspapers published in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Russian-language newspapers published in Russia]]\n[[Category:Eastern Bloc media]]\n[[Category:Gazprom subsidiaries]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1917]]\n[[Category:1917 establishments in Russia]]\n[[Category:Russian-language newspapers]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in the Russian Empire]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Russia]]\n[[Category:Media in Saint Petersburg]]\n[[Category:Media in Moscow]]\n", "name_user": "Shuipzv3", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Izvestia"}
{"title_page": "Tereshchenko Cabinet", "text_new": "{{Infobox government cabinet\n|cabinet_name=Sergey Tereshchenko's Cabinet\n|total_number=\n|legislature_term=1st\n|outgoing_formation=\n|former_members_number=\n|opposition_party=[[People's Congress of Kazakhstan|People's Congress]]\n|opposition_leader=[[Olzhas Suleimenov]]\n|successor=[[Kazhegeldin Cabinet|Kazhegeldin]]\n|previous=[[Sarsenov Cabinet|Sarsenov]]\n|current_number=\n|political_party=[[Independent (politician)|Independent]]<br>[[People's Union of Kazakhstan Unity]]\n|jurisdiction=Kazakhstan\n|legislature_status=Minority {{Composition bar|33|177|hex=#00AFCA}}\n|cabinet_number=23rd|flag=Flag_of_Kazakhstan.svg\n|incumbent=14 October 1991\n|image=\n|date_formed=14 October 1991\n|date_dissolved=12 October 1994\n|government_head=[[Sergey Tereshchenko]]\n|state_head=[[Nursultan Nazarbayev]]\n|election=\n}}\nThe '''Tereshchenko Cabinet''' was the composition of the [[government of Kazakhstan]] from 16 October 1991 to 12 October 1994 under the leadership of Prime Minister [[Sergey Tereshchenko]]. The cabinet ceased to exist after the [[Supreme Council (Kazakhstan)|Supreme Council]] passed a vote of no-confidence in May 1994.<ref>http://countrystudies.us/kazakstan/34.htm</ref> Despite that, Tereshchenko still held the post for a couple of months until he was finally dismissed by President [[Nursultan Nazarbayev]] on 12 October following a corruption scandal by the Minister of Internal Affairs.<ref>http://www.country-data.com/cgi-bin/query/r-7545.html</ref>\n\n== Composition ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Functions\n!Holder\n!Start\n!End\n|-\n|[[Prime Minister of Kazakhstan|Prime Minister]]\n|[[Sergey Tereshchenko]]\n| align=\"right\" |{{nobr|16 October 1991}}\n| align=\"right\" |12 October 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |[[First Deputy Prime Minister of Kazakhstan|First Deputy Prime Minister]]\n|Evgeny Ezhikov-Babakhanov\n|28 June 1991\n|February 1992\n|-\n|Daulet Sembaev\n|February 1992\n|10 December 1993\n|-\n|[[Oleg Soskovets]]\n|February 1992\n|November 1992\n|-\n|[[Akezhan Kazhegeldin]]\n|10 December 1993\n|12 October 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"12\" |Deputy Prime Minister\n|Kalyk Abdullaev\n| align=\"right\" |August 1991\n| align=\"right\" |July 1992\n|-\n|Daulet Sembaev\n| align=\"right\" |October 1991\n| align=\"right\" |February 1992\n|-\n|Qadyr Baykenov\n|June 1991\n|January 1993\n|-\n|Baltash Tursumbaev\n|June 1991\n|January 1993\n|-\n|Myrzatai Joldasbekov\n|June 1991\n|January 1993\n|-\n|Asygat Jabagin\n|January 1993\n|September 1994\n|-\n|Galym Abilsiitov\n|January 1993\n|October 1994\n|-\n|Syzdyq Abishev\n|June 1993\n|June 1994\n|-\n|Quanysh Sultanov\n|January 1993\n|March 1994\n|-\n|Sergey Kulagin\n|June 1993\n|October 1994\n|-\n|Janibek Karibjanov\n|January 1993\n|June 1994\n|-\n|Tulegen Jukeev\n|March 1994\n|October 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Trade\n|Oktyabr Zheltikov\n| align=\"right\" |June 1990\n| align=\"right\" |June 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Industry\n|Ivan Vlasov\n| align=\"right\" |February 1991\n| align=\"right\" |February 1992\n|-\n|Albert Salamatin\n| align=\"right\" |December 1992\n| align=\"right\" |June 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Industry and Commerce\n|Vyacheslav Kostyuchenko\n| align=\"right\" |June 1994\n| align=\"right\" |October 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Economy\n|Beisenbai Izteleuov\n| align=\"right\" |January 1993\n| align=\"right\" |February 1994\n|-\n|Mars Urkumbaev\n| align=\"right\" |February 1994\n| align=\"right\" |September 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Finance\n|Tuleubek Abdikadirov\n| align=\"right\" |April 1990\n| align=\"right\" |November 1992\n|-\n|Erkeshbai Derbisov\n| align=\"right\" |November 1992\n| align=\"right\" |October 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Material Resources\n|Kanat Turapov\n| align=\"right\" |February 1992\n| align=\"right\" |December 1992\n|-\n|Ministry of Energy and Electrification\n|Bulat Nurjanov\n| align=\"right\" |April 1990\n| align=\"right\" |February 1992\n|-\n|Ministry of Energy and Fuel Resources\n|Kadyr Baikenov\n| align=\"right\" |February 1992\n| align=\"right\" |June 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Energy and Coal Industry\n|Vladimir Karmakov\n| align=\"right\" |June 1994\n| align=\"right\" |October 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Foreign Economic Relations\n|Syzdyq Abishev\n| align=\"right\" |December 1990\n| align=\"right\" |June 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Foreign Affairs\n|Tuleutai Suleimenov\n| align=\"right\" |December 1991\n| align=\"right\" |April 1994\n|-\n|Kanat Saudabaev\n|April 1994\n|October 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Science and New Technology\n|Galym Abilsiitov\n| align=\"right\" |February 1992\n| align=\"right\" |August 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Geology and Subsoil Protection\n|Lev Trubnikov\n| align=\"right\" |February 1992\n| align=\"right\" |November 1993\n|-\n|Ministry of Oil and Gas Industry\n|Ravil Cherdabaev\n| align=\"right\" |June 1994\n| align=\"right\" |October 1994\n|-\n|Minister of Ecology and Bioresources\n|Svyatoslav Medvedev\n| align=\"right\" |February 1992\n| align=\"right\" |October 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Communications\n|Igor Ulyanov\n| align=\"right\" |March 1987\n| align=\"right\" |June 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Highways\n|Shamil Bekbulatov\n| align=\"right\" |January 1981\n| align=\"right\" |February 1992\n|-\n|Ministry of Transport\n|Nigmatjan Isingarin\n| align=\"right\" |February 1991\n| align=\"right\" |June 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Transport and Communications\n|Nigmatjan Isingarin\n|June 1994\n|October 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Housing and Land Development\n|Askar Kulibaev\n|September 1993\n|October 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Agriculture and Food\n|Valentin Dvurechensky\n|December 1990\n|February 1992\n|-\n|Ministry of Agriculture\n|Baltash Tursumbaev\n|February 1992\n|November 1993\n|-\n|Ministry of Defense\n|Sagadat Nurmagambetov\n|May 1992\n|October 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Internal Affairs\n|Mikhail Bersenyov\n|April 1990\n|April 1992\n|-\n|Vladimir Shumov\n|April 1992\n|September 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Print and Media\n|Quanysh Sultanov\n|August 1991\n|January 1993\n|-\n|[[Altynbek Sarsenbayuly]]\n|January 1993\n|October 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Tourism, Physical Education and Sports\n|Karatai Turysov\n|August 1991\n|December 1993\n|-\n|Ministry of Youth, Tourism and Sports\n|Byrganym Aitimova\n|December 1993\n|October 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Public Education\n|Shaysultan Shayahmetov\n|June 1988\n|October 1993\n|-\n|Erejep Mambetkaziev\n|October 1993\n|October 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Culture\n|Erkegali Rahmadiev\n|February 1992\n|October 1993\n|-\n|Serik Ashlyaev\n|October 1993\n|October 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Health Care\n|Aksultan Amanbaev\n|April 1992\n|April 1992\n|-\n|Vasiliy Devyatko\n|April 1992\n|October 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Labor\n|Sayat Beisenov\n|March 1991\n|October 1993\n|-\n|Viktor Sobolev\n|October 1993\n|October 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Social Security\n|Zaure Kadyrova\n|1990\n|February 1992\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Social Protection\n|Zaure Kadyrova\n|February 1992\n|June 1994\n|-\n|Baikarim Tutenov\n|June 1994\n|October 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Justice\n|Galihan Erjanov\n|May 1990\n|June 1993\n|-\n|Nagashbai Shaikenov\n|June 1993\n|October 1995\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Government of Kazakhstan|Tereshchenko]]\n[[Category:1991 establishments in Kazakhstan]]\n[[Category:Cabinets established in 1991|Tereshchenko]]\n[[Category:Cabinets disestablished in 1994|Tereshchenko]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox government cabinet\n|cabinet_name=Sergey Tereshchenko's Cabinet\n|total_number=\n|legislature_term=1st\n|outgoing_formation=\n|former_members_number=\n|opposition_party=[[People's Congress of Kazakhstan|People's Congress]]\n|opposition_leader=[[Olzhas Suleimenov]]\n|successor=[[Kazhegeldin Cabinet|Kazhegeldin]]\n|previous=[[Sarsenov Cabinet|Sarsenov]]\n|current_number=\n|political_party=[[Independent (politician)|Independent]]<br>[[People's Union of Kazakhstan Unity]]\n|jurisdiction=Kazakhstan\n|legislature_status=Minority {{Composition bar|33|177|hex=#00AFCA}}\n|cabinet_number=23rd|flag=Flag_of_Kazakhstan.svg\n|incumbent=14 October 1991\n|image=\n|date_formed=14 October 1991\n|date_dissolved=12 October 1994\n|government_head=[[Sergey Tereshchenko]]\n|state_head=[[Nursultan Nazarbayev]]\n|election=\n}}\nThe '''Tereshchenko Cabinet''' was the composition of the [[government of Kazakhstan]] from 16 October 1991 to 12 October 1994 under the leadership of Prime Minister [[Sergey Tereshchenko]]. The cabinet ceased to exist after the [[Supreme Council (Kazakhstan)|Supreme Council]] passed a vote of no-confidence in May 1994.<ref>http://countrystudies.us/kazakstan/34.htm</ref> Despite that, Tereshchenko still held the post for a couple of months until he was finally dismissed by President [[Nursultan Nazarbayev]] on 12 October following a corruption scandal by the Minister of Internal Affairs.<ref>http://www.country-data.com/cgi-bin/query/r-7545.html</ref>\n\n== Composition ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Functions\n!Holder\n!Start\n!End\n|-\n|[[Prime Minister of Kazakhstan|Prime Minister]]\n|[[Sergey Tereshchenko]]\n| align=\"right\" |{{nobr|16 October 1991}}\n| align=\"right\" |12 October 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |[[First Deputy Prime Minister of Kazakhstan|First Deputy Prime Minister]]\n|Evgeny Ezhikov-Babakhanov\n|28 June 1991\n|February 1992\n|-\n|Daulet Sembaev\n|February 1992\n|10 December 1993\n|-\n|[[Oleg Soskovets]]\n|February 1992\n|November 1992\n|-\n|[[Akezhan Kazhegeldin]]\n|10 December 1993\n|12 October 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"12\" |Deputy Prime Minister\n|Kalyk Abdullaev\n| align=\"right\" |August 1991\n| align=\"right\" |July 1992\n|-\n|Daulet Sembaev\n| align=\"right\" |October 1991\n| align=\"right\" |February 1992\n|-\n|Qadyr Baykenov\n|June 1991\n|January 1993\n|-\n|Baltash Tursumbaev\n|June 1991\n|January 1993\n|-\n|Myrzatai Joldasbekov\n|June 1991\n|January 1993\n|-\n|Asygat Jabagin\n|January 1993\n|September 1994\n|-\n|Galym Abilsiitov\n|January 1993\n|October 1994\n|-\n|Syzdyq Abishev\n|June 1993\n|June 1994\n|-\n|Quanysh Sultanov\n|January 1993\n|March 1994\n|-\n|Sergey Kulagin\n|June 1993\n|October 1994\n|-\n|Janibek Karibjanov\n|January 1993\n|June 1994\n|-\n|Tulegen Jukeev\n|March 1994\n|October 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Trade\n|Oktyabr Zheltikov\n| align=\"right\" |June 1990\n| align=\"right\" |June 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Industry\n|Ivan Vlasov\n| align=\"right\" |February 1991\n| align=\"right\" |February 1992\n|-\n|Albert Salamatin\n| align=\"right\" |December 1992\n| align=\"right\" |June 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Industry and Commerce\n|Vyacheslav Kostyuchenko\n| align=\"right\" |June 1994\n| align=\"right\" |October 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Economy\n|Beisenbai Izteleuov\n| align=\"right\" |January 1993\n| align=\"right\" |February 1994\n|-\n|Mars Urkumbaev\n| align=\"right\" |February 1994\n| align=\"right\" |September 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Finance\n|Tuleubek Abdikadirov\n| align=\"right\" |April 1990\n| align=\"right\" |November 1992\n|-\n|Erkeshbai Derbisov\n| align=\"right\" |November 1992\n| align=\"right\" |October 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Material Resources\n|Kanat Turapov\n| align=\"right\" |February 1992\n| align=\"right\" |December 1992\n|-\n|Ministry of Energy and Electrification\n|Bulat Nurjanov\n| align=\"right\" |April 1990\n| align=\"right\" |Feburary 1992\n|-\n|Ministry of Energy and Fuel Resources\n|Kadyr Baikenov\n| align=\"right\" |February 1992\n| align=\"right\" |June 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Energy and Coal Industry\n|Vladimir Karmakov\n| align=\"right\" |June 1994\n| align=\"right\" |October 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Foreign Economic Relations\n|Syzdyq Abishev\n| align=\"right\" |December 1990\n| align=\"right\" |June 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Foreign Affairs\n|Tuleutai Suleimenov\n| align=\"right\" |December 1991\n| align=\"right\" |April 1994\n|-\n|Kanat Saudabaev\n|April 1994\n|October 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Science and New Technology\n|Galym Abilsiitov\n| align=\"right\" |February 1992\n| align=\"right\" |August 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Geology and Subsoil Protection\n|Lev Trubnikov\n| align=\"right\" |February 1992\n| align=\"right\" |November 1993\n|-\n|Ministry of Oil and Gas Industry\n|Ravil Cherdabaev\n| align=\"right\" |June 1994\n| align=\"right\" |October 1994\n|-\n|Minister of Ecology and Bioresources\n|Svyatoslav Medvedev\n| align=\"right\" |February 1992\n| align=\"right\" |October 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Communications\n|Igor Ulyanov\n| align=\"right\" |March 1987\n| align=\"right\" |June 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Highways\n|Shamil Bekbulatov\n| align=\"right\" |January 1981\n| align=\"right\" |February 1992\n|-\n|Ministry of Transport\n|Nigmatjan Isingarin\n| align=\"right\" |February 1991\n| align=\"right\" |June 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Transport and Communications\n|Nigmatjan Isingarin\n|June 1994\n|October 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Housing and Land Development\n|Askar Kulibaev\n|September 1993\n|October 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Agriculture and Food\n|Valentin Dvurechensky\n|December 1990\n|February 1992\n|-\n|Ministry of Agriculture\n|Baltash Tursumbaev\n|February 1992\n|November 1993\n|-\n|Ministry of Defense\n|Sagadat Nurmagambetov\n|May 1992\n|October 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Internal Affairs\n|Mikhail Bersenyov\n|April 1990\n|April 1992\n|-\n|Vladimir Shumov\n|April 1992\n|September 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Print and Media\n|Quanysh Sultanov\n|August 1991\n|January 1993\n|-\n|[[Altynbek Sarsenbayuly]]\n|January 1993\n|October 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Tourism, Physical Education and Sports\n|Karatai Turysov\n|August 1991\n|December 1993\n|-\n|Ministry of Youth, Tourism and Sports\n|Byrganym Aitimova\n|December 1993\n|October 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Public Education\n|Shaysultan Shayahmetov\n|June 1988\n|October 1993\n|-\n|Erejep Mambetkaziev\n|October 1993\n|October 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Culture\n|Erkegali Rahmadiev\n|February 1992\n|October 1993\n|-\n|Serik Ashlyaev\n|October 1993\n|October 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Health Care\n|Aksultan Amanbaev\n|April 1992\n|April 1992\n|-\n|Vasiliy Devyatko\n|April 1992\n|October 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Labor\n|Sayat Beisenov\n|March 1991\n|October 1993\n|-\n|Viktor Sobolev\n|October 1993\n|October 1994\n|-\n|Ministry of Social Security\n|Zaure Kadyrova\n|1990\n|February 1992\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Social Protection\n|Zaure Kadyrova\n|February 1992\n|June 1994\n|-\n|Baikarim Tutenov\n|June 1994\n|October 1994\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Ministry of Justice\n|Galihan Erjanov\n|May 1990\n|June 1993\n|-\n|Nagashbai Shaikenov\n|June 1993\n|October 1995\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Government of Kazakhstan|Tereshchenko]]\n[[Category:1991 establishments in Kazakhstan]]\n[[Category:Cabinets established in 1991|Tereshchenko]]\n[[Category:Cabinets disestablished in 1994|Tereshchenko]]\n", "name_user": "S.Didam", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eComposition:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tereshchenko_Cabinet"}
{"title_page": "Burying the Ex", "text_new": "{{short description|2014 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Burying the Ex\n| image          = Burying the Ex.jpeg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Joe Dante]]\n| producer       = Carl Effenson<br>Kyle Tekiela<br>Frankie Lindquist<br>Mary Cybriwsky<br>Alan Trezza<br>David Johnson\n| writer         = Alan Trezza\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Anton Yelchin]]\n* [[Ashley Greene]]\n* [[Alexandra Daddario]]\n* [[Oliver Cooper]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Joseph LoDuca]]\n| cinematography = Jonathan Hall\n| editing        = Marshall Harvey\n| studio         = [[Voltage Pictures]]<br>Elevated Productions<br>Act 4 Entertainment<br>Scooty Woop Entertainment<br>ArtImage Entertainment \n| distributor    = [[Image Entertainment]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2014|9|4|[[71st Venice International Film Festival|Venice]]|2015|6|19|United States}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $604,517<ref name=\"NUM\">{{cite web |title= Burying the Ex (2015) - Financial Information |url= https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Burying-the-Ex#tab=summary |website= [[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate= April 10, 2020 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Burying the Ex''''' is a 2014 American [[Zombie comedy|zombie comedy film]] directed by [[Joe Dante]] and written by Alan Trezza. The film stars [[Anton Yelchin]], [[Ashley Greene]], [[Alexandra Daddario]] and [[Oliver Cooper]]. It screened out of competition at the [[71st Venice International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Venice\">{{cite web |url=http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/71st-festival/line-up/off-sel/out-of-competition/ |title=International competition of feature films |accessdate=August 10, 2014 |work=Venice |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728222533/http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/71st-festival/line-up/off-sel/out-of-competition/ |archivedate=July 28, 2014  }}</ref><ref name=\"Deadline\">{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/07/venice-film-festival-lineup-2014-movie-list/ |title=Venice Film Festival Lineup Announced |accessdate=August 10, 2014 |work=Deadline}}</ref> The film was released on June 19, 2015, by [[Image Entertainment]].\n\n==Plot==\n{{long plot|date=June 2018|reason=Plot is more than 1000 words, between 400 and 700 is recommended}} <!-- trim a third or more -->\nNice guy and horror fanatic Max ([[Anton Yelchin]]) is dating the beautiful-but-manipulative Evelyn ([[Ashley Greene]]). Evelyn is an extreme [[environmentalist]] working for a blog company that promotes \"going green\", while Max works a dead-end job at the local horror memorabilia shop. Max often finds himself trapped trying to do whatever he can to keep Evelyn happy, including changing his diet and selling his old car. In addition to this, Max dreams of opening up a horror memorabilia shop of his own, much to Evelyn's dismay. One day at the shop, Max unloads the latest shipments and finds a [[Satan]] [[Genie]], an object that claims it can grant anyone's wants or desires. Believing it to just be another silly item for the shop, Max places it on the shelf in the storage room and dismisses it.\n\nLater that night, he and Evelyn have sex in the shop and make a promise to each other that they'll be together forever. Shortly thereafter, Max has Evelyn move in with him. Max and Evelyn initially decide to celebrate this new step in their relationship by grabbing a bite to eat. Wanting Evelyn to try something he enjoys for a change, Max suggests they go to a horror themed [[Ice cream parlor|ice cream shop]] run by Olivia ([[Alexandra Daddario]]). Evelyn is immediately unkind to Olivia, believing her and Max were flirting with each other. As Max pleads his case to her, Evelyn tearfully admits that she doesn't want to lose him and that he's the only thing in her life that has made her happy since her mother's death.\n\nAll seems to be great until Max comes back home to discover that Evelyn has redecorated their apartment to what she finds aesthetically pleasing and has put away all of Max's collectables and posters, ruining their price values. This leads to an argument where Max states that he and Evelyn should be making decisions together instead of her taking the reins on every little thing. Feeling that Evelyn's overbearing nature will lead him to be unhappy for the duration of their relationship, Max plans to break up with her but is too scared to do so. Max turns to his slacker half-brother Travis ([[Oliver Cooper]]) for advice. Travis suggests that Max break up with Evelyn in a public place so he can make a quick getaway and have everyone present see her for the control freak she truly is. However, the plan backfires when Evelyn accidentally gets hit by a bus on her way to the park. She dies in the middle of the road while in the arms of a tearful Max.\n\nA couple weeks go by and Max has shut himself off emotionally, feeling responsible for Evelyn's death. Travis swings by his place and, after seeing the funk he's in, encourages him to get back out and move on. Max eventually runs into Olivia again and starts to hit it off with her. As the night progresses, Max and Olivia learn that they both share the same fascination for horror. But when Max and Olivia visit the [[Hollywood Forever Cemetery]], Evelyn is shown to have risen up from the dead and has dug herself out of the ground. After Olivia walks Max back home, he's quickly greeted by an undead Evelyn at the door. Evelyn is overjoyed and believes hers and Max's love is being given a second chance and thinks they're still dating. Frightened, Max realizes that the Satan Genie from the shop made their wish of being \"together forever\" has brought Evelyn back from the dead. Still wanting to pursue Olivia, Max actively attempts to hide Evelyn from her. He's also left to ponder how exactly he's going to officially dump Evelyn. Max presumes that the answer to his problems lie with the Satan Genie, only to have it shatter on the ground when he loses his footing. For his backup plan, Max then researches the occult/spell books the shop has available in the hopes of finding something that will send Evelyn back to her grave. He tries these techniques, but to no avail; as they have no effect on Evelyn whatsoever.\n\nTravis stumbles upon Max with a drunken Evelyn, and is reluctant to help him. He soon has a change of heart and tells Max that the only true way he can get rid of Evelyn is to decapitate her with a machete. Max tries to accomplish this but backs out at the last minute. The day before Halloween, Olivia drops by the shop to visit Max. It's later interrupted by a phone call from Evelyn. Olivia, who still doesn't know that Evelyn's a zombie, thinks Max hasn't gotten over her yet, but offers him an invitation to a screening of ''[[Night of the Living Dead]]'' at the cemetery. Travis steps up to the plate and offers to kill Evelyn so Max can meet Olivia at the movie. Travis shows up at the apartment under the guise of searching for an old DVD Max never returned and intentionally prolongs his stay, annoying Evelyn. She then develops a sudden craving for brains and ends up eating Travis. Meanwhile, Max and Olivia are enjoying each other's company and end up having sex in the back of Olivia's car.\n\nUpon Max's return, he discovers Travis's corpse in the living room. Knowing that Evelyn is now determined to kill anyone who gets in her way, Max tricks her into drawing a hot bubble bath for themselves in order to barricade the bathroom door and trap her inside. He rushes out of the apartment to get the police but leaves his cell phone behind by mistake. Evelyn wastes no time breaking free and escapes. She then kidnaps Olivia after reading the texts between her and Max. Having had no luck with the police, Max hears through one of the [[Scanner (radio)|police scanners]] about someone knocking over a malt shop and realizes Olivia's in trouble. Back at the apartment, Max sees Olivia tied up and Evelyn threatens to kill her. A battle ensues between Max, Evelyn, and Olivia, ending with Travis (now revealed to be a zombie himself) fatally stabbing Evelyn through the chest with the machete. With Evelyn finally gone, Max and Olivia take her body back to the cemetery and bury her.\n\nOne year later, Max and Olivia's relationship is still going strong. Max has long since quit his job, became business partners with Olivia, having joined his horror memorabilia store and her ice cream shop as an enterprise of their own and is now truly happy. Max then surprises Olivia with an engagement ring, which she gladly accepts. And Travis, still in his zombie form, is shown sign-spinning outside the shop.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Anton Yelchin]] as Max\n* [[Ashley Greene]] as Evelyn\n* [[Alexandra Daddario]] as Olivia\n* [[Oliver Cooper]] as Travis\n* [[Archie Hahn (actor)|Archie Hahn]] as Chuck\n* [[Mark Alan]] as Goth Bartender \n* [[Gabrielle Christian]] as Coco \n* [[Mindy Robinson]] as  Mindy\n* [[Dick Miller]] as Grumpy Cop\n\n==Production==\n''Burying the Ex'' was originally produced as a 15-minute short in 2008, written and directed by Alan Trezza. It starred [[Danielle Harris]] as Olivia and [[Mircea Monroe]] as Evelyn, with the male lead (then named Zak) played by [[John Francis Daley]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1262121/ Burying the Ex (2008) - IMDb]</ref> Trezza later expanded the short into a feature film script. According to an interview with director Joe Dante in 2014:\n<blockquote>I met Alan several years ago, got the script for the feature, which was not substantially different from the one we shot. I thought it was funny and different. Cut forward five years. Unexpectedly, after another project fell through, money appeared so we could make the movie, but we had to shoot cheaply and quickly. We shot in 20 days and it was a lot of fun, a hectic shoot, but there was a lot to do. We were clever about our locations and shooting all within the same area of town... The four leads are really fun and creative and brought a lot to the table.<ref name=\"joe\"/></blockquote>\nPrincipal photography began November 17, 2013 and ended December 19, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pro-labs.imdb.com/title/tt3339674/details |title=IMDbPro |publisher=Pro-labs.imdb.com |date= |accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Mary Woronov]] played the owner of a store called Bloody Mary's. However, she was cut out of the film.<ref name=\"joe\">{{cite web|author=Ryan Turek |url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/363669-joe-dante-interview-burying-the-ex/ |title=Exclusive Interview: Joe Dante Talks to Us About Burying the Ex |publisher=Shock Till You Drop |date=September 3, 2014 |accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDante said the film was \"very [[EC Comics]], but it\u2019s not a comic book movie, I think the characters are a little bit more real...  I was left alone in terms of creativity.\" He added that the film was made for his fans.<ref name=\"joe\"/>\n\n== Release ==\nIn January 2015, [[Image Entertainment]] acquired the release rights of the film,<ref>{{cite web|last=Barton |first=Steve |url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/88129/image-entertainment-joe-dante-burying-ex-vod/ |title=Image Entertainment and Joe Dante Burying the Ex on VOD and More! |publisher=Dread Central |date=February 2, 2015 |accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref> and set the release of the film in the United States, to summer 2015 via [[Video on demand]].<ref>{{cite web|author=MrDisgusting |url=http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3330569/joe-dantes-burying-ex-resurrected-vod/ |title=Joe Dante's 'Burying the Ex' Resurrected By Image |publisher=Bloody-disgusting.com |date=February 2, 2015 |accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref> The film was released on June 19, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|last=Lesnick |first=Silas |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/443221-cs-exclusive-joe-dantes-burying-the-ex-poster-and-stills#/slide/1 |title=CS Exclusive: Joe Dante's Burying the Ex Poster and Stills! |publisher=ComingSoon.net |date= |accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref> with the official trailer being released on May 26.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.wickedhorror.com/horror-news/weve-dug-up-a-trailer-for-burying-the-ex/|title = We've Dug Up a Trailer for Burying the Ex|last = Doup\u00e9|first = Tyler|publisher = Wicked Horror|date = May 26, 2015|website = wickedhorror.com|accessdate = May 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 28%, based on 39 reviews, with an average rating of 4.38/10. The critics' consensus reads: \"''Burying the Ex'' boasts flickers of director Joe Dante's former flair, but neither the concept nor its execution live up to the standard set by his best efforts.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/burying_the_ex_2015/ |title= Burying the Ex (2015) |website= [[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date= June 20, 2015 }}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 34 out of 100, based on 18 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/burying-the-ex |title=Burying the Ex Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |date=September 12, 2014 |accessdate=June 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Category\n! Subject\n! Result\n|-\n| California on Location Award\n| Location Professional of the Year \u2014 Independent Feature Film\n| Gregory Alpert\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Rondo Hatton Classic Horror\n| Rondo Statuette for Best Movie\n| [[Joe Dante]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award]]\n| colspan=2|[[Saturn Award for Best DVD or Blu-ray Release|Best DVD or Blu-ray Release]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|3339674|Burying the Ex}}\n\n{{Joe Dante}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burying the Ex}}\n[[Category:2014 films]]\n[[Category:2010s comedy horror films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American comedy horror films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Features based on short films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Joe Dante]]\n[[Category:Human-zombie romance in fiction]]\n[[Category:Voltage Pictures films]]\n[[Category:American zombie comedy films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2014 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Burying the Ex\n| image          = Burying the Ex.jpeg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Joe Dante]]\n| producer       = Carl Effenson<br>Kyle Tekiela<br>Frankie Lindquist<br>Mary Cybriwsky<br>Alan Trezza<br>David Johnson\n| writer         = Alan Trezza\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Anton Yelchin]]\n* [[Ashley Greene]]\n* [[Alexandra Daddario]]\n* [[Oliver Cooper]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Joseph LoDuca]]\n| cinematography = Jonathan Hall\n| editing        = Marshall Harvey\n| studio         = [[Voltage Pictures]]<br>Elevated Productions<br>Act 4 Entertainment<br>Scooty Woop Entertainment<br>ArtImage Entertainment \n| distributor    = [[Image Entertainment]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2014|9|4|[[71st Venice International Film Festival|Venice]]|2015|6|19|United States}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $604,517<ref name=\"NUM\">{{cite web |title= Burying the Ex (2015) - Financial Information |url= https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Burying-the-Ex#tab=summary |website= [[The Numbers]] |accessdate= April 10, 2020 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Burying the Ex''''' is a 2014 American [[Zombie comedy|zombie comedy film]] directed by [[Joe Dante]] and written by Alan Trezza. The film stars [[Anton Yelchin]], [[Ashley Greene]], [[Alexandra Daddario]] and [[Oliver Cooper]]. It screened out of competition at the [[71st Venice International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Venice\">{{cite web |url=http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/71st-festival/line-up/off-sel/out-of-competition/ |title=International competition of feature films |accessdate=August 10, 2014 |work=Venice |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728222533/http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/71st-festival/line-up/off-sel/out-of-competition/ |archivedate=July 28, 2014  }}</ref><ref name=\"Deadline\">{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/07/venice-film-festival-lineup-2014-movie-list/ |title=Venice Film Festival Lineup Announced |accessdate=August 10, 2014 |work=Deadline}}</ref> The film was released on June 19, 2015, by [[Image Entertainment]].\n\n==Plot==\n{{long plot|date=June 2018|reason=Plot is more than 1000 words, between 400 and 700 is recommended}} <!-- trim a third or more -->\nNice guy and horror fanatic Max ([[Anton Yelchin]]) is dating the beautiful-but-manipulative Evelyn ([[Ashley Greene]]). Evelyn is an extreme [[environmentalist]] working for a blog company that promotes \"going green\", while Max works a dead-end job at the local horror memorabilia shop. Max often finds himself trapped trying to do whatever he can to keep Evelyn happy, including changing his diet and selling his old car. In addition to this, Max dreams of opening up a horror memorabilia shop of his own, much to Evelyn's dismay. One day at the shop, Max unloads the latest shipments and finds a [[Satan]] [[Genie]], an object that claims it can grant anyone's wants or desires. Believing it to just be another silly item for the shop, Max places it on the shelf in the storage room and dismisses it.\n\nLater that night, he and Evelyn have sex in the shop and make a promise to each other that they'll be together forever. Shortly thereafter, Max has Evelyn move in with him. Max and Evelyn initially decide to celebrate this new step in their relationship by grabbing a bite to eat. Wanting Evelyn to try something he enjoys for a change, Max suggests they go to a horror themed [[Ice cream parlor|ice cream shop]] run by Olivia ([[Alexandra Daddario]]). Evelyn is immediately unkind to Olivia, believing her and Max were flirting with each other. As Max pleads his case to her, Evelyn tearfully admits that she doesn't want to lose him and that he's the only thing in her life that has made her happy since her mother's death.\n\nAll seems to be great until Max comes back home to discover that Evelyn has redecorated their apartment to what she finds aesthetically pleasing and has put away all of Max's collectables and posters, ruining their price values. This leads to an argument where Max states that he and Evelyn should be making decisions together instead of her taking the reins on every little thing. Feeling that Evelyn's overbearing nature will lead him to be unhappy for the duration of their relationship, Max plans to break up with her but is too scared to do so. Max turns to his slacker half-brother Travis ([[Oliver Cooper]]) for advice. Travis suggests that Max break up with Evelyn in a public place so he can make a quick getaway and have everyone present see her for the control freak she truly is. However, the plan backfires when Evelyn accidentally gets hit by a bus on her way to the park. She dies in the middle of the road while in the arms of a tearful Max.\n\nA couple weeks go by and Max has shut himself off emotionally, feeling responsible for Evelyn's death. Travis swings by his place and, after seeing the funk he's in, encourages him to get back out and move on. Max eventually runs into Olivia again and starts to hit it off with her. As the night progresses, Max and Olivia learn that they both share the same fascination for horror. But when Max and Olivia visit the [[Hollywood Forever Cemetery]], Evelyn is shown to have risen up from the dead and has dug herself out of the ground. After Olivia walks Max back home, he's quickly greeted by an undead Evelyn at the door. Evelyn is overjoyed and believes hers and Max's love is being given a second chance and thinks they're still dating. Frightened, Max realizes that the Satan Genie from the shop made their wish of being \"together forever\" has brought Evelyn back from the dead. Still wanting to pursue Olivia, Max actively attempts to hide Evelyn from her. He's also left to ponder how exactly he's going to officially dump Evelyn. Max presumes that the answer to his problems lie with the Satan Genie, only to have it shatter on the ground when he loses his footing. For his backup plan, Max then researches the occult/spell books the shop has available in the hopes of finding something that will send Evelyn back to her grave. He tries these techniques, but to no avail; as they have no effect on Evelyn whatsoever.\n\nTravis stumbles upon Max with a drunken Evelyn, and is reluctant to help him. He soon has a change of heart and tells Max that the only true way he can get rid of Evelyn is to decapitate her with a machete. Max tries to accomplish this but backs out at the last minute. The day before Halloween, Olivia drops by the shop to visit Max. It's later interrupted by a phone call from Evelyn. Olivia, who still doesn't know that Evelyn's a zombie, thinks Max hasn't gotten over her yet, but offers him an invitation to a screening of ''[[Night of the Living Dead]]'' at the cemetery. Travis steps up to the plate and offers to kill Evelyn so Max can meet Olivia at the movie. Travis shows up at the apartment under the guise of searching for an old DVD Max never returned and intentionally prolongs his stay, annoying Evelyn. She then develops a sudden craving for brains and ends up eating Travis. Meanwhile, Max and Olivia are enjoying each other's company and end up having sex in the back of Olivia's car.\n\nUpon Max's return, he discovers Travis's corpse in the living room. Knowing that Evelyn is now determined to kill anyone who gets in her way, Max tricks her into drawing a hot bubble bath for themselves in order to barricade the bathroom door and trap her inside. He rushes out of the apartment to get the police but leaves his cell phone behind by mistake. Evelyn wastes no time breaking free and escapes. She then kidnaps Olivia after reading the texts between her and Max. Having had no luck with the police, Max hears through one of the [[Scanner (radio)|police scanners]] about someone knocking over a malt shop and realizes Olivia's in trouble. Back at the apartment, Max sees Olivia tied up and Evelyn threatens to kill her. A battle ensues between Max, Evelyn, and Olivia, ending with Travis (now revealed to be a zombie himself) fatally stabbing Evelyn through the chest with the machete. With Evelyn finally gone, Max and Olivia take her body back to the cemetery and bury her.\n\nOne year later, Max and Olivia's relationship is still going strong. Max has long since quit his job, became business partners with Olivia, having joined his horror memorabilia store and her ice cream shop as an enterprise of their own and is now truly happy. Max then surprises Olivia with an engagement ring, which she gladly accepts. And Travis, still in his zombie form, is shown sign-spinning outside the shop.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Anton Yelchin]] as Max\n* [[Ashley Greene]] as Evelyn\n* [[Alexandra Daddario]] as Olivia\n* [[Oliver Cooper]] as Travis\n* [[Archie Hahn (actor)|Archie Hahn]] as Chuck\n* [[Mark Alan]] as Goth Bartender \n* [[Gabrielle Christian]] as Coco \n* [[Mindy Robinson]] as  Mindy\n* [[Dick Miller]] as Grumpy Cop\n\n==Production==\n''Burying the Ex'' was originally produced as a 15-minute short in 2008, written and directed by Alan Trezza. It starred [[Danielle Harris]] as Olivia and [[Mircea Monroe]] as Evelyn, with the male lead (then named Zak) played by [[John Francis Daley]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1262121/ Burying the Ex (2008) - IMDb]</ref> Trezza later expanded the short into a feature film script. According to an interview with director Joe Dante in 2014:\n<blockquote>I met Alan several years ago, got the script for the feature, which was not substantially different from the one we shot. I thought it was funny and different. Cut forward five years. Unexpectedly, after another project fell through, money appeared so we could make the movie, but we had to shoot cheaply and quickly. We shot in 20 days and it was a lot of fun, a hectic shoot, but there was a lot to do. We were clever about our locations and shooting all within the same area of town... The four leads are really fun and creative and brought a lot to the table.<ref name=\"joe\"/></blockquote>\nPrincipal photography began November 17, 2013 and ended December 19, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pro-labs.imdb.com/title/tt3339674/details |title=IMDbPro |publisher=Pro-labs.imdb.com |date= |accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Mary Woronov]] played the owner of a store called Bloody Mary's. However, she was cut out of the film.<ref name=\"joe\">{{cite web|author=Ryan Turek |url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/363669-joe-dante-interview-burying-the-ex/ |title=Exclusive Interview: Joe Dante Talks to Us About Burying the Ex |publisher=Shock Till You Drop |date=September 3, 2014 |accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDante said the film was \"very [[EC Comics]], but it\u2019s not a comic book movie, I think the characters are a little bit more real...  I was left alone in terms of creativity.\" He added that the film was made for his fans.<ref name=\"joe\"/>\n\n== Release ==\nIn January 2015, [[Image Entertainment]] acquired the release rights of the film,<ref>{{cite web|last=Barton |first=Steve |url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/88129/image-entertainment-joe-dante-burying-ex-vod/ |title=Image Entertainment and Joe Dante Burying the Ex on VOD and More! |publisher=Dread Central |date=February 2, 2015 |accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref> and set the release of the film in the United States, to summer 2015 via [[Video on demand]].<ref>{{cite web|author=MrDisgusting |url=http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3330569/joe-dantes-burying-ex-resurrected-vod/ |title=Joe Dante's 'Burying the Ex' Resurrected By Image |publisher=Bloody-disgusting.com |date=February 2, 2015 |accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref> The film was released on June 19, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|last=Lesnick |first=Silas |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/443221-cs-exclusive-joe-dantes-burying-the-ex-poster-and-stills#/slide/1 |title=CS Exclusive: Joe Dante's Burying the Ex Poster and Stills! |publisher=ComingSoon.net |date= |accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref> with the official trailer being released on May 26.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.wickedhorror.com/horror-news/weve-dug-up-a-trailer-for-burying-the-ex/|title = We've Dug Up a Trailer for Burying the Ex|last = Doup\u00e9|first = Tyler|publisher = Wicked Horror|date = May 26, 2015|website = wickedhorror.com|accessdate = May 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 28%, based on 39 reviews, with an average rating of 4.38/10. The critics' consensus reads: \"''Burying the Ex'' boasts flickers of director Joe Dante's former flair, but neither the concept nor its execution live up to the standard set by his best efforts.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/burying_the_ex_2015/ |title= Burying the Ex (2015) |website= [[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date= June 20, 2015 }}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 34 out of 100, based on 18 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/burying-the-ex |title=Burying the Ex Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |date=September 12, 2014 |accessdate=June 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Category\n! Subject\n! Result\n|-\n| California on Location Award\n| Location Professional of the Year \u2014 Independent Feature Film\n| Gregory Alpert\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Rondo Hatton Classic Horror\n| Rondo Statuette for Best Movie\n| [[Joe Dante]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award]]\n| co